<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS RALLY AND GET BACK ON TRACK
</HEADLINE>
  By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The Los Angeles Lakers regained their composure
in the second half and retook home-court advantage in the Western
Conference finals, beating the Portland Trail Blazers, 93-91,
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' winning basket came when Kobe Bryant passed to an
open Ron Harper, who made the shot with 29 seconds left in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers had the ball with 12 seconds left but could
not score.
</P>
<P>
   The game and series swung toward the Lakers in the fourth
quarter. They took off on an 11-3 run for a 83-74 lead with 7
minutes 23 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers' frustration boiled over into an altercation
between Portland leader Scottie Pippen and the Lakers reserve Rick
Fox. Both players squared off, had to be separated and were
assessed technicals, but momentum was clearly with Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   After leading by 12 points early in the third quarter, the Trail
Blazers began to fade. Bryant slid a pretty back-door bounce pass
to Ron Harper under the basket to cut the the Lakers' deficit to
two points, 65-63. They finally tied the score on A.C. Green's jump
shot with 2 minutes 47 seconds left in the quarter and grabbed
their first lead at 69-67 on Harper's two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams traded baskets and the lead in the final two minutes
of the third quarter, until Shaquille O'Neal's two free throws put
the Lakers ahead by 72-71 at the end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the raucous atmosphere of the Rose Garden, the Lakers
slowly built second-half momentum. Then trailing by 61-49 early in
the third quarter, they reeled off eight straight points. Harper
capped the run with an acrobatic shot while plowing into Pippen and
sending his former Chicago Bulls teammate sprawling across the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first half, the Trail Blazers' balance and depth
revealed serious flaws in the Lakers, who were lucky to trail by
only 55-45 at halftime. They were that still in the game because
Bryant assumed the offensive leadership. Bryant scored 18 points on
8 of 13 attempts while O'Neal was trying to figure out how to get a
shot off against Portland's defense.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who had nine points at halftime of Game 2, managed eight
points Friday night while taking only six shots. He also had seven
rebounds. Next for the Lakers was Fox, who added five points in
seven minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did make a 7-0 run to climb to 47-40 midway through
the second quarter, but the Trail Blazers finished with an 8-5 edge
for their
</P>
<P>
   10-point halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Neal struggled, Arvydas Sabonis matched O'Neal in the
middle, scoring nine points and getting three rebounds. Sabonis
scored four more points in the first half than he did in the
previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   Damon Stoudamire led the Trail Blazers in the first half with 11
points.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed Wallace and Steve Smith added 10 apiece. Portland
received a huge boost off the bench from Stacey Augmon, who
blindsided the Lakers with eight points in 8 minutes of the second
quarter. Augmon, who had taken only one shot in the first two
games, made 4 of 6 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Without Bryant, the Trail Blazers might have blown out the
Lakers in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, mostly exploiting a 9-inch height advantage against
Stoudamire, scored 14 points on 6-of-8 shooting as Portland took a
30-22 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Bryant, the Lakers shot 52.6 percent in the first
quarter, but couldn't match the 68.4 percent clip of the Trail
Blazers, who again stymied O'Neal early.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sabonis immediately came out and significantly outplayed
O'Neal, making both his field goal attempts, dropping two free
throws and grabbing one rebound in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal resembled the Sabonis of Game 1 with his line: Zero
points and zero rebounds. O'Neal took only one shot in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sabonis had help, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen and Wallace again roamed freely on defense, buzzing along
the perimeter, then dropping down to harass O'Neal in a game of
human bumper cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have three strong, long guys doubling on me,'' O'Neal said
before Game 3. ``In order for this team to go far, it's not going
to be me scoring 40 and nobody else doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' worst fears were realized in the first three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers hit six of their first eight shots and
effortlessly rolled to a quick 15-2 lead. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
