<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CANDIDATES SQUARE OFF IN MEXICO'S SECOND PRESIDENTIAL DEBATE
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ While striking teachers fought outside the site of
a televised debate, Mexico's top three presidential candidates each
tried to convince voters they represented the true path to change
in this troubled country.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida Ochoa, whose party has controlled the
presidency for 71 years, promised to ``distribute income more
justly'' and ``consolidate the advances'' Mexico has made in recent
years in democracy and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But two challengers pounded Labastida as a candidate of the
status quo, whose Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, is
responsible for Mexico's deeply ingrained problems with corruption
and inequality.
</P>
<P>
   Leading challenger Vicente Fox Quesada, a conservative who is
running neck-in-neck with Labastida, exhorted Mexicans to ``opt for
a change'' by joining his ``alliance for change'' and voting out
the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who don't want the PRI anymore are the majority,''
he said, urging voters to choose him over another opposition
candidate, leftist Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano of Mexico's
Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask you to build a bridge to the country we all dream of,''
Fox said. ``That Mexico is close, just as close as July 2 is.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, who is running in third in polls, portrayed Fox as a
conservative who also bore responsibility for Mexico's problems and
told voters to vote their conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like you,'' he said. ``I know my conscience and my vote
do not have a price.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate followed a week of public relations disasters for
Fox, who has mounted one of the most aggressive opposition
campaigns in history against the PRI. There were no immediate
claims of who won the debate. For much of the 90-minute event the
candidates argued over complicated economic proposals and accused
each other of lying about promises.
</P>
<P>
   Most polls show Fox either a few points behind Labastida or dead
even. Several polls have even put him slightly ahead. A wily
marketing expert, Fox has cited selective polls in his attempt to
wage psychological warfare and position himself as a frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from this second televised encounter could have a
critical impact on the candidates' campaigns as Mexico heads into
the final stretch before the election.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the charismatic Fox has achieved historic momentum
in this campaign. A rancher, and former Coca-Cola executive and
governor of Guanajuato state, Fox has made great strides beyond his
party's conservative, middle-class base by reaching out to Mexico's
poor and disaffected with blunt language.
</P>
<P>
   By pledging to build a pluralistic government, he has picked up
support from leftists, too. Fox represents the conservative
National Action Party, or PAN, but he is also backed by Mexico's
environmentalist Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   This week, prior to the debate, Fox squabbled on live television
during an impromptu meeting with his rivals over when and how to
hold the debate. The episode delighted Labastida and Fox was widely
ridiculed in cartoons, headlines and in commentaries.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Fox acknowledged that he was ``stubborn''
during negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But he said, ``you need character, strength and real leadership
to get rid of 70 years of corruption, poverty and desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's performance Friday was critical to overcoming the damage
he suffered earlier in the week, said University of Guanajuato
political expert Luis Miguel Rionda. ``Never before has there been
this sense of uncertainty about an election during the final month.
The coin is really up in the air between Fox and Labastida.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
