<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BUTTER (Vologda, Russia) _ As any gourmand around here
will tell you, there are but two types of butter in Russia. There
is ordinary, bland butter, bought by ordinary, bland people and
consumed on ordinary, bland occasions. And there is Vologda Butter.
Vologodskoye Maslo is butter so cultured that it was originally
called Parisian butter, even though it is made in Vologda oblast.
This is profitable butter. And this is why some scruple-deprived
people are making counterfeit Vologda Butter. A foreign journal by
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FOREIGN-POLICY (Washington) _ News analysis: The most
important foreign policy vote so far this year, the 237-197 House
approval of the China trade deal, was no new affirmation of
internationalism by an often provincial Congress, but a
reaffirmation of one of its oldest truths: Members vote their
districts. That is, they vote their districts if their constituents
have an interest, and a trade bill is a singular foreign policy
measure because the question of jobs gained and lost commands
attention from lawmakers and constituents ordinarily not much
concerned about the rest of the world. By Adam Clymer. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES (Undated) _ In an important advance against
diabetes, researchers in Canada are reporting that transplants of
insulin-producing cells have enabled eight patients with a severe
form of the disease to stop taking insulin injections. Two to 14
months after being transplanted in a simple procedure resembling a
transfusion, the cells are still working in all eight patients,
half of whom were treated almost a year ago, at the University of
Alberta. The patients, who had Type 1 diabetes, in which the body
produces little or no insulin of its own, no longer have any
symptoms of the disease. Although they no longer need insulin to
control their blood sugar, they now must take other drugs to
prevent rejection of the transplants. By Denise Grady. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and
graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NJ-CORZINE (Undated) _ The checks began cascading in a month
before the elections in New Jersey last November _ $20,000 to the
campaign arm of the Democrats in the State Senate, $15,000 to the
Democratic machine in Hudson County, $15,000 to the one in Union
County _ out of nowhere, it seemed, affluent guardian angels were
coming to the party's aid. The organizer of the donations, and one
of the chief givers, was Jon Corzine, the Democratic contender for
the Senate, a rookie candidate. By Clifford J. Levy. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   TONGASS-ROADS (Sitka, Alaska) _ At 17 million acres, the Tongass
is more than three times the size of any other national forest. But
as the Clinton administration promotes its recently announced plan
to safeguard the forests by banning new road-building throughout
much of the system, the Tongass is the one national forest
specifically exempted. This has galvanized many environmental
groups and conjured up the epic battles that have been fought over
this rain-forest wilderness since the 1970s. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES (Undated) _ In an important advance against
diabetes, researchers in Canada are reporting that transplants of
insulin-producing cells have enabled 8 patients with a severe form
of the disease to stop taking insulin injections. Two to 14 months
after being transplanted in a simple procedure resembling a
tranfusion, the cells are still working in all 8 patients, half of
whom were treated almost a year ago at the University of Alberta,
in Edmonton. The patients, who had Type 1 diabetes, in which the
body produces little or no insulin of its own, no longer have any
symptoms of the disease. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   NY-INTERNET-CAFE (London) _ A London entrepreneur plans to open
an Internet cafe in Times Square with 1,000 terminals, which would
make it the largest in the U.S. By Andrew Ross Sorkin. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FREEH-RENO (Washington) _ The Justice Department considered but
decided against an independent counsel to investigate FBI Director
Louis Freeh for inaccurate congressional testimony in 1997 during a
hearing about the FBI laboratory's mishandling of cases. Attorney
General Janet Reno concluded that while Freeh's testimony was
inaccurate, there was no evidence of criminal intent that would
warrant the appointment of an independent prosecutor. By Neil A.
Lewis. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FUEL-CELLS (Carlsbad, Calif.) _ An intense race is on to design
and manufacture fuel cells, low-pollution devices that generate
electrical current from chemical reactions. Although they are
similar in many ways to batteries, fuel cells can be quickly
regenerated by pumping in new chemical fuel. They are now teetering
on the edge of becoming big business: Several hundred units have
been sold already, and some analysts predict a billion-dollar
market by 2005. But the last steps are not coming easily. By
Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT phot clients and
graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-INSURANCE (Undated) _ After falling for two years, car
insurance premiums around the country are climbing once again,
resuming a steady quarter-century rise. Several big insurers _
including Progressive, Geico, State Farm and Allstate _ have begun
imposing higher prices, and analysts say that by the end of the
year most other leading companies are likely to follow suit. The
insurers said they were forced to act because of rising expenses
for repairs and treatment of injuries. By Joseph B. Treaster. 1,500
words.
</P>
