<HEADER>
A7379 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     05-27 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME NEWS AND VIEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's purple-and-gold, news-and-views edition of The Sporting
Muse:
</P>
<P>
   News: The Lakers beat Portland 93-91 to regain the edge in the
NBA's Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Views: The Lakers can thank coach for the win. Not Phil Jackson,
but Mike Dunleavy.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers coach had a 12-point lead and the momentum in
the third quarter when he started moving personnel in and out of
the lineup. After turning Shaquille O'Neal into the biggest
non-factor in the western hemisphere with constant double- and
triple-team defenses, Dunleavy suddenly went small with his subs.
</P>
<P>
   On the bench was Arvydas Sabonis. On the bench was Scottie
Pippen. In-and-out was Rasheed Wallace. When you have a team like
the Lakers on the ropes, a team with some superb personnel but
ebbing confidence, the last thing you do is release the
stranglehold. If the Blazers go for the kill in the third quarter,
as they did in game 2, the Lakers don't regain the home advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy also didn't make very good use of Bonzi Wells or Brian
Grant. The latter seems at his best when he's playing at the same
time as Wallace and/or Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   News: Ron Harper hits the game-winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   Views: It takes a lot of patience and courage for O'Neal and
Kobe Bryant to let a Harper, Glen Rice or Robert Horry take a shot
in that situation. But this is an essential of the triangle
offense, the willingness to take the uncovered opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   In the Game 2 loss, these opportunities were missed or
squandered. Friday, Horry had a great third quarter on both ends
and Harper came up with the game-winner and several solid defensive
stops. Double H needs to step up, too, because Rice is playing
spotty and Rick Fox is clueless.
</P>
<P>
   News: Pacers take 2-0 lead over Knicks in Eastern final.
</P>
<P>
   Views: The New York press is wailing over Patrick Ewing possibly
being sidelines, but the Knicks are actually a better team without
the elderly, immobile center. They made their playoff run a season
ago without him, and his absence forces Jeff Van Gundy to play more
uptempo, which suits Knicks like Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   And while the consensus says the Lakers or Portland will rout
the east champ in the finals, I wouldn't be so quick to judge.
Indiana has no answer for Shaquille O'Neal or Portland's big men,
but a team with a shooter like Reggie Miller should never be
discounted. Likewise, the Knicks have enough athletes to compete
and would benefit from last year's finals appearance.
</P>
<P>
   News: Dodgers rail at suspensions handed down for fracas with
the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Is it proper to use the world overkill'' when talking
about a player-fan altercation.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball's new cop, Frank Robinson, obviously is
trying to make a statement about brawls and confrontations. Many of
the players ticketed weren't doing much more than standing around.
</P>
<P>
   But they were standing in the seats. Short of a blatant fan
assault, which doesn't include stealing someone's hat, there's no
reason for a player to enter the stands -- especially since they're
sober and the guys in the stands likely are not.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers do the simple thing and back off, they aren't hit
with multiple suspensions and no one has to listen to G.M. Kevin
Malone prattle on about integrity of the pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   My only question for Robinson: Why wasn't Malone suspended,
since he ran on the field during the brawl, and why wasn't Davey
Johnson suspended, since he's the figurative head of the family
that went off?
</P>
<P>
   News: Dodgers send Orel Hershiser to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Orel's recent appearances were ugly, but I have a hard
time believing he can't be of service to the Dodgers. The work of
Alan Mills, Mike Fetters and Terry Adams hasn't exactly been
brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   News: Former USC star Seth Etherton makes his major league debut
for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Etherton becomes the 19th pitcher used by the Angels this
season, and it's not even June. If each team uses 20 pitchers this
season, 600 different pitchers will have performed in the majors.
And we wonder why there's so much scoring.
</P>
<P>
   News: Baseball pennant races develop early.
</P>
<P>
   Views: Baseball sometimes gets breaks it doesn't deserve.
Despite balanced schedules that trash division rivalries and the
advent of the wild card, the 2000 season is shaping up as a
stunner.
</P>
<P>
   All four teams in A.L. West are .500 or better (through
Thursday), Chicago and Kansas City are giving Cleveland a run in
the A.L. Central, and the Yankees and Red Sox are locked in what
looks like an old-fashioned race.
</P>
<P>
   The N.L. is far less discerning, with Atlanta and Arizona
seemingly locked into division titles. But the wild card fight,
which includes the Dodgers, at the moment looks like a six-team
pileup.
</P>
<P>
   News: Bobby Knight gets a hand-slap from Indiana officials in
midst of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Views: I have no problem with this, but only because I really
want to see Knight go out on his shield, with one hand on a
referee's or player's neck and the other giving fans of (fill in
the Big Ten opponent) the finger.
</P>
<P>
   News: Salt Lake City Olympic Committee releases private geld''
(money) memo regarding IOC member enticements.
</P>
<P>
   Views: It is totally amazing that allegedly intelligent people
feel the need to write incriminating things down on paper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
