r a BC-HOUSING-AZR &LR;      05-27 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPOLITANO PENALIZES 21 MULTIHOUSING UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY ROBBIE SHERWOOD  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Builders around the state are still building apartments
that are not accessible for the disabled despite requirements that
have been around for a decade, Attorney General Janet Napolitano
said Friday, May 26.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano has slapped 21 new or nearly new apartment and
condominium complexes around the state with ``administrative
charges'' for such problems as ramps that are too steep for
wheelchairs to climb or doorways too narrow to pass through.
</P>
<P>
   The builders, who were not identified, must make repairs costing
thousands of dollars or risk being sued by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about punishing builders, it's about protecting
the right of the disabled to live wherever they want,'' Napolitano
said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation merely scratches the surface of the problem,
Napolitano and disability advocates say. Prompted by complaints,
investigators randomly selected 32 new or nearly new properties.
Only one, a complex in Bisbee, completely complied with Arizona
fair-housing laws. A handful had not yet finished construction or
had problems too minor for citations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was absolutely no surprise to us at all, but it shouldn't
even be an issue,`` said Darrel Christenson of the advocacy group
Arizona Bridge to Independent Living. ``The Fair Housing Act has
been around for a long time now, and it's not as if developers,
contractors and city officials don't know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Christenson said some disabled people who, in an accessible
home, could live alone have been forced into nursing homes at
higher-than-normal rents. Among the 10,000 people on the waiting
list for Section 8 affordable housing in Phoenix, more than 3,000
claim disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   About 700,000 Arizonans have disabilities, though not all
require specialized living arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Fair-housing laws dictate, among other things, that apartments
with no elevators must make every ground-floor unit accessible to
wheelchairs, said Robin Coulon, an assistant attorney general in
the civil rights division.
</P>
<P>
   Doorways must be wide enough to pass through, bathrooms and
kitchens large enough to maneuver, and walls reinforced in case
they need to be equipped with rails. In apartments with elevators,
all units must meet this standard.
</P>
<P>
   The worst offenses found were ramps too steep and doorways too
narrow for wheelchair passage, Coulon said. ``That's pretty basic
stuff, and in apartments built since 1998, that's pretty egregious.
It's now going to be very expensive to reframe those doorways, but
it would not have been if they did it earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors found major violations, defined as those that would
cost more than $100 to correct, at complexes in Phoenix, Tucson,
Sahuarita, Casa Grande, Gilbert, Prescott, Cottonwood and Peoria.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems, building industry experts say, is that the
federal fair-housing guidelines are vague, and that local
governments have no authority to reject plans based on
non-compliance. Secretary of Housing and Urban Development Andrew
Cuomo recently announced an effort to more clearly outline the
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we have been asking for for years,'' said Wayne
Kaplan of the Arizona Multi-Housing Association. ``We will continue
to work with the Attorney General's Office and other agencies to
mutually resolve differences and misunderstandings. But the big
problem is trying to get a clear understanding of what is
accessible.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Robbie.Sherwood(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8146. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
