r n BC-BUDGET-CALIFORNIA-SFC     05-27 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ASSEMBLY PASSES $100 BILLION DRAFT BUDGET BILL  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The Assembly passed a $100 billion state budget
Friday, sending the weighty document on to a budget conference
committee that will spend the next two weeks hashing out the
details.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-to-10 vote on the Assembly's budget plan marked the first
time in 10 years there has been wide bipartisan support for a draft
budget bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans cautioned their support will fade if Democrats
do not increase the $2.7 billion currently devoted to tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget contains the good, the bad and the ugly,'' said
Assembly Minority Leader Scott Baugh, R-Huntington Beach. ``We're
not interested in a budget that doesn't have substantial and
permanent tax relief. I hope when this budget returns to the floor,
it will have some good and probably some bad, but no ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats hold a majority in both houses, they need
Republican votes to reach the two-thirds approval necessary to send
the budget to Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh said Republicans want $4 billion in wide-ranging tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of tax cuts comes as state government is flush with a
$12.3 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has offered nearly $2.5 billion in tax cuts, including a
controversial plan to exempt teachers from the state income tax.
That proposal is not included in the Assembly bill.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Robert Hertzberg, D-Sherman Oaks, said he is
not dismissing Davis' tax exemption plan outright.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll give it a fair hearing,'' he said. But behind him, Baugh
shook his head ``no'' at the question. Baugh has said he will not
support Davis' proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Democratic governor's cuts would come from one-time
income tax rebates of as much as $150 per single taxpayer or up to
$300 for couples who file jointly.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said Davis' proposal would leave out taxpayers who
earned too little to pay state income taxes last year. Forty-one
percent of families and individual taxpayers would receive no
rebates, according to a study by the Institute on Taxation and
Economic Policy, a nonprofit, Washington-based research
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats have proposed about $1.4 billion in cuts
through sales tax rebates in the budget, which is for the fiscal
year that starts July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Republicans brought up 17 budget amendments, mostly
dealing with tax cuts and abortion, but Democrats blocked them from
the bill. Some GOP members also warned against the massive spending
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``This state budget is growing faster than your family budget,
and it is growing at the expense of your family budget,'' said
Assemblyman Tom McClintock, R-Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Assemblyman Rico Oller of San Andreas warned, ``The
downturn will come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will remember this day as the one when we spent the
reserve,'' Oller said. ``It will cause us to be in a very tight
spot in a few years. This is a bad budget _ no one would run their
house or business this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also are pushing for more money for education,
community colleges and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Baugh said there are areas where mass transit does not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is far too much emphasis on mass transit,'' he said.
``We need to dedicate more money to highways, to help people stuck
in gridlock.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern also was raised over the lack of funds for special
education. A pending lawsuit may force the state to refund more
than $1 billion to school districts for special education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Assembly, Senate and Davis will spend the
next two weeks working on some compromise, in an attempt to meet
the state's constitutional deadline of June 15 for passing a
budget. Last year was the first time in many years that lawmakers
met the deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
