<SLUG> BC-INDY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACING FEUD BREWS ANEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM PEDLEY, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Don't start celebrating that open-wheel truce
just yet.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two weeks, people around Indianapolis Motor
Speedway have done their best to keep this year's Indy 500 from
becoming a key battleground in the five-year war between the Indy
Racing League and Championship Auto Racing Teams.
</P>
<P>
   But as Sunday's race approaches, it appears that CART vs. IRL
again has become the theme of Indy 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The first prominent salvo came Thursday from Al Unser Jr., who
is competing at Indy for the first time since 1995, the last time
CART drivers raced there.
</P>
<P>
   Unser sounded fairly upbeat about his return to Indy on Thursday
_ until the subject of driver Juan Montoya came up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd better respect Indianapolis,'' said Unser, a two-time
Indy winner who jumped from CART to the IRL this season, ``because
Indianapolis will bite you hard. You don't walk away from those.
They carry people out of here on stretchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser wasn't smiling.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of detente, Unser was given the chance to soften
his statements. Instead, he strengthened them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' he said when asked whether he really meant what he was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't just talking through my you know what.''
</P>
<P>
   What particularly irks Unser is Montoya's aggressive driving
style, which Montoya learned in Formula One and has honed in CART
the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Likely at Unser's behest, and with Montoya in mind, IRL stewards
in Thursday's drivers' meeting ``made it clear that anybody who
moves (crowds) anybody else down the track on the straightaways
gets the black flag,'' Unser said. ``That's called defensive
driving. It's driving with your mirrors. And it is not allowed in
the (IRL) Northern Light Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Unser found an opportunity to blast CART on behalf of the
IRL.
</P>
<P>
   ``CART allows one (blocking) move. That one move will kill
you,'' Unser said. ``Ask Jeff Krosnoff. That one move killed him in
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Krosnoff was killed in a CART race in Toronto in 1996 when his
car flew into a fence after colliding with Stefan Johansson's.
 &LR; brkstr:III  &LR; tx:Montoya, one of two full-time CART drivers at Indy
this year along with Jimmy Vasser, had left the track Thursday
before Unser made his comments and has chosen not to respond to
them. But he has sounded less than thrilled to be in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Montoya expressed some annoyance with what some
perceive as the stodginess of Indianapolis Motor Speedway and its
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much tradition here,'' he said. ``I'm not saying
it's bad, but it's too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Indy fans, Montoya said, ``If you don't give them an
autograph, you're an (expletive). In Formula One, it's impossible
for fans to get autographs.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he regard an Indy 500 victory as a blow struck for CART?
</P>
<P>
   ``We come here,'' Montoya said. ``(Team owner Chip Ganassi) gave
me a car. He decided he wanted to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know, I just drive the car as fast as I can. Simple.''
 &LR; brkstr:III  &LR; tx:Ganassi took advantage of a decision by CART to
hold open the last two weeks in May to give teams and drivers the
opportunity to race in the 500.
</P>
<P>
   Ganassi bought IRL equipment for Montoya and Vasser, and here
they are.
</P>
<P>
   Before a CART press dinner Wednesday night, with cameras rolling
and tape recorders recording, Ganassi toed the peace-and-harmony
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a T,'' he said, ``everybody (at the speedway, which is
owned by IRL founder and president Tony George) has been great.
Nobody has even mentioned the CART-IRL thing all week long.''
</P>
<P>
   But during dinner, a speaker stepped to the microphone and
shouted something to the effect that CART was going to kick the
behind of the IRL on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ganassi grinned broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Indy legend and IRL stalwart A.J. Foyt returned serve Friday
when asked his opinion of Ganassi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Floyd Ganassi (Chip's father) is a great guy,'' Foyt said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, legendary driver Mario Andretti indirectly criticized
George in a news conference, saying politics were ruining the
sport. George countered that Andretti was just bitter because his
son Michael has not been able to race at Indy since the split and
may never be able to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another salvo came from speedway staffers on qualifying day.
When IRL driver Greg Ray knocked Montoya off the pole late last
Saturday, the media-room staff broke protocol by erupting in
cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Just a race? Hardly.  &LR; brkstr:III  &LR; tx:So far, words have been the
weapon of choice in the battle between the IRL and CART at Indy
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants that battle to carry over on the track.
</P>
<P>
   When the green flag drops Sunday, 33 cars will head toward the
first turn at 200 miles per hour. Leading that pack will be Ray,
with Montoya immediately to his right.
</P>
<P>
   History and reputation indicate that Montoya will be looking to
come out of turn one as the race leader.
</P>
<P>
   Ray may or may not allow that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aggressive by nature,'' Ray said. ``He's aggressive by
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said he will tap his aggressiveness if his car is running
well and the situation is right.
</P>
<P>
   If not, and there is the potential for disaster, he'll back off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only going to drive to my comfort level,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   And that goes for the whole race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't give a darn about the first 199 laps,'' Ray said. ``If
the car is good, I'll go. If not, I won't.''  &LR; brkstr:III  &LR; tx:Ask
George about a return of some of the excitement to the 500 this
year, he'll tell you it never left.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed most IRL loyalists will insist that the race remains as
exciting as it was before CART teams fled in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indy is still Indy,'' former CART driver Robby Gordon said
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Many around the sport and the city of Indianapolis disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Miller has covered the race for 31 years. He said George
is ``kidding himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the race used to be the focal point of the city.
Tickets were almost impossible to come by, and those that were to
be had were in the hands of scalpers and were out of the price
range of ordinary fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be open the gates, make ice and count the money,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   No longer.
</P>
<P>
   The race still attracts almost a half-million fans for the race.
But Miller said that Indy has become a one-day event in that such
events as practice, qualifying and carbureation day now attract
little interest.
</P>
<P>
   Unser said fans still turn out for that stuff, but it doesn't
look that way because increased seating has spread people around.
</P>
<P>
   But just about everybody seems to agree that at least a bit of
the excitement has returned this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be more of a positive buzz nationally,'' George
said. ``The only way I have to gauge that is walking around.''
 &LR; brkstr:III  &LR; tx:There seems to be several reasons for whatever
renewed interest there is in the 500.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of 19-year-old Sarah Fisher in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Unser.
</P>
<P>
   The return _ albeit in a limited role _ of Roger Penske, who is
sponsoring Jason Leffler's car.
</P>
<P>
   And especially, the entry of Ganassi's two drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is renewed interest,'' IRL driver Scott Sharp said.
``Yes, I think so. There are just a lot of good stories here this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   All of those stories, however, have ties to the good old days,
the pre-split days.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is driving for Derrick Walker, also a current CART team
owner and one of the original founders of CART.
</P>
<P>
   Penske is a CART team owner and also a founder of the CART
series.
</P>
<P>
   And Target//Ganassi racing is the top team in CART.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, talk of reuniting the two series was the hot topic
at Indianpolis. This year, it is a non-topic.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, just about everybody says. Many agree with Miller, who
said Indy will never be Indy again until there is only one
open-wheel series in this country.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, he cautions, maybe not even then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
