r a BC-ROYAL-KAN &LR;      05-27 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYALS FEEL THE POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK KAEGEL, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ After the rain came a deluge of home runs Friday
night at Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals smashed a club-record four home runs _ by Jeramine
Dye, Mark Quinn, Brian Johnson and Carlos Febles _ in the sixth
inning as they scored eight times and wiped out the Anaheim Angels'
4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After seven innings, the Royals led 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   Dye led off the sixth with a homer over the right-field wall,
his 14th this season but his first since May 7.
</P>
<P>
   The power surge continued against Angels right-hander Seth
Etherton, making his major-league debut, as Quinn followed with a
425-foot blast to the grass beneath the center-field scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   That ended Etherton's debut, with Jeff Weaver arriving to
inherit a 4-3 lead. But Joe Randa singled, Carlos Beltran doubled,
and Johnson lofted a three-run homer to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Rey Sanchez walked, Johnny Damon singled, and Febles arched
another three-run drive into the left-field seats for a 9-4 lead
that ended Weaver's outing.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals had hit three home runs in an inning 14 times
previously but four was a first.
</P>
<P>
   By then there had been seven homers in the game, five by the
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The start of the game was delayed 1 hour, 11 minutes by rain. A
half-hour after the scheduled 7:05 start a glorious rainbow arched
east of the stadium, then a fainter second rainbow appeared.
</P>
<P>
   At least the crowd of 22,394 had that entertainment before
Royals right-hander Chris Fussell finally unfurled the first pitch
at 8:16 in soggy 75-degree weather.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
