<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATES HINGE ON FED, NOT FISCAL POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Has anyone noticed that federal budget surpluses have
failed to produce the interest rate decline many economists and
political leaders said would be the reward for conquering chronic
budget shortfalls?
</P>
<P>
   The result, in fact, has been the opposite. Just as the federal
budget began to move from red ink to black a couple of years ago,
the trend of interest rates turned up, which was contrary to
conventional wisdom espoused during the anti-deficit crusade.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Were the experts wrong? Perhaps. More likely,
though, the false promise of lower interest rates was more a matter
of sugar-coating prospective outcomes in the name of promoting what
was perceived as a greater good.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, economists worthy of their doctorates know full
well there is no convincing correlation between balanced budgets
and interest rates, and never has been. During the '70s, '80s and
'90s, in fact, the interest rate-budget deficit correlation was
frequently inverse, as rates often declined even as deficits
soared.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, those same economists know that there is always much
more at work than fiscal policy when it comes to interest-rate
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing that kept the promise of budget surpluses from
translating into lower interest rates was the hedge fund crisis in
September '98 that gave the financial world a case of high anxiety.
It was serious enough to prompt the Federal Reserve to intervene,
and thereby assure global financiers it would guarantee the
system's integrity. The rising demand for supersafe money havens
perforce led to rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the Fed decided it had had enough of the stock
market's irrational exuberance and began raising the key rates
under its control. All this time, of course, the budget surpluses
were expanding, but the credit markets paid no attention. In any
showdown between fiscal rectitude and Fed tightening, it's no
contest. The Fed rules.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of the disconnect between fiscal policy and
interest rates has been in Japan, which has opened the red-ink
floodgates in the name of trying to stimulate the economy out of a
decade of malaise. Despite running the highest budget deficits in
the industrialized world recently, however, interest rates in Japan
are virtually zero. For a time, in fact, interest rates in Japan
were negative, which means some major players were actually paying
financial intermediaries to hold their money.
</P>
<P>
   Again, what has happened in Japan has been more a response to
monetary policy machinations than anything dictated by market
forces responding to fiscal policy developments.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to say that ending the era of chronic U.S.
budget deficits wasn't a worthwhile achievement. The only honest
justification Americans ever had for opposing federal profligacy,
though, was that keeping government spending in balance with its
revenue was the right and responsible thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   If any average American, however, bought into the fanciful claim
that the end of deficits would make it easier to buy a car or a
house or a washing machine on credit, they were ignoring the
reality of what was happening around them.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates will ease when the Fed says they will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
