<HEADER>
A7390 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-UPS-KAN &LR;      05-27 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Volunteer experience gives UPS managers a new perspective  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ The way Ron Alexander tells it, he was a
starched-white-shirt kind of manager in a starched-white-shirt kind
of place.
</P>
<P>
   When they took away his pager, his cell phone and his laptop, he
felt violated.
</P>
<P>
   Stripped of his corporate identity and its trappings, he was put
to perhaps the most significant management test of his United
Parcel Service career: He was sent to a poverty-stricken border
area near McAllen, Texas, to do community service work for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander wasn't in trouble. In fact, the month separated from
his responsibilities was a prize _ an appointment to the company's
Community Internship Program.
</P>
<P>
   The UPS district security manager, who oversees 29 buildings and
operations in the Kansas City area and Kansas, was given a
``volunteer'' assignment that ranked him among 50 (out of about
2,300 UPS managers worldwide) who are chosen annually for the
once-in-a-career opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost like a secret honor society, where those tapped
aren't exactly sure why they were chosen and, perhaps even more
curious, aren't specifically told what they're expected to get out
of it.
</P>
<P>
   But a few days after Alexander returned to Kansas from working
among the most wrenching rural poverty he'd ever seen, he said he
saw one lesson clearly:
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody came into my office and was complaining about some
problem, and I was listening...but in the back of my mind I was
thinking, `You think you've got problems?' I was able to accept and
handle the situation without getting upset. I think I have a better
appreciation now for priorities and for what real problems are.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting a package from Point A to Point B on time continues to
be the vital core part of Alexander's business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a big deal, and I'm still running around a lot and
taking phone calls day and night to get it done,'' Alexander said.
``It's still a big, big deal to the organization if someone messes
up in the chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a commitment, but I'm not as intense. I don't know
if the feeling will last, but for now I think I have a better
perspective on balancing my work life.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a common reaction from Community Internship Program
participants. Don Wofford, UPS corporate community relations
manager in Atlanta and a ``graduate'' of the program, said 1,100
UPS managers had had similar experiences since the selective
volunteer interlude began being offered in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a gimmick to inject humanity or appreciation for
diversity into the management ranks. It's also a signal that
participants have been marked as up-and-comers and people worth
keeping. Six of UPS's top 14 management team members are Community
Internship grads.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they get back to their regular work, we look for four
major outcomes,'' Wofford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope for greater awareness of the economic and social
conditions that exist in this country today; we want them to have
greater understanding of these situations; we want them to be
sensitive to the cultural differences they've seen, and we want to
encourage involvement in the areas in which they live, whether it's
participating in food drives or other volunteer work or whatever
problems their own back yards present.''
</P>
<P>
   From March 17 to April 13, Alexander's group of nine UPS
managers _ from all over the United States and China _ met in the
U.S. border city of McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   They were allowed one trip home in the middle of the month, but
otherwise they stayed in a ``second-rate hotel.'' Contact with
their offices was all but forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   The company hooked them up with a social service agency that
worked with a largely Mexican population.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's group, without an experienced handyman among them,
was assigned to provide electricity, plumbing and significant
structural repairs to the dirt-floored shacks of two families.
</P>
<P>
   They had a Time//Life handyman's tip book and a $1,000 spending
budget to buy supplies. Alexander said they made frequent trips
into the local Wal-Mart for nails and other necessities.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Wofford said, UPS sent three similar management
groups into an impoverished section of Chicago, into the Chinatown
neighborhood of New York City and into a poor Appalachian area near
Chattanooga, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   It costs UPS a half-million dollars a year to support the
program. Participants continue to draw full pay, and their travel,
lodging and meal expenses are covered. It's worth the expense and
hassle of covering for key managers when they're absent from work,
Wofford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a global company,'' he said. ``We need managers who have
enlarged perspectives.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why UPS changes its Community Internship work sites to
correspond to social or economic conditions. Over the years,
they've put more emphasis on understanding Hispanic culture, and
they're trying to add an opportunity to learn more about
Asian-American culture.
</P>
<P>
   The focus reflects the changing demographics of the United
States, as well as the customers and employees of UPS, Wofford
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who sees more and more workers with Hispanic
backgrounds being hired at his Kansas and Kansas City-area
operations, said he learned important lessons about cultural
differences.
</P>
<P>
   One example sticks in his mind:
</P>
<P>
   ``Like young people everywhere, there were some down there who
had loud stereo systems in their cars. You'd hear that boom, boom,
boom on the streets. But down there, whenever we'd pull up next to
a car with Hispanic teen-agers, if they'd notice us next to them,
they'd unfailingly turn down the volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't just happen once or twice. It happened every time.
It showed a respect for elders that's part of the culture, and
that's important to understand when I'm dealing with young Hispanic
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS asks the managers to keep a private journal of their
Community Internship experiences, but they don't have to turn it
in. And there's no official debriefing when they return to the
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, nobody talks about it much at all,'' Alexander said.
``It's really a low-profile kind of deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Wofford said, there's a track record of greater community
voluntarism and social service support at the UPS facilities where
managers have gone through the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are managers who can make things happen,'' Wofford said.
``They influence a lot of people. There is a ripple effect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
