<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPLETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR: MOST TRIPLETS DELIVERED EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MAUREEN WEST  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Doctors deliver triplets too early, resulting in more
health problems for babies and higher hospital bills, according to
a report by the Phoenix area's premier multiple-births specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers of triplets are pleading with doctors to deliver them at
30 or 31 weeks because they are getting so large and are in such
discomfort, Dr. John Elliott told the American College of
Obstetricians and Gynecologists this week.
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott said doctors shouldn't be too ready to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easy way out seems to be to deliver early and put them in
the nursery or intensive care,'' Elliott said. ``Toughing it out
for even one or two weeks more can make a tremendous difference in
infant health and cost of care.''
</P>
<P>
   A pre-term baby at 30 weeks costs $217,000 per infant, while one
born at 36 weeks costs about $15,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple-birth moms from fertility clinics all over the United
States are coming to Phoenix to deliver at Good Samaritan Regional
Medical Center because of the national reputation of Elliott and
his associates. Elliott and his partners, Phoenix Perinatal
Associates, have delivered 51 sets of quadruplets and 260 sets of
triplets.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital last year opened a special living area for mothers
of multiples, who stay for up to four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty percent of our success is learning to psychologically
deal with the mother, and the other 50 percent is the medical part
of it _ knowing what drugs to use to hold back contractions,'' said
Elliott, who studied psychology as an undergraduate.
</P>
<P>
   With advances in reproductive technologies, many women who
previously could not conceive are becoming pregnant. But new
treatments and drugs have also increased the number of multiple
births. In 1980, there were 1,337 triplet births in the United
State. By 1998, there were 6,919.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, the number of births involving three or more babies
nearly doubled from 57 in 1988 to 111 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Often Elliott's relationship with his triplet mothers is
adversarial. Triplet mothers under his care often deliver by
Caesarean section at 34, 35 or 36 weeks. Full term is about 38
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel my body stretching beyond what it is supposed to
stretch, and I couldn't walk,'' Margie Jones of Phoenix said,
describing the final days of her triplet pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would plead with doctors every day, but I am ecstatic that I
made it this far,'' added Jones, who on Wednesday gave birth to
three boys. She was pregnant 34 weeks, six days.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was in the hospital for 55 days, after complications arose
during the 27th week of her pregnancy. She was on magnesium to
control contractions and developed a blood clot in her lung.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hell,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Mihelich remembers well those dark days, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, Elliott would come in and say, `One more day,' ''
she said. ``Sometimes, he would start the day with a pep rally with
my husband and anyone else he could bring in. I hated them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihelich gave birth at 34 weeks on Dec. 17 to three healthy boys
_ Anthony, Benjamin and William _ who were all out of the hospital
by early January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awful, but I'm glad he did it. Every day I carried them
was two days they didn't have to spend in the neonatal intensive
care unit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott studied records of 1,000 U.S. mothers of triplets over
the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   He found that 35 percent of the early deliveries, before 34
weeks, were made at the doctor's discretion, not because of a
medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers are in tremendous discomfort or pain. But when you ask
them to decide between seeing their child in an incubator, hooked
up on a breathing machine, they will choose being uncomfortable,''
Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   But some doctors also are concerned about the mothers' health if
they carry too long. Others don't feel comfortable with techniques
that help women carry babies longer.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said the estimated risk for maternal death for a mother
carrying triplets is 1 in 3,000 vs. 1 in 10,000 for a mother
carrying one child.
</P>
<P>
   Although other doctors generally agree with Elliott that 34 to
35 weeks is the ideal time to deliver triplets, it's not an easy
decision for doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always in the back of a doctor's mind is: What if something
happens to one or all of the babies at 32 or 33 weeks and I didn't
do as the family wished,'' said Dr. Richard Dickson of Obstetrix, a
Tucson practice that specializes in complicated pregnancies. ``Some
are women who have been trying for years to have children.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Culbertson, an obstetrician who has delivered single
babies, twins and a few triplets, understands why some doctors
would deliver at 31 or 32 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Culbertson said he and other doctors don't believe in using high
dosages of drugs, as Elliott and his associates do, to stop
contractions and delay deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle that all doctors struggle with is that many of the
drugs used to keep babies in the uterus carry some degree of risk
for moms and babies,'' Culbertson said. ``There comes a point when
the benefit of using the medication may be outweighed by the
risk.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Maureen.West(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8167 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
