<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE LEARN HOW TO HANDLE MENTAL PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ March 15. Melissa Crites makes a frantic 911 call,
telling the dispatcher that her 24-year-old son is suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   She warns the Kansas City police that he is mentally ill, and
has been hospitalized eight times before for his illness. She also
warns police that he wants them to kill him. Police call this
``suicide by cop.''
</P>
<P>
   When police arrive in the 8400 block of Ward Parkway Plaza,
Crites breathes easier. Until she hears three shots. Her son had
charged police holding a steak knife above his head. He was
critically wounded.
</P>
<P>
   A police investigation showed that the shooting was justified,
that the man rushed at officers and that they had no time to do
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   But Crites complained later that she thought the police could
have done something else to calm him down: ``The officers did
exactly what my son wanted them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The scenario repeats itself daily across the nation. Encounters
between police and the mentally ill can end tragically. But a
program out of Memphis, Tenn., that soon will begin in Kansas City
offers hope to the mentally ill and their families, who often rely
on police for help.
</P>
<P>
   The program can mean the difference between a police officer
inflaming a difficult situation or defusing it.
</P>
<P>
   Called Crisis Intervention Teams, or CIT, it is a 40-hour course
that teaches police how to detect signs of mental illness in a
person's behavior and how to calm frenzied people with words
instead of force.
</P>
<P>
   The program was developed in Memphis a decade ago by police and
mental health professionals. Since then, it has been credited with
reducing violent encounters and helping more mentally ill people
find treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Other states have noticed its success. Washington, Illinois and
New Mexico are among the states that have adopted the program.
</P>
<P>
   The Crisis Intervention Teams program is coming to the area
because of a Lee's Summit police officer, Nikk Thompson, who
learned of the program over the Internet after another frustrating
encounter with a mentally ill homeless person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the police) are the initial responders to people with
mental illness and, frankly, I don't think we've been doing our
jobs,'' said Thompson, who once had to shoot a suicidal Vietnam
veteran who pointed a weapon at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen so many homeless guys who we'd pick up and then they
just end up right back on the street again. Police get frustrated
answering these types of calls, calls that can be very dangerous.
But when you think about what the families of these people have to
deal with for a lifetime, that really humbles you....This program
is about helping people because it's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson wrote a proposal to his department's chief, Ken Conlee,
and was soon on his way to Memphis. Now, Thompson and another
officer, Don Crippes, are certified and are ] working to get the
program into area police academies.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, two officers from Memphis will explain the program
to area police departments. By January, there will be at least nine
more Crisis Intervention Teams-trained officers in the Lee's Summit
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Two Kansas City officers will be trained by January, said Capt.
Jan Zimmerman, commander of the advanced training unit.
</P>
<P>
   Although mental health professionals conduct seminars for police
officers, ``this program is truly a community policing initiative
that offers great benefits to everyone,'' Zimmerman said. ``Mental
illnesses come into so many contacts with the police, from criminal
behavior to vagrancy. Now these officers will be trained to
recognize those symptoms and know which agencies are available to
help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Area mental health advocates are elated that the program is
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried for five years to bring CIT in,'' said Guyla
Stidmon, executive director of the Alliance for the Mentally Ill of
Greater Kansas City. ``Many times the police are the persons who
have the first encounters because the illness has often gone
undiagnosed. Sometimes the symptoms behind the illnesses make it
impossible to avoid the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happens, if the police are not trained properly to
respond to these calls, calls often from families, well, that's
when tragedies occur....But CIT is just the first step to help the
mentally ill. The creation of a mental health court is needed, too,
to prevent gaps in service. It's not an either-or solution. We need
them both, and we need them quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Katheryn Shields, Jackson County executive, talked about mental
health courts in her February State of the County address. Florida
and Washington have mental health courts.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is based loosely on the same concept as a drug court,
where offenders are offered a choice between treatment or jail
time. In the mental health court, people who have committed minor
crimes would be steered into treatment and medication programs
instead of jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the early stages of organizing a task force to
look at how we could do this, but I hope to have it up and running
by this time next year,'' Shields said.
</P>
<P>
   She has asked Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird to be a
co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had such good success with drug court; I immediately
thought this sounded like a good one, too,'' he said. ``The
inability of the system to deal with the mentally ill has created a
grave problem for jails across the nation, not just here. A great
shortcoming is that we have no system in place to help the mentally
ill. We offer no help, no treatment. It's a gigantic hole in the
system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
