r a BC-CHINA-KAN &LR;      05-27 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE VENTURE IN KANSAS SHOWS HOW TRADE MAY BE ENHANCED BY
REMOVAL OF BARRIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Chang Jiping kneels in a dry Kansas field south
of Lawrence. A breeze wafts his flannel shirt in the midmorning
heat. With a small knife and tape, the 40-year-old Chang grafts
branches of Chinese pear dates onto the roots of wild dates planted
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   While titans of American business thumped their chests this week
after the House of Representatives approved a bill to treat China
no different from other trading partners, Chang simply nodded his
head in approval.
</P>
<P>
   American business groups saw the vote as a turning point that
could lead to billions of dollars in exports to China, which agreed
to lower tariffs on imports. American agriculture in particular is
expected to benefit from greater sales of grains, pork and beef.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, mostly labor unions and environmental groups, predict
the main export of big business will be production jobs from the
United States to China, where factory workers make about 15 cents
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Average Americans may be confused about how it will affect them.
</P>
<P>
   But the budding venture of Chang Jiping suggests the success or
failure of increased trade between the world's largest economy and
the world's most populated country will result from factors far
more intricate than the feuding factions have expressed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, his plan to grow pear dates in Kansas turns both
arguments in on themselves. It brings Chinese capital to the United
States. It has the possibility of teaching American agribusiness
about a food crop the Chinese have been cultivating for 5,000
years. If the business grows, it would create jobs and wealth for
Americans. And it would provide American consumers greater choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to work on something that would be good for the two
sides, to develop trade and culture between both sides,'' Chang
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese love pear dates because they are ``sweet and crisp
and juicy,'' Chang said. They can be eaten green, ripe or dried.
</P>
<P>
   Chang and the Chinese partners in his company, Pioneer
Agriculture Technology and Trade, have grand expectations for pear
dates. Kansas growing conditions are much like his native Shanxi
Province. They see an immediate market in the growing Asian
population in North America, and they believe when Americans try
them, they will appreciate the unique fruit.
</P>
<P>
   If things go well, he expects to turn an initial investment of
about $200,000 into an industry that will result in millions of
dollars in sales for his Chinese partners and for Kansas fruit
farmers to whom he is trying to introduce the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people who have tasted date think they are wonderful,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the fruit did not strike the fancy of Frank Morrison, a
recently retired Kansas fruit horticulturist, he said there is no
doubt that it can be grown in Kansas. ``I thought it was a bit
dry,'' said Morrison, who has helped Chang with the project.
</P>
<P>
   Until test marketing validates it, Morrison is not encouraged by
the crop's prospects. But Mark Keim of Keim's Produce in Lawrence
believes pear dates will be enthusiastically received.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we will be able to sell more than he can grow,'' said
Keim, who tried the dates during a visit to Chang's orchard.
``People can't get enough of things that are unique.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Kansas Professor Clyde Stoltenberg has watched
Chang's plan unfold. Stoltenberg, co-director for the Center for
International Business at Kansas University, thinks a small venture
like Chang's can do much to develop understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just involves people getting to know people on a one-to-one
basis,'' said Stoltenberg. ``It is quite consistent with the idea
that most business growth in this country is coming from
medium-sized business, not the big ones.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees Chang's patience and persistence mimicking how most
trade between the two countries will develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not be an overnight phenomenon,'' Stoltenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Chang's story began in 1992, when as a midlevel manager in the
Shanxi Power Co., he was sent to KU for training in American
management techniques. A year later, the company sponsored Chang
while he earned a master's degree in economics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Chang returned to China. He remained in touch with
contacts at the university and harbored a plan to start a business
that would unite his U.S. experience with his Chinese heritage.
While attending a conference in Lawrence in 1997, he received
encouragement from state development officials.
</P>
<P>
   He was pondering what that business should be when an associate
brought a wooden box of pear dates to his office. Biting into one,
he had a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   He knew the climates of Kansas and the Shanxi province were
similar. Kansas had lots of land and growing the dates there meant
they would be fresh for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Chang felt so certain of his destiny that when he came to the
United States in early 1998 to lay the groundwork for the project,
he brought an agriculture expert and a suitcase full of fig seeds.
He knew U.S. Customs would not let the seeds through unchallenged,
but he also knew the plan would lose a year if he missed the 1998
planting season. With help from Morrison and other contacts in
Kansas, he persuaded Customs officials to release the seeds within
a week.
</P>
<P>
   Chang planted seeds on land near Lawrence. He also managed to
get a fruit grower near Garden City, Kan., and one near Sabetha, to
plant seeds as a further test of the product. Last spring, grafts
were made, and by last fall some of the trees bore fruit.
</P>
<P>
   It will take about five years for the shrublike trees to fully
mature. When they do, Chang said they can produce 6,000 pounds per
acre. He hopes to sell the fruit for about $2 a pound for a gross
yield of $360,000 per acre.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he also is growing Chinese vegetables that he sells
to restaurants, at a farmer's market and to the local grocery to
generate income.
</P>
<P>
   Without elaboration, Chang said he believes China's admittance
into the World Trade Organization, which this week's House vote
helps achieve, will be good for both the U.S. and China. He thinks
it will open up his country to some new ideas and it will be good
for his family and friends in China as it exposes China to new
ideas. It should help Pioneer Agriculture Technology and Trade's
pear date business and it should make it easier for other plans to
export U.S. products to China.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, at the request of some Chinese vegetable growers,
Chang returned with some American fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They liked Miracle-Gro very much,'' Chang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
