r s BC-BBN-HERSHISER-LADN     05-27 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSHISER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER SENT TO SINGLE-A
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Orel Hershiser is back starting. He's set to do so
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the San Bernardino Stampede against Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   The manner in which the Los Angeles Dodgers have juggled their
roster reached a new level of creativity Friday as veteran
right-hander and fan favorite Orel Hershiser was optioned to the
organization's Single-A affiliate in the California League.
</P>
<P>
   The move was made to make room for right-handed reliever Mike
Fetters, who was activated from the disabled list. And it was
Hershiser who proposed it to the front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very used to being useful and I'm very used to
contributing and being an integral part,'' said Hershiser, who's
1-2 with a 10.70 ERA and hasn't pitched since May 9. ``As you sit
and evaluate the ballclub and everybody's role, I could see as a
team guy, my spot was being wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, 41, isn't going to the minors to fade into oblivion
and resurface as a member of the Dodgers front office. He's moving
down to start, get in shape and be ready for what L.A. hopes will
be a playoff push the final few months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball rules stipulate an optioned player must remain in the
minors for at least 10 days unless there's an injury. Originally,
the Dodgers agreement with Hershiser stated he would remain in the
minors for no more than 21 days. However, that stipulation was
removed after further consultation, a source said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Hershiser isn't expected to spend too much time with
the Stampede. He's hoping to make three or four starts and then
return when the roster crunch works itself out.
</P>
<P>
   As a player with five years or more of major-league service,
Hershiser had to agree to the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just to get in shape and be ready to pitch,'' Hershiser
said. ``The last 30 days I have 4 innings. That's less work than
you would get in spring training. You need innings. You need
competitive innings to be effective. Ability and health are not a
question. I just want to get myself in shape and go do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding enough innings to keep Hershiser sharp has been
impossible. He's struggled adapting to his role since being shifted
from starter to reliever after an April 19 start in which he hit
four Houston batters in 1 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said it's been tough on him
mentally trying to figure out how best to utilize Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   He tried the bullpen, but that didn't work. In four relief
outings, Hershiser's 0-1 with a 15.18 ERA. His last appearance
lasted a third of an inning and ended when Arizona's Damian Miller
hit a 12th-inning grand slam to cap a five-run rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a situation where he thought it would be best for the
team if he went out and got some work in,'' Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone said. ``Our starters here have been pretty good and
our bullpen has been pretty good, and he wasn't getting his work
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser signed as a free agent with the Dodgers during the
winter. He's being paid $2 million this season, and the club holds
an option for 2001. At the time of his signing, he was regarded as
an insurance policy for the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   And with Carlos Perez coming off a season in which he was 2-10
with a 7.43 ERA, it was thought the Dodgers would cash in that
policy quickly. But Perez, who is 4-2 with a 5.74 ERA, has exceeded
expectations and earned his keep in the rotation - at least for
now.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement was announced between Perez and the Dodgers earlier
this month that pushed the deadline of Perez's five-year right to
decline a demotion to May 31. It's likely that agreement will be
extended in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers also remain committed to developing young
right-hander Eric Gagne, who's 0-3 with a 4.33 ERA in seven games
(six starts). All of which leaves Hershiser still in search of a
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Hershiser) was put in the starting rotation right now,
he'd probably figure out a way to get some people out,'' Johnson
said. ``It's not a question of proving anything to anyone. I can
watch a guy on the side, so can (pitching coach) Claude Osteen, and
you can tell he still has plenty of weapons left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
