<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PENSION FUND ATTORNEY HAD QUALMS ABOUT LOAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JERRY KAMMER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - A one-time union pension funds attorney testified
Friday, May 26, that the unions considered backing out of a $10
million loan for Fife Symngton but gave it to the former Arizona
governor anyway because Symington's financial statement showed he
was flush.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Coppersmith, a private attorney and former Arizona
congressman, told the U.S. Bankruptcy Court that he was asked by
pension fund administrator Donald Eaton to see ``if there was any
way out'' of the 1990 loan, which financed Symington's Mercado
office and retail project in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Symington was a real estate developer at the time, and was
running his first campaign for governor. He filed for personal
bankruptcy in 1995, during his second term in office.
</P>
<P>
   The pension funds are suing Symington, claiming that he used a
bogus financial statement to get the $10 million loan. They are
asking Judge George Nielsen to keep Symington on the hook for the
loan, which Symington personally guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Coppersmith's testimony backed earlier testimony from a pension
fund administrator who said the funds were nervous about making the
loan for the Mercado. The administrator said the funds feared they
had committed too many real estate loans to the Phoenix market,
which slid into a severe recession in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The partnerships Symington directed lost the Mercado and about a
dozen other properties, including the Camelback Esplanade in
Phoenix, now one of the most successful commercial properties in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying about Eaton's nervousness over the fledgling Mercado,
Coppersmith said, ``This was not a loan he was eager to make.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coppersmith said the pension funds concluded that they were
legally and ethically committed to make the loan, after receiving a
financial statement from Symington that reported he was financially
strong despite the increasing shakiness of the real estate market.
</P>
<P>
   That financial statement, in which Symington reported a net
worth of $12 million, is the centerpiece of the trial, which will
resume July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Symington acknowledges errors in the statement, but insists they
were accidental.
</P>
<P>
   Symington attorney Rob Shull argues that the pension funds were
legally bound to make the loan because of a 1987 commitment for
which Symington paid $110,000. Shull says the pension funds
committed themselves to make the loan unless Symington was
insolvent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Jerry.Kammer(at)Arizona Republic.com or (602)
444-8185. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
