r a BC-LAUSD-SEARCH-LADN     05-27 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUSD-SEARCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SEARCHES FOR NEW SCHOOL SUPERINTENDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHERRY JOE CROSBY AND DAVID R. BAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The secretive search for a new superintendent of
Los Angeles schools has turned to the head of a government agency
that boosts foreign investments and the former chief of a North
Carolina district, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   George Munoz, president and chief executive officer of the
Overseas Private Investment Corp., and John Murphy, former
superintendent of the Charlotte-Mecklenburg Schools could interview
with the board on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither could be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Romer, former governor of Colorado, was interviewed by the
school board on Thursday. And sources said Henry Cisneros, former
U.S. Housing Secretary, is still under consideration despite his
public withdrawal of his name.
</P>
<P>
   The board has conducted its search in private and without any
public input, citing a tight deadline and the fear that disclosing
names could scare away some candidates. Board President Genethia
Hayes has said the district wants to select a superintendent by
June 5, three weeks before interim Superintendent Ramon Cortines'
term expires June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz oversees OPIC, a 200-employee government agency that
finances and insures long-term U.S. investments in developing
countries and emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   The businessman attracted attention at an early age. In 1984, he
became president of the Chicago Board of Education at age 33. He
became known as an ardent supporter of bilingual education and
dropout prevention programs. President Clinton, who met Munoz at a
literacy conference in Little Rock, Ark., in 1990, later nominated
him to become the chief financial officer of the U.S. Treasury
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy served as superintendent of the Charlotte-Mecklenburg
Schools from 1991 to 1995. The nation's 23rd-largest school system,
it serves more than 100,000 students in kindergarten through 12th
grade.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the superintendent search described Murphy as a
strong-willed reformer. During his tenure in Charlotte-Mecklenburg,
he replaced 90 of 125 principals. He left the district after
tangling with local school board members and politicians over his
reform policies that required replacing or reassigning poorly
performing employees.
</P>
<P>
   He now oversees educational services for the Arvida Co., a Boca
Raton, Fla.-based developer of master-planned communities.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the board met with another finalist, Romer,
for five hours and asked the veteran politician how he would run
the nation's second-largest school district.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes said board members were impressed by Romer's passion for
education and his knowledge of the city and the 711,000-student
district, which faces a severe shortage of schools and qualified
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were favorably impressed with former Gov. Romer,'' Hayes
said. ``The bottom line is that he did a very good job about
understanding the demographics of the district and the political
complexities in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The board also was struck by Romer's political connections,
Hayes said. As head of the Democratic National Committee, he knows
some of America's most influential power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly doesn't hurt that the man knows the president of
the United States,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   Some district officials also said that Romer's political
connections could help Los Angeles Unified ward off unwelcome
interference from Sacramento, where state legislators are
contemplating appointing a watchdog over the district.
</P>
<P>
   During his interview with the board, Romer initiated discussion
about his perceived weaknesses, such as his age. He is 71.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes described Romer as an energetic and active man who sported
minor cuts on his hands from chopping wood and performing other
chores.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Hayes said she is looking for a candidate who is
capable of running the district in the throes of serious change.
Candidates' age and ethnicity should not be primary considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it turns out our answer is wrapped up in a 71-year-old
white guy from Colorado, so be it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
