<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7404 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROYALS-LAD     05-27 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROYALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DENIED FIRST PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A funny thing happened to the Angels on the
way to their fourth consecutive win and sole possession of first
place in the A.L. West: They got blindsided by a Kansas City Royals
uprising in the sixth inning that resulted in eight runs, turning a
4-1 Angels lead into a 9-4 loss before 22,394 Friday night at
Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The game also featured the first career ejection of Angels
manager Mike Scioscia, who came to the defense of Garret Anderson,
who was ejected moments earlier after a face-to-face argument with
home plate umpire Tony Randazzo.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals set a club record with four home runs in the fateful
sixth inning, two that were allowed by starter Seth Etherton, who
pitched well in his major league debut. He gave up a leadoff homer
to Johnny Damon on his second pitch of the game, but didn't allow
another run until entering the sixth with a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up back-to-back homers to Jermaine Dye and Mark
Quinn, Etherton was removed from the game with a 4-3 lead and a
chance at getting the victory. But the Angels bullpen, which has
been so good lately, was hammered in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Weaver allowed a single and a double before giving up a
three-run homer to Brian Johnson. Weaver then gave up a walk and a
single before Carlos Febles pounded another three-run homer for the
9-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels might have been reeling a bit when Anderson came to
the plate in the eighth inning. After taking a 2-1 pitch for a
called strike -- the ball appeared outside -- Anderson found
himself screaming face-to-face with Randazzo.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't say anything to him, I never say anything to
umpires,'' said Anderson, whose ejection was the first of his major
league career. ''I've never had an umpire initiate something like
that. He tried to provoke something, but I still didn't say
anything until he took his mask off and got in my face.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically he got mad at me for tracking the ball through the
zone. I do that all the time. I want to see if the ball goes over
the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He did say something,'' said crew chief Ed Montague. ''He
leaned out over the plate looking at the pitch. That can be an
attempt to show up the umpire.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I said don't be doing that and he did it again,'' Randazzo
said of Anderson tracking the pitch. ''He said 'What are you going
to do about it?' and I ejected him.''
</P>
<P>
   Randazzo first reached the majors last year in the National
League for the last month of the season. Montague had been in the
National League for 25 years before this season, when the umpires
work in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know what the problem is?'' Montague said. ''(Randazzo)
doesn't know the kid, he doesn't know his body language. You learn
body language. Whenever a kid reacts like that it puts an umpire in
a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said he felt Randazzo was the aggressor and was wrong
in throwing out his center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought Tony was really out of line,'' Scioscia said. ''The
umpire was far too aggressive in that situation. Garret didn't say
anything. He shows up and plays the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Before all the fireworks late in the game, Etherton settled into
a groove in the middle innings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things went pretty well until the sixth,'' said Etherton, who
gave up three runs and seven hits. ''I was able to settle down a
little bit and make pitches when I needed to. My biggest struggle
tonight was my inconsistent delivery. I was flying open a little
bit. It had to do with an adrenaline rush. I've never had that many
people watch me pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd was Etherton's family, which came out from Orange
County for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took a 2-1 lead in the second inning on Anderson's
two- run homer (No. 12). Bengie Molina's two-out, RBI single in the
fourth made it 3-1 and Darin Erstad's solo homer (No. 7) in the
fifth gave the Angels a 4-1 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7405 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROYALS-LAD     05-27 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROYALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DENIED FIRST PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A funny thing happened to the Angels on the
way to their fourth consecutive win and sole possession of first
place in the A.L. West: They got blindsided by a Kansas City Royals
uprising in the sixth inning that resulted in eight runs, turning a
