DiSARCINA'S INJURY MIGHT CLOUD FUTURE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The season-ending shoulder injury to
shortstop Gary DiSarcina has brought to the surface questions
involving his future with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The club holds an option for 2001 at $3.45 million. But whether
it decides to bring him back next season might affect the future of
other core players, like Darin Erstad, Tim Salmon and Troy
Percival.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts of Erstad and Salmon are up after 2001, and
Percival's ends after this season with the club holding an option
for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon and Percival would be eligible for free agency after
2001, Erstad after 2002. The club did make one significant signing,
locking up Garret Anderson through 2004 with a four-year, $20
million deal.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of DiSarcina's future relates to others in
terms of financial commitment and an effort by the club to keep
possibly its most popular player inside the clubhouse. DiSarcina's
teammates will keep an eye on the outcome, but won't guess as to
what might happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can speculate to death in this game,'' said Erstad, one of
DiSarcina's best friends on the team. ``I'll deal with whatever
happens when it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we're a better team with him, but we don't
have that luxury this year,'' Erstad said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to fill the intangibles,'' manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``We'll miss what Gary brings as far as being a
field leader and his confidence out there. ... I don't think it's
fair to expect anyone to have the level of experience or
intangibles DiSarcina has.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Garret Anderson's second-inning homer Friday was
the Angels' 42nd of the month, breaking a club record for May (41
in 1961). ... To make room on the roster for Friday's starter Seth
Etherton, the Angels optioned pitcher Brett Hinchliffe to Triple-A
Edmonton.
</P>
</TEXT>
