<SLUG> BC-ROBO-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULLY AUTOMATED VIDEO STORE OPENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Talk about low overhead. RoboVideo in Encino,
California, is open 24 hours a day -- but owners Les Butler and
Laurent Sebban don't have to worry about finding someone to work
the graveyard shift or paying anyone overtime.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have employees.
</P>
<P>
   Or racks and shelves displaying videocassette boxes.
</P>
<P>
   What they do have is 1,000 first-run movie titles that customers
literally help themselves to. And their sights are set on taking
some business from Blockbuster, the Goliath of the video rental
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Butler and Sebban say theirs is the first fully automated video
store in the country, putting the San Fernando Valley at the
forefront of a concept that may become cutting-edge in the video
rental universe.
</P>
<P>
   Similar stores have operated in Europe for about 10 years so the
kinks have been worked out, notes Sebban, a native of southern
France.
</P>
<P>
   ``This worked very well in Europe so I started thinking it would
be a good idea to bring it to America,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In the store tucked behind Starbucks in Encino, at the southwest
corner of Louise Avenue and Ventura Boulevard, the decor is sparse.
The floor is painted with strips of azure and sky blue. Walls
bedecked with movie posters are also blue, trimmed with yellow and
red. Small TV monitors are positioned flush with the walls near the
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Three video selectors are recessed into the back wall and one is
tucked next to the north wall.
</P>
<P>
   These function as the store's clerks.
</P>
<P>
   The equipment for a store this size costs about $125,000 and
Sebban, a Van Nuys resident, and Butler, who lives in Hollywood,
are the U.S. distributors. They hope about a dozen automated stores
will open in the West Los Angeles and Valley area over the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Their system uses bar code technology and is Windows based.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works:
</P>
<P>
   A customer gets a debit-type card and puts an amount on it, say
$20, that can be used for rentals. Then the card can be inserted
into one of the selector stations and the customer is prompted
through the process, much like at an ATM machine.
</P>
<P>
   Movie titles can be viewed according to categories, such as
action and comedy. Titles also can be viewed alphabetically.
</P>
<P>
   The customer can see a poster from the movie and a description.
</P>
<P>
   Once the selection is made, the customer presses the rent
button, removes the card and inserts it in the dispenser. About 15
to 20 seconds later a door opens and the video slides out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, you've got your video store right in front of
you, at your finger tips. And you don't have to walk up and down
aisles looking at boxes,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   When the card runs out of money, customers can put more on it --
either with a credit card or cash.
</P>
<P>
   Returns are just as easy. Put the card in the dispenser, the
door opens and the video returns to whence it came.
</P>
<P>
   That would involve the ``robo'' part of the store -- a big beige
metal contraption that houses the video titles and the hardware and
software that gets them out of storage and into customers' hands.
</P>
<P>
   RoboVideo also has a free-standing kiosk that could be placed in
a shopping mall and one that could be fitted to the front of a
regular video store, thus turning it into a 24-hour operation. Each
kiosk holds 500 titles.
</P>
<P>
   Butler and Sebban believe convenience will be the key to
RoboVideo's success. The membership card also opens the door after
hours.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Northridge resident Beverly Chang likes about the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   She works nearby and had dropped off one video and rented a DVD
during her lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really convenient. You don't have to deal with (clerks)
and it's really fast. You can just come in, rent what you want and
it's cheaper than Blockbuster,'' she said. ``And I've gotten
everything I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, Butler and Sebban think they also have price on their
side.
</P>
<P>
   For the ``grand opening special,'' rentals are $1.50, $1.75 and
$2 for six, 12 and 24 hours, respectively. In about two months the
prices increase to $1.75, $2.25 and $2.75.
</P>
<P>
   So far Blockbuster is not worried about the automated
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition is always great in the marketplace. We're
certainly going to be focused on our initiatives. We're doing
everything we can to make video rentals as convenient as possible
for our customers,'' said Blockbuster spokesman Randy Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
