<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUHNER, BELL DOUBLE-TEAM DEVIL RAYS WITH BAT, GLOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ David Bell and Jay Buhner both came up
big on the field Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Only Buhner came up big in the box score.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners right fielder slammed his 10th homer, had two
singles, walked twice, scored two runs and drove in four in
Seattle's 11-4 win over Tampa Bay. A .274 hitter at game time,
Buhner pushed his average up to a luscious .292.
</P>
<P>
   Bell went 1-for-6 at the plate, didn't score a run and didn't
drive one in. But if he had no impact on the box score, he had
far-reaching impact on the game. Bell's defense at third base was
good for preventing anywhere between three and five runs.
</P>
<P>
   It's not box-score friendly, perhaps, but it's certainly
pitcher-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll never see a pitcher who doesn't notice the defense
around him,'' starter Aaron Sele said after improving to 5-2 with a
seven-inning stint. ``If you're not watching the game, you maybe
don't notice what David did.''
</P>
<P>
   If you were watching, you couldn't help it.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, converted back to third base after spending most of his
Mariners life last year as a second baseman, started two huge
double plays, shutting down a rally in the first inning and
undercutting another rally before it had a chance to materialize in
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   In between, he made a couple of terrific plays worth only one
out _ but each worth the price of admission. He took a hit away by
cutting in front of shortstop Alex Rodriguez early, and he took
another hit away by spearing a ball down the line late.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, David won the game,'' infield coach Larry Bowa said.
``You wouldn't know it to look at the box score, but you ask the
pitchers _ they know.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell's biggest play of the night came in the eighth inning.
Seattle had given Sele an 8-4 lead, but 111 pitches into the game,
Sele didn't have anything left. Manager Lou Piniella turned to Jose
Mesa, and Mesa was immediately scorched for a double and a walk to
open the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's John Flaherty smoked a ball that had ``base hit''
written where the commissioner's signature should be, but Bell
erased it. He dove to pluck the ball, got to his knees to throw and
started a double play that all but eliminated the Devil Rays as
competitors in this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``David has done it time and again,'' said Rodriguez, who kept
the eighth inning scoreless with a nifty diving stop of a line
drive but was more interested in talking about Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won a couple of games because of the way he plays
defense. Tonight was not new. He took them out of innings a couple
of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell has a .237 batting average that bugs him. But the bugs
don't reside in his glove. He plays defense for keeps to keep his
average from getting him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm not a .230 hitter,'' said Bell, who hit .268 a year
ago. ``I've got to help out any way I can, and if I'm not hitting,
then I can help out by playing defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, on the other hand, has been hitting most of the year. He
had a bases-loaded walk in a six-run Seattle first inning, singled
in the third, singled and drove in a run in the fifth, walked to
set up a run in the seventh and simply massacred a Roberto
Hernandez pitch in the ninth for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners began the season concerned that Buhner, injured
much of the past two seasons and coming off surgery, would not be
an everyday player. He isn't, not quite _ he gets Saturday's game
off, for example _ but he plays more than three quarters of the
time, and he's given terrific value for the time he's been in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   His 10 homers and 36 RBIs, both third-best marks on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay's done a really nice job this year. He really has,''
Piniella said. ``He's hit for a nice average, and he's hit for
power with some RBIs. He's been a good fit for us.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, has Sele, who is back home in Seattle after spending
his prior big-league career in Boston and Texas. He's off to a 5-2
start with a 4.27 ERA, and while he didn't dominate the Devil Rays,
he held them at bay while the Mariners were building up the lead.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the lead-building in the first inning took so long that
Sele had to go run and stretch all over again between leaving the
bullpen before the game and throwing his first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll trade that half-hour delay for six runs any time,'' Sele
said. ``It took me a little while to get it together after that.
But David helped with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Cox's first big-league homer, a two-run shot in the first,
cut into Sele's big lead, but Bell closed out the inning by
starting a double play with Bubba Trammell at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may not see it in the box score, but we don't win this
game without what David Bell did tonight,'' Sele said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0024 </DOCNO>
