<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL HAS MESSAGE: FOLLOW ME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The Most Improved Player in the league? With
apologies to Indiana's Jalen Rose, he was at the Rose Garden on
Friday. Shaquille O'Neal bloomed in front of this city's
disbelieving eyes in the second half of the Lakers' 93-91 win over
the Trail Blazers in Game 3 of the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal scored 18 of his 26 points in the final two quarters and
if his strong finish after a slow start came too late to sway the
NBA voters, well, it was not a moment too soon to impact this
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were staring at a serious abyss at the start of the
third quarter that was some of O'Neal's doing. He didn't have a
rebound or a point in the first 12 minutes and the way the Trail
Blazers were swarming him, he was lucky to get off the one first-
quarter attempt he sort of heaved like a shot put toward the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, the 7-footer had as many personal fouls (two) as
offensive rebounds. He was looking a lot like the frustrated player
that folded last year whenever the calls and the balls didn't go
his way.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, the Lakers trailed 55-45 at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the third quarter, which revealed the depth of
O'Neal's development in this, his eighth year in the league. He
didn't recoil from the pressure, he rose above it. He asserted
himself physically, making 5 of 8 shots. But more importantly, he
stayed strong mentally and his teammates rallied behind his
stoicism to take a 2-1 lead into Sunday's Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Watching O'Neal fight for rebounds and re-direct shots and
create his own space out of nothing in the second half, it was hard
to believe that Rodney Rogers received three votes to O'Neal's two
in the Most Improved Player balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, remember, went from the Clippers to Phoenix, a move akin
to an orphan being adopted by the Huxtables.
</P>
<P>
   We'll grant Rogers the Most Improved Environment. But to go from
a disgruntled, disinterested Clipper to the NBA's sixth man of the
year is not really making strides, it's making amends.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to us O'Neal had a much harder mission, trying to
elevate his game without the benefit of a change of scenery. Of
course, there was the change in Lakers personnel and it seemed
clear from the start new coach Phil Jackson's strategy was to goad
O'Neal into greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the Trail Blazers blanketed O'Neal with Arvydas
Sabonis and Brian Grant and Rasheed Wallace, Jackson surrounded the
7-footer with challenges. He called him out to block more shots,
the better to change the trajectory of a game; he commanded him to
make more foul shots because nothing buoys a team's offense like
getting two points for free.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had O'Neal's ear; that much became clear when the center
swatted 239 shots during the regular season, the most since his
rookie year in Orlando. He had five blocked shots in Game 1 of this
series and did OK at the free-throw line despite the Trail Blazers'
best efforts to embarrass him, making 12 of 25 attempts in the
fourth quarter to key the Lakers' 15-point win.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, O'Neal's improvement at the free-throw line
has been harder to see, sometimes, than the sweat he leaves on the
court. He missed 12 of 17 attempts in Game 2 and that, combined
with his listlessness on the defensive end - as evidenced by his
zero blocked shots - told the story of the Lakers' 29-point blowout
loss that allowed the Trail Blazers to even the series at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   So when O'Neal strode into the Rose Garden, there was some
question as to whether he'd be a thorn in the Trail Blazers' side
or compost for Portland's blossoming boldness.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a luxuriant place for the league's Most Valuable
Player to find himself, having to prove his indomitability anew.
</P>
<P>
   And not just to the Trail Blazers. O'Neal had something to
demonstrate to his teammates, too; namely that when the going got
tough, he would get them going.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, what winners do. They draw their teammates
into their eddy, the better to pull the opponent under. Scottie
Pippen certainly understood that in Game 2, hitting 6 of 10 shots
and playing stifling defense as the Trail Blazers suffocated the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, it was O'Neal's turn. Instead of retreating
turtle-like when the Trail Blazers smothered him, O'Neal came out
in the third quarter like a hare. He set the pace with a defensive
rebound of the Trail Blazers' first miss. He had a layup and a
blocked shot - his first of the game - before the quarter was four
minutes old.
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of O'Neal's 5-for-8 shooting from the field (and
3-for-5 shooting from the foul line), the Lakers took a one-point
lead into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had opened a crack in the Trail Blazers' armor. And his
teammates, as they've been waiting to do, followed his lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 0210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7410 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-WEST-SPI &LR;      05-27 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE GARDEN THRONY HOME AS LAKERS RALLY TO NIP BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ They were once the Jackals who stole one in La
La Land.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Portland Trail Blazers just plain robbed
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That is if you buy into another assessment from coach Phil
Jackson after his Los Angeles Lakers' 93-91 comeback victory in
Game 3 of the Western Conference finals at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Normally Jackson's appraisals are considered psychological mumbo
jumbo, not to be taken seriously. But this time he could not have
been more right.
</P>
<P>
   Portland led for nearly three quarters, only to surrender the
lead and fall behind by eight points in the fourth quarter. The
Blazers stormed back to tie and even had a chance to win at the
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of going into Game 4 Sunday with a chance to send
the series back to Los Angeles ahead by two games, the Blazers fell
behind 1-2 in the best-of-seven affair and blew the home-court
advantage they had taken away.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure? Squarely back on the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just tightens things up,'' said Jackson, who called the
Blazers ``jackals'' for celebrating their Game 2 win in Los
Angeles. ``Now the pressure is on them in Sunday's ballgame to try
and maintain. That spells death door for Portland. This is a series
when you get that kind of momentum, you've got to ride it.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland, which used an energetic first quarter to go ahead by
13 points, knew it blew Game 3 long before the game's final
sequence. Trailing by two with 11 seconds left, Blazers guard Damon
Stoudamire drove the lane and dished out to center Avydas Sabonis.
</P>
<P>
   But when Sabonis avoided a lunging Shaquille O'Neal, he was met
at the basket by Lakers guard Kobe Bryant, who blocked Sabonis'
shot at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, Ron Harper was left alone on the baseline where
he sank a baseline jumper that broke a 91-91 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just lost our rhythm,'' Blazers forward Scottie Pippen
said. ``We just weren't as sharp, defensively and offensively. We
just have to try and forget about this one. ... We still feel good
about ourselves. We let this slip away. Obviously they know it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers will take what amounted to a number of Blazer
gifts. Portland turned the ball over 15 times. The miscues
accounted for 25 Lakers points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turnovers we made were costly,'' Blazers coach Mike
Dunleavy said. ``That was the biggest difference in the game. We
made some bad decisions on our turnovers. We were throwing the ball
into the (crowd). Now we're in a situation where it's our turn to
respond to a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who was held to eight points in the first two quarters,
led the Lakers' surge. He scored 16 points in a third period where
L.A. outscored Portland 27-16 and erased a 55-45 halftime deficit.
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Green's baseline jumper provided the game's first tie,
65-65, with 2:49 left. The Lakers eventually took their first lead
a minute later when Harper sank two free throws for a 69-67
advantage. O'Neal then converted three of four free throws that put
the Lakers ahead 72-71 heading in to the final frame.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' biggest lead was 83-74 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaching staff and the players got on me,'' O'Neal said.
``They said I wasn't working hard enough to get shots. They said
they wanted me to be aggressive and score. It's not to our
advantage for me to shot over two and three guys. I have to get
deep (inside the paint), so that's what I tried to do. Once I got
deep, I just went (to the basket) quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers did not double-team O'Neal as much in the second
half. They could not keep him from catching the ball deep in the
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's based on reads,'' Dunleavy said of when to double O'Neal.
``We did a better job _ I don't know if it was energy or not _ of
getting to him in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers arrived in Portland with just one adjustment
following their 106-77 Game 2 loss on Monday. Instead of using Glen
Rice to guard Pippen, Jackson put a more athletic Bryant on the
versatile forward.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who had success against Pippen in the regular season,
seemed to relish the assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie was just doing a lot of staring,'' said Bryant, who
scored 25 points ``He wasn't doing a lot of talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pippen: ``It's just about going out an playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Pippen's energy level and spirit were high, he scored
just 12 points and shot 5-for-13.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Portland appeared to be headed toward another blowout in
the first half with a Pack-a-Shaq defensive scheme working
smoothly. The Blazers blanketed O'Neal with aggressive double- and
triple-teams from various spots on the floor throughout the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal shackled in the paint, the Lakers' offense settled
for outside shots and Bryant's creativity. Bryant's 14-point first
quarter kept the Lakers within 30-22 after an emotionally-charged,
raucous start.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time since we've been together that we've
had to lead the team together,'' Bryant said. ``We're up for the
challenge. We're not going to let our teammates down.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
