<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7412 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBN-BOS &LR;      05-27 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For New York fans, this act is nothing special  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are 8 million stories in the Naked City and one
belongs to the nitwit who vaulted out of Yankee Stadium's upper
deck in the third inning of Friday night's Yankee-Red Sox joust.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ultimate in Yankee Stadium moments _ last performed
during a Boston-New York series in 1989. Friday night's fan lay
still on the screen behind home plate for several minutes while
Wilson Delgado and Paul O'Neill were retired by Ramon Martinez.
Play was halted for another few moments before the would-be
Wallenda finally crawled to the safety of a luxury box.
</P>
<P>
   That was the highlight of the night for Gotham fans as Ramon
Martinez (7 2/3 strong innings), Rich Garces, and Derek Lowe
slammed the door on the Yanks and put the Red Sox back in first
place with a 4-1 victory over the world champs.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how to break it to you guys, but this series is not
a very big deal in New York. The local papers are full of Knicks,
Devils, Rudy G., and the heinous Wendy's massacre in Flushing, but
there was hardly a word about Sox-Yanks in Apple rags.
</P>
<P>
   Games Saturday and Sunday night are already sold out, but fans
at the Stadium will likely have mini-TVs in their laps to see if
the bowser trio of Latrell Sprewell, Marcus Camby, and Larry
Johnson can make a shot against the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that New York is simply a Knicks town come playoff
time. It's just that Boston's obsession with New York is not wholly
reciprocal. Bill Parcells noticed this when he left the Patriots
for the Jets. That rivalry also plays much bigger in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox and Yanks were tied for first place, sharing the best
record in the American League. It marked the first time they'd met
when tied for first place since 1978 (except for the first week of
the '95 season). Most participants tried to downplay the late-May
meeting, but Yankee manager Joe Torre acknowledged, ``Whether it's
Fenway Park or Yankee Stadium, you can tell who you're playing by
the energy. The adrenaline really flows when you play the Red
Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens drew a big media crowd and shared his thoughts on
pitching against Pedro Martinez Sunday night. The Rocket needs no
reminding that Pedro and the Red Sox humiliated him at Fenway last
October. Meanwhile, Pedro was still taking care of personal matters
in the Dominican Republic and unavailable for pregame comment. (He
was spotted in the dugout later to watch Ramon.) Too bad. We would
have enjoyed introducing him to the inimitable George King, one of
the two men who jobbed him out of the 1999 MVP award by not putting
him anywhere on the 10-man ballot. For the record, King said he'll
be in Boston when the Yanks come to Fenway next month.
</P>
<P>
   Another hot locker belonged to Carl Everett. The Sox center
fielder was in big demand because of comments he reportedly made
about the Yankees early this spring. Everett was originally
property of the Yankees, and they left him unprotected in the
expansion draft. Everett has backed off some of the stronger stuff
about Paul O'Neill being over the hill and Derek Jeter being
overrated, but he still doesn't like the Yankee organization. Sox
publicist Kevin Shea (a.k.a. ``Dean Wormer'') stood guard by
Everett's locker to make sure there were no more inflammatory
quotes. Everett still managed to rip broadcaster Joe Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   The starting lineups were hardly impressive. Boston was without
Nomar Garciaparra and Jose Offerman. The Yankees went without Derek
Jeter and Chuck Knoblauch. Skittish Knoblauch was a late scratch
because of an alleged strain of his left forearm, but one wonders
if management wants him to overcome his Matt Young disease
(incapable of throwing to first) away from the national spotlight
of Sox-Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter played a minor league game in Tampa Friday night and hoped
to fly by private jet to New York to be ready for the Red Sox
Saturday. Nomar is also slated to vault off the disabled list and
into the lineup. However, the series is not big enough for George
Steinbrenner. The Boss is not expected in the Bronx all weekend.
Perhaps he's studying the lottery field for the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   There were a couple of changes at the Stadium. Jimy Williams's
office was cut in half to make space for a coaches' room, and
fences have been erected in front of both dugouts to protect
uniformed personnel from foul shots. Ancient Yankee coach Don
Zimmer was cracked on the coconut during the playoffs last year and
the mesh on the Yankee side is adorned with a sign that reads,
``Don Zimmer Fence Co.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Friday marked the beginning of the
no-beer-in-the-bleachers rule, the first ``Boston sucks'' chants
rained down from the cheap seats at 7:09 p.m., just as David Cone
wound up to throw the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, destined to be on the spot for the rest of the night,
was loudly booed when he stepped to the plate in the first, but he
hit a ``take that'' two-run single to center, then stole second.
Playing with righteous rage, he looked like Roger Clemens pitching
against the Red Sox for the first time in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It was like that for most of the night. It was a lot like last
year when the Sox beat the Yankees eight times in 12 regular-season
meetings. No need revisiting what happened in October of '99.
There'll be time for that . . . in October 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
