<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBN-BOS &LR;      05-27 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 Command performance: Ramon puts on show in Bronx  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Red Sox 4 Yankees 1
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes, especially for a fan base that treats his
little brother as if he were the fifth Beatle, it seems as if Ramon
Martinez is mistaken for a Frank Sinatra Jr., trying to do a
passable impression of a more talented and famous namesake.
</P>
<P>
   But long before Pedro the Younger hit the top of the charts,
Ramon the Elder was composing his own formidable body of work.
Different riffs, more subtle shadings, perhaps, but with the
unmistakable markings of a great artist at work.
</P>
<P>
   And while the klieg lights will be turned on full blast Sunday
night for Pedro Martinez-Rocket Clemens redux, Ramon Friday night
showed the New York Yankees that he still has some high notes left
in him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, displaying a command of the strike zone that would
have made his brother jealous _ 107 pitches, 77 for strikes _
allowed just a run in 7 2/3 innings in a 4-1 win that vaulted the
Sox out of a first-place tie with the Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great performance out there, a Ramon-type
performance,'' said Pedro Martinez, who returned from a two-day,
excused hiatus in his native Dominican Republic to witness his
brother's finest effort this young season. ``It's about time things
started to fall in place for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, the self-proclaimed Yankee hater, delivered a
two-run single in the first to spot Martinez a 2-0 lead, and Mike
Stanley followed two innings later with a two-out, two-run home run
off Yankees starter David Cone. Rich Garces picked up Martinez by
striking out Bernie Williams with a runner on second to end the
eighth, and Derek Lowe rang up his 10th save before a crowd of
54,470 that included one misguided fool who thought he could fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when you've thought you've seen everything,'' Stanley
said of Stephen Laurenzi, the 24-year-old man who climbed on the
railing of the upper deck behind home plate and took a header into
the screen while the Yankees were batting in the third inning.
``Only in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez lasted just 2 1/3 innings in his last start, when he
was beaten, 7-5, by the Tigers Sunday after sitting out 10 days
because of a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of game I can pitch,'' Martinez said of his
performance Friday night in which he did not issue a walk (he hit
one batter) and gave up seven hits, including Clay Bellinger's
third-inning home run for the only Yankee run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel terrible with myself, when I have those games where I
pitch just two innings,'' he said. ``That's not me. I think about
those games. The only thing that makes me feel good is knowing my
arm is in good shape, and it's just a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett, whose disdain for the Bombers is widely known in all
five boroughs, delivered a two-run single in his first at-bat
against the team that drafted him in the first round 10 years ago,
then let him go in the expansion draft two years later. He might
never have had the chance if Cone had turned Brian Daubach's
first-and-third comebacker into an inning-ending double play
instead of turning his attention to Jeff Frye, who was trapped off
third base.
</P>
<P>
   Frye, who had doubled and taken third on John Valentin's bounced
single through the left side, did a dash-dot-dash pattern down the
third base line long enough to let both runners move up into
scoring position. Everett followed with a line single to center,
and it was 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think David would like to have that ball back to the mound
back,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``It's a double-play
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez benefited from the kind of base-running blunder that
was absent from the Yankees' repertoire when these teams last met
during the American League Championship Series in October. Three
successive singles with no outs in the fifth netted the Yankees
nothing, as they wound up with two runners on third.
</P>
<P>
   Boss Steinbrenner was in Tampa, otherwise there might have been
mass firings on the spot _ Bellinger and Chris Turner, the young
catcher who held up at third even though center fielder Everett had
dived for Ricky Ledee's single and had given up on making a play at
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bellinger made the right read and the wrong decision,'' Torre
said. ``Just because you read it as a base hit doesn't mean that
everybody does. On the front end, I don't think Chris was as sure
it was a base hit as (Bellinger) was. Willie held him up at third
because there was nobody out. It was just a bad play, and there's
no excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the last spot of trouble Martinez encountered. He set
down 10 straight until Paul O'Neill's opposite-field, ground-rule
double with two outs in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because he hurt his arm doesn't mean you lose your
head,'' said Torre. ``I thought he pitched a very heady game
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez gave way to Rich Garces, who recently ate at a
Venezuelan restaurant in Watertown, Casa de Pedro, that is not
named after the Sox pitcher but features a dish called salmon Pedro
Martinez. The suspicion is that was too small a piece of fish for
El Guapo, who snacked on toasted Bombers Friday night, striking out
Williams to end the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about last year,'' said Garces, who faced down
the Yankees here with the bases loaded in Game 1 of the ALCS.
``It's unbelievable. You can't hear yourself breathing out there.
But this was the type of situation you've got to keep calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie Williams is one of the best hitters in the major
leagues. But I got ahead of him with a curveball, threw a couple of
fastballs inside, then came back and got him with the curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe gave up a two-out double in the ninth before turning out
the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage, Sox. It's the Dartmouth kid, Brian Rose, Saturday
afternoon, Pedro Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But this one belonged to Ramon. Maybe Garces will go back to
that restaurant in Watertown and find a dish named after the Elder,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon was unbelievable today,'' Garces said. ``He was
incredible. We're happy for him. We need him to pitch like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 0231EDT &QL; 
