<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7414 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LA     05-27 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BACK IN CHARGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Kobe Bryant needed no prompting. Shaquille
O'Neal needed only a nudge or two. And Ron Harper, all he needed
was a few feet of space.
</P>
<P>
   And now everything the Los Angeles Lakers need is back within
their sights. A series that seemed perilously close to slipping
through their fingers is once more situated firmly back in their
palms, held in a tight clench.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's brilliant shooting got the Lakers started Friday night,
O'Neal's power pushed them to the finish and Harper's final jumper
made it all stand up as the Lakers tipped the Portland Trail
Blazers 93-91 before 20,135 at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Lakers a 2-1 lead in the best-of-seven
Western Conference finals and restored, for now, their home-court
advantage. Game 4 is Sunday at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out tonight,'' Harper said, ``with a frame of mind to
get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   They worked the job in shifts. Bryant started with a 14-point
first quarter on his way to a 25-point night. O'Neal carried the
third by scoring 13 of his game-high 26 points. Then Harper closed
the store.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a pass from Bryant, Harper swished a 19-foot baseline
jumper to break a 91-91 tie with 29.9 seconds left. It was a fine
bit of redemption for the veteran guard, who has been the Blazers'
favorite man to leave while double-teaming O'Neal and Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's rewarding for Ron,'' coach Phil Jackson said,
``especially when they've been leaving him in this series with open
shots, to hit a shot that counted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers got two chances to tie the game, but Rasheed Wallace
lost the ball on the first possession, and the second ended with
Bryant swooping in to block Arvydas Sabonis on his drive to the
hoop as the clock ran down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just closed the lane,'' Bryant said. ``Shaq did a great job
running Sabonis off the 3-(point) line. ... I wanted to close
Sabonis down because he's an excellent passer, but he penetrated,
went up for his shot and I was fortunate enough to get a hand on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Good fortune seemed to accompany Bryant all night. He was
assigned to guard Scottie Pippen and silenced him for most of the
game, holding him to 12 points. And after two subdued offensive
performances, Bryant came out firing Friday, hitting fadeaways and
off-balance jumpers with ease. He was 8 for 13 by halftime, and his
final point total equaled his production in Games 1 and 2 combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were kind of unsure as a ballclub the type of game
it was gonna be, what kind of pace it was gonna be played at,''
Bryant said, ``and I wanted to come out and try to set the tone,
send a message not only to us as a ballclub that we can win here,
but to the Portland team as well that the team you're facing
tonight isn't the same as you faced last game.''
</P>
<P>
   It took O'Neal longer to get the message. He struggled to work
through the double-teams, went scoreless in the first quarter and
by halftime had been outscored, 9-8, by Arvydas Sabonis. Portland
shot 56.1 percent in the half, built a 55-45 lead, and as Jackson
noted, ``we were feeling pretty fortunate just to be down by 10
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Then O'Neal made his move, finding space to work, and sometimes
creating it himself. He made 5 of 8 shots in the third as the
Lakers outscored the Blazers 27-16, grabbed their first lead of the
game late in the quarter and took a 72-71 advantage into the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went cold, and they got hot at the same time. And that's a
bad combination,'' said Portland's Steve Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaching staff and the players kind of got on me (at
halftime),'' O'Neal said. ``They said I wasn't working hard enough
for the shot. In the first half, I felt they (defenders) were
coming really, really fast and I find it's not to our advantage for
me to take a lot of shots over two or three people. So I was just
trying to pass it out. But they said they wanted me to be more
aggressive and score. So I was looking to score a little bit
more.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the Lakers are looking to sweep this two-game set in the
Rose City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just tightens things up,'' Jackson said. ``We found a way
to get back in this series by reclaiming home-court advantage, and
now the pressure's on them in Sunday's ballgame to try and
maintain, because we can put another notch in our belt in this next
game on Sunday - that spells really death's door for Portland. And
they know it. And this is a series that if we can get that kind of
momentum, we gotta ride it. And we're gonna have to ride it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
