<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7415 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN     05-27 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS MISS OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ That was Scottie Pippen slamming his fists onto
an overmatched press table. That was Scottie Pippen ripping down a
stack of towels outside the Portland Trail Blazers' dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers, most of them anyway, tried their best to give
credit to the Los Angeles Lakers for their 93-91 comeback victory
Friday night in Game 3 of the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was no disguising the frustration of their emotional
loss immediately after Arvydas Sabonis' final jump shot in the lane
was blocked by Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers had played almost brilliantly in the early going to
build a quick 14-point lead. They were in control, hitting their
outside shots, dominating the boards, almost looking like they were
going to roll to an easy victory before a fired-up crowd.
</P>
<P>
   All for it to slip away. For the home-court advantage they had
stolen in Los Angeles to be quickly given back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to forget about this one,'' Pippen said. ``We let
this one slip away. Obviously, they know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had his own strange game of ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this series, Lakers coach Phil Jackson had
Kobe Bryant guard Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   This would be the same Pippen whom Jackson has been trying to
play mind games with since before the season even began. The player
Jackson said would have to lead the Blazers, because no one else
would.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen responded aggressively in Game 2 when he constantly drove
to the basket, scoring 21 points and grabbing 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But matched against Bryant, Pippen seldom drove the lane and
often settled for being a playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   At the half, it seemed to be working well enough. Pippen had hit
only 2 of 6 field goals but had a game-high five assists and five
rebounds. And the Blazers had a 10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   But still hounded by Bryant, Pippen missed on all three
field-goal attempts in the third quarter and went without an assist
as the Lakers charged back to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   With 4:03 in the fourth quarter and the Lakers up by six, Bryant
picked up his fifth foul and Pippen again became a factor. He hit a
3-pointer and twice drove the lane for short jumpers over Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   But he also had a shot blocked by Shaquille O'Neal and threw
away a pass under the basket. Pippen finished with 12 points (5 of
13), nine rebounds and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   He had fallen to the ground when Glen Rice lost the ball in the
last seconds, giving the Blazers their fateful final chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Robert) Horry was stepping on me to keep me down,''
Pippen said. ``By the time I got up, Damon (Stoudamire) was
penetrating and then he kicked it out to Arvydas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officials are not going to call that (foul). It's a better
percentage to shoot the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers were left to heal their emotional wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have won that game,'' said Blazers forward Brian
Grant. ``It shouldn't have come down to that (shot).
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we gave this game away. We had the opportunities
to put it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the game was riddled with chances for the Blazers to run
away with the game, but they never could shake the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just turned the ball over too much in the second half,''
said Portland forward Detlef Schrempf. ``Then we had breakdowns on
defense and let them have some easy baskets. You can't do that with
a team like the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a veteran team. We've lost playoff games before. We know
we have to win one down there again now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
