<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SHOO THE BLUES AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The doldrums ended about the same time the ball
hit by Todd Hundley fell into the right-field stands in the bottom
of the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Suspensions, fines, the frustration of being severely penalized
by baseball and the chaos that encompassed it lingered heavily in
the Dodger Stadium air from the moment batting practice commenced
but lifted instantly when Hundley's shot left the yard.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers reacted to the blast by scoring five
times in the sixth inning and beat the Philadelphia Phillies 11-4
Friday in the opener of a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody was kind of feeling the same way,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said. ``We came out and we were lackluster.
It was big to put this thing behind us and deal with what we have
to deal with. It's kind of hard to stop thinking about it, but (we
had to) put it behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, who had four RBI, added his second two-run homer of the
game in the seventh inning and Kevin Brown (4-1) pitched seven
innings and drove in his first two runs as the Dodgers ended a
two-game losing streak by beating the National League's worst team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of concerned early in the game if we were going to
get it going,'' said Hundley, who has 13 homers and 32 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shook the cobwebs off and got back to playing good
baseball. In batting practice, everyone was so dead. ... With all
the things going on, we have to keep our minds and concentrate on
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball handed down suspensions and fines to 16
players and three coaches on Wednesday, and the Dodgers were
feeling the hangover effects. It didn't help when Brown allowed
three runs in the third inning, two of which came on Rob Ducey's
homer, as the Phillies took a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Hundley provided the spark with his two-run homer to right,
which brought life to the sleep-walking Dodgers. Brown retired the
next six batters, and even though a squeeze bunt by Tom Prince gave
the Phillies a 4-3 lead in the sixth, the tenor had already
shifted. And a Philadelphia error led to five unearned runs in the
bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros tied it 4-4 with a double off the top of the wall
and Adrian Beltre had an RBI single to give the Dodgers the lead.
Kevin Elster, who later homered, was intentionally walked to load
the bases for Brown, and he picked up his second hit in 18 at-bats
to put the Dodgers ahead 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do your job well enough on the mound, (hitting) is not
an issue,'' Brown said. ``(But) it's great. That's part of the fun
of being in the National League. It's a lot more fun when you do
get a hit instead of making an out.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth ended the inning with an RBI single. The
Dodgers secured the win in the seventh when Hundley homered again
in the seventh. It marked the 11th time Hundley's homered twice in
a game, and it was the sixth time a Dodger has done it this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To start the game, I was completely clueless,'' Hundley said.
``I went to (hitting coach) Rick Down and asked for help to
straighten things out. I got back off the plate and tried to hit
the ball hard instead of trying to hit it nine miles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
