<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-NCAA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S CURRIER SURVIVES WALK ON THE WILD SIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FULLERTON, Calif. _ Rik Currier waited for his coach and
wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was gone,'' the USC junior said when Mike
Gillespie visited the struggling pitcher in the second inning of
Friday's NCAA baseball regional opener against Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   But Currier rebounded from his shaky beginning to throw eight
strong innings to lead the top-seeded Trojans past the Hokies 8-3
at Cal State Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   USC (39-18) moves into today's 4:30 p.m. winner's bracket game
against Loyola Marymount.
</P>
<P>
   Currier (13-3) took the mound as the Trojans' most effective
starter. He was the Pacific-10 Conference co-pitcher of the year
and was named a second-team All-American by Collegiate Baseball on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first two innings, fourth-seeded Virginia Tech
(34-24-2) seemed unimpressed with Currier's credentials. Six of the
first nine Hokies batters reached base to plate two first-inning
runs and create another jam for Currier in the second. Virginia
Tech had runners on first and second with no outs.
</P>
<P>
   With Ronald Flores hurrying to get warm in the bullpen,
Gillespie visited Currier, who had issued three walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When coach Gillespie comes out you know he has something to
tell you or you're gone,'' Currier said.
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie considered pulling his ace with the idea that he could
return later in the regional if needed. He encouraged him to
``pitch well,'' knowing that Currier had lasted at least six
innings in each of his previous eight starts.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever strategy Gillespie was considering was made moot by
Currier, who promptly picked off the runner on second, Nick
Perlozzo.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Foutz then struck out and Addison Bowman fouled out,
deflating the Hokies and raising Currier's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we score a run ... then we have a good chance of getting
(Currier) out of the game,'' Foutz said. ``We planned on trying to
get on them as early as possible. We wanted to let them know we
were here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans needed no more incentive. Currier did serve up a
solo homer to Kevin Bice in the sixth, but the Dana Point resident
allowed just four baserunners after his chat with Gillespie. He
finished with seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, USC pounded out four doubles, three by Justin Gemoll,
and two home runs in a 15-hit attack.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Concepcion's two-run homer tied the game at 2-2 in the
bottom of the second, and Seth Davidson increased the lead to 6-2
with a two-run shot to dead center off Jason Bush (9-6) in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was keeping the faith. I really felt that if we could put a
stop to (Virginia Tech), we would not be held down,'' Gillespie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie hinted that Currier, despite throwing 124 pitches,
could comeback on Sunday if the Trojans advance to the championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Currier) was definitely on the ropes. ... I love a pitcher
that can get out of trouble and pitch well like that,'' said Hokies
coach Chuck Hartman, whose team beat USC in a similar underdog
situation in a 1997 regional opener in Tuscaloosa, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played great baseball after that and put us away.''
</P>
<P>
   Loyola Marymount 6, Cal State Fullerton 4: Lions left-hander
Billy Traber had moments of distress, but the West Coast Conference
pitcher of the year rarely wilted under the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Traber (10-4) worked his way out of several jams, including a
near disastrous one in the ninth, to lead the Lions (40-17).
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Fullerton (36-20) loaded the bases with no outs, but
Traber retired Chris Beck on a fly out, Jake Epstein on a sacrifice
fly and Aaron Rifkin on a ground out to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Traber had an early five-run cushion but watched the Titans cut
the lead to 5-2 and load the bases with no outs in the fifth. But
Traber, a likely high pick in the upcoming draft, struck out Steve
Woodward, Beck and Epstein in succession to avoid any damage.
</P>
<P>
   Traber struck out 13 and allowed nine hits for his fourth
complete game.
</P>
<P>
   The third-seeded Lions also faced a conference pitcher of the
year in Titans right-hander Adam Johnson from the Big West.
However, LMU scored five runs off Johnson (7-4) in the first three
innings, highlighted by David Maffei's two-run home run in the
first.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Titans meet Virginia Tech in a 1:30
elimination game this afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
