<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ABOUT LAST NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore is desperate to get chicks.
</P>
<P>
   Married chicks. Single chicks. Old chicks. Young chicks.
Anywhere a chick, chick?
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't stop turning off women, he'll never be president.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing seems to help. He got buff. He put on a pair of
provocatively tight jeans. He shook his booty _ and even his Palm
Pilot _ at a big fund-raiser. He's surrounded by female advisers.
He throws all sorts of policy ideas to women. The guy practically
lactates.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's getting the brush. In the latest New York Times
poll, George W. Bush has a wide lead with men and, amazingly, edges
out Gore with women (who elected Bill Clinton), 44 to 42 percent.
Even feminists are nagging Gore about his lack of oomph.
</P>
<P>
   Gore pollster Harrison Hickman went to Capitol Hill the other
day to tell Democrats there was some good news: The campaign had
conducted a focus group to ask women who would make a better date _
Al Gore or George W. Bush _ and Gore won.
</P>
<P>
   As The Wall Street Journal reported, Hickman said the women in
the focus group found the vice president ``thoughtful, reflective
and interested in what women have to say,'' while the Texas
governor was seen as ``the type who would drive up in a flashy
convertible, honk the horn instead of coming to the door, lean
against his car chewing gum and spend all night talking about
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, someone at the meeting told me, was viewed as ``the nicer
guy, who would be more stable and reliable. Bush was seen as a guy
who would dump you in a heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's supporters were appalled that his campaign
was wasting time and money on focus groups that looked at women's
hormones rather than their brains.
</P>
<P>
   I personally am appalled that the Gore campaign equates going on
a date with picking a president.
</P>
<P>
   Going on a date is really, really hard.
</P>
<P>
   And anyhow, I know someone who went on a blind date with Al Gore
eons ago. ``It was a complete dud,'' my friend recalls. ``He didn't
talk to me. He wasn't a conversationalist, in any sense of the
word.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Gore has probably changed a lot. For one thing, he
has learned to cover his imperfections.
</P>
<P>
   People magazine reported that he is using a pressurized makeup
wand to spray a ``light mist'' of foundation on his face, an
expensive accessory used by Hollywood actresses. After the spray
was applied, the delighted candidate gushed to his makeup artist,
``I have never looked better.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans mocked Alpha male for using a magic wand, but women
might want to take it into account when they're choosing which
candidate to date. It would be nice to have a guy who could share
the secret of how to stop makeup from caking.
</P>
<P>
   I conducted my own focus group with girlfriends who know the
candidates. This is how they weigh the pros and cons of an evening
of Tennessee waltzing or Texas two-stepping.
</P>
<P>
   W. advantages: You could count on Tex-Mex with good guac, and
putt-putt afterward. If the China trade bill comes up in
conversation, Condi's just a phone call away. If you're mugged, an
NRA posse will gallop to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   W. disadvantages: Aches and pains from a manic schedule of
jogging, tennis, fishing and golfing. You could never go to his
place. It would be a toxic-waste dump _ the only thing in the
fridge, Gatorade and a jar of grape jelly. He'd pick you up in a
Bonneville stuffed with old buddies and Bushes. He'd try to prove
gravitas by casually jamming a copy of Lingua Franca into his jeans
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Al advantages: He'll pander to you and pick your favorite
restaurant. He offers primo transportation, bulletproof limos and
Air Force Two. If the date isn't going well, he'll call a
facilitator. He'll amuse you with wild exaggerations about his
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Al disadvantages: He'd talk to your parents too earnestly for
too long. He'd take you to a revival house to see ``The Sorrow and
the Pity.'' He'd bring his global warming charts and talk about his
Inner Ecology. You'd have to be prepared for the date to become a
fund-raiser. (Al would soften the blow by calling it a
``non-finance-related, community outreach event.'') If the date was
going really well, he might shout and growl, the way he does when
he gets excited at labor rallies and black churches. Afterward, he
might force you to do a focus group to analyze how the night went.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7434 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-ARMS-CONTROL-REVIEW-N     05-27 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMS-CONTROL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE LIFE AFTER MUTUALLY ASSURED DESTRUCTION? 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cold War is over. There are no longer two superpowers,
poised to obliterate each other and the world, restrained only by
the Strangelovian doctrine of MAD, or Mutually Assured Destruction.
And yet the world still bristles with 30,000 or so nuclear arms,
many on permanent high alert, while the ranks of nuclear powers
keep growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Cold War, these weapons were considered regrettable
but necessary because of the Communists,'' George Perkovich, an
arms expert at the W. Alton Jones Foundation, a private group in
Charlottesville, Va., said. ``Well, the Communists are gone, we won
the Cold War, but we still have the weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a peculiar state of affairs, and a frightening one, and
for the first time in years, those whose business is arms control
are trying to construct a better way to deal with the Pandora's Box
of the nuclear age.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have decided that traditional arms control is broken,''
said Stephen Hadley, a Pentagon official in the Bush administration
and a campaign adviser to Governor Bush. ``We've been keeping a
large inventory of nuclear weapons that we don't need and that the
military doesn't want.''
</P>
<P>
   Centrist thinkers on both sides of the political aisle are
calling for deep cuts in remaining arsenals, for building
antimissile defenses against rogue states, and for getting serious
about stopping the spread of missile technology and nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Impatience with the status quo can be seen everywhere. President
Clinton is moving toward approving a limited antimissile system,
initially of 100 interceptors in Alaska. Next week in Moscow, he is
to meet with Russian president Vladimir Putin about amending the
1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty and making deep offensive cuts.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said last week that as president he would reduce
America's nuclear arsenal to its ``lowest possible number,''
perhaps unilaterally. ``Our mutual security need no longer depend
on a nuclear balance of terror,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Even the United Nations has bestirred itself. Last weekend, a
conference to review the 1968 Non-Proliferation Treaty ended with
the first-ever statement of ``unequivocal'' commitment from the
United States and other nuclear powers to achieve comprehensive
nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the shift _ besides sheer exasperation with decades of
policy immobility _ lie significant changes in the strategic
environment. Offensive weapons technology has spread far beyond the
old nuclear club, and there has been steady progress in learning
how to shoot down missiles from land, sea and space. These
technological shifts will only gain in speed, and promise to
fundamentally alter the field of play in the years and decades
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The new theoreticians, who have been talking informally in
Washington for at least a year, also point to a depressing tally of
arms control failures. ``The old paradigm has difficulties, many of
them,'' said Jan Lodal, a former Pentagon official in the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Among the troubles he cites are stalled arms control
negotiations between Moscow and Washington, the growing irrelevance
of the nuclear test ban treaty, which was shaken in 1998 by Indian
and Pakistani bomb tests and crippled last year when the Senate
rejected it, and the developing threat of long-range missiles from
North Korea, Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those arguing for new approaches to the nuclear dilemma
aim to deprive the atom of its prestige and power in global
matters, to make it clear that a state can be a player on the world
stage without the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no longer this cataclysmic threat of a major war every
day, so we have to put nuclear weapons into the background of
international affairs,'' said Perkovich. To this end, the nuclear
powers should drastically cut their arsenals and take arms off high
alert, as Bush proposed last week. That would help curb atomic envy
in India, Pakistan and Japan, said Perkovich, author of ``India's
Nuclear Bomb'' (University of California, 1999). Deep cuts, he
added, would make America less of a nuclear hypocrite in world
eyes, bolstering its moral authority in fighting the spread of
missile technology and nuclear arms and aiding the enforcement of
all kinds of international rules and inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Iraq,'' Perkovich said. ``They're wavering on
enforcement. To get that, you need international support.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is happy about the new thinking. Old-school arms
controllers say the new theorists have yet to explain how
antimissile defenses would avoid stimulating new arms races and
strategic insecurity, which could create conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be something new here, because people are searching
for an alternative to doing nothing, or doing the president's
plan,'' said Joseph Cirincione, a senior associate at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace. In his view, however, arms
control is inseparable from the certainty that the first use of
nuclear weapons would mean one's own destruction. ``You can't cut
the Gordian knot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is what makes antimissile arms the most contentious part of
the new calculus. Even if affordable and feasible against
rogue-state threats, missile defenses, paradoxically, are often
seen as endangering the stability that comes with MAD (which is why
the ABM treaty sought to scrap them).
</P>
<P>
   If mutual destruction did not seem assured, the major nuclear
powers would base their war plans on overwhelming any shield with
swarms of warheads, critics argue. So Russia would refuse to cut
its arsenal further and China, which now has 20 or so warheads that
can threaten the United States, might deploy hundreds of new ones,
experts say. And that could spark chain reactions in India,
Pakistan and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deploying a national missile defense will surely crush hopes
for the positive arms control steps,'' said John Isaacs, president
of the Council for a Livable World, a Washington arms control
group.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominously, the rest of the world might view with alarm
a United States protected by antimissile defenses, reasoning that
it could fire a massive first strike at an opponent's offensive
weapons and use antimissile arms to protect itself against any weak
retaliation. Analysts worry that the very existence of this
possibility could, in times of crisis, trigger war.
</P>
<P>
   The new thinkers say such fears can be managed through intense
strategic cooperation not just with allies, but with rivals and
even foes. The keys are avoiding any surprises, relentlessly
emphasizing benign intent and bringing others under the
new-paradigm umbrella by sharing warning systems and possibly even
antimissile arms. They point to East-West talks on defense sharing
in the closing days of the Cold War, and say new initiatives might
be much broader, involving more nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question,'' said Michael Krepon, president of the
Henry L. Stimson Center, a policy group in Washington at the center
of the new strategic thinking, ``is whether the impulse to build
defenses destroys the prospect for a cooperative transition.'' If
so, he said, ``you're stuck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5676 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-ARMS-CONTROL-REVIEW-N     05-27 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMS-CONTROL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE LIFE AFTER MUTUALLY ASSURED DESTRUCTION? 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cold War is over. There are no longer two superpowers,
poised to obliterate each other and the world, restrained only by
the Strangelovian doctrine of MAD, or Mutually Assured Destruction.
And yet the world still bristles with 30,000 or so nuclear arms,
many on permanent high alert, while the ranks of nuclear powers
keep growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Cold War, these weapons were considered regrettable
but necessary because of the Communists,'' George Perkovich, an
arms expert at the W. Alton Jones Foundation, a private group in
Charlottesville, Va., said. ``Well, the Communists are gone, we won
the Cold War, but we still have the weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a peculiar state of affairs, and a frightening one, and
for the first time in years, those whose business is arms control
are trying to construct a better way to deal with the Pandora's Box
of the nuclear age.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have decided that traditional arms control is broken,''
said Stephen Hadley, a Pentagon official in the Bush administration
and a campaign adviser to Governor Bush. ``We've been keeping a
large inventory of nuclear weapons that we don't need and that the
military doesn't want.''
</P>
<P>
   Centrist thinkers on both sides of the political aisle are
calling for deep cuts in remaining arsenals, for building
antimissile defenses against rogue states, and for getting serious
about stopping the spread of missile technology and nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Impatience with the status quo can be seen everywhere. President
Clinton is moving toward approving a limited antimissile system,
initially of 100 interceptors in Alaska. Next week in Moscow, he is
to meet with Russian president Vladimir Putin about amending the
1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty and making deep offensive cuts.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said last week that as president he would reduce
America's nuclear arsenal to its ``lowest possible number,''
perhaps unilaterally. ``Our mutual security need no longer depend
on a nuclear balance of terror,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Even the United Nations has bestirred itself. Last weekend, a
conference to review the 1968 Non-Proliferation Treaty ended with
the first-ever statement of ``unequivocal'' commitment from the
United States and other nuclear powers to achieve comprehensive
nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the shift _ besides sheer exasperation with decades of
policy immobility _ lie significant changes in the strategic
environment. Offensive weapons technology has spread far beyond the
old nuclear club, and there has been steady progress in learning
how to shoot down missiles from land, sea and space. These
technological shifts will only gain in speed, and promise to
fundamentally alter the field of play in the years and decades
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The new theoreticians, who have been talking informally in
Washington for at least a year, also point to a depressing tally of
arms control failures. ``The old paradigm has difficulties, many of
them,'' said Jan Lodal, a former Pentagon official in the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Among the troubles he cites are stalled arms control
negotiations between Moscow and Washington, the growing irrelevance
of the nuclear test ban treaty, which was shaken in 1998 by Indian
and Pakistani bomb tests and crippled last year when the Senate
rejected it, and the developing threat of long-range missiles from
North Korea, Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those arguing for new approaches to the nuclear dilemma
aim to deprive the atom of its prestige and power in global
matters, to make it clear that a state can be a player on the world
stage without the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no longer this cataclysmic threat of a major war every
day, so we have to put nuclear weapons into the background of
international affairs,'' said Perkovich. To this end, the nuclear
powers should drastically cut their arsenals and take arms off high
alert, as Bush proposed last week. That would help curb atomic envy
in India, Pakistan and Japan, said Perkovich, author of ``India's
Nuclear Bomb'' (University of California, 1999). Deep cuts, he
added, would make America less of a nuclear hypocrite in world
eyes, bolstering its moral authority in fighting the spread of
missile technology and nuclear arms and aiding the enforcement of
all kinds of international rules and inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Iraq,'' Perkovich said. ``They're wavering on
enforcement. To get that, you need international support.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is happy about the new thinking. Old-school arms
controllers say the new theorists have yet to explain how
antimissile defenses would avoid stimulating new arms races and
strategic insecurity, which could create conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be something new here, because people are searching
for an alternative to doing nothing, or doing the president's
plan,'' said Joseph Cirincione, a senior associate at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace. In his view, however, arms
control is inseparable from the certainty that the first use of
nuclear weapons would mean one's own destruction. ``You can't cut
the Gordian knot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That is what makes antimissile arms the most contentious part of
the new calculus. Even if affordable and feasible against
rogue-state threats, missile defenses, paradoxically, are often
seen as endangering the stability that comes with MAD (which is why
the ABM treaty sought to scrap them).
</P>
<P>
   If mutual destruction did not seem assured, the major nuclear
powers would base their war plans on overwhelming any shield with
swarms of warheads, critics argue. So Russia would refuse to cut
its arsenal further and China, which now has 20 or so warheads that
can threaten the United States, might deploy hundreds of new ones,
experts say. And that could spark chain reactions in India,
Pakistan and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deploying a national missile defense will surely crush hopes
for the positive arms control steps,'' said John Isaacs, president
of theCouncil for a Livable World, a Washington arms control
group.
</P>
<P>
   Even more ominously, the rest of the world might view with alarm
a United States protected by antimissile defenses, reasoning that
it could fire a massive first strike at an opponent's offensive
weapons and use antimissile arms to protect itself against any weak
retaliation. Analysts worry that the very existence of this
possibility could, in times of crisis, trigger war.
</P>
<P>
   The new thinkers say such fears can be managed through intense
strategic cooperation not just with allies, but with rivals and
even foes. The keys are avoiding any surprises, relentlessly
emphasizing benign intent and bringing others under the
new-paradigm umbrella by sharing warning systems and possibly even
antimissile arms. They point to East-West talks on defense sharing
in the closing days of the Cold War, and say new initiatives might
be much broader, involving more nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key question,'' said Michael Krepon, president of the
Henry L. Stimson Center, a policy group in Washington at the center
of the new strategic thinking, ``is whether the impulse to build
defenses destroys the prospect for a cooperative transition.'' If
so, he said, ``you're stuck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
