<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7435 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SPREWELL-REDEEM-REVIE     05-27 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPREWELL-REDEEM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM PARIAH TO POSTER BOY  
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By ALAN SCHWARZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The verdicts came in a downpour of piety only hours after
Latrell Sprewell's infamous choking of his coach, P.J. Carlesimo,
in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit News: ``Today, athletes spit at umpires, attack
teammates on the practice field and, in the case of Golden State
Warriors guard Latrell Sprewell, put a stranglehold on their coach
and threaten to kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Daily News: ``Sprewell still doesn't understand he
crossed a line. Maybe he is another athlete who doesn't think there
are any lines at all.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS News: ``In an era when millionaire athletes routinely behave
like spoiled brats ... ''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Chronicle: ``Sprewell's behavior escalated to
this point because pro athletes so rarely face consequences
commensurate with their indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times: ``So here we sit, knocked flat by another
pro athlete without a moral compass.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were just a few of the 487 news dispatches about Sprewell
that week featuring the word athlete, almost always as a
generalization. Sports Illustrated dubbed him ``not so much a
person as an issue''; in one harrowing lesson, readers were told,
he had taught us everything we needed to know about sports stars.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, after Sprewell's run-and-gun skills have helped
make the New York Knicks contenders for the National Basketball
Association championship, the moral has ripened into one that is
more difficult to swallow. Sprewell is now one of the most popular
athletes in New York, even embraced by the league itself in
commercials. His metamorphosis from pariah to prodigy is a lesson
all its own, less about athletes than their audience.
</P>
<P>
   In sports there is a half-life to public disdain, an inevitable
erosion that typically takes two to three years. Even the most
hardened opinions give way to the exhilaration of tape-measure home
runs or monster dunks, especially when delivered in a home uniform.
Those instants of inebriation are the ultimate subliminal
advertising: Without even knowing it, fans get nudged toward
thinking, ``Well, he can't be that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sprewell's case, his capricious and occasionally reckless
style of play after joining the Knicks went from crass to
charismatic, particularly because it energized an otherwise dull
club. (He has also gone over two years without choking his coach.)
Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy has said that New York ``loves
reclamation projects,'' and he's right. After all, drug offenders
like Lawrence Taylor, Dwight Gooden and Darryl Strawberry have
repeatedly returned to ovations that only get louder and louder.
</P>
<P>
   Gotham is so renowned for welcoming visiting offenders, however,
that Shea Stadium security is quaking at the impending arrival of
the Atlanta Braves' John Rocker on June 29. Six months after his
xenophobic rant about New Yorkers, Rocker is midway through the
vindication cycle _ his hometown fans are cheering him, while
opposing crowds still punish him with boos and threats. One Los
Angeles Dodgers fan even ran out onto the field as Rocker prepared
to pitch and mooned him. (Alas, the gesture lost some edge when the
fan later accepted $500 from an Atlanta radio station to meet
Rocker face-to-face, and the two shook hands and yukked it up
during batting practice.)
</P>
<P>
   Why are Braves fans cheering Rocker, and why will he ultimately
find the same national absolution as Sprewell and Roberto Alomar,
who spit on an umpire in 1996 and finds little trouble anymore?
Partly because of his talent, but also because today's media
culture so excoriates its chosen malefactors so self-righteously
for so long that they become victims themselves. (In an Internet
poll following Jim Gray's aggressive interview of Pete Rose on NBC
last October, 92 percent of fans said they wanted the convicted
gambler back in baseball.)
</P>
<P>
   This sympathy has less to do with forgiveness than with
redistributing blame. Also boredom: As the 24-hour sports channels
have found other sideshows to harp on _ the National Football
League now has not one but two players accused of murder _ Rocker
is on his way to being old news, left to lie fallow until his
career blooms anew.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell navigated the road to redemption perfectly last season.
He wore wire-rimmed glasses during interviews to appear less
threatening, but retained the corn-row hairdo that kept him hip. He
spoke of just trying to fit in, while starring in a sneaker
commercial so contrite about his past behavior that he proclaimed
himself ``The American Dream.'' Perhaps he was. Months later, the
Knicks signed Sprewell to a $62 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he seeks to propel the Knicks to the NBA finals,
Sprewell's days as a lightning rod for athlete villainy seem a
lifetime away. Back then, The Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel said the
firestorm was ``a referendum on the modern athlete.'' It was about
more than that, and the verdict is in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0038 </DOCNO>
