<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5678 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SOUTH-CLOSURE-REVIEW-     05-27 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-CLOSURE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAYING `THE END' DOESN'T MEAN IT'S ALL OVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By KEVIN SACK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eleven days ago, when prosecutors in Birmingham, Ala.,
charged two former Ku Klux Klansmen with the deadly 1963 bombing of
a black church, there was a lot of talk about closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be some kind of closure, one way or another,''
said Doug Jones, the young U.S. attorney who has overseen the
reinvestigation of the bombing that killed four girls.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John Cross, who was the pastor at 16th Street Baptist
Church when the dynamite detonated 37 years ago, said he felt
elated about the indictments. ``Perhaps this will bring closure,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But what is closure, really? Is it a psychological phenomenon or
a political one or some melding of the two? Has the word become so
overused that it is all but meaningless? Can a judicial resolution
lessen the agony of the victims and families, or does it serve only
to revive pain that had long ago subsided?
</P>
<P>
   These questions are complicated, say psychiatrists, clergy and
those who have experienced grievous losses themselves. And science
has yet to reach many conclusions in what is a relatively young
field.
</P>
<P>
   But all across the world, from South Africa to Chile to
Mississippi to cities like New York that have built Holocaust
museums, the search for closure has become a driving force in
politics, law and culture.
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, former President Nelson Mandela's government
made the remarkable choice of placing healing above vengeance _ and
some say justice _ by granting amnesty to thousands of apparatchiks
of the apartheid regime who agreed to testify before the country's
Truth and Reconciliation Commission. Chile's courts, encouraged by
the newly installed Socialist government, are pushing ahead with
the prosecution of the 84-year-old former dictator Gen. Augusto
Pinochet on charges he was involved in the kidnapping, murder and
torture of thousands of his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   In Neshoba County, Miss., officials are delving again into the
murders of three civil rights workers in 1964. Across the South,
authorities have reopened a number of decades-old cases that were
never adequately investigated because white police officers,
prosecutors, witnesses and jurors sympathized more with white
suspects than with black victims. The May 17 indictments of Thomas
E. Blanton Jr. and Bobby Frank Cherry in the Birmingham bombing
were the latest example. Only one of the four men identified as
suspects, Robert Chambliss, was ever tried and that was 14 years
later; he died in prison in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   At its most elemental, closure is a byproduct of justice, truth
and discovery, psychiatrists and experts say. Finality does not
necessarily alleviate the anguish associated with unjustifiable
loss. But it does, in certain cases, help victims and relatives
move on. And it often restores faith in people, in government and
even in God when a previously unjust system acknowledges past
failings and tries to correct them, however belatedly.
</P>
<P>
   But people respond in different ways, and some traumas defy
closure, researchers caution. ``For some people, this may be very
painful and wake up memories and concerns that they put aside many
years ago,'' said Dr. Susan Nolen-Hoeksema, a professor of
psychiatry at the University of Michigan who studies how people
react to trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven Southwick, a professor of psychiatry at the Yale
University School of Medicine, said it was important to distinguish
between seeking justice and seeking revenge. ``While seeking
justice seems to help many individuals,'' he said, ``it is commonly
felt that seeking revenge tends to further immerse the individual
in the pain of traumatic loss, making it difficult to move on in
life.'' Southwick added, ``One may never fully put to rest the
traumatic loss of a loved one.''
</P>
<P>
   For many of those who have been through the experience, however,
there is little question about the cathartic benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Myrlie Evers-Williams was home the night her husband, the NAACP
field secretary Medgar Evers, was shot in the back in their
driveway in Jackson, Miss., in 1963. She sat through two trials in
1964 as all-white juries deadlocked over the complicity of Byron de
la Beckwith. Evers-Williams, who later presided over the national
NAACP, pressed for justice for 30 years. When a jury finally found
de la Beckwith guilty in 1994, she felt an almost physiological
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall this feeling of release that was very spiritual,''
she said, ``and it was as though all of the demons in my body
exited through every pore of my being. It was as though I could
almost see it rushing out. For the first time in all those years, I
became free, my children became free and I felt that Mississippi
became freer, as did all of America. That was the point of
closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellie Dahmer waited 32 years to see Sam Bowers, a former
Klansman, convicted of the firebombing that killed her husband,
Vernon, a local NAACP leader. ``It certainly gives you a feeling
that at least your country cares about you,'' she said. ``We felt
so often that we had been so badly mistreated because we were
black.''
</P>
<P>
   As both Evers-Williams and Dahmer suggest, closure can be as
important for a place _ in their case the South _ as for survivors.
Successful prosecutions of long-ago crimes are often viewed as
political statements, as poignant assertions that times have
changed. In that sense, closure can be as liberating for future
generations as for those who suffered the pain, said Morris Dees,
co-founder of the Southern Poverty Law Center, which monitors cases
of racial violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people have problems in a family and sweep them under the
rug and don't deal with them openly and honestly,'' he said,
``they're just going to fester.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
