<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are Saturday's top news stories from The New York Times
News Service for AMs of Sunday, May 28:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE-EXCLUSIVE (Undated) _ Exclusive: On the latest
warnings from U.S. intelligence officials as President Clinton
nears a decision on whether to build a limited national defense
system. By Michael R. Gordon and Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ONLINE (Emblam, India) _ India is fast becoming a
laboratory for small experiments that aim to link isolated rural
pockets to the borderless world of knowledge through computers. By
Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   ULSTER-UNIONISTS (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ The Unionists
vote on whether to continue in the peace process. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-HABIBIE (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ An interview with
President B.J. Habibie. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OPENNESS (Istanbul, Turkey) _ A new climate has emerged
in Turkey in which painful episodes of the recent past can be
discussed more openly. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-PEACE (Undated) _ Around the world women are taking
greater steps to help end and heal the wounds of wars. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IVORY-MAPOUKA (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ As the political
transition drags on in what was once the most stable country in
West Africa, an unexpected entry in the winners' column has been
mapouka _ a dance that had been treated in official corners as
something close to an infectious disease. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-PARLIAMENT (Cairo, Egypt) _ Iran's new reformer-dominated
parliament opened Saturday in Tehran, the first since the Islamic
revolution to include a majority of members who appear eager and
ready to challenge the conservative clergy's dictates over how
Iranians live their daily lives. Bu Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-BEAUTY (Miami) _ The worship of beauty has become an
obsession, if not a high art, in South Beach, the celebrated strip
of flesh and flash that might just be the center of physical beauty
in America. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL-GRADUATES (Undated) _ Profiles of four people who stand
out among the more than 2 million people who earned degrees this
spring. By Jacques Steinberg and Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and sidebar: BROWN-GRADUATION (Providence, R.I.) _
Instead of conferring 1,000 degrees, Brown University presented
only one Saturday, to Casey Shearer, a beloved member of the senior
class who died less than a week before he was to graduate. By Julie
Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-TRADE (Undated) _ The American labor movement is badly
divided on political strategy after last week's vote in favor of
the China trade bill, which labor opposed. And some union leaders
and Democratic consultants say this split could set back Vice
President Al Gore's electoral chances as well as Democratic hopes
of regaining control of the House of Representatives. By Steven
Greenhouse. Eds: Will also moved in `p' category.
</P>
<P>
   SANTACRUZ-HOMELESS (Santa Cruz, Calif.) _ Santa Cruz, which
out-Berkeley's Berkeley, has just passed an ordinance that will
allow homeless people to sleep in two designated spots in
industrial parks. This defies what most cities are doing _ passing
ordinances outlawing homelessness _ and says much about Santa Cruz,
where a socialist on the city council is considered one of the more
conservative members. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   BENNINGTON-DISPUTE (Bennington, Vt.) _ A onetime leading school
of high art and lofty thought has fallen mightily and is now mired
in a nasty fight between its president and its faculty. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DISTRACTED-DRIVERS (Undated) _ The increasing use of cell phones
and other high tech items in cars leaves safety experts fearing
that distracted drivers may soon drive up the accident rate. By Jon
Nordheimer.
</P>
<P>
   GAS-PRICES (Dallas) _ After falling a good bit, gasoline prices
have soared to the highest levels of the year in many parts of the
nation. Drivers now filling up are paying record prices for the
Memorial Day weekend. And analysts say tight supplies, particularly
in the Midwest, could push prices even higher. By Richard A. Oppel
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CRIME (New York) _ In dozens of interviews across the city in
the last two weeks, it was difficult to catch many people _
especially the affluent _ in the act of worrying about the return
of crime to where they live and work. By Randy Kennedy and Alan
Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   With NY-WENDYS-MURDERS (New York) _ Two men face arraignment
Saturday in the quintuple slaying of five Wendy's employees and the
wounding of two others.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-DIET (Washington) _ Americans are eating better than they
were in the 1980s, but the diets of nine out of 10 still need
improvement, federal officials said Saturday. By Christopher
Marquis.
</P>
