<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7438 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CARTLAND-NOVELS-REVIE     05-27 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTLAND-NOVELS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DO I LOVE THEE? LET ME COUNT THE WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By JENNY LYN BADER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best-selling author in the world managed to ignore both the
sexual and the technological revolutions. She survived the whole of
the 20th century keeping her love scenes chaste and dictating her
work to a secretary.
</P>
<P>
   When Dame Barbara Cartland died last Sunday at the age of 98,
she had written 723 books. She earned a place in the Guinness Book
of World Records, with nearly a billion copies sold. And she had
become the answer to a Trivial Pursuit question, ``Who has the
longest entry in Who's Who?'' The full entry, which lists a
staggering array of titles, was once performed as a cabaret act.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring authors, take note: If you're planning to stay on top
of the best-seller list, your titles should turn heads. Cartland
replaced sex with ellipses, but she kept her covers provocative.
Judge for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cartland knew that readers of romance novels like to see the plight
of the central character revealed in the title _ especially if the
character is an anxious virgin or an emotionally unstable
aristocrat: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A Virgin in Mayfair; A Virgin in Paris; The Mysterious
Maid-Servant; The Innocent Heiress; The Reluctant Bride; The
Frightened Bride; The Unpredictable Bride; The Wicked Marquis; The
Impetuous Duchess; The Marquis Who Hated Women; The Odious Duke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Even Cartland's histories and biographies have extremely
evocative titles: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Outrageous Queen: A Biography of Christina of Sweden; Polly:
The Story of My Wonderful Mother; Metternich: The Passionate
Diplomat; The Private Life of Charles II: The Woman He Loved; The
Private Life of Elizabeth, Empress of Austria; The Scandalous Life
of King Carol.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Some of the better titles juxtapose animals and people, or
offer incongruous or distressing pairings: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Hell-Cat and the King; Diona and a Dalmation; The Prince and
the Pekinese; Ola and the Sea Wolf; Sex and the Teen-ager; The
Saint and the Sinner; Lucifer and the Angel; The Goddess and the
Gaiety Girl; The Passion and the Flower; The Duke and the
Preacher's Daughter; Pride and the Poor Princess; The Prude and the
Prodigal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; As the author of the ``I Love You'' virus recently learned,
anyone seeking a large readership should use the word love in a
title: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Love Is an Eagle; Love Is Innocent; Love and the Loathsome
Leopard; Love Holds the Cards; Love Climbs In; Love Has His Way;
Love Leaves at Midnight; Love Wins; Love Rules; Love is the Key;
Love at the Helm; Love to the Rescue; The Explosion of Love; The
Perfection of Love; The Windmill of Love; The Castle Made for Love;
A Rhapsody of Love; The Vibrations of Love; The Karma of Love; The
Twists and Turns of Love; Wish for Love; Love Under Fire; Love in
Hiding; Love in the Dark; Never Laugh at Love; Food for Love;
Recipes for Lovers; No Time for Love; In the Arms of Love; A
Portrait of Love; A Game of Love; A Dynasty of Love; A World of
Love; The Goddess of Love; A Gentleman in Love; The Dawn of Love;
The Wings of Love; The Drums of Love; The River of Love; The Fire
of Love; Signpost to Love; Moments of Love; Little White Doves of
Love; Elizabethan Lover; Barbara Cartland's Book of Love and
Lovers; Barbara Cartland's Etiquette for Love and Romance; The
Ghost Who Fell in Love.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Yes, human beings are such romantics they will even buy books
in which love might be the villain: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Love Is the Enemy; Love Is Contraband; Love for Sale; Love
Locked In; The Judgment of Love; The Many Facets of Love; No Escape
From Love, Punished With Love; Armour Against Love; Lies for Love;
The Wild Cry of Love; The Slaves of Love; The Cave of Love; A Game
of Love; The Love Pirate; The Love Trap; Conquered by Love; The
Prisoner of Love; A Fugitive From Love; The Problems of Love.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Titles lacking love may need heart: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Knave of Hearts; The Queen of Hearts; Women Have Hearts; The
Waltz of Hearts; A Duel of Hearts; The Captive Heart; The Smuggled
Heart; The Unknown Heart; The Hidden Heart; Call of the Heart,
Desire of the Heart; No Heart Is Free; A Sword to the Heart; The
Heart of the Clan; A Hazard of Hearts; The Chieftain Without a
Heart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Some titles promise to unlock the mysteries of marriage and sex
roles, not to mention aphrodisiacs: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Men Are Wonderful; Woman, The Enigma; The Husband Hunters;
Living Together; Wanted: A Wedding Ring; The Wild Unwilling Wife; A
Very Unusual Wife; Bride to the King; The Incredible Honeymoon;
Romantic Royal Marriages; Husbands and Wives; Marriage for the
Moderns; Love, Life and Sex; Vitamins for Vitality; The Magic of
Honey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Astronomical references can give the book a nice, dreamy feel: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Touch the Stars: A Clue to Happiness; Count the Stars; Seek the
Stars; Touch a Star; A Runaway Star; Stars in My Heart; Stars in
Her Eyes; Terror in the Sun; Love in the Moon; Light of the Moon; A
Shaft of Sunlight, Pure and Untouched; Moon Over Eden; Riding to
the Moon; Love in the Clouds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A good sense of geography can help locate the characters and
orient the reader:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Paradise in Penang; Heaven in Hong Kong; Alone in Paris; Lovers
in Lisbon; Lovers in Paradise; Just Off Piccadilly; To Scotland and
Love; An Innocent in Russia; A Ghost in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; It's always smart to hint that you've got a secret or two: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Youth Secret; Secret Harbor; The Secret Fear; The Secret of
the Glen; Secret of the Mosque; Barbara Cartland's Book of Useless
Information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Book buyers, like everyone else, are fond of the supernatural: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Enchanted; Lost Enchantment; The Enchanted Moment; The
Enchanting Evil; The Enchanted Waltz; Winged Magic; The Magic of
Love; Bewitched; Against This Rapture; Gift of the Gods; The Gods
Forget; Flowers for the God of Love; A Witch's Spell; Love Strikes
a Devil; The Kiss of the Devil; Stolen Halo; A Halo for the Devil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; When in doubt, use alliteration: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Temptation for a Teacher; The Temptation of Torilla; Love, Lords
and Lady-Birds; Look Lovely, Be Lovely; The Golden Gondola; A Duel
of Jewels; A Kiss for the King; Fascinating Forties: A Book for the
Over-Forties; Broken Barriers; Desperate Defiance; The Power and
the Prince; Dollars for the Duke; The Duchess Disappeared; A Duel
With Destiny; Drena and the Duke, Walking to Wonderland; A Serpent
of Satan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finally, a sexy title can pose a pressing question: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For What?; First Class, Lady?; Magic or Mirage?; Who Can Deny
Love?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ... Who, indeed? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
