<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7441 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-HYPERCONVENIENCE-FOOD     05-27 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYPERCONVENIENCE-FOODS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING HYPER OVER CONVENIENCE FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone knows America is a nation in a hurry _ especially the
makers of packaged foods. First there was the TV dinner. Then came
fast food for meals on the go. Now, with the pace of life
approaching warp speed, it's time for something marketers call
hyperconvenience food, portable comfort cuisine and dashboard
dining.
</P>
<P>
   In their continuing quest to trim the amount of time spent on
cooking and eating, packaged-food producers are streamlining every
aspect of dining _ shopping, preparation, the act itself and
cleanup. Supermarkets are clustering meal components near each
other to reduce the time spent wandering the aisles. Short-cuts
like prewashed, peeled vegetables are everywhere. Products like
yogurt that can be squeezed from a tube, snack bars that
theoretically nourish as completely as regular meals and scrambled
eggs in push-up containers are proliferating. And any food that can
be shaped to fit into automobile cup holders is considered to have
a great advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Whether fueled by time-pressed parents or unraveling family
life, ``convenience continues to dominate the food scene,'' said
John L. Stanton, a professor of food marketing at St. Joseph's
University in Philadelphia. ``People want to eat the right things
but when it comes to trading health for time, time wins.''
</P>
<P>
   At Pepsico, executives refer to hyperconvenience as a marketing
concept. ``It's accentuating the immediacy or the urgency of the
consumer,'' a company spokesman said. ``It is convenience to the
nth degree.''
</P>
<P>
   One source of inspiration is the military, which knows a thing
or two about feeding people on the march. Heater Meals of
Cincinnati has begun repackaging products for the general public
that it has long sold as army rations. Using technology tested over
and over in battle, the company offers meals like lasagna and
flame-broiled turkey in styrofoam containers that heat up when the
diner sets off a chemical reaction between a jigger of salt water
and a slab of iron and magnesium. The food is piping hot within 14
minutes, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got all kinds of markets, like truck drivers, the
National Guard and campers,'' said Derrick Wills, a marketing
assistant for Heater Meals. ``Natural disasters, too, when you need
a meal and don't have the resources to cook.'' Can overstressed
families be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   Other marketers are eager to push convenience dining in new
directions. Witness the new McSalad Shaker from McDonald's. No need
to toss the salad with a couple of retro serving spoons: Just pour
the dressing over the salad in a plastic soda cup, cover the cup
with a rounded plastic top and shake the ensemble to distribute the
ingredients evenly. The container fits neatly into a car cup
holder, though people are expected to eat the salad with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Breakaway Foods of Bluebell, Pa., has shoehorned that old
standby, macaroni and cheese, into a microwaveable cardboard tube
with a push-up stick. The product, IncrEdibles, is hitting
supermarkets this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to be left behind, Frito-Lay has come up with Frito
corn chips in the same package with a portion of chili. ``With
snacking being a fourth meal, people are looking for fast fuel,''
said Lynn Markley, a Frito-Lay spokeswoman. ``These kits are the
ideal fuel for Americans on the go.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar line has been developed by the 7-Eleven convenience
store chain, which calls it ``dashboard dining.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the move toward utensil-less meals was inevitable, even
as it blurs the line between humans and animals. ``During the last
five years, there's been a real acceleration of food that is
designed to be eaten directly from the package,'' said Thomas Hine,
the author of ``The Total Package'' (Little, Brown, 1995), a study
of packaging trends and their impact on consumers. ``This is to add
an extra level of convenience that can be charged for. It's a way
of ratcheting up the profit margin.''
</P>
<P>
   In researching his book, Hine interviewed marketing consultants
who commissioned teen-agers to photograph their families. The
consultants found that people were frequently eating directly out
of boxes, bags or other containers. ``They discovered that an
extremely high percentage of food is eaten right out of the
package, whether the package was designed for that or not,'' Hine
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, teen-agers and other family members _ whether
because of schedules or dysfunction _ were shown eating meals at
different times, rather than sitting down to dinner together. In
Hine's latest book, ``The Rise and Fall of the American Teen-Ager''
(Avon), he concludes that the scattershot approach to the family
dinner hour is linked to social problems like drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Still, such findings are music to the ears of food marketers'.
Robert Berman, the founder of Breakaway Foods, said his eureka
moment came while watching his 14-year-old daughter play with her
food. ``We were having dinner in an Italian restaurant, and she had
finished eating four or five bites of her spaghetti when she
started twirling it around her fork and holding it up in the air,''
he recalled. ``Then she started twirling it around a bread stick
and held it up. I started wondering if there was ever a portable
pasta. I did some research, and found that there hadn't been one in
3,000 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began the IncrEdibles line, which now includes scrambled
eggs (with or without sausage and bacon), as well as chili and a
healthier-sounding entry with broccoli mixed in with macaroni and
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are constantly pressed for time and on the move,''
Berman said. ``When I was growing up in the '50s and '60s, my mom
made breakfast every day and the family sat down for dinner every
night. It's a very different pace we live today. Breakfast is
pretty much gone, as far as sitting down and eating. Lunch is on
the way out, and dinner is under attack.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0047 </DOCNO>
