<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-RESTAURANT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND WAIT TILL YOU TASTE THE STUFFED SHELLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a city aswarm with new restaurants clamoring for
recognition, the National Rifle Association managed to clear one
hurdle with ease. Back in May 2000, it caught the public's
attention by announcing plans to open a theme restaurant, the NRA
Sports Grille, in Times Square. Now, a year later, for the second
hurdle: Can it win the hearts, minds and, most important, the
stomachs of a gun-shy city eaters?
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Sports Grille will give them plenty to talk
about. Diners used to passing a velvet-rope barrier now face a new
obstacle: a metal detector that identifies patrons who have
forgotten to bring a sidearm. Once issued with a loaner, the diners
may want to stop for a Ruby Ridge cocktail at the Minuteman Bar, or
proceed straight to the Charlton Heston Room, a soaring space
decorated with stills from the actor's finest performances,
although one, from ``The Ten Commandments,'' seems to be an outtake
(I am certain that the stone tablets never referred to the right to
bear arms).
</P>
<P>
   The menu at the Sports Grille, billed as ``110 percent American
cuisine,'' relies heavily on game, and here diners need to exercise
caution. It is one thing to pick your way through the buckshot in a
Scottish grouse, and quite another to work your way around the
bullets from an AK-47 assault rifle. But it's a small price to pay
for authenticity. Most dishes on the menu are identified not only
by place of origin, but also by manner of death. My Texas antelope,
for example, was brought down at 1,500 feet by Edward ``Buddy''
Barnes, using a Weatherby MarkV Super VarmintMaster. It was tender
and flavorful, so fresh it was nearly twitching. A hefty slab of
Montana elk, however, had a distinctly metallic taste, not
surprising considering that the animal was picked off from a
helicopter by five men wielding Uzis.
</P>
<P>
   At Sports Grille, diners learn that shooting fish in a barrel is
no mere expression. The management, seeing the runaway success of
Greek restaurants in which customers personally pick out their fish
for dinner, have gone the extra step, and allowed customers to
choose a fish and then finish it off. It does add a certain thrill
to the meal. Salmon may be fighters, but I can tell you that one
Teflon-coated bullet from a Smith and Wesson Baby Sigma makes them
fold up pretty quickly. Although the emphasis is on meat dishes, I
found the fish to be first rate at the Sports Grille, and I can
particularly recommend the subtle and intriguing Congressional
Special: weakfish prepared tableside, where an NRA lobbyist removes
the backbone with no difficulty whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   The Sports Grille is a cheery, high-energy restaurant, although
conversation is made difficult by a soundtrack booming out
inspirational messages from the NRA executive vice president, Wayne
LaPierre, against a background of small-arms fire.
</P>
<P>
   Tipping is also a problem. How do you leave less than 20 percent
to a waiter in camouflage gear carrying a Glock 9-millimeter pistol
and 1,000 rounds of ammunition?
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I take that for you?'' my server asked, reaching for my
credit card. I snatched it back and said, smiling, ``The only way
you'll get is it to pry it from my cold, dead fingers.'' He didn't
laugh. In fact, his eyes narrowed, and I can swear I saw his hand
move toward his gun.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of place. &QL;
</P>
