<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7443 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-LEBANON-REVIE     05-27 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-LEBANON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL GAMBLES ON THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 18 years, the blue and white Star of David snapped over the
crumbling ramparts of Beaufort Castle, the Crusader stronghold
commanding the folding ravines and abrupt gullies that twist
through southern Lebanon and northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th century fortress has endured as a symbol of power, for
whoever ruled its battlements could rain destruction in any
direction.
</P>
<P>
   But in the two decades since Israel invaded Lebanon to dislodge
the Palestinians, such direct power has proved elusive in the
rugged southern Lebanese countryside. For all its physical presence
in the south, Israel was unable to ever bring the region completely
to heel. So now it has taken a grand gamble: that by simply leaving
southern Lebanon _ and, at least for now, turning it over to
Israel's bitterest enemies _ it will be better positioned to pursue
a broader strategic peace.
</P>
<P>
   And on its northern border, the linchpin of that peace is not in
Lebanon's small villages and rocky hills at all, but 40 miles away,
in Damascus, Syria, the capital from which Israel assumes the
Islamic guerrillas of Hezbollah can be controlled _ or set loose.
It is Syria, after all, whose 35,000 troops have not relinquished a
military embrace of Lebanon that dates from the Lebanese civil war
in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Israel has withdrawn completely from Lebanese territory,
then it is on a much higher political ground to justify retaliation
for any attacks because it is no longer occupying foreign
territory,'' said Edward Djerejian, a former American ambassador to
Syria and Israel. ``They are truly protecting their international
border from within.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak has threatened to unleash Israel's
full might against Syria in retaliation for any cross-border
violence. ``Now a new dynamic is at work,'' said Itamar Rabinovich,
who was Israel's chief negotiator with Syria from 1992 to 1996
while he was ambassador to Washington. When Israeli troops were in
Lebanon, he said, the force served as insulation _ a punching bag
that Syria could hit just by giving a nod to Hezbollah. ``Everybody
knew that the Syrians were indirectly responsible or encouraged the
attacks, but they were not directly responsible,'' he said. ``Now
there is a real danger that any attack on Israel proper would lead
to a full collision between Israel and Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   When Israel captured Beaufort Castle from the Palestinians in
1982, the architect of the invasion, Ariel Sharon, told Israeli
reporters that the castle had been taken without a single casualty.
A young lieutenant stepped forward to say that actually six men
were killed. It was an early portent that the cost of keeping an
army in Lebanon would prove far higher than anticipated.
Ultimately, Israel lost more than 900 men _ the last at Beaufort
Castle on Feb. 11. Lebanese casualties were in the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   But all that bloodshed left little imprint on the larger issues
of peace with Syria. Despite all the fighting between proxies, the
main issue _ control of the Golan Heights _ simply wasn't
addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has kept its own border with Israel quiet since 1974, and
a big Israeli hope is, obviously, that Damascus might keep Lebanon
equally calm now in hopes of regaining the Golan Heights. Also,
with an impending transition of power from President Hafez Assad to
his son, Syria may well not want a new fight.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Syria's status as Lebanon's puppeteer has just
become harder to justify with the Israeli occupation over. Still,
the Syrians have said a struggle against Israel must continue as
long as issues like the future of Palestinian refugees in Syria and
Lebanon remain unresolved. And that touches on one of the most
problematic aspects of the Israeli gamble: In the Middle East it is
impossible to dismiss the ability of any one fringe group to ignite
the center.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most prominent flags replacing the Star of David at
Beaufort is yellow, with a fist hoisting a rifle over broad green
Arabic letters spelling Hezbollah. This militia, with its strong
ties to Syria and Iran, didn't even exist in 1982. Israel invaded
Lebanon that year to eliminate the Palestinian movements then
headquartered there and to install a puppet Christian government in
Beirut. At first, southern Lebanon's Shiites, weary of the
Palestinians' state within a state, welcomed the Israelis. But when
Israel too proved highhanded, Shiite resentment blossomed.
Hezbollah was born of a twin desire to drive out the Israelis and
to gain some say in governing the Shiites' own land.
</P>
<P>
   Now Hezbollah represents the largest question hanging over the
abrupt Israeli departure: whether, in the absence of any other
force, it will bring quiet or will try to transfer the war of
attrition across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has long been opaque about its intentions. Its rise
was engineered in part by Iran, and those ties remain close; Iran's
foreign minister, Kamal Kharrazi, breezily swept through southern
Lebanon last week. Still, Iran's most committed radicals are in a
power struggle at home and may not want to meddle.
</P>
<P>
   How completely Iran or Syria can direct Hezbollah has always
been unclear anyway. Now that the group has mastery of the south,
there is an obvious temptation to feel a strong sense of autonomy.
``They have something to defend now,'' said Prof. Nubar Hovsepian,
the assistant director of Middle East studies at Rutgers
University. ``They are part of the Lebanese equation, not just a
marginal presence. They have a stake in getting resources to build
up the area of the country where the Shiite have a majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Lebanon has long been poor and neglected. Hezbollah
succeeded in no small part by providing services in the area it
controlled, and now that area has been vastly enlarged.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah also controls a few seats in Parliament, but far fewer
than the older, more established Shiite party, Amal. Amal, too,
lofted their flag above Beaufort last week. But it was the calm,
methodical way in which Hezbollah exerted control over the south
that was being most closely watched for a sign of how peace _ or
new war _ might proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the original Crusaders who controlled Beaufort, Reynald of
Sidon was known for charming Saladin, the most powerful regional
military commander in the late 1100s. Reynald often used the front
of extended peace talks to buy time to strengthen the castle's
fortifications. Eventually Saladin tired of the game and laid siege
until the place surrendered. It has been changing hands _ and
defying the ambitions of conquerors _ ever since.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
