<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5686 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-HISTORY-REVIEW     05-27 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HISTORY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL RETHINKS ITS HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The television screen snaps into focus on a Tel Aviv army
recruitment office in 2015, where a strapping Israeli raised in the
United States has come home for his military service. ``I'm here to
defend my country,'' he says, resonating with classic Zionist
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The officer he faces has flowers in his shoulder-length hair and
a glazed look in his eyes. ``Why do you want a gun?'' he asks.
``Guns are dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To defend my country against the Syrians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with the Syrians?'' asks a second officer wearing
bellbottoms and a peace medallion. ``My wife is Syrian.''
</P>
<P>
   The sketch, on the Israeli equivalent of ``Saturday Night
Live,'' mocks a future Israel at peace. And while the notion may
amuse the hip north Tel Avivians who wrote and performed the
sketch, it is no joking matter to others in Israel. They fear that
peace will mean an obliteration of the Jewish state through a slow
refusal to engage the enemy, a lowered guard and intermarriage.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's images of Israeli soldiers retreating from Lebanon
as Muslim guerrillas declared victory, and the prospect of yielding
more West Bank land to the Palestinians amid threats of unrest,
have made that fear the focus of growing anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some Israelis say the future is already here, that their
nation, steeped now in consumerism and cable television, is nearly
drained of the shared, antimaterialist conviction on which it has
survived. While most hope that by yielding land and ending
occupation they are sowing further peace and prosperity, some also
fear that therein lie the seeds of self-destruction _ that the
young will lose their commitment to defense.
</P>
<P>
   It is that anxiety that underlies the ferocity of another
national debate, over new histories of Zionism and changes in the
school curriculum. These revise the standard Zionist self-image _
the righteous, selfless pioneer _ in favor of a more complicated
and less heroic one. They portray early Zionists both as humans
drawn into war's inhumanity, and as European colonialists.
</P>
<P>
   This fight is in the background as Israel stakes out a new
strategy for confronting Syria and Lebanon; it illustrates a deep
internal conflict over whether Israelis today see themselves as
having a special mission or, after centuries of discrimination,
should only seek ``normality.'' And it raises the question of how
Israel measures up morally and politically against its neighbors.
The new scholarship assumes that Israel shares the blame for the
conflict with its adversaries and should come to terms with them as
moral and cultural equals.
</P>
<P>
   The contested revisionism, known as ``new history,'' presents
evidence of deliberate mistreatment and expulsion of Palestinians
as well as efforts to block diplomatic arrangements with the
surrounding states while publicly proclaiming a thirst for peace.
To the new historians, Israel's occupation of southern Lebanon and
its use of a proxy militia there were a continuation of a
disastrous policy that dismissed Arabs as either peasants or
mercenaries.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to co-opt the locals and punish those who failed to play
along were part of a pattern that emerged before the state was
established in 1948, it is argued. Evidence of early misdeeds began
piling up from newly-opened state archives in the 1980s. When
published, the revelations were controversial. But it was the
addition of such notions to ninth grade textbooks this past year
that created a storm. Some Israelis say that teaching the young
about early Zionist sins is the start of mass suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Hillel Halkin, a writer and translator, lamented in a recent
issue of Commentary magazine that the textbook changes are ``a
process of numbing and emotional divorce'' that, in effect, invites
students to decide whether Jews or Arabs have a stronger claim on
the land'' and saps Israel's ability to defend itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jews of Israel are an exhausted people, confused and
without direction,'' writes Yoram Hazony, a young, conservative
Israeli analyst whose new book is called ``The Jewish State: The
Struggle for Israel's Soul.'' (Basic Books). In the book Hazony
assails not only the new history but the growing intellectual and
political movement in Israel that is broadly known as
``post-Zionism.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, post-Zionism asserts that the task of saving the
world's Jews by bringing them to their homeland and making it
secure is now complete. At the same time, about a sixth of Israel's
citizens are not Jewish either because they are Arabs or
not-fully-Jewish refugees from the former Soviet Union. The
post-Zionist conclusion is that Israel should reduce or end its
Jewish character, changing its identity from ``the Jewish state''
to a state of all its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   This alarms Hazony, who says that the devotion to land and
Jewish nationalism that characterized his parents' generation is
hard to find today.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle between old-style Zionists and the post-Zionists
is, ultimately, a battle over individualism in a society that
spurned it for so long. Anyone who visited Israel in the late 1960s
will recall the smug superiority of a nation nearly without drugs,
crime or disaffected young people, where the young were outfitted
in scouting uniforms and hiking the wilderness, vying for top jobs
in the air force.
</P>
<P>
   Today Israel has dozens of cable channels and a choice of
consumer goods to rival any Western country. It has the largest
number of Nasdaq-traded companies outside the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Some young Israelis are beginning to see their nation as just
one among many and the new history only confirms that.
</P>
<P>
   For liberals, the shift in history teaching is welcome news and
a necessary preface to peace because it fosters the growth of
individualism, which they see as a vital check on group
coerciveness. In other words, they say, by freeing Israel of a
single self-congratulatory narrative, the new historians and
post-Zionists have offered freedom from what Yaron Ezrahi, an
Israeli political scientist, calls ``the tyranny of supposedly
shared meaning.'' When one's heros are reexamined and understood to
suffer from weakness and even inhumanity, one's adversaries become
less menacing. They, too, are only human. With that understood,
they say, negotiation is easier.
</P>
<P>
   As the curriculum shift and the Lebanon retreat make evident,
Israel's liberals are winning the struggle over how to cast the
national narrative. It remains to be seen whether they can get the
promised peace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
