<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7445 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-ANTITRUST-REMEDIES-RE     05-27 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTITRUST-REMEDIES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNCERTAIN ART OF LEGAL REMEDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By STEVE LOHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a court filing last week Microsoft called the government's
proposal to break the company in two ``the antitrust equivalent of
the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyerly hyperbole, it seems, but in the old days _ the very old
days _ antitrust offenders couldn't afford to take any chances. In
388-386 B.C., a group of Athenian grain dealers formed a corn
monopoly and manipulated prices, according to research by Spencer
Weber Waller, a professor at the Brooklyn Law School. The dealers
were caught, prosecuted and put to death.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, the issue of the appropriate punishment in antitrust
cases has been a conundrum, if not a lethal one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kill companies occasionally, but we've never killed any
people with antitrust enforcement in America,'' said Herbert
Hovenkamp, a professor at the University of Iowa law school.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust is a flexible doctrine intended to prohibit
``anticompetitive behavior'' _ a concept whose definition shifts
according to the economic and political thinking of the day. So the
remedial steps, too, have varied widely over the years.
</P>
<P>
   There are two broad approaches: ``structural'' remedies, which
involve breaking up the offending company; and ``conduct''
remedies, which involve prohibiting certain kinds of corporate
behavior, like threatening rivals or writing contracts that
restrict competition.
</P>
<P>
   Both approaches have drawbacks. Breaking up a company is
drastic, irrevocable and runs the risk of doing more harm than
good. Restraints on a company's behavior can be easily sidestepped,
may do little to curb its market power and may require constant
policing by a court or government.
</P>
<P>
   In the Microsoft case, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson appears to
be seriously weighing a breakup of the company. In his court in
Washington last Wednesday, Jackson pointedly asked the government
why it did not go even further and recommend breaking up Microsoft
into three companies instead of just two. The judge may issue his
remedies order as soon as this week, but no matter what he decides,
Microsoft will appeal both his sanctions and his legal ruling,
which found the company to be a monopolist that used its market
power to stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   The track record of antitrust remedies is decidedly mixed, even
humbling. For decades, from Standard Oil in 1911 through United
Shoe Machinery in 1968, the courts tended to look approvingly on
structural remedies, says Hovenkamp, editor of the 18-volume
treatise ``Antitrust Law,'' begun in 1978 by Philip Areeda of the
Harvard Law School, who died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   United Shoe Machinery is the classic cautionary tale for
skeptics of the structural approach. The government sued the
company and in 1953 a district court in Boston found that it had
violated the law but declined to break it up. In his opinion, Judge
Charles Wyzanski explained that federal judges are not experts in
economics or politics and ``their prophecies as to the economic
future are not guided by unusually subtle judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, the government asked the Supreme Court to modify
Wyzanski's remedies order so that United Shoe could be broken up.
In 1968, the Supreme Court agreed with the government and United
Shoe was split up, even though United Shoe's share of the
shoe-making machinery market declined from 85 percent to 48 percent
between 1953 and 1968.
</P>
<P>
   United Shoe eventually collapsed, though the role of the
government's misguided ministrations is unclear. Among antitrust
scholars, however, ``A lot of people who have studied it since
believe that the courts got it wrong,'' Hovenkamp observed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but 1968 was the height of the ``big is bad'' bias
against business and for the notion that government should step in
to restrain corporate power. That changed by the late 1970s, as
international rivals began to challenge America companies and as
free-market academics, led by University of Chicago theorists,
influenced antitrust thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The courts, in general, have been skittish about splitting up
companies in antitrust cases since the 1980s. A qualified exception
was the AT&AMP;T breakup in 1984, but that was unusual, a consent
decree applied to a government-sanctioned monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust experts say the structural approach to antitrust
remedies is gaining renewed respect. One reason, they say, is that
the consent decree the Justice Department signed with Microsoft in
1994 is widely seen as a failure.
</P>
<P>
   The decree, antitrust experts say, was a backward-looking remedy
that did little to restrain Microsoft's market power in an industry
moving ahead at a rapid clip. ``The government was shooting at a
moving target, and it aimed, shot and missed,'' noted William
Kovacic, a professor at the George Washington University law
school.
</P>
<P>
   The cases in which breakup remedies will now receive serious
consideration by the courts, according to antitrust experts,
involve ``durable'' monopolies (at least five years old) for which
there is ``no reasonable prospect'' that the market will become
competitive unless the monopolist is split up.
</P>
<P>
   So much for theory. In the Microsoft case, what are the chances
that the company will be broken up after all the appeals are over?
A straw poll of six antitrust scholars who are not affiliated with
either side in the case rated that probability at 20 percent to 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, all six wanted to do their handicapping
anonymously. There have been too many surprises already, they say,
in the antitrust soap opera formally known as the United States of
America vs. the Microsoft Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
