<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7453 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MIAMI-BEAUTY-ART-2TAK     05-27 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-BEAUTY-ART-2TAKES(620)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY REIGNS SUPREME FOR LOYAL CONGREGATION IN FLORIDA'S SOUTH
BEACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1-3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ The soft drink sat untouched, cold, sweet and
inviting. Tabitha Flores, a part-time swimsuit model, stared at the
sweating can as if it were a serpent trying to lure her from the
Garden of Eden.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred and twenty calories,'' Flores said, ``will kill
you here.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores, sitting in a consultation room in her plastic surgeon's
opulent office, lives and plays here in South Beach. She feels she
must be beautiful _ svelte, taut, curvaceous, tanned and
expensively styled _ to belong in this community where striking
beauty is commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   She had asked for a diet soda, but the sugary kind was all her
doctor had. ``This Pepsi,'' she said, flashing a smile of perfect,
recently bleached teeth, ``could ruin my weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   South Beach is utterly absorbed by beauty, peopled with fashion
models and dreamers and others who just like moving about a place
where bartenders pose like Grecian statues, cafe hostesses are
achingly lovely, and waiters and waitresses sway blank-faced
between tables as if on an invisible catwalk _ as if the ghost of
Gianni Versace were looking on from a dark corner table.
</P>
<P>
   The southernmost tip of the city of Miami Beach, South Beach is
home to several of the country's top-tier modeling agencies. This
naturally draws beautiful people _ of all colors, straight and gay
_ to this fanciful place of pastel Art Deco hotels, emerald ocean
and chic, throbbing nightclubs where the unpretty, uncool and
unfashionable are unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Beach is Babylon,'' said Flores, who is also vice
president of a marketing company. She is aware, she stressed, of
the shallowness of it, of the kind of society this culture of
beauty creates. But like so many other people here, she loves
walking out into it, competing, posing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a cultural fixation on beauty here,'' said Scott
Schieman, assistant professor of sociology at the University of
Miami. ``It's currency,'' he said, and it determines someone's
worth in the eyes of the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what rules,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just the number of aspiring models who make the
culture of beauty so complete here. Only a fraction of beautiful
people actually make a living from their looks, from fashion
shoots, cosmetics advertisements and runway jobs, say experts on
the fashion industry. Yet, many live the life.
</P>
<P>
   They hold firm to the ritual of cosmetic surgeries, marathon
workouts, endless dieting and scientific tanning, perpetuating a
society based on looks: on high cheekbones, perfectly rounded
breasts, sharply chiseled muscles, tiny waists and the latest fine
Italian anything. Here, a plain-looking person can stand out like a
pair of hip waders in a Victoria's Secret catalog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear snakeskin, something showing a lot of skin, very low
cut, and a drop-dead pair of stilettos,'' Flores said of her
typical weekend outfit. ``It's a costume party out there. It isn't
real life.''
</P>
<P>
   She is 5-foot-4, 112 pounds, with a 26-inch waist. She recently
had her breasts augmented to a 34-C. ``You want to be looked at,''
she said. ``Here, when people look at you, you're doing pretty
well.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the men entrusted with keeping the Beach beautiful is
Baruch Jacobs, a 43-year-old cosmetic surgeon who has augmented
some of its better-known bodies. There is little stigma attached to
it here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a patient who ordered a breast enlargement,'' Jacobs
said. ``A few days before she was set for the enlargement, she
decided not to. The modeling contract requested she not enlarge.''
She went ahead and bought the implants, and kept them until her
two-year contract was over, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The difference between South Beach and other magnets for beauty
_ like Los Angeles _ is the sheer concentration of it, some fashion
industry experts said. South Beach is less than a mile long and a
mile wide but draws beauty from all over the United States, Europe
and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have prettied-up the landscape,'' said Jason D.
Christenson, director at Wilhelmina Miami, a modeling agency here.
</P>
<P>
   It is also different from Los Angeles in the pure premium placed
on looks. In Los Angeles, movies and television are a dream. Here,
muscles are more valuable than remembering lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hollywood the waiters want to be actors,'' said Barbara
Neumann, who heads the men's division at Ford Modeling Agency on
South Beach. ``Here, they want to be models.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On a sweltering Saturday afternoon stretching into balmy
evening, the main drag, Ocean Drive, may be the most beautiful
place on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the buildings, or even the wide beach, where dingy
sand is specked with cigarette butts and shreds of trash.
</P>
<P>
   The people are the view.
</P>
<P>
   Breathtakingly beautiful women, bursting out of bathing suits
that seem made of only slightly more cotton than that in an aspirin
bottle, parade past the sidewalk cafes, and bored young men in $400
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana sunglasses do not even look up from $20 croissants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wear J. Crew here, you look like a nun,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Marlboro might be America's brand, but here women hold Gauloises
in languid, manicured fingers. Three men, all of whom have shaved
the hair from their chests, argue in French. Yellow Ferraris prowl
by.
</P>
<P>
   On the beach itself, men and women, much too European in their
fashion sense to wear anything except black thongs, tan for hours,
ignoring the puffy, pedestrian tourists and a few families with
children who provide contrast for the cosmetically perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes them so beautiful is being beside people who are
not so beautiful,'' Christenson said.
</P>
<P>
   As night fell, Vladimir Leiva stood on the sidewalk, passing out
cards to promote a restaurant. He is so good-looking that, when
women pass him, they go, ``Ooooohhhhhh.''
</P>
<P>
   His tan is dark and his muscles strain at a tight black shirt.
His hair, the color of ink, is slicked back from a sharply defined
face. He seems to have overdone his cologne, but here, too much is
often barely enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a fashion show,'' Leiva said, looking out on the
evening parade of people on Ocean Drive. ``I do it for myself,'' he
said of his body, wardrobe and persona. ``Beauty, image, counts a
lot. There's a lot of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiva is not a model but a clothing importer and exporter who
doubles at night as a promoter at Casa Salsa, a restaurant owned by
Ricky Martin, the Puerto Rican pop singer and Latin sex symbol.
Like many people here, Leiva talks about the dangers of ``getting
lost'' in the superficiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a lot of people using people,'' he said. ``The models
come with nothing, and they're trying to make it so big. They'll do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It creates an odd social dynamic. South Beach is as much about
money as beauty, yet striking people who yearn for glamorous lives
work in low-paying jobs to survive. Still, one cannot seem poor, or
the casting calls may never come.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends would buy $300 shoes because it is important to
have that look,'' said Vanessa Cofresi, a 27-year-old makeup artist
from Puerto Rico who has been a part-time model since she was 13.
``People here look at what you wear, what car you have, who you
hang around with.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have that in the modeling world but there's more of
that here,'' Cofresi said. ``It is important to have a good-looking
partner. I've had friends tell me, if he's not good looking, he
shouldn't be in our group.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lois West, associate professor of sociology at Florida
International University, said the focus on beauty lends itself to
a lifestyle without any real substance or intellectual depth. Many
who live here concede that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no books, no books anywhere,'' Flores said.
</P>
<P>
   But she has lived in a more serious world. A successful
businesswoman who moved to South Beach from Washington last year,
Flores reinvented herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important up there is what's in your brain,'' she said.
``Here, you have to be attractive first.'' She is 32, so she must
work hard, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tan three, four times a week,'' Flores said. ``I work out
every day. You've got to keep up your pedicures. I am constantly
bleaching my teeth. I do facial peels continuously, grow my hair
longer, because it's sexier. You want to have the new Cartier
watch, Moschino outfits. A lot of women do it for men. I do it
because it's fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You change how you look, but if you're not careful, the devil
changes you,'' Flores said. ``South Beach is a bad habit and you
keep coming back for more.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of the most beautiful here is Sofia Vergara, featured on
countless covers of Spanish-language magazines. But even she, whose
calendar sold 500,000 copies this year, is unsure of her beauty in
a teeming sea of it. ``On the Beach,'' she said, ``you're more
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone in South Beach is beautiful. But Hilario
Machando, 86, who was cruising South Beach on his rusty bicycle
with his pet Chihuahua in the basket, loves living here, anyway,
and loves that God has granted him eyes to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids live in Kendall,'' he said of a Miami suburb, ``but I
never go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-TRADE-DEMOCRACY-REVIE     05-27 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, TRADE BRINGS FREEDOM. EXCEPT WHEN IT DOESN'T 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The arguments that finally persuaded wavering
members of Congress to grant China permanent trade status last week
had very little to do with tariffs or even whether China's
state-run industries would finally allow American farmers to
deliver beef and wheat directly to the world's largest market.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it came down to one of the biggest bets in geopolitics:
Most of the members of Congress who voted ``yes'' said they
believed President Clinton's oft-repeated assertion that the faster
the Chinese people are enmeshed in Western markets, legal systems
and technology, the faster they will be tempted to cast off the
one-party rule of the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When over 100 million people in China can get on the Net,''
Clinton argued in a commencement speech days before the vote, which
he won by a surprisingly wide margin of 237-197, ``it will be
impossible to maintain a closed political and economic society.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? Who knows. Clinton may be well into a second career as
an investment banker or a third one as a movie producer before
anyone has the foggiest sense of whether last week's decision to
end the annual congressional review of China's trading rights, and
usher the country into the World Trade Organization, has any real
effect on political freedom in China.
</P>
<P>
   Yet recent history suggests it is not an entirely wild gamble.
Look around the rest of Asia, where there is a clear _ if sometimes
tenuous _ connection between the growth of market capitalism and
the growth of some kind of democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan and South Korea are the success stories that everyone
points to, places where the arrival of high technology, commercial
legal systems and a gradual opening of the market was followed by
an end to autocratic rule. But economists and political theorists
have spent years arguing over the precise connections between freer
markets and freer political systems and _ no surprise _ they can't
agree on much.
</P>
<P>
   And for every success story there are exceptions like Singapore
and Malaysia, which have managed to embrace free enterprise while
maintaining strict one-party control. Or Russia, where political
liberty has preceded the introduction of a real market economy. But
there are a few common themes:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Free markets don't equal freedom. But they make it a lot harder
for the government _ or corrupt bureaucrats _ to rule over everyday
choices. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Before China began to embrace market principles, a Communist
Party official would get up at 5 a.m. in cities like Shanghai, go
to the market and decide who got what. As in the old Soviet Union,
the system worked for a while _ goods and services got produced,
and people didn't starve. Usually. In short, the apparatchik played
the role that pricing plays today, allocating scarce resources. And
since handing out goodies was the local official's main source of
power _ to say nothing of an opportunity to have his pockets
stuffed with bribes _ the arrival of a market economy means the
diminution of the party's arbitrary power.
</P>
<P>
   Entry into the WTO promises to reinforce this process. ``The
arrival of foreign competition means the local party officials will
lose their control over what the big factory in town produces, or
even how many people it employs,'' says Nicholas Lardy, a China
expert at the Brookings Institution. Chang Lin Tien, the former
chancellor of the University of California at Berkeley, just
returned to Taiwan a week ago to witness the swearing in of the new
president, and he says it got him thinking about what prompted the
change from the martial law of his youth to the election of the
opposition leader, Chen Shui-bian, earlier this year. ``We had some
ruthless leaders,'' he said, ``but as the economy came up, and
Taiwan became part of the global market, it ended up giving more
and more influence to the local Taiwanese and less to the party.
State-owned enterprises just couldn't compete.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A rising middle class first demands a decent apartment, then a
car, and sooner or later a vote. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Well, sometimes. In South Korea, American efforts to push a
series of authoritarian leaders toward greater freedom failed
before the country's workers began making decent wages. ``When I
think about our first efforts to convince South Korean leaders to
liberalize, well, we saved the life of Kim Dae Jung,'' said William
H. Gleysteen Jr., the former American ambassador to Seoul,
referring to the onetime dissident who is now president. ``But a
lot of the other efforts didn't amount to much. Then people started
to buy cars, to travel, and to demand a bit more political space.
They became less compliant with the government.'' By 1987 the
movement had become unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The IMF may be much reviled, but sometimes it aids and abets a
democratic coup. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Suharto did not found the Indonesian state, but he ruled over it
for 35 years. For years the CIA speculated how his regime would end
_ heart attack, coup, assassination. ``We forgot about economic
chaos,'' says one of the agency's old Asia hands. Once the Asian
economic crisis began, the International Monetary Fund began
demanding changes _ including the dismemberment of Suharto's family
enterprises, which were skewing the government's budgets. And that
unleashed political forces that Suharto couldn't withstand. The IMF
made a lot of mistakes, and the Indonesian bailout was not intended
to oust Suharto. In retrospect, though, the world got a more open
Indonesia and one less authoritarian ruler. ``Of course there was
no plan,'' says Jeffrey Garten, a former senior official in the
Commerce Department. ``But from the beginning of the Clinton
administration there was a sense that economic liberalization and
political liberalization would somehow go together. Of course, no
one envisioned how this dangerous cocktail would come together.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Internet will change this. But no one knows how. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is probably right that the Chinese will never be able to
control discourse on the Internet (which doesn't stop them from
trying). And while it may be a force for democracy, it may also
prove a spur for anti-market, anti-American feelings. No sooner had
the House passed the trade bill last week than Chinese scholars
like Han Deqiang were on the Web preaching the dangers. Han told
China Online, an electronic newsletter for executives, that through
the WTO. ``American economic hegemony could easily control China.''
Oh, and he added: ``There are 133 WTO members. Look at some of the
African countries, the corruption there is much worse than in
China.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
