<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Religion Loses a Round to Women in Israel
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Supreme Court ruled that women can hold group
services, wear prayer shawls and read aloud from Torah scrolls at
the Western Wall, a part of the Jewish temple complex that was
destroyed by the Romans in A.D. 70, and Judaism's most revered
shrine.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with strict Orthodox Jewish tradition, men and women
worship at the wall in separate areas divided by a partition, and
only the men hold services. The court gave the government six
months to arrange for women's services.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've come out of the Middle Ages,'' said Anat Hoffman, a
leader of the women's group. ''Today the Western Wall became part
of the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was condemned by Orthodox officials and rabbis.
Deputy Religious Affairs Minister Yigal Bibi, a member of the
National Religious Party, said the Supreme Court had issued yet
another ruling that would ``nullify the state of Israel as a Jewish
state and turn it into a state of all its citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard is Hiring
</P>
<P>
   Neil Rudenstine, the 26th president of Harvard University _ and
only the sixth appointed since the Civil War _ plans to step down
next spring after a decade leading the nation's oldest and most
prestigious university.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine, who took a three-month leave because of exhaustion
in 1994, said he is not too tired to continue. Rather, having
completed a $2.6 billion capital campaign _ the largest ever in
higher education _ he thinks it is time for a new regime to plan
for the next round of fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Water Standards
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has proposed revising its
standards for arsenic, a cancer-causing pollutant, in drinking
water. The new standards would cut the maximum allowable from 50 to
5 parts per billion.
</P>
<P>
   Water utilities objected that going below 10 parts per billion
would be too costly, while environmentalists said the agency was
not going far enough, since the risks of cancer under the new rule
would still be 1 in 10,000. The agency estimated that annual
household water bills could rise $85 in small communities, where
most of the problems are found.
</P>
<P>
   A Flying 800 Pound Gorilla
</P>
<P>
   UAL Corp., the parent of United Airlines, the world's largest
airline, bid $4.3 billion in cash to acquire US Airways, the
nation's sixth-largest carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating problems with regulators, United said it will sell
more than 200 US Airways routes out of Ronald Reagan National
Airport in Washington to Robert Johnson, the founder of Black
Entertainment Television.
</P>
<P>
   United said it will not raise domestic fares for two years after
completing the deal. Antitrust experts said they expect Washington
to take a hard look at the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Hour
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court struck down a 1996 law requiring cable systems
to limit sex channel transmissions to late-night hours, when
children would be less likely to watch, if they could not prevent
signals from those channels from ``bleeding'' through to
nonsubscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The justices all agreed that shielding children from graphic sex
on cable TV was a valid goal, but split 5-4 over what limits the
First Amendment placed on achieving it.
</P>
<P>
   Under another section of the law, cable systems must provide
individual blocking devices on request, and the majority said this
was more respectful of individual choice and less burdensome on
free expression.
</P>
<P>
   Lose Some, Win Some
</P>
<P>
   A disciplinary committee of the Arkansas Supreme Court
recommended that President Clinton be disbarred for ``serious
misconduct'' connected to his sworn testimony about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Through his lawyers, Clinton vowed to fight to keep his law
license during disbarment proceedings before a state court judge in
Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   By midweek, the presidential pall lifted, as the MCI Center in
Washington was packed with 13,625 people, who donated $26.5
million, at the biggest political fund-raiser ever held. Donors
gave between $50 and $500,000 each, and the elaborate affair
cemented the president's legacy as the most prolific political
fund-raiser in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Famous for 24 Seconds
</P>
<P>
   After decades of rejection, Danny Biasone, the bowling alley
proprietor from Syracuse, who invented professional basketball's
24-second shot clock, was finally elected to the Basketball Hall of
Fame last week.
</P>
<P>
   Biasone, who owned the Syracuse Nationals from 1946 until 1963,
created the shot clock in 1954 in an attempt to speed up the pro
game, which had been suffering from low scoring and dwindling
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in the National Basketball Association's 1954-55
season, the 24-second clock revived both scoring and attendance in
the fledgling league. Biasone died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
