<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Sunday, May 28. The N.Y. Times News Service supervisor is
Ned Kilkelly.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead:
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE-EXCLUSIVE (Undated) _ Exclusive: On the latest
warnings from U.S. intelligence officials as President Clinton
nears a decision on whether to build a limited national defense
system. By Michael R. Gordon and Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lede:
</P>
<P>
   ULSTER-UNIONISTS (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Northern
Ireland's largest Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, voted
Saturday by a narrow margin to return to a power-sharing
administration with their Catholic rivals in Sinn Fein, the
political representatives of the Irish Republican Army. By Warren
Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1:15 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Above Fold
</P>
<P>
   GORE-WESTPOINT (West Point, N.Y.) _ Vice President Al Gore,
giving the commencement address Saturday at the U.S. Military
Academy, criticized Gov. George W. Bush's support for a national
missile defense system along with a reduction in nuclear warheads.
``An approach that combines serious unilateral reductions with an
attempt to build a massive defensive system will create instability
and thus undermine our security,'' Gore told the West Point
graduates. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-RACE (Undated) _ The New York Senate race has been
transformed from a battle over a tiny number of undecided voters
into a broad and complex contest, with voting blocs and geographic
preferences that had seemed fixed suddenly up for grabs after Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's departure, Republican and Democratic strategists
say. By Eric Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 3 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-BEAUTY (Miami) _ The worship of beauty has become an
obsession, if not a high art, in South Beach, the celebrated strip
of flesh and flash that might just be the center of physical beauty
in America. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT1-3.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-HABIBIE (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Former President B.J.
Habibie, once the most powerful person in the land, has quickly
become an irrelevance in Indonesia's political scene. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-ONLINE (Embalam, India) _ India is fast becoming a
laboratory for small experiments that aim to link isolated rural
pockets to the borderless world of knowledge through computers. By
Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   GAS-PRICES (Dallas) _ After falling a good bit, gasoline prices
have soared to the highest levels of the year in many parts of the
nation. Drivers now filling up are paying record prices for the
Memorial Day weekend. And analysts say tight supplies, particularly
in the Midwest, could push prices even higher. By Richard A. Oppel
Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
