<HEADER>
A7464 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      05-27 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following scheduled items from The N.Y. Times Week
in Review for Sunday, May 28, have all moved.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Support for normal trading
rights for China was based in part on the argument that free trade
can foster democracy. Around the rest of Asia, there is a clear _
if sometimes tenuous _ connection between the growth of market
capitalism and the growth of some kind of democratic institutions,
although there are exceptions. Free markets don't equal freedom,
but they make it a lot harder for the government or corrupt
bureaucrats to rule over everyday choices. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-HISTORY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Israel is engaged in a
national debate over new histories of Zionism and changes in the
school curriculum. These revise the standard Zionist self-image _
the righteous, selfless pioneer _ in favor of a more complicated
and less heroic one. These new histories portray early Zionists
both as humans drawn into the inhumanity of war and as calculating
European colonialists. An assumption of much of the new historical
scholarship is that Israel shares the blame for the conflict with
its adversaries and should come to terms with them as moral and
cultural equals. The fight over history is in the background as
Israel stakes out a new strategy for confronting Syria and Lebanon,
its remaining Arab adversaries to the north. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-EUROPE-REVIEW (Berlin) _ The Cold War has been over for a
decade, and the big questions _ Euromissiles, Soviet divisions,
global peace itself _ have disappeared from U.S. relations with
European capitals. Beyond the intermittent flaring of Balkan
crises, their place has largely been taken by genetically altered
food, banana trade, capital punishment and even child custody.
America's apparent determination to build a national missile
defense system could still spur a major confrontation with Russia
that would be deeply troubling to Washington's European allies.
But, in general, how to live, what to eat and whether to accept the
death sentence seem to have become the stuff of trans-Atlantic
tiffs. The recurrent rows over such questions are sometimes viewed
as a sign of the fraying ties between Europe and the United States.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   SCHORK-JOURNALISM-REVIEW (Berlin) _ Journalism, it is said,
provides a first draft of history. It is a cliche, yet sometimes an
unlikely combination of war and a witness illustrates the hallowed
truth that lurks behind a hollow phrase. I write this sitting in
Berlin, dreaming of Bosnia, and thinking of Kurt Schork, the
Reuters correspondent whose dispatches from Sarajevo helped shape
the world's view of a war as morally indelible to my generation of
correspondents as Vietnam was to another. Schork, 53, was killed
Wednesday in an ambush in Sierra Leone. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ARMS-CONTROL-REVIEW (Undated) _ New frontiers in arms control:
For the first time in many years, arms control experts are
exploring new, potentially better ways to actually control them.
Top thinkers of the political left and right are declaring
traditional arms control all but dead and calling for deep cuts in
remaining arsenals, for building anti-missile defenses against
rogue states, and for finally getting serious about stopping the
spread of missile technology and nuclear arms. It's thinking about
the unthinkable in a new way. By William Broad.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-LEBANON-REVIEW (Undated) _ The question hanging over the
abrupt Israeli departure is whether, in the absence of any other
force, Hezbollah will bring quiet or if they will attempt to
transfer their war of attrition across the border. The unknown
answer will reverberate across a spectrum of Middle East issues,
but none more than the attempts by Israel and its neighbors to
erect some form of workable peace. By Neil Macfarquahar.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-CLOSURE-REVIEW (Atlanta) _ When prosecutors in Birmingham,
Ala., charged two former Ku Klux Klansmen with the 1963 bombing of
a black church, there was talk about closure. But what is closure?
Is it merely a psychological phenomenon or a political one or some
melding of the two? Has the word become so overused and applied to
so many disparate circumstances as to become all but meaningless?
Can a judicial resolution really soothe the agony endured by
victims, families and other wounded parties, or does it only serve
to revive pain that had long ago subsided? Across the world, from
South Africa to Chile to Neshoba County, Miss., to cities like
Washington and New York that have built Holocaust museums, the
search for closure has become a driving force in politics, law and
even culture. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   HYPERCONVENIENCE-FOODS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Everyone knows America
is a nation in a hurry _ especially the makers of packaged foods.
First there was the TV dinner. Then came fast food for meals on the
go. Now, with the pace of modern life approaching warp speed, it's
time for something marketers call hyperconvenience food, portable
comfort cuisine and dashboard dining. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   NRA-RESTAURANT-REVIEW (New York) _ In a city aswarm with new
restaurants clamoring for attention, the National Rifle Association
plans to open a theme restaurant, the NRA Sports Grille, in Times
Square. Can it win the hearts, minds and, most important, the
stomachs of a city filled with picky eaters? If nothing else, the
Sports Grille will give them plenty to talk about. By William
Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   SPREWELL-REDEEM-REVIEW (New York) _ A look at the rehabilitation
and redemption of controversial basketball star Latrell Sorewell.
By Alan Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   CARTLAND-NOVELS-REVIEW (Undated) _ When Dame Barbara Cartland,
the romance novelist who was the world's best-selling author, died
May 21 at the age of 98, she had written 723 books. Some of her
staggering array of titles are listed. By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   ANTITRUST-REMEDIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ As Washington ponders the
recommendations for Microsoft, all involved parties should be
reminded that the track record of antitrust remedies is decidedly
mixed. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
