<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-PARLIAMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE BREWS AS IRAN'S REFORMERS TAKE OVER PARLIAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Iran's new reformer-dominated parliament opened
on Saturday in Tehran, the first since the Islamic revolution to
include a majority of members who appear eager and ready to
challenge the conservative clergy's dictates over daily life.
</P>
<P>
   But the difficulties facing the young reform movement, which has
seen 18 independent newspapers closed and several of its liberal
activists jailed by hard-line judges, were clearly visible during
the opening ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Only 249 of the 290 seats in the parliament were filled. The
empty seats represented districts where the conservative Council of
Guardians either has not yet certified election results or has
voided the victories of reform candidates who won in the first
round of voting on Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The council only recently approved partial results of the
heavily pro-reform vote in the capital, Tehran, and then only at
the command of Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei. New
elections for vacant seats have not yet been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The machinations over the composition of the new parliament, the
sixth since the Shah was overthrown and replaced with a theocratic
regime in 1979, reflected the broader conflict between entrenched
religious conservatives and the impatient pro-democracy movement
supporting President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, a moderate cleric elected in a landslide vote in 1997,
has advocated democratic reforms, a free press and depoliticizing
the judiciary and security forces, which are dominated by
hard-liners.
</P>
<P>
   While he has been able to form a liberal cabinet to his liking,
he has accomplished little in the way of legislation. The previous
parliament was controlled by conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The new parliament, which includes a record low number of only
37 Muslim clerics, will also have to take conservative resistance
to any reforms into account. The Council of Guardians, in addition
to its power over elections, also must approve all legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But Khatami told the legislators on Saturday that they have the
responsibility to debate and look into all areas of Iranian life
and government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a parliament that has a heavy responsibility and must
play a fundamental role in stabilizing the system,'' Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts in Iran estimate that up to 70 percent of the
new members of parliament are sympathetic to Khatami or directly
allied to him, although they represent a variety of views on such
matters as press freedom, or how to rescue the economy and reduce
unemployment in the overwhelmingly young country.
</P>
<P>
   Some, although not all, reformers have said they want to ease
restrictions on books, music, satellite television receivers and
the press, for example. Others have said the first priority for the
new parliament should be to help expand political activity.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami's aides have said they want to move slowly to avoid
further antagonizing conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parliament must amend the laws in such a way as to pave
the way for democratization of the country,'' said Abbas Abdi, a
reform activist and writer. ``It must pass laws that provide
security and political stability. Without these, economic reform
will not be possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential disputes that lay ahead remained in the background
at the opening session, which became instead a moment of defiant
celebration for Khatami forces.
</P>
<P>
   Abdolvahab Massavi Lari, the Minister of Interior and an ally of
the president, gave a long speech in which he openly expressed
irritation with the way the Council of Guardians handled the
parliamentary elections. Criticism of the council, appointed by the
country's supreme religious leader, had long been taboo.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the new members also demonstrated their iconoclastic
leanings. All 11 women members appeared in headscarves and
shapeless long coats, as required of Iranian women in public
places.
</P>
<P>
   But two of them, Tahereh Rezazadeh from Shiraz and Elaheh Koulai
from Tehran, did not cover themselves with the additional black
square of fabric _ called the chador _ that has been the
established uniform for women who are members of parliament and,
indeed, any woman entering a government building, since the
revolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
