<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIAL-GRADUATES-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFILES OF 4 WHO CLIMBED, AND SCALED, PERSONAL WALLS TO ACADEMIC
SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG with EMILY YELLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One is a single mother who was thrown out of high school in the
1980s and nearly killed herself, only to be reborn in college as a
short story writer.
</P>
<P>
   Another first walked into a schoolhouse just after World War I
and earned her Ph.D. eight decades later, at 90, nearly blind.
</P>
<P>
   A third is graduating from college at 18 with a double major in
music and mathematics, as well as a Rhodes scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth grew up playing childhood war games in Soviet-era
Czechoslovakia and became one of the first female cadets to
graduate from The Citadel military college.
</P>
<P>
   They have never met and have little in common. But they are
among the more than two million people who have earned associate's,
bachelor's, master's and doctoral degrees this spring and whose
names are being read aloud at commencement exercises on sunny lawns
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Taking notes, passing tests, writing papers and going to classes
can be arduous under the best conditions, but these four graduates
had to scale personal walls _ sometimes of their own making,
sometimes thrown up in front of them by others _ that were higher
than those climbed by most.
</P>
<P>
   Their stories follow:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Drug Addiction: Writer Discovers Her Own Voice &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Christine Lincoln's journey to Washington College, a small
liberal arts institution in Chestertown, Md., was as circuitous as
it was perilous.
</P>
<P>
   And she is as amazed as anyone that she is alive, let alone the
recipient of one of the best-endowed literary prizes bestowed on an
undergraduate. The award, which she received from a faculty
committee at commencement May 21, is for $54,266 and named for
Sophie Kerr, a pioneering female journalist and author.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to recall her adolescent self, Lincoln, who is 34, said:
``I was getting into fights. I was using drugs. I started out with
marijuana and alcohol, probably at 13. By the time I was 17, I was
using anything _ cocaine, uppers and downers, diet pills.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, which should have been her senior year at Baltimore
City College High School, she was expelled. Though she would attend
and graduate from another school the next year, her drug abuse
would not abate.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling she needed to escape ``the streets, and my friends,''
Lincoln enlisted in the Air Force. She worked as a radiology
technician at Andrews and Dover Air Force Bases, and secured an
honorable discharge in 1991. But the next year she grew so
depressed that, one night, she swallowed ``every pill that was in
my house and took all the alcohol I could get my hands on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so angry when I woke up,'' she said, ``that I was
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   A 30-day stay in a rehabilitation center in Texas was followed,
a year later, by the birth of her son, Takii, who was beset with
medical problems and required several operations in his early
years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, her son healthy and her sobriety holding, Lincoln began
thinking about her life. And, like the memory of a soft breeze from
a long-ago vacation, she remembered being a 9-year-old who was told
by a teacher, ``Chris, you're a writer,'' after she submitted a
short story in which she had bestowed human qualities on a house.
</P>
<P>
   And so she began taking English courses at Baltimore City
Community College. While there, Lincoln read a newspaper article
about the writing program at Washington College, and its Sophie
Kerr prize. She decided on the spot to apply, and resolved to
obtain scholarship money to cover the $20,000 annual tuition.
Captivated by her spirit and history, the college agreed.
</P>
<P>
   At Washington, which is two hours from Baltimore, Lincoln
discovered Somerset Maugham (```Of Human Bondage,' God, I loved
that''), Toni Morrison (``Everything she's ever written''), and, to
her surprise, Sylvia Plath (``When I took that poetry class, I
thought, `Man, I'm not a poet,' but she blew me away. She's so
real.'')
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, she found her own voice, spinning yarns of
rural life that increasingly centered on struggling black survivors
like herself. Her first story, ``The Music,'' tells of a family
reeling in denial amid persistent physical abuse. In ``Sap
Rising,'' a young woman agonizes over whether to accept the hand of
a downtrodden farmer not unlike her father, or follow the clarion
call of a faraway land.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, her bank account newly flush, Lincoln intends to pack
up her son and begin her own adventure, moving to South Africa,
which she first visited on a college trip. She will study African
literature and work in a program in Johannesburg that uses creative
writing to ``heal teen-agers traumatized by violence.'' She is also
working on a novel, and hoping that a publisher will purchase her
collection of short stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibilities for my life are endless,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Late Start: Long, Hard Climb to Academic Peak &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At 90, Elizabeth Eichelbaum has had enough experiences to fill
several lives, and has earned nothing if not a rest. But she had
other ideas, and this month was awarded a Ph.D. in education from
the University of Tennessee in Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   Eichelbaum arrived in the United States in 1921, an 11-year-old
who had narrowly survived the ravages of the Russian Revolution and
who had been separated from her mother for more than a decade,
until the two were reunited in New York. She has little memory of
her father.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to attend school in Russia during World War I, she
finally entered public school in the fifth-grade in Harlem. But in
eighth-grade she felt she had to drop out to work in a dress shop.
</P>
<P>
   After that, her life strayed further from the classroom. She
married and raised four sons, including twins; ran a delicatessen
in Detroit; and nursed her husband through battles with diabetes
and heart disease, to which he succumbed in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   She herself has lived with a brain tumor that doctors diagnosed
early in the 1970s as not life-threatening. Undaunted, she went on
to earn a high school equivalency diploma in 1975. Eager to pursue
a lifelong love of painting, she then enrolled as an art student at
Wayne State University in Detroit. She was 65, and would later
receive a bachelor's degree and a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   On May 12, despite having macular degeneration, which has left
her nearly blind, Eichelbaum donned a graduation robe once again
and stepped onto a Knoxville stage to accept her doctorate. Her
thesis focused on the value of art therapy to older adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad when I had no education,'' said Eichelbaum, her
voice unwavering. ``I had people I met who'd ask me what university
I went to, when I didn't even have more than four years of grade
school.''
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, she said, it was her own opinion that weighed
more heavily than the judgments of others. ``I thought, this is
what I needed and didn't get and I'm going to get it,'' she said.
``It never left my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   All her sons went to college before their mother did. The twins,
now 67, live in New York City, where one, Stuart, is an artist, and
the other Edward, is a sex therapist who has appeared on
``Geraldo.'' Her third son, Marvin, 61, owns several clothing
stores in Savannah, Ga. And her youngest, Stanley, 54, is an
international real estate developer.
</P>
<P>
   All four were in the audience when she received her doctorate,
joined by most of her four grandchildren and eight
great-grandchildren. One grandson wrote a letter to ``Dear Abby''
in April, extolling his grandmother's accomplishment. Abby
responded: ``Readers, Elizabeth has proved it can be done, so
what's stopping you? Go back to school if that is your dream.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent, unusually hot afternoon, Eichelbaum provided a
ready example of her endurance and perseverance. With the energy of
someone decades younger, she prepared a lunch of homemade vegetable
soup, turkey sandwiches and fresh fruit salad for herself and two
visitors in her Knoxville apartment. She insisted on serving and
clearing, as she says she does at the dinner parties she often
throws for 20 or more guests.
</P>
<P>
   In describing her marathon quest to reach the pinnacle of higher
education, Eichelbaum said: ``It wasn't a case of maybe. I just
waited for the opportunity and I'm finally finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son Marvin remembers an aphorism of his mother's that seems
to have guided her life: ``If we ever complained that we could not
get on a sports team, or get into a certain college, my mother
would say, `The only thing you can't do is live when it's time to
die.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ahead of His Class: Finishing College When Most Begin &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Forgive Michael Lanham, but the idea that anyone would take
eight decades to progress from fifth &UR; - &LR; grade to doctorate is
unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up on a cattle and tobacco farm in Gravel Switch, Ky.,
population about 100, Lanham finished kindergarten, first &UR; - &LR;  and
second &UR; - &LR; grades in one year, all before he turned 6. He skipped
ninth &UR; - &LR; grade and graduated from high school at 14.
</P>
<P>
   Though it did not hurt that Lanham's mother, Jan, was the
coordinator of the gifted students program for the Marion County
school system _ ``She oversaw the accelerations,'' he says _ his
mind was clearly racing faster than his peers'. He began reading
when he was 2, his family says, was able to do simple math by the
time he was 5, and had mastered high school geometry, English and
French by age 10.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, at 18, he is to graduate from Centre College, a liberal
arts institution of about 1,100 students in Danville, about 65
miles southeast of Louisville. In the fall, he will begin studying
at Oxford on a Rhodes scholarship, among the youngest recipients of
the scholarship in at least two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``For as long as I can remember, it's just been the person I've
been,'' Lanham said. ``Because I skipped grades so young, I've been
used to being with people who are three years older. My family has
played a large role in keeping me down to earth and realizing that
there is always more I can be doing _ and that I don't need to
coast on my reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   The fall after he finished high school, Lanham enrolled at
Centre College. His baby-soft face had yet to sprout a whisker. But
at well over 6 feet, he fit in.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first day on campus,'' he said, ``a girl who I've since
become friends with came up to me and said, `Do you know there's a
15-year-old on campus?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Yes. It's me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lanham found dorm life easy, having attended several sleep-away
camps and study programs, and was never especially tempted to
indulge in alcohol. He also dated several older girls, but they
have usually been from his hometown and were still in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his height _ he now stands 6 feet 9 inches tall _
Lanham seemed destined for the basketball team. But it was not to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer dancing as a physical activity to any sport,'' he
said. ``I enjoy the dancing part of the musicals I've been in.''
They include ``Cabaret,'' in which he was in the chorus, and ``A
Little Night Music,'' for which he oversaw all musical direction.
</P>
<P>
   Lanham, to no one's surprise, concentrated on multiple
disciplines in the classroom. He took enough pre-medical courses to
apply to medical school, as well as a double major in music and
mathematics. At Oxford he intends to study mathematical biology,
which tries to create models to explain and predict the way
diseases spread or populations grow.
</P>
<P>
   He imagines growing up to be a scientist, or a conductor, or
maybe both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really feel I push myself to do any more than I am
able to do,'' he said. ``I've tried to do the best in everything I
apply myself towards.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest Lanham appear superhuman, consider the denouement of a
long-scheduled telephone interview with him. In an audible panic,
he suddenly realized that he had forgotten to charge the battery on
his cordless phone, the only phone in his dorm room. Seconds later,
before he could even finish asking a reporter for his number, the
phone was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at home several days later, his father, Kevin, laughed.
``He's just as typical as any 18-year-old,'' the father said.
``He's very mature, but he messes up, just as we all do, from time
to time.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   An Immigrant: Citadel Cadet Came to the U.S. at 14 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Despite being born and reared in Prague, Petra Lovetinska said
she felt surprisingly prepared for life at The Citadel, the
tradition-steeped military college in Charleston, S.C. Until she
sat down to breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't eat the school grits,'' she said. ``Those could
kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovetinska's unusual path to The Citadel, from which she
graduated this month with the rank of cadet major, began in the
fields near her family's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was as girl as a girl can be, with all the pretty dresses my
mom made for me,'' she said. ``The next day I'd be running in
camouflage, hiding in bushes, playing soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   When her father, who worked for the Czech State Department as a
chauffeur and housekeeper, was transferred to the republic's
embassy in Washington in 1992, Lovetinska moved there, too, at 14.
Unable to say much in English beyond, ``My name is Petra'' and ``I
don't understand,'' Lovetinska enrolled at Woodrow Wilson High
School in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The granddaughter of a lieutenant colonel in the Czech Army,
Lovetinska found herself gravitating toward the Junior ROTC
program, where she rode in a helicopter and spent hours on the air
rifle range.
</P>
<P>
   ``From then, my life sort of changed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Intent on a military career but not yet an American citizen,
Lovetinska learned that The Citadel had no such citizenship
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the first female cadet class _ the trailblazing
first female cadet, Shannon Faulkner, had survived less than a week
before withdrawing, a year earlier _ Lovetinska said she was not
immune from ribbing from her classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to me wasn't really any different than what
happened to the guys,'' said Lovetinska, 22. ``Sometimes the guys
punch each other in the chest, as an acknowledgment of something
good happening to them. For me, they'd sort of hit me in the back
or the leg.''
</P>
<P>
   She took more good-natured abuse, she said, for her heavy
accent. ``It sort of added to the mystique,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her background even won her a role in the annual talent show as
``someone who knocked down the Berlin Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she says she was too young when the wall came down to
really reflect on communism, she has since realized that it was
oppressive for people to ``have to watch yourself and make sure you
have the right friends.''
</P>
<P>
   At The Citadel, Lovetinska said she delighted in studying
political theory _ ``from Plato and Aristotle, all the way to Marx
and Hegel'' _ as well as taking classes in naval science and
history. She was also awarded the Palmetto Medal, for good service.
But she said she absorbed some practical lessons outside the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm getting the y'all and I reckon down,'' she said. ``The
guys tried very hard to teach me how to speak Southern.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Michael Cribb, of Georgetown, S.C., became her
fiance. They are to marry on Dec. 15, 2001, but life is sure to be
difficult: He is in the Army, assigned to Fort Stewart, Ga.; having
attained her citizenship, she is to be commissioned into the Marine
Corps later this year, her assignment unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Among the greatest challenges for Lovetinska was finding the
money to pay The Citadel's tuition and fees, which grew to $18,500
from $15,200 while she was there.
</P>
<P>
   For that, she had some help: Langhorne Motley, an alumnus and
former assistant secretary of state, drafted 113 alumni and other
friends to serve as ``Petra's Plank Holders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like one of the things that only happens in the
movies,'' she said. ``I don't think the Plank Holders realize they
gave me more than just money to go to school. They gave me a whole
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
