<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7479 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-EXCLU     05-27 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-EXCLUSIVE-1095(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISK OF ARMS RACE SEEN IN U.S. MISSILE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL R. GORDON and STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As President Clinton nears a decision on whether to build a
limited national missile defense, U.S. intelligence officials are
warning that such a system could set off a Cold War-style arms race
among China, India and Pakistan, administration officials say.
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. officials have repeatedly said an anti-missile
defense would not be aimed at Beijing, they acknowledge that the
system being designed would significantly undercut or even
neutralize China's small nuclear force.
</P>
<P>
   That could lead China to add to its nuclear arsenal. And if
China built up its force, its regional rival India could do the
same, as could India's rival Pakistan, heightening tensions along
the world's newest nuclear frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario, which intelligence officials are expected to
outline for Clinton in an official intelligence estimate due in
June, has raised questions about the administration's own efforts
to slow the spread of nuclear weapons and the ballistic missiles
needed to launch them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If China increases the number of missiles it has, would India
think it has to increase its missiles?'' asked a senior U.S.
official familiar with the analysis being prepared. ``And if India
increases its missiles, then Pakistan does.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he plans to decide later this year whether to
proceed with a missile defense based on four criteria: missile
threat, technological viability of the program, effect on arms
control, and cost. The response from China and Russia is an
important factor in Clinton's decision.
</P>
<P>
   While newly disclosed defense documents indicate that in the
mid-1990s the Pentagon was researching ways to counter a limited
Chinese missile attack, defense officials say that is no longer the
U.S. policy. The system under consideration, they insist, is
intended to counter relatively small, unsophisticated missile
threats from countries like North Korea, Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, says
Beijing's concerns may be eased not only by reassurances about the
intent of the system but by general progress in economic and
political relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other dimensions to the relationship with the
Chinese that are of far more long-term importance than national
missile defense,'' Berger said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has expended enormous diplomatic energy _
unsuccessfully so far _ trying to persuade the Russians that a
missile defense system would not threaten its much larger strategic
forces. It has made even less headway with the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons. Unlike Russia, which still maintains
a force of more than 5,000 warheads from the Cold War, China has
deployed a minimal nuclear force, which consists primarily of 18
single-warhead land-based CSS-4 missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The argument that the Clinton administration has used with the
Russians _ that a limited missile defense is not a threat, because
it could be easily swamped by a major Russian missile attack _ does
not apply to the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   China's old liquid-fueled CSS-4 missiles are kept at a low state
of alert, with the nuclear warheads stored separately from the
missiles. It also has 12 missiles on a submarine that rarely strays
far from its port, from which it cannot reach the United States.
And China seems convinced that the system would come closer to
neutralizing its current nuclear force than has been publicly
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't deny to the Chinese that the system has some
capability against Chinese missiles, but that is not what it is
designed to do,'' the undersecretary of defense for policy, Walter
Slocombe, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is China's apprehensions about the future course
of relations with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. defense officials make plans according to a rival's
perceived capabilities, not its intent. The Chinese make the same
point, and complain that despite the assurances of the Clinton
administration, they cannot be certain that a future administration
will continue this policy, especially since China has often been
cast as a threat by conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official said: ``The Chinese tell us,
`You may not be directing the system against us, but what about the
next guy? How can we be confident that the next administration may
not have a different policy? It could use the system against us,
just as it does against North Korea.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese fear that the Clinton administration could adjust
and expand its limited defense, which in its first phase will
consist of a battle-management radar site in Alaska and 100
interceptors. And George W. Bush, the Republican candidate, has
said the United States will develop a far more ambitious defensive
system if he is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Still another reason for the Chinese suspicions is that the
Pentagon has previously worked on defensive systems to counter the
Chinese arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   During the Bush administration, the Pentagon instructed TRW
Corp., a U.S. military contractor, to develop ground-based
interceptors that would stop ``limited attacks by China'' using
CSS-4 missiles, according to a 1993 document prepared by the U.S.
Army.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon insists that countering China is no longer a goal,
and its Ballistic Missile Defense Organization declined to say
whether it is still studying ways to intercept Chinese warheads.
</P>
<P>
   But defense officials acknowledge that the planning documents
are constantly updated with the latest science and intelligence
estimates of ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond a direct threat from China, there are other reasons the
Pentagon might want to develop the means to thwart its missile
systems. U.S. intelligence officials cautioned in a 1999 analysis
of ``foreign missile developments'' that Russia and China might
sell countermeasures that the United States is explicitly trying to
counter _ like decoy warheads _ to developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's missile-defense organization has also
acknowledged that the new U.S. defense would have the ``residual
capability'' to defend against the ``unauthorized launch by an
established nuclear power of a few missiles with simple
countermeasures,'' a definition that includes the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system has to be able to respond to more than just North
Korea,'' a defense industry official said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to ease China's concerns, the Clinton administration has
argued that while an anti-missile system might be effective against
China's current arsenal, it would be less so against the updated
arsenal that China has long planned to build.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Clinton administration began seriously
considering anti-missile defenses, the Chinese were planning to
deploy a solid-fuel land-based missile of intercontinental range
that could be moved around on a truck, as well as a new
submarine-launched missile.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence officials project that by 2015, under
Beijing's current modernization plan, the Chinese will have
``several tens'' of new and old missiles that can reach the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   A missile defense, then, would have little effect on the Chinese
strategic modernization, Pentagon officials assert. China, they
add, is more anxious about the provision of anti-missile technology
to Taiwan than it is about a defense to protect the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these arguments, however, Pentagon officials acknowledge
that they know very little about the missiles, warheads and
countermeasures that the Chinese plan to deploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assume the Chinese plan to modernize their force,'' a
senior Pentagon official said. ``It's impossible to say how much it
would be affected by a national missile defense of the kind we're
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Some senior intelligence experts nonetheless believe that a
missile defense would prompt the Chinese to build up their
strategic forces beyond what they had previously planned, in order
to ensure that it remained viable.
</P>
<P>
   Such a response by China would be consistent with orthodox
arms-control theory, which holds that the construction of a missile
defense generally prompts an adversary to build more missiles in
the hope that at least some can get through the defense.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. intelligence community's assessment will be contained
in a new official intelligence report on the responses of foreign
governments to a U.S. missile defense. The White House asked in
December that the report be prepared, so that Clinton could
consider it in making his decision on a missile defense. Officials
caution that the estimate is still being prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would expect them to continue and perhaps even enhance
countermeasures,'' a senior U.S. official said. ``We have projected
that they will have several tens of missiles by 2015. National
Missile Defense might prompt them to do more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be likely,'' the senior official added.
</P>
<P>
   One way for the Chinese to extend their build-up would be to add
new warheads to their old 18 CSS-4s, transforming them from
single-warhead missiles into four-warhead missiles. They might also
double the size of their projected land-based mobile missiles.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Chinese could have more than 100 warheads by
2015, that is more than the 100 interceptors that the United States
plans to deploy in the first phase of its missile defense. The
Chinese, the administration official said, might even deploy more
than 200 warheads if the United States continues to expand its
missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   China's expanded force of nuclear-tipped long-range missiles
might not be directed at India, they say. But it would be a
possibility that the Indians could not ignore, and as a result
India might build up the short-range missiles it used to direct at
China.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials are divided over whether India would
respond in such a way, but the emerging analysis has dramatically
raised the stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to balance its concerns over stability in South Asia
with its interest in missile defense, the Clinton administration is
likely to redouble its negotiating efforts with the Chinese and
perhaps even explore new forms of arms control with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, however, Washington has a difficult job ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
