<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-27 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SPORTSWORLD, MEET SHRINKWORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because our Bob Knight problem was framed as either a moral
question _ Is it wrong to throw chairs, talk dirty and choke your
players? _ or as a pragmatic question _ Is it imprudent for a
university president to jeopardize major donations by dumping an
iconic coach? _ we will probably have to deal with the blustery
bully for a while. Until he slugs someone who really matters, such
as a rich Indiana booster, or has three losing seasons in a row,
Knight will continue to have an impact on young lives in formation
and offer an affirming role model to abusive coaches and corporate
managers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Had our Bob Knight problem been properly framed as a
psychological question _ does this man have a personality disorder
and is it having an adverse emotional impact on others? _ we might
be a lot closer to getting rid of him, or at least getting him into
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   But that would entail having in place an objective, competent
mental health presence in SportsWorld. At the moment, what we have
is a gaggle of performance enhancers, personnel evaluators and the
head-shrinking equivalent of the stereotypical orthopedic surgeon
who thinks he is a coach with an M.D. (``Snap out of that
depression, Jimbo; this is the seventh game.'') No brain, no gain.
</P>
<P>
   This current grist for thelipsite(at)aol.com comes from a week
at the American Psychiatric Association's annual meeting, in
Chicago, earlier this month. The key symposium for me, numbingly
entitled, ``Psychopharmacological Approaches to the Athletic and
Exercise Population,'' was provocative and groundbreaking, and
poorly attended. Just as psychiatry has yet to crack SportsWorld's
taboos against athletes appearing emotionally needy, so jock
culture has yet to become an area of serious study in ShrinkWorld.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Ronald Kamm of New Jersey, who led the symposium, thinks
that a bridge between the two worlds can be built by the likes of
Julie Krone, the recently retired Hall of Fame jockey; Cincinnati
Reds pitcher Pete Harnisch; and Jack Farrell, a champion skeet
shooter, talking unselfconsciously about their therapy and
psychiatric drugs. They were all paid by the drug companies to talk
about their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch was in spring training with the Mets in 1997 when he
became depressed. Interviewed by Kamm in a 16-minute video,
Harnisch said that Mets management responded poorly to his illness,
but that after seven months of talk therapy and antidepressants (he
started with Prozac, was helped by Paxil) he got his game back.
Since then, he said, a number of players have approached him for
advice and to share stories.
</P>
<P>
   Farrell, 67, a retired engineer, went into depression after he
quit smoking cigarettes. Anger management was one of his main
problems, he said; Paxil made him a better shooter because ``I'm
calmer and I don't flinch.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone's story of her reluctance to ask for help even after she
felt suicidal and her eventual return to self after talk therapy
and Zoloft evoked dozens of phone calls and e-mail messages to
thelipsite(at)aol.com. Most were from other athletes, elite and
recreational, sharing their stories. They were thrilled that she
called her condition a ``mental illness,'' a step toward
de-stigmatizing it. There were quibbles. A noted
psychopharmacologist, Dr. Arthur Rifkin of Hillside Hospital in
Queens, N.Y., thought that two years of talk therapy before taking
drugs was too long (Krone's psychiatrists had vainly urged her to
start sooner). Bob Carolla of the National Alliance for the
Mentally Ill pointed out that the football players Alonzo Spellman
and Earl Campbell have also spoken out publicly about their
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago symposium was sponsored by the International Society
for Sport Psychiatry, a nine-year-old group of about 80 members
searching for its place in an arena dominated by the aggressive
marketing of psychologists who promise to raise your batting
average and lower your golf score. In papers that were presented,
Dr. Antonia Baum of George Washington University, Dr. Ira Glick of
Stanford and Dr. Robert Burton of Northwestern called for research
into the effect of psychiatric drugs on ``finely tuned'' elite
athletes, and a re-examination of the banning of substances that
might treat mood or anxiety disorders. Burton is also co-editor,
with Dr. Daniel Begel, of the newly published book ``Sport
Psychiatry'' (Norton).
</P>
<P>
   A sexier symposium, on Coach Knight or even Latrell Sprewell,
might have drawn better against such competing offerings at the
same time that night as the movies ``Life is Beautiful'' and ``Good
Will Hunting,'' followed by psychiatric evaluations. And a
Knight-Spree entry might have been more on the mark; the emotional
impact of jock culture is incalculable.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there was an independent body of SportsWorld therapists
available to help the needy, one can assume that neither Knight nor
Indiana would sit for a session. Psychiatrists tend to be too lofty
to give distant diagnoses, probably a good thing, but some general
speculation about Knight's lack of control (or calculated use of
abuse?) might be instructive. There is good video available.
</P>
<P>
   No video exists of Sprewell choking P.J. Carlesimo, but that
would have been a perfect episode for analysis, assuming the
National Basketball Association could stand the psychiatric
spotlight on what might have been the case of an emotionally
troubled player pushed too far by a coach with unresolved issues of
his own. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
