<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7496 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ULSTER-UNIONIST-TRIMS     05-27 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULSTER-UNIONIST-TRIMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER UNIONIST BACK JOINT ROLE WITH IRA ALLIES
</HEADLINE>
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Northern Ireland's largest
Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, voted on Saturday by a
narrow margin to return to a power-sharing administration with
their Catholic rivals in Sinn Fein, the political representatives
of the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome meant that governing of the province, which had been
shifted back to London reluctantly in February with the suspension
of the new home rule government, will revert to Belfast within
days, and that the continually imperiled Northern Ireland peace
accord will have survived another precarious lapse.
</P>
<P>
   A motion that was deliberately drafted to be a vote on the
continuing leadership of the Unionists' leader, David Trimble, won
the support of 53 percent of the 862 delegates of the party's
ruling council. Trimble, under attack by a growing number of
hard-liners, had said the balloting would not be a ``back me or
sack me'' vote, but that is what it became when the wording of the
resolution asked simply whether people did or did not support ``the
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is perfectly obvious, as you can see, that we have
stretched ourselves remarkably,'' Trimble said at a news conference
as delegates streamed out of the modern glass-walled Waterfront
Hall on the Lagan River, which boosters hold up as a symbol of a
future in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble had had to wage a strenuous campaign to overcome
resistance in his party, and he told reporters, ``It is obvious
there are limits to how much more we can be stretched.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the disappointment the last time he had held a news
conference at the same spot, in November, after winning his party's
support for agreeing to joint rule with Sinn Fein the first time.
That government was suspended by Britain after only nine weeks when
the IRA failed to respond to the Unionists' decision with expected
moves to begin disarming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have operated in reliance on promises made by the
republican movement, and let there be absolutely no doubt this time
that my colleagues and I will hold the republican movement to the
promises they made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The promise was a pledge by the IRA on May 6 to permit
inspections of its secret arms dumps and to ``completely and
verifiably'' put its arms ``beyond use.'' The earlier failure by
the guerrilla organization to address disarmament had blocked
progress in putting into place the provisions of the peace
settlement of April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the growing opposition in Trimble's own party, bolstered by
the hard-line Democratic Unionists led by the Rev. Ian Paisley,
mounted a successful challenge that obliged Trimble to postpone the
meeting, originally scheduled last Saturday, to this Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the vote, Britain's Northern Ireland secretary,
Peter Mandelson, signed the order to restore home rule. The 10-man
cabinet is to meet on Thursday, and the first session of the
Northern Ireland Assembly on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,600 people have died in the past three decades of
sectarian violence. The 1998 accord is an effort to balance the
interests of pro-British Protestants and pro-Irish Catholics and
turn their dispute from a violent one into a political one.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble on Saturday said he expected to see action ``within
weeks'' on the IRA's pledge to open its hidden arsenals to
inspection. The two monitors, the former Finnish president, Martti
Ahtisaari, and the former general secretary of the African National
Congress, Cyril Ramaphosa, visited Belfast earlier this month for
briefings on their duties.
</P>
<P>
   They said they would make repeated trips to arms dumps to verify
that weapons are locked away and disassembled, and would report
their findings to John De Chastelain of Canada, a retired general
and head of an international commission overseeing the disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, there has been fevered campaigning by
Trimble supporters and opponents, who saw in Saturday's decision
not only a reckoning for the peace process but a crossroads for
their party.
</P>
<P>
   Across the province there were door-to-door visits, saturation
telephone canvassing and leafleting that left rural mailboxes
bulging. Some party members from farm areas complained of the
aggressive tactics of the anti-agreement campaigners and said they
preferred the quiet persuasion of Trimble.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional appeal to the delegates at the closed meeting,
Trimble warned that a ``No'' vote would consign the party to the
political wilderness and turn the province over to republicans and
nationalists. He urged self-confidence, and a test of the IRA
promises.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-agreement faction, unable to base its opposition solely
on the arms issue once the IRA had made its offer, broadened its
demands by focusing on cherished symbols of national identity: A
debate that had been confined to weapons widened to embrace issues
like whether the British or Irish flag flies above government
buildings, what name the new police force bears and what emblems
appear on police badges and caps.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly sensitive is the matter of what to call the Royal
Ulster Constabulary, which is 93 percent Protestant and enjoys
little trust from Catholics. An international commission headed by
Chris Patten, the former governor of Hong Kong, recommended a new
force with more balanced recruitment and the name Northern Ireland
Police Service, but the hard-liners insisted that the RUC title _
whose reference to ``Royal'' denotes allegiance to the United
Kingdom _ be kept.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson tried to help Trimble's cause by saying that he would
keep the RUC name in the incorporation deeds of the new force; he
also promised other refinements to the Patten report to meet
Unionist objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who attacked the agreement played on the fears that it
would diminish their identity and undermine their tradition,''
Mandelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did no such thing. It cherished diversity, securing British
identity while recognizing and respecting nationalists and
republicans who did not share that identity.''
</P>
<P>
   In the political nomenclature of Ulster, republicans and
nationalists, almost all of whom are Catholic, are those who want
to see the province ultimately become part of Ireland, while
unionists, who are largely Protestant, want to see it remain part
of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's concessions to Trimble on these points has cost the
current support of the Sinn Fein, whose president, Gerry Adams,
said he could no longer recommend the formation of the new police
force to his members. It is a crucial consideration for the future,
because whatever the new service is called, it will not be
effective unless it can attract Catholics and start to redress the
imbalance in its members.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Polling by Belfast newspapers showed the membership of the
Ulster Unionists at the district level to be more accepting of
political coexistence with Catholics than the membership of the
ruling council. Trimble has said he plans reforms to do away with
bloc votes on the council held by a militant youth wing and the
traditional Orange Order, who have sided with the hard-liners.
Saturday's personal endorsement should give him the freedom to take
those actions and reduce the opposition to his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The rejectionists' challenge gained strength this time because
it was led openly by Trimble's most forceful opponent in the party,
Jeffrey Donaldson, 37, a member of parliament who has coveted
Trimble's leadership position and appeared to be seizing this
opportunity to wrest it away. But Saturday the delegates did not
warm to his criticisms of Trimble, and persuaded him to withdraw an
amendment proposing an alternative plan.
</P>
<P>
   The final tally showed that Trimble lost the support of some
people who had voted with him in the past, but also picked up
backing in surprising places.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sean O'Callaghan, a convicted former IRA killer who is the
guerrilla army's highest-ranking defector, came forward to tell
Unionist gatherings this past week that he was convinced that the
IRA's new promises on arms constituted the long-awaited pledge from
the republican side that ``the war is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the power of a history lesson among the
tradition-minded Ulster Protestants, O'Callaghan said, ``If in 1940
Churchill had allowed foreign inspectors to inspect Royal Air Force
planes and various installations and report back to Nazi Germany, I
don't think anyone in Britain would have believed that he seriously
intended to go to war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
