<HEADER>
A7499 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-WESTPOINT-670&AMP;AD     05-27 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-WESTPOINT-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 GORE CRITICIZES BUSH FOR POSITION ON MISSILES
</HEADLINE>
  By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ Vice President Al Gore, speaking Saturday at
the U.S. Military Academy, criticized Gov. George W. Bush's support
for a national missile defense system along with a reduction in
nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``An approach that combines serious unilateral reductions with
an attempt to build a massive defensive system will create
instability and thus undermine our security,'' Gore told the West
Point graduates at the academy's Michie Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuclear unilateralism will hinder, rather than help, arms
control,'' Gore said before handing out diplomas to the 944
graduates in dress uniforms and white gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reductions alone do not guarantee stability,'' he said. ``It
is how reductions are made and how they interact with defensive
systems that makes the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who became a specialist in arms control after he was
elected to Congress in the mid-1970s, said: ``Reductions have to be
carried out in a way that reduces the risk of confrontation. If
you're not careful, you could have a reduction of missiles and a
more dangerous world.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Feurth, Gore's longtime national security adviser, said
that Gore's comments Saturday were based on his long-standing
principles and the fact that President Clinton was going to Russia
next week, and that they were not intended as a response to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Feurth told reporters after Saturday's speech: ``Everything he
said about strategic stability and so on came straight out of
things that he was writing and talking about in the House of
Representatives and as a senator when he first began to enter the
field of arms control, and it is mainly triggered by the fact that
the president is about to leave for Moscow in a matter of a few
days to engage in exactly this set of issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speech is not political, the speech is policy-based. The
ideas that the vice president presented have been in his record for
a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not mention Bush, his rival for the presidency, by
name. But Bush proposed just such a plan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was invited to the academy in his capacity as vice
president and his commencement speech was billed an official
vice-presidential event, not a campaign appearance. As such, he
told reporters on Friday night, his remarks on the academy grounds
would not be ``political'' in nature.
</P>
<P>
   But in a discussion with reporters on Friday night on Air Force
II on his way to Newburgh, N.Y., from Memphis, Tenn., Gore sharply
criticized Bush's proposal. He said it would reignite the arms
race, and by saying so, he seemed to ensure that his differences
with Bush would be part of the news media's coverage Saturday. His
comments Saturday were less pointed, but against the backdrop of
his comments on Friday night, his message was unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   His comments on Friday constituted Gore's first public reaction
to Bush's proposal, which the governor delivered in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing Bush for opposing the comprehensive test ban treaty,
which the Senate defeated last fall, Gore said on Friday: ``If you
kill the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty that our country wrote and
tested all over the world and give a green light to more nuclear
testing all over the world and then send a signal that we're going
to concentrate not on deterring an attack with retaliation but
rather this hugely expensive Star Wars approach, that is a formula
for encouraging more offensive missiles aimed at the United States,
more nuclear testing around the world and a reignited arms race.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at the graduation exercise, Gore outlined the Clinton
administration's efforts toward creating a national missile defense
system that would protect all 50 states from a limited attack. ``We
believe, however, that it is essential to do this in a way that
does not destroy the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty,'' Gore said.
``The ABM Treaty is the cornerstone of strategic stability in our
relationship with Russia.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   What Bush proposed would almost surely entail violating the ABM
Treaty of 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said in his speech on Tuesday at the National Press Club:
``While deterrence remains the first line of defense against
nuclear attack, the standoff of the Cold War was born of a
different time. Yet almost a decade after the end of the Cold War,
our nuclear policy still resides in that already distant past.''
</P>
<P>
   He proposed measures that would include building a defensive
system that would cover all 50 states and could be extended to
protect allies in Europe, the Middle East and Asia. In addition to
holding out the possibility of large unilateral arms cuts, he said
most American nuclear weapons should be removed from hair-trigger
alert status.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the cadets, Gore said of Clinton's Moscow
visit: ``This is an historic meeting. The president should leave
with the full support of the American people,'' a subtle reminder
to Republicans that partisan differences over national security
historically stop at the water's edge when the president travels
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The stage at Michie Stadium is one of the most prestigious
forums in military history, and the only political figures allowed
to speak from it are the president, vice president and the speaker
of the House of Representatives. This has drawn criticism in recent
days from former Sen. Bob Dole, who had announced his presidential
candidacy in 1995 and was invited _ then disinvited _to speak
because his appearance was deemed political.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
