<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7507 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-RIDGE-CONSERVATIVES-A     05-27 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIDGE-CONSERVATIVES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDGE DERIDES CRITICS ON RELIGIOUS RIGHT, BUT LIKES BEING ON BUSH
SHORT LIST
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. _ Of all the things he is being called lately by
his critics, ``liberal'' and ``dove'' make Gov. Tom Ridge laugh out
loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet the only combat ever seen by the guy who wrote that
has been in front of a Nintendo machine,'' said Ridge, his
credentials as a Bronze Star combat veteran of Vietnam unsullied by
the slings and arrows now pelting him from within his own
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam-fighting experience in Vietnam of the husky,
55-year-old Pennsylvania governor comes in handy these days. He is
being targeted by the social conservative right for being a Roman
Catholic who unapologetically favors a woman's right to choose
abortion, yet remains prominently featured on a list of potential
running mates of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the putative
Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor says there is no litmus test, and I believe
him,'' Ridge said, referring to the simmering abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   But social and religious conservatives see things differently,
and have issued stern warnings to Bush of dire consequences in
November if he picks someone like Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The base in the Republican Party is pro-life,'' James C.
Dobson, the conservative religious leader, said on Wednesday. ``You
can't win without that base.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge, his abortion rights stand firmly defying party platform
dogma, remains the most mentioned prospective running mate. He set
a Republican record for this heavily Democratic state with a
780,000-vote victory margin in his 1998 re-election. A Bush-Ridge
ticket might well deliver this critical battleground, the
fifth-largest state in electoral votes, to the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In two elections, Ridge has shown considerable crossover
attraction among Democratic voters. He has the power to garner up
to 30 percent of them, according to polls _ a factor that Bush must
weigh as he charts a centrist strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans also note that Bush had to be more sensitive
to the nation's large Catholic vote after his controversial speech
in the South Carolina primary at Bob Jones University, a campus
that critics denounce as anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   And while Ridge's support of abortion rights might signal a
harsh party split for some Republicans, others said his candidacy
as vice president would draw more women to the Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this wonderful speculation,'' remarked Ridge, his smile
broad but fatalistic as he noted that the decision on a running
mate was entirely Bush's to make after a long process involving ``a
lot of other people,'' in the Texas governor's words.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if? What if?'' asked Ridge, happily teasing himself as
much as his boosters and critics. He seems to be enjoying the
freedom of having no say in the matter as he looks forward to being
the state host at the Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But as the vice-presidential question is debated, conservative
critics in National Review and other publications, nettled by his
support of abortion rights, are busily vetting Ridge's 12-year
record in Congress to argue that, even beyond the abortion issue,
he is not an authentic conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protectionist,'' another charge made against Ridge, brings
more open laughter here in the executive chamber of the governor,
who noted that he was a card-carrying member of the hod-carriers
union when he was a college student who worked in construction
during the summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for Nafta, in Congress,'' Ridge said, bemused at what
he was reading lately from conservative polemicists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, this gets comical,'' he continued. He repeatedly used
the word ``conservative'' to characterize himself in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Only the November election, he said, with all the variables
brought to the voters by the candidates and their campaigns, might
settle the question of whether the Republican Party is ready for an
abortion rights candidate on the ticket beside the anti-abortion
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the decibel level may be going down a little bit on
this issue,'' said Ridge, whose political career in Pennsylvania
has not measurably suffered from his support of abortion rights,
even after his being obliquely criticized by his bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think we're done with the very important struggle
we're having within the party as to how to deal with it,'' he
continued. ``Certainly, my friend Governor Bush disagrees with me,
and a majority of the delegates at the convention probably disagree
with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're not going to change the platform. But it's
interesting to note there are some people in the party who, instead
of defeating Al Gore, would suggest that if the No. 2, whether me
or somebody else, doesn't share their belief on abortion, they
might abandon the party.''
</P>
<P>
   One quarter where Ridge is bolstered in his insistence that he
is a true-blue conservative is across the Statehouse, within the
Democratic minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Ridge is a perfect fit for George Bush,'' said state Sen.
Christine Tartaglione, speaking in her role as the state Democratic
chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``His actions speak louder than his words,'' Tartaglione said,
contending that Ridge, in the state's recent tax cuts of more than
$1 billion, favored big business interests at the expense of needy
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all wait for Tom Ridge's leadership,'' she said scornfully.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's supporters quickly cite a raft of new social
welfare and education laws to argue that he is the very model of
the ``compassionate conservative'' that Bush has proclaimed as the
cornerstone of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And Ridge has just the sort of paradoxical touches in his resume
that politicians dream of.
</P>
<P>
   His parents were postwar strivers; his father, a Navy veteran,
worked two jobs to finance his children's parochial school tuition.
Up from public housing, the family bought a modest house in Erie,
that is still home to the governor's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My DNA is a little confused,'' Ridge said lightly in noting
that his father was a fervid blue-collar Democrat while his mother
was a no less fervid Republican ward worker. The family dinner
table was a forum that respected politics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Harvard after winning a needs-based
scholarship and, while studying at Dickinson Law School in
Pennsylvania was drafted into the Army and served in the infantry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dwell on Vietnam; I draw on it,'' said Ridge who, with
a similar margin of removal, recalls the feverish anti-war protests
at Harvard as a fascinating backdrop that did not draw him away
from his studies.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As the attacks by social conservatives heighten, the governor
does not hesitate to defend his view on abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult personal decision that has enormous
emotional, psychological, intensely physical and oftentimes
religious dimensions to it,'' he said. ``This is a tough decision
for people to make. One of the things I talk about is trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to whether I would place ultimate responsibility
in that very difficult personal decision, with so many dimensions
to it, in the hands of government _ I mean, some of the people in
my party would criminalize it! _ or leave it up to the individual,
leave it up to the woman.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the intramural sniping, the old combat sergeant admits
he enjoys the extra political notice and power that seems to come
with the vice-presidential speculation, however fruitless it may
prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the what-if factor,'' Ridge said, describing a state of
``irrational exuberance'' that he is experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a heck of a ride,'' the governor added. ``I've already
got a great job, and I'm going to help my old friend George Bush
get elected president. And you know? I think he can carry
Pennsylvania without me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
