<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISTRACTED-DRIVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELL PHONES PROLIFERATE ON HIGHWAYS, RAISING SAFETY CONCERNS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Pa., N.Y.)  By JON NORDHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As millions of Americans travel this Memorial Day weekend they
are joined by family, friends and what has become for many an
indispensable companion on a car trip, the cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of other drivers will also be on the highways
equipped with wireless and Internet hookups in vehicles that can
deliver faxes to the driver's seat, provide maps to neighborhood
streets or faraway destinations, or route hungry travelers to good
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The information highway is merging with the nation's highways at
breakneck speed, and safety experts fear that with so many
distractions _ even television _ the devices may lead to an
increase in traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Some law enforcement officials say cell phones have become the
latest, and most common, distraction on the highway, and some have
begun to note an increase in the number of accidents caused by
drivers using cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   But safety researchers say no reliable data exist that show cell
phone usage by motorists to be any more distracting than tuning car
radios or drinking coffee.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the proliferation of cell phone use by drivers has
raised the concerns of public safety officials and the
telecommunications industry. A few communities, but no states, have
banned the use of phones while driving.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, in a report
two years ago, recommended more research about cell phones in cars,
more education of drivers about their use and tracking by the
police when phones are thought to be involved in accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officers say their experience tells them that
drivers are violating common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the communications found in the office and home are
becoming commonplace in cars and trucks and there's no question
they can be very distracting,'' said Col. Charles C. Hall, director
of the Florida Highway Patrol. ``Put a telephone in the hand of a
very aggressive driver and you have a greater problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry estimates that Americans now own more than 92
million cell phones, up from 69 million in 1998 and about 6 million
10 years ago. Surveys show that four out of five cell phone owners
will place or receive calls while driving. One out of four,
however, phone frequently while driving and a high percentage of
these are heavy, daily users.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the wireless industry and state governments need to do is
to constantly reach out to consumers and tell them that when they
get behind the wheel of a car they must drive responsibly,'' said
Tom Wheeler, president of the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association, a trade organization in Washington representing about
400 manufacturers and providers of wireless equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my pet peeves is when individuals apply for a driver's
license they have to know how many feet they have to park away from
a driveway but absolutely nothing about the safe use of a phone
while driving,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler said state governments have rightly rejected legislation
to restrict the use of hand-held phones by drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need more laws,'' he said. ``But we do need a lot
more in the way of public education.''
</P>
<P>
   Bills have been prepared in more than 20 states, including New
York, to limit cell phone use on the roads but all have failed.
</P>
<P>
   But similar measures keep popping up in pockets of local
government. Hilltown Township, Pa., a suburb north of Philadelphia,
is one of only a handful of communities that have laws controlling
phone calls from a car. Louis A. Mosiello, a Westchester County,
N.Y., legislator from Yonkers, is pressing for an ordinance in the
county to ban hand-held phones while driving.
</P>
<P>
   Public awareness and political action are temporarily heightened
at news of isolated incidents that link cell phones with highway
accidents. Robert Carratelli, 43, of West Palm Beach, Fla., was
convicted this month of six counts of vehicular homicide in
connection with an accident involving cell phone use last year in
Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   Phone company records showed Carratelli, an advertising
executive, was on his cell phone at the approximate time when his
speeding Mercedes ran a red light at 76 miles an hour and plowed
into a car carrying three retired couples on their way to a
concert. All six, who had retired to Florida from the New York City
area, died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
