<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Superstar Pitcher Who Might Have Been a Yankee
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of November 1993, general managers were
meeting in Naples, Fla., and the Yankees' general manager, Gene
Michael, was there in quest of a starting pitcher. Among others,
Michael had an eye on a young right-hander employed by the Los
Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene Michael was one of the guys most interested in Pedro,''
recalled Fred Claire, who was then the Dodgers' general manager.
``He really was the only one who was inquiring. He had a great
interest. I said: `Gene, I don't want to talk to you about who you
might offer. I'm not going to trade him. He's a great young man and
has a great upside.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No pitcher ever had a greater upside than Pedro Martinez, the
dominating pitcher, who is scheduled to start for the Boston Red
Sox against the Yankees Sunday night. Had Michael been successful
in prying Martinez from the Dodgers, he could have been pitching
for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   As the Dodgers' plans developed, they did trade Martinez, less
than three weeks after Michael expressed his serious interest. They
traded him to the Montreal Expos because the Expos offered them a
second baseman, Delino DeShields. Jody Reed, who had been
Montreal's second baseman in 1993 and had become a free agent,
rejected an offer he shouldn't have refused. To his great regret,
Reed said no to a three-year, $7.8 million contract and later had
to accept a contract with Milwaukee for $350,000 for one year. As
much as Reed's decision hurt him economically, it hurt the Dodgers
competitively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, it turned out to be a terrible deal for us,''
Claire said. Had they not needed a second baseman, he added, he
would, as he told Michael, not have traded Martinez. But even given
that need, Claire said: ``What I didn't put enough weight on was
the spirit of Pedro. I recognized it but didn't put a high enough
value on it. This young man has something that few people I
encounter has and I should have recognized that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette, the general manager who acquired Martinez for the
Expos, left Montreal about two months later and became the Boston
general manager. He reluctantly left Martinez behind but was intent
on getting him again. He did, four years to the day after he
obtained him from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro has always been my favorite player,'' Duquette said,
``because of his unique skills and his personality and his
competitiveness. We are so lucky to have him. We owe a great debt
to the Expo organization. He was a gift to the franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beattie, Duquette's successor in Montreal, didn't want to
trade Martinez, but he explained why he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably could have paid him,'' Beattie said, ``but he
wasn't going to sign with us until we did other things to show we
were going to be competitive. We couldn't afford to do those other
things. We couldn't convince him, so we felt the best thing to do
was move him before he became a free agent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox won the arm of the right-hander by offering Carl
Pavano, a good young pitcher, and Tony Armas Jr., a minor league
pitcher they had received from the Yankees for Mike Stanley three
months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple clubs turned us down when we asked for their
players,'' Beattie said. ``I'm sure some of those organizations
look at it now and say, `How could we say no?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees wouldn't trade Eric Milton for Martinez (they sent
him to Minnesota for Chuck Knoblauch less than three months later),
and Cleveland declined to give up Bartolo Colon, who is in their
starting rotation now.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie can still feel the pain from trading Martinez. ``I
definitely would have loved to have kept him,'' he said. ``He's got
quality pitches, he's a great competitor, he's an intelligent
player and he works hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette credited Martinez with turning the Red Sox into a
legitimate contender. The Red Sox have reached the postseason in
each of the pitcher's first two seasons with them and appear to be
headed there again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who has won the Cy Young award in each league, gained
a permanent spot in postseason lore last October by pitching six
hitless innings of relief against Cleveland in the fifth and
deciding game of their division series. He followed that remarkable
performance by holding the Yankees to two hits in seven innings
after the Yankees had won the first two games of the league
championship series. The Yankees, however, won the next two games,
assuring that they wouldn't see Martinez in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a situation we certainly wanted to do everything we
could to avoid,'' David Cone said. ``I don't think any team in
baseball would want that scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's playoff performance wasn't even his best against the
Yankees last year. In September he struck out 17 and allowed just
one hit, a home run by Chili Davis. That gave him a two-start
record of 29 strikeouts and three hits allowed in 16 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could've won without any fielders behind him that night,''
Paul O'Neill said of the September game.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez enters Sunday night's game with the lowest earned run
average (1.19) and the lowest opponents' batting average (.167) in
the major leagues. Last season he had the majors' lowest ERA and
was three points away from having the lowest batting average
against.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what Sandy Koufax was like during his incredible
five-year run that everyone talks about,'' Cone said, ``but Pedro's
having that type of run, maybe even better. He's having arguably
one of the best runs of all time. One year, two year, three year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Giambi of Oakland, one of this season's most productive
hitters, called Martinez's pitches ``electric.'' Larry Rothschild,
the Tampa Bay manager and a former pitcher and pitching coach, said
Martinez's fastball, curve and changeup are outstanding
individually and collectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an at-bat against him,'' Giambi said, ``you get one pitch
to hit and if you don't hit it, you're heading back to the
dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Giambi said that he likes to face Martinez. ``It's such a
challenge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild, too, acknowledged that he enjoyed watching Martinez
work even if he beats the Devil Rays. ``I almost hate to admit
that,'' the manager said, ``but he's so good at what he does you
have to sit back and realize you're watching one of the best there
is and take solace from that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Making Baseballs
</P>
<P>
   Major league officials were in Costa Rica last week touring the
Rawlings factory that makes major league baseballs. Orlando
Hernandez was there two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I visited twice, once before I signed and once after I
signed,'' said the Yankees pitcher, who lived in Costa Rica
immediately after defecting from Cuba. ``I've never seen anything
like that. I saw it in Cuba, but it wasn't the same. The quality of
the materials is better in Costa Rica. What impressed me the most
was the way they make a baseball. It took me 35 minutes to make a
baseball myself. The boss said to me, `You may be a good
ballplayer, but you don't know anything about making baseballs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who apparently is the only major league player who
has visited the factory, was asked if the ball he made was juiced.
He laughed and said through a translator, ``If the baseballs were
made the way I made it, there would be no home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Indians' Pitching Woes
</P>
<P>
   For several years the Cleveland Indians tried unsuccessfully to
secure a No. 1 pitcher. Last winter they finally succeeded, luring
Chuck Finley into the fold as a free agent. The pitching gods,
however, are still laughing at them.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day earlier this month, two starters, Charles Nagy
and Jaret Wright, and a reliever, Ricardo Rincon, went on the
disabled list. Last week another reliever, Paul Shuey, joined them.
Wright was scheduled to return and start Saturday night, but Nagy
had bone chips removed from his right elbow and is expected to be
out for eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians used two rookies in their place last week. Paul
Rigdon dazzled the Yankees, shutting them out on two hits in his
seven-inning effort, but Tim Drew, brother of J.D., lasted only
three batters into the second inning against Detroit, giving up
five runs (three earned).
</P>
<P>
   Vidro's Hitting Soars
</P>
<P>
   When Jose Vidro first reached the major leagues, in 1997, he
replaced an injured Vladimir Guerrero on the Montreal roster. Last
week he supplanted the highly talented Guerrero as the Expos'
leading hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The unheralded second baseman, who in his first full major
league season last year batted .304, reached .399 last week and
then entered Saturday night's game in San Diego at a league-leading
.391 to Guerrero's .381.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked him as a hitter,'' Jim Beattie, the Expos'
general manager, said. ``He reminds me of Edgar Martinez in his
knowledge of hitting, the way he uses his hands to hit, the way he
uses the whole field to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Vidro had hit eight home runs, Beattie added,
``Edgar didn't have a lot of power when he came up, but he
developed it at the big league level. Jose has a chance to hit 20
to 30 home runs depending on how hot he gets. He has a great
approach to hitting and he's a smart player.''
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old switch-hitter also was leading the league in
hits (70) and multihit games (22) and was tied for the lead in
doubles (17). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
