<HEADLINE>
FURIOUS DEBATE RAGES ON SLEEPING IN PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CRUZ, Calif. _ Every night, the people with no roofs to
sleep under sit on the benches along downtown Pacific Avenue. They
wait until the neon signs in the pubs go dark and the stream of
cars cruising down the street becomes a trickle. Then they take
their nighttime places.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe up against a doorway or behind the Safeway supermarket
trash bins, or, after a bit of a hike, in the woods, deep enough so
that the unleashed dogs won't sniff them out.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out where to sleep, an old-timer named Daryl said the
other day, is hard work. Not only must you be up and out by dawn.
``Where you start out,'' he said, ``isn't necessarily where you end
up the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because like so many cities all over the country, Santa
Cruz bans sleeping on the streets _ or, in fact, in cars, in parks,
under trees. But the police let the sleepers alone unless someone
complains. Still, spend a few days in one spot, Daryl said, and the
complaints come.
</P>
<P>
   But now Santa Cruz is defying the national trend in moving
homeless people out of public places. The City Council has voted to
create ``safe sleeping zones'' for homeless people in two
industrial parks. The sleeping zones, where people could sleep in
their vehicles or on the ground with their blankets or sleeping
bags, will have trash bins, portable toilets and a police officer
dedicated to patrolling those areas.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council passed the measure on Tuesday on a preliminary
4-2 vote (with one member absent) and is expected to pass a final
vote in two weeks. The measure will then take effect on a trial run
in mid-July, height of this beach-and-boardwalk town's tourist
season. In November, city voters will decide a ballot measure that
seeks to make the zones permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, proposed by Mayor Keith Sugar after intense public
pressure from a group that has been trying to have the sleeping ban
lifted for years (most recently by waging a five-month hunger
strike) comes with some restrictions. People could legally sleep in
the zones between 9 p.m. and 7 a.m. Structures, tents, or other
camping accessories like stoves would continue to be illegal.
People would not be allowed within 300 feet of any home. And after
three nights in any one spot, they would have to move to another
spot at least 500 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities, including Berkeley and Eugene, Ore., have tried to
designate sleeping zones, only to abandon efforts when the zones
became unmanageable. But Santa Cruz, Sugar said, will be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a situation where people can come from out of town
and bed down,'' Sugar told skeptics after the vote. ``It will give
the homeless a place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But others are not so sure. Michael Rotkin, a self-described
``socialist-feminist'' who was absent for the vote but would have
voted no, said the measure will only undermine support for homeless
people. ``I've knocked on three-quarters of the doors in Santa
Cruz,'' he said, ``and the single biggest issue that people bring
up spontaneously is, what are you going to do about all the bums on
the streets? And these are political progressives.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Cruz, which is at least as politically left-wing as
Berkeley, has publicly agonized over its public sleeping ban for
years. Time and again the City Council has discussed the idea of
softening the law. Each time, people have objected. Business owners
here would complain that customers would be scared off by
panhandlers or drug users or the merely truly needy, tattered and
torn. Others wondered whether legalizing public sleeping would make
Santa Cruz one big camping ground.
</P>
<P>
   Still others objected on philosophical grounds. Shouldn't Santa
Cruz be helping these people off the streets rather than helping
them stay on them?
</P>
<P>
   The city, with 52,000 residents, offers an array of services for
its homeless population of 750 to 1,500 people, including a center
with free showers, meals, voice mail and lockers, schools for
homeless children. A number of churches and other nonprofit
organizations also provide services.
</P>
<P>
   But the city lacks shelter beds. David Norse, a proponent of
ending the sleeping ban, said that recent studies showed that
homeless people were four to 12 times as likely as housed people to
be the victims of attacks. The sleeping ban puts the homeless
``physically in peril,'' and ``throws all law into disrespect,'' he
said, because it means that the homeless are encouraged to break
laws in order to sleep at night.
</P>
<P>
   The measure to ease the ban, proponents say, will also clear the
homeless people out of downtown, making it easier on the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But summer seems to have a way of doing that too. The tourists
on their long Memorial Day weekend were out in force on Pacific
Avenue on Friday night, spilling out of the bars and hanging out on
the benches, and for some reason no one could say, there was not a
homeless person to be found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
