<HEADER>
A7523 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      05-27 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pacers Are Taking Steps to Secure Their Future
</P>
<P>
   With each jab step, each shot from beyond the arc, Reggie
Miller's future grows more secure, just as the future of his
Indiana Pacers teammates grows more secure.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, who appeared to need a roster overhaul after the
younger, athletic Knicks jumped over them in last season's Eastern
Conference finals, have aged more gracefully than Dick Clark; more
gracefully than even Donnie Walsh could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of laughing about it,'' said Walsh, the Pacers' team
president, ``because everybody has been telling me for three or
four years, you know, `You guys are going to have to break up the
team.' I never really felt that way. That's why I'm really proud of
how they played, because I wasn't as sure this year as I was in
years past.''
</P>
<P>
   The playoff performances of Miller, Mark Jackson, Jalen Rose and
Austin Croshere have all but ensured Indiana's makeup for the next
few seasons. Walsh held off signing Miller and Jackson to
extensions, a development that caused a rift between the team and
its veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Only a month ago, Jackson's return was thought to be a huge
question mark. But as the Pacers try to advance to the finals for
the first time in the team's NBA history, the improvisational point
guard seems a good bet to return as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to re-sign Reggie,'' Walsh said. ``I just
didn't want to do an extension before I saw what the team was
because we had too many free agents. I've already made up my mind
on that. I would bring them all back.''
</P>
<P>
   With six of his top eight players eligible for free agency, the
notion of detonating the roster in the off-season was a
possibility. ``I didn't want to sign up a bunch of guys and then
the team goes down and you're stuck,'' Walsh said last month.
</P>
<P>
   But with Miller putting up impressive numbers in the playoffs _
he shot down Milwaukee in Game 5 of the first round, erupting for
41 points, and hit almost every important shot he needed to against
Philadelphia in the second round _ the likelihood of the All-Star
swingman finishing his career with the Pacers is almost guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   One overlooked fact in Indiana's run toward the finals was that
the Pacers were not only chasing an elusive championship, but many
of them were also playing for contracts. In the cases of Miller and
Jackson, they were playing for perhaps the last big money deal they
will sign in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   As the Knicks can attest to when Patrick Ewing put up monster
numbers during his free-agent-to-be season in 1996-97, financial
incentive can often make old legs look young again.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Miller, who is in the last year of a four-year, $36
million contract, had warranted the most lucrative deal possible
after this season under collective bargaining agreement rules,
Walsh said: ``You'd have to give it to him, because he's been
successful. I've always tried to pay guys their value, no matter
what their leverage is. So I don't go by where else he could go and
all that. When we sit down, my intention is to re-sign him.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller most likely won't sign for the absolute maximum, but
he'll get a deal close to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie has earned the right to finish his career in Indiana,''
said Arn Tellem, the agent for both Miller and Jackson. ``We have
every intention of working out a deal. They've shown, as a team,
they can play together and compete for a title for a few more
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh has one other major detail: finding Larry Bird's
replacement. Bird has said he would retire after three seasons as
coach, with the possibility that he might remain in the front
office. The more likely scenario has Bird serving as a consultant
from his Florida home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is he won't stick around after it's over,'' Walsh
said. ``I hate losing Larry. It's been as good a time as I've had.
This has been special. After he leaves, people will step back and
go, `You know, we were all writing that this guy could never be a
head coach.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Jordan Factor
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan attacked the game with ferocity when he played,
outmaneuvering opponents before he conquered them. He was so
competitive and driven, he wanted to bury you, whether the game was
basketball, golf or cards on the team charter.
</P>
<P>
   But in the world of contract negotiations, if the other side
thinks it lost and it thinks you have won handily, you have made a
bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   As he continues his coaching search for the Washington Wizards,
the franchise's head of basketball operations has talked with Lenny
Wilkens, St. John's coach Mike Jarvis and John Paxson, Jordan's
former teammate, and others.
</P>
<P>
   While the meetings begin in an amicable and cordial manner, they
often evolve into: This is how Michael does things, according to at
least two people with knowledge of his coaching search. It is not
that he bullies his prospective employees but that he almost
insultingly lowballs them, offering a pittance for arguably one of
the toughest, no-win jobs in the National Basketball Association,
according to the two people. Jordan was unavailable for comment.
Jarvis' contract demands exceeded what Jordan was willing to pay.
Somehow, agents have put into their clients' heads that they need
to be making at least what John Calipari made _ $3 million a season
_ to jump from a college to a pro job.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Jordan should not be blamed for his intransigence, the
idea that his candidates should be so giddy and thankful to be
working under the greatest player in history. After all, he is
constantly reminded of his exalted status by those close to him.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was in Chicago federal court last Tuesday over a
disagreement with his partners in a bankrupt restaurant. He is
asking that he be allowed to put his name on a future Chicago
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   His partners, Gene and Joseph Silverberg, a pair of Chicago
clothiers who developed Michael Jordan's Restaurant, say their
contract gives them control of the name in Chicago. The trial was
muddled with monotonous legalese. But how about that star witness,
David Falk?
</P>
<P>
   ``In marketing, Michael Jordan's name is like magic in a
bottle,'' Falk, the leadoff witness, told the court. He also
testified, ``Michael Jordan is the most popular human being on the
planet,'' conveniently leaving out Pope John Paul II and Muhammad
Ali, among others.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Associated Press, Falk also testified that the
Silverbergs made statements to the news media that denigrated
Jordan once the legal battle got under way, and thus failed to
adhere to provisions of the contract requiring them to protect the
superstar's ``clean-cut, Americana image.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan visited companies like Coca-Cola and McDonald's when he
emerged as a marketing giant, Falk said. Falk said that ``in
keeping with John Kennedy's inaugural, we told them, `Ask not what
Michael Jordan can do for you but ask what you can do for Michael
Jordan.'''
</P>
<P>
   You know what? Whoever takes the Washington job should kiss
Michael's Gucci loafers and work free. Shame on anyone who would
dare ask for more.
</P>
<P>
   Time to Open the Books
</P>
<P>
   First, it was the San Antonio Spurs shamelessly using Tim
Duncan, David Robinson and a recovering Sean Elliott to campaign
for a new arena last fall, essentially asking taxpayers to forgo
education and other civic needs to help an owner who could not
afford a new luxury-boxed, technodrome by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ray Wooldridge, the Charlotte co-owner, said the Hornets
would continue losing $1 million a month until the Charlotte
Coliseum was replaced. He proposed that the Hornets pay about 25
percent of the cost of a $250 million uptown arena, with the rest
coming from public sources.
</P>
<P>
   To the city's credit, Wooldridge has been asked by city council
members to prove that his team is losing nearly $1 million a month
by opening the team's accounting books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would assume they are losing money, but if we are coming
down to a significant amount of public money, then I think we need
to see their books,'' said Joe White, a council member who
advocates a public referendum on arena funding.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Graham, another council member, said: ``One of the
things they definitely don't have is public confidence. They have
to win the public-relations war, and right now they're losing
badly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets have lost money the past two seasons. Fewer than
12,000 fans attended a playoff game against the Philadelphia 76ers
last month, barely more than half of the building's capacity.
</P>
<P>
   But with new owners with deep pockets buying into the league _
like the billionaire Mark Cuban, who purchased the Dallas Mavericks
_ isn't it time the league took a harder look at luring more
financially solvent businessmen into the fold, instead of people
who ask their ticket-gouged fans to subsidize new buildings? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
