<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reed, Rice and Irvin Near the End
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Cowboys wide receiver Michael Irvin was never an angel.
Away from the field, Irvin and trouble were often good pals. But as
a player, he was one of the toughest, at times most spectacular,
pass catchers of the past decade. Now he faces retirement because
of a spinal injury.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco wide receiver Jerry Rice is considered by many to
be the best ever at his position. But he has been in a battle with
his longtime team, which has considered cutting him for salary cap
reasons. A deal will probably be worked out soon, but the fact that
the team even contemplated releasing Rice is surreal.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Reed played for the Buffalo Bills for 15 seasons before
recently being cut. He is second on the career reception list with
941. He is also looking for a job.
</P>
<P>
   This is the tough part of football, watching great players at
the end of their careers struggle with their mortality. Irvin, Rice
and Reed have had spectacular professional lives, yet all three are
now wondering how things will end, in some cases struggling
physically, and in others, getting little interest from teams
because of their ages.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin was one of the main reasons the Cowboys won three Super
Bowls. He holds every significant team receiving record and is
among the top 10 in National Football League history in receptions
and yards.
</P>
<P>
   Then came that disastrous day in Philadelphia last season. On
Oct. 10 at Veterans Stadium, Irvin's head hit the turf awkwardly
after he was tackled, and doctors later discovered that he has a
narrow spinal cord that makes him susceptible to serious injury if
he takes a blow to the head or neck. He has not played since that
game.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors recently advised Irvin that he should never play again
and he is mulling retirement. One Cowboys team official said in an
interview last week that Irvin had had a difficult time reaching
his decision and had been extremely emotional. The official also
said that even though Irvin planned to announce his retirement in
the coming weeks, there were still days when he went back and forth
and considered trying to play next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's hard on him,'' Dallas running back Emmitt Smith
said. ``It's hard on any man that has to put down the game in the
fashion that he has to put it down. It's a tough situation. Nobody
wants to go out like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice is fighting a similar battle. He wants to finish his career
in San Francisco, and he probably will. But it has not been easy.
The 49ers wanted Rice to take a serious pay cut or they threatened
to release him. Since then both sides have neared a compromise, but
once the season begins, Rice will have to deal with another
difficult aspect.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers will have to find a way to both satisfy Rice, who
still believes he is a first-option pass catcher, as well as their
other younger receivers. Rice is prone to complain if he does not
get the ball enough, and will probably do so again if not enough
passes are thrown his way.
</P>
<P>
   Reed did his share of complaining last season with the Bills as
his role diminished. This off-season the team decided to cut the
cord with Reed, who was Buffalo's fourth round pick in 1985. His
career numbers are dazzling. He has 941 catches for 13,095 yards
and 86 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But now he cannot catch on with another team, and he is trying.
Chances are another team will pick him up later this summer, but
right now teams want to wait until after the June 1 cut day and see
if other wide receivers, younger ones, are available. Reed could
end up with his former general manager, Bill Polian, now in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, fans may be forced to watch the three men go through some
uncomfortable times. Irvin will probably retire, and Rice and Reed
will try to play with declining skills. Still, the place in history
of Irvin, Rice and Reed is assured, especially for the latter two,
who are locks for the Hall of Fame. And Irvin has a good chance of
joining them in Canton, Ohio, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Owners Reward Assistants
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's owners meetings last week produced some interesting
news. Among the topics:
</P>
<P>
   _ When the league expands to 32 teams in 2002 with the addition
of the Houston franchise, the number of playoff teams will most
likely swell from 12 to 14. The last time the league increased the
size of its playoff field was in 1990, from 10 to 12 teams.
</P>
<P>
   _ The NFL expanded its ``violent crime policy'' _ now called the
``personal conduct policy.'' The additions make good sense. The
league's screening process of incoming players will now include
testing, interviewing and evaluating at the annual scouting
combine. There will also be a mandatory intervention process to
support and counsel at-risk players as well as the training of
coaches by professional counselors to identify at-risk players.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hundreds of assistant coaches, through the NFL Coaches
Association, for months have been negotiating with the league for
improved benefits. The main goal of the coaches was to lower the
retirement age from 65. Coaches wanted to use a formula that would
allow them to receive retirement benefits once a combination of age
and years in service reaches 75. In other words, if an assistant is
50 years old, and has coached in the league for 25 years, he would
be eligible to retire and receive benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches got their wish. Owners approved that new retirement
formula by a vote of 30-1. That is a victory for the assistant
coaches who were seriously contemplating a lawsuit against the
owners. This also shows that owners will at least listen to a
convincing argument, which the assistants had.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just happy the owners have done something significant
for the coaches,'' said Larry Kennan, executive director of the
coaches association. ``The owners were very gracious and we are
appreciative of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The assistant coaches believe that the NFL might set up a
committee of owners and head coaches to address the future concerns
of assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Incomplete Hostility
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan was coach of the Oakland Raiders over a decade
ago, fired by the owner, Al Davis, after just 20 games. Shanahan
became coach of the Denver Broncos in 1995 and since then is 9-1
against the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   The current hostility between Shanahan and Davis was rooted in
Shanahan's dismissal and never subsided. One example of the
animosity, from several years ago, was when Shanahan asked
quarterback Elvis Grbac during warm-ups to throw a pass in the
direction of Davis. The ball barely missed Davis' head. Davis then
turned and made an obscene gesture toward Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   The battle between the two men and their organizations escalated
last weekend. Davis publicly complained that Denver circumvented
the salary cap by deferring $22 million in total payments to
running back Terrell Davis and the retired quarterback John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Bowlen, the Denver owner, contends he did not know the
payments had to be made immediately, and once informed otherwise by
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue, made those payments at once. Bowlen
said Davis was making the charges because the Broncos consistently
beat Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of salary-cap violations goes beyond the Broncos and
Raiders and is a hot topic in the league right now. The Pittsburgh
Steelers were recently fined $150,000 by the NFL for secretly
agreeing to pay offensive tackle Will Wolford $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is also under investigation for possible
salary-cap abuses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
