<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-500-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE SHELTERED LIFE TO THE POLE POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Greg Ray is a rebel, albeit one who wears mousse
and crisply pleated pants.
</P>
<P>
   His parents fiercely prohibited him from racing cars or doing
anything remotely dangerous growing up in Plano, Texas. They told
him he could not have Go Karts, Jet Skis or even the sports car he
had saved money for by working throughout high school.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ray could not have speed, of course he craved it all the
more. He was addicted to watching the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   At 25 he had a wife, a successful career in the family business
renting and chartering yachts, and two Porsches in the garage. But
watching reruns of Indy races on cable at 2 a.m., yelling at the
drivers making mistakes, Ray had an early midlife crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think you are so good,'' the voice inside him said,
``why don't you try it?'' Eight months later, without telling his
parents, Ray went to driving school. He won the race there, and
then nine of his next 10.
</P>
<P>
   From daydreaming about being Racer X sneaking into the back row
of the Indy 500, Ray, now 33, is sitting on the pole Sunday for the
84th Indianapolis 500. He is the reigning Indy Racing League
champion and is no longer anonymous. His father, Benny, is no
longer critical. His mother, Ginger, is still petrified whenever he
gets behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had started racing go carts earlier, maybe I would have
won Indy a few times by now, but who knows?'' Ray said. ``I think
it came at the right time. I feel more blessed to have lived 25
years on the other side of the fence as a spectator. And then when
I got involved, to find I had natural ability, I think I had a lot
more respect for it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ray bought a $250,000 truck, trailer and car to jump-start
his career in 1991, his father rebuked him for making an
irresponsible business decision. ``He called me five different ways
of stupid,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   The two barely spoke for his first year in racing. But with his
father in attendance for the first time the next year, Ray went
from starting last to passing the champion on the final lap of a
race at the Texas Motor Speedway, and his father was converted.
``We laugh about it now,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray had more trouble proving his worth to sponsors when he moved
up to the IRL in 1997, after winning championships in smaller
series. It was at Indy in 1998 that he made his breakthrough:
driving for the low-budget Thomas Knapp Motorsports, Ray was the
second-fastest qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one car, two engines, four mechanics and one driver,''
Ray recalled. And little else. Fans were handing him $20 and $50
bills to finance his ride, and he tacked one to the inside of his
car.
</P>
<P>
   Ray led 18 laps that year before he fell out of the race with
gearbox problems. But his aggressive style was enough to get him
noticed, and he signed with the high-profile Team Menard at the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Ray will make his fourth start at Indy, having edged
the driver from the rival Championship Auto Racing Teams series,
Juan Montoya, by a tenth of a second in qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, driving for Chip Ganassi, began racing when he was 5 in
Colombia. His early success is in stark contrast to Ray's late
development, and the two drivers represent an underlying story to
this year's race.
</P>
<P>
   Ganassi is the only CART team at Indy, ending a five-year
drought but not the political feud with the IRL. The better known
open-wheel racers are associated with CART, which has unofficially
boycotted the race since 1996 when the Indianapolis Motor Speedway
president, Tony George, formed the IRL and required different
engine specifications.
</P>
<P>
   While the Indy 500 has been depleted of stars the last four
years, there is a sense of excitement pulsing through the Brickyard
this year. With Montoya, Jimmy Vasser and Al Unser Jr., in the
race, winning would be much more significant, Ray said. ``By
bringing all the drivers together, it allows you to assess,'' Ray
said. ``You want the biggest challenge you can get, so if you are
able to come out on top, it means something.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray commented on the significance of the two series' coming
together. ``I would like to see everybody in the same arena on a
weekly basis,'' he said. ``But CART, IRL, whatever, I'm just a
driver. I want to win; it's not one series versus the other. It's
drivers versus the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but the mechanics did not see it that way when Ray
snatched the pole from Montoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came in after qualifying, I saw just about every
mechanic from every Indy Racing League team high-fiving my car,''
Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
