<SLUG> BC-TEN-U.S.-MEN-1045(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TENNIS: BEYOND AGING STARS, U.S. TALENT IS SCARCE 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Take a cursory look at the men's draw for the French
Open, which begins here Monday, and U.S. tennis appears to remain
in fine shape and gifted hands. At the top is the No. 1-seeded
player, the defending champion and future Hall of Fame inductee
Andre Agassi. At the bottom is the second-seeded and future Hall of
Famer Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras and Agassi have been the world's most successful and
visible players over the last decade: winning 18 Grand Slam singles
titles between them and maintaining, with able support from Michael
Chang, Todd Martin and the recently retired Jim Courier, the United
States' place at the top of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   But if you look more closely at the handwriting on the wall in
Paris, a more troubling picture emerges. Agassi and Sampras are the
only Americans who are seeded, and of the eight other U.S. men who
will play at Stade Roland Garros, the majority are older than age
24 and no longer at the peak of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the seven U.S. men who tried to play their way into this
Grand Slam event, not one made it past the first round in last
week's qualifying tournament. And in the last five Grand Slam
events, only two U.S. men have advanced through the qualifying
tournament for the main draw: 30-year-old Alex O'Brien at this
year's Australian Open and 33-year-old Richey Reneberg at last
year's Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras and Agassi are still motivated and intimidating, but
Agassi is now 30 and Sampras is 28 and increasingly injury prone.
Where is the next wave? And more important, is there a next wave?
</P>
<P>
   Nick Bollettieri, the coach whose academy in Bradenton, Fla.,
was the Darwinian place where Agassi, Courier and other top
Americans developed their forehands and attitude, is afraid he
knows the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in for a dry spell,'' he said. ``If you check the New
York Yankees out 10 to 15 years ago, they were winning everything,
and they forgot their farm team and then went into a tremendous
drought. And that is exactly what is going to happen to American
men's tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Solomon, another prominent U.S. coach and a former French
Open finalist, is similarly pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My true opinion, and I won't win any popularity contests with
this, is that our system is an antiquated system as far as
producing champions,'' he said. ``They say it's a cyclical thing.
But I say no. We have a gap, and it looks like it will be a big
gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon added: ``It's going to be an awful situation in three to
four years when all these guys stop. The USTA is going to have egg
on its face when it's the round of 16 at the U.S. Open and there
are no American players in it. And if there are no American guys
around, who in this country is going to want to watch it and follow
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the U.S. Tennis Association are well aware of the
risk, but they take heart from the excellent recent play of Andy
Roddick, a 17-year-old from Boca Raton, Fla., who is the world's
top-ranked junior and turned professional in March.
</P>
<P>
   They also point to a series of initiatives the organization has
begun in the last three years, which include increasing the number
of small professional events in the United States, tinkering with
the junior tennis system and creating a comprehensive regional
network staffed by instructors who have either played or coached at
the elite level.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came into this job 2 1/2 years ago, obviously the
question was, `Where are the next American stars?''' the USTA's
director of player development, Doug MacCurdy, said. ``I'm a little
more interested in the whole system of development and ensuring
that we have a lot of players to draw from. At our strongest point
in men's tennis as a nation, we had a lot of players battling each
other and by natural selection some moved into the upper ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a system does not produce a Sampras or Agassi or a Yevgeny
Kafelnikov. But a system can produce, like Spain and Sweden have
shown, an awful lot of good players, and we have to use that
numbers game to our advantage, because I would assume there are
probably still a lot more people playing tennis in the United
States than anywhere else and recent participation levels are
encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   It also bears remembering what happened the last time there was
widespread concern about the U.S. men's game. That was in the late
1980s, when John McEnroe and Jimmy Connors were in decline. For a
three-year span _ from 1986 to 1988 _ no U.S. man reached a Grand
Slam singles final, and in 1987, amid gloomy predictions of a
long-term void, the USTA created its first player development
program to help foster and finance young talent at home.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the next wave was already preparing to break.
Agassi reached No. 3 in the world in 1988. In 1989, Chang became
the youngest man to win the French Open. Sampras became the
youngest man to win the U.S. Open in 1990, and the following year,
Courier broke through, beating Agassi in the French Open final and
soon reaching No. 1 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   End of crisis. End of concern. Until now, when the
highest-ranked U.S. man under the age of 25 is Jan-Michael Gambill,
currently 67th on the ATP list at age 22. Behind him are
23-year-old Paul Goldstein, who is 79th, and 23-year-old Justin
Gimelstob, 99th, followed by six young Americans ranked between 145
and 212: Cecil Mamiit, Michael Russell, Kevin Kim, Bob Bryan,
Taylor Dent and James Blake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I could certainly not say that here are three players
who will fill the shoes of Sampras and Agassi and the others at the
top of the game, I do think there will be a certain opening, and
somebody will walk through it,'' MacCurdy said.
</P>
<P>
   Chang agrees that there could be surprises. ``I don't think when
we came out that anyone ever thought we were going to do so well,
so I think time will tell a lot for the next bunch,'' Chang said.
``But all I know is that I don't think you're going to see a group
like our group for a long time. I'm not just talking about the four
of us who won Grand Slams. I'm also talking about Todd Martin, Mal
Washington, David Wheaton and Jeff Tarango. All these guys were
from the same class, and you just don't see that many coming in
such a large group behind us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The volume of top U.S. players has been decreasing regularly
since the Open era began in 1968. At the U.S. Open that year, 48 of
the 96 players in the men's draw were Americans, as were 51 of the
64 in the women's draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at every decade after that, and it has been a fairly
steady decline to where it is now: about 20 percent of the women
and 15 percent of the men, and that includes wild cards,'' MacCurdy
said. ``I'd attribute that primarily to the growing popularity of
and involvement in the game in the rest of the world, and a lot of
steps federations and individuals took.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy was the first nation to begin a national tennis school in
the 1970s, but it has been in other European countries like France,
the Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, Sweden, Switzerland, the Czech
Republic, Austria and Spain that the greatest developmental strides
have been made. Spain has been particularly successful in producing
top men's players. At the end of 1999, it had 12 players in the top
100 _ one more than the United States _ even though stars like Alex
Corretja and Carlos Moya had poor seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Spain has succeeded for a variety of reasons. By developing an
extensive system of satellite and challenger tournaments,
essentially minor leagues, it allowed plenty of chances for its
players to acquire experience and ranking points close to home.
Many young Spanish coaches were also willing to take financial
risks and sacrifice their personal lives by traveling with young
prospects on the circuit, and the fact that nearly all the best
facilities are in Barcelona meant that the top players could train
and develop together frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have each other to compete against, and that's what I had
with Andre and Michael,'' Sampras said. ``You need rivals, good
competitors at home. It seems to me every time you turn your head
in the locker room there's another young Spaniard coming up.
Unfortunately in our country, it's a little thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Another competitive advantage is that because of differences in
school requirements, top Spanish players can begin playing full
time earlier than Americans. Corretja and the newest Spanish star,
Juan Carlos Ferrero, who is seeded 16th in his first French Open,
have been playing satellite events since their midteens. The same
is happening in France and in parts of South America, which has
reassumed a prominent position in the men's game in the wake of the
success of Chile's Marcelo Rios and the Brazilian Gustavo Kuerten.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the men's game, there are probably a couple of thousand
good players who are playing virtually full-time tennis at the ages
of 15, 16, 17,'' MacCurdy said. ``Obviously it doesn't work out for
a lot of them. But very few American kids at that age would take
the risk and say, `I'm going to just play tennis.' The young
professional is a problem for us.''
</P>
<P>
   To compensate, the USTA has increased the number of challenger
and satellite events in the United States from 46 in 1993 to 100
this year. It has also increased the number of International Tennis
Federation junior events in the United States from eight to 13 in
the last three years. Perhaps most significant, it has sent more
full-time coaches on the road with small groups of young
professionals who might otherwise lack the means to hire such
experts at a critical phase in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say my major goal would be to stop the bleeding that has
gone on for such a long while,'' MacCurdy said. ``And to begin to
add fairly slowly. I'd love to see one or two additional top 100
players a year.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Mamiit and Goldstein are still trying to break into
the top 70 on the ATP list at age 23, younger players like Lleyton
Hewitt of Australia, Marat Safin of Russia, Andreas Vinciguerra of
Sweden, Juan Ignacio Chela of Argentina and Ferrero (all 20 or
younger) have already won tournaments and are considered major
threats in Grand Slam events.
</P>
<P>
   Precocious success is rarely a coincidence in tennis. Remember
Sampras, Agassi and Chang. And unless the Americans can make up
lost ground and time in a hurry, it will be very difficult for
their fans at home to forget Sampras, Agassi and Chang in the lean
years ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
