<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENNINGTON-DISPUTE-ART-1020(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENNINGTON COLLEGE FINDS ROAD TO RECOVERY ROCKY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT6 and NYT7 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENNINGTON, Vt. _ Bennington College, a tiny, quirky, hilltop
jewel box of liberal artsiness, is hardly a stranger to
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1932 as a women's college challenging educational
orthodoxy, the upstart developed a history of innovation, a
tradition of teacher-practitioners _ often cutting-edge figures in
art, drama, dance and literature _ working in close relationship
with their student-apprentices and, in recent decades, academic
politics of exceeding viciousness.
</P>
<P>
   But with the college having fallen on hard times by 1994, its
niche nibbled away by changes in the Ivy League and other
institutions, its student body reduced in quantity and quality, its
faculty lapsing toward mediocrity and its finances in peril, the
trustees, the administration and the faculty came up with a
restructuring plan called the Symposium after a two-year agonizing
reappraisal.
</P>
<P>
   A third of the faculty _ 26 of 79 professors _ was fired in a
single stroke in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people knew about Bennington was that it's the most
expensive college,'' said Elizabeth Coleman, the tough-minded
president who came to Bennington after serving as dean of the
undergraduate division at the New School University in New York
City. But, she said, that was ``the only thing'' they knew.
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived, in 1987, she was shocked to discover that
College Board scores at the once highly selective school had fallen
to an average 1100 out of a possible 1600.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the college administration says, Bennington is on the road
to recovery, with money raised, admissions rising and three
dormitories planned. But the college is once again in turmoil with
dissident and dismissed faculty members casting Coleman as a
dictatorial figure who crushes any criticism. Two trustees have
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Hoagland, the distinguished nature essayist who is
perhaps the best-known faculty member, has publicly called for
Coleman's resignation, as has the writer Jamaica Kincaid, who has
taught at the college and is married to a member of the music
faculty, Allan Shawn.
</P>
<P>
   The infighting has been bitter. In an exchange of letters in the
local newspaper, The Bennington Banner, Mary Oliver, who holds a
Pulitzer Prize in poetry and an endowed chair at Bennington and
supports Coleman, told Kincaid, in so many words, to stick to her
gardening.
</P>
<P>
   The past academic year has been marked by the dismissal of four
faculty members _ one in the middle of the semester _ seen by their
supporters as critics of the administration and by Coleman as
having fallen short in their professional qualifications and
responsibilities. The novelist Roland Merullo, who had counted
himself a close friend of Coleman's, resigned his teaching job in
protest. There have been emotional meetings on campus, and a
protest demonstration was mounted by the American Association of
University Professors demanding tenure protection.
</P>
<P>
   What is striking is that nearly all of the critics, in their
next few breaths, give Coleman credit for having saved the college
six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did good for the college _ in fact, she may have saved it
_ in her first half-dozen years,'' Hoagland said in an interview.
``But her temperament is a warrior temperament _ it's not right for
the healing process that's needed now. She is vindictive; she has
proven that a number of times.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the trustees dated March 28, pecked out on one of
the old manual typewriters on which he has written 17 books and
more than 100 essays, Hoagland wrote, ``I have never seen a faculty
as intimidated and unhappy as Bennington's is now, nor autocratic
power exercised so quirkily and punitively by a college president,
at such a cost to academic freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Hoagland's characterization of her personality,
Coleman replied: ``I think it's silly. It's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 Symposium changes, which had attracted national
attention _ not all of it favorable _ included abolishing
traditional departments like literature, which had become political
power centers, and setting up a new employment system. Bennington
had what was called ``presumptive tenure,'' with five-year
contracts that, in practice, were almost always renewed. Now there
would be shorter contracts and a faculty review process. Coleman
said she intended to restore a standard of high achievement in the
teachers' outside professional work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to create a continuum between the work they were
doing in the world and their teaching at Bennington,'' Coleman said
in a two-hour interview. ``The board said, `Let's make the most
exciting, compelling design possible. Let's go for the gold.' In a
funny way they could do this because they had nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall semester, Coleman declined to renew the contracts of
two teachers, Steven Cramer, a poet, and Tony Eprile, a South
African novelist, even though they had been recommended by the
faculty review committee.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the trustees' chairman, John W. Barr, an investment
banker and poet, wrote a memorandum to the faculty suggesting that
the review committee be scrapped because its ``tendency toward
uniform enthusiasm'' for rehiring teachers made its recommendations
``unilluminating and frequently interchangeable.'' All five
committee members resigned in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as spring semester began, Coleman told Derek E. Campbell,
a popular, 59-year-old drama professor who had taught here for nine
years and had been highly recommended by the review committee, that
his contract would not be renewed. She said he had not acted enough
in theaters outside the area.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell contends he was let go for criticizing Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dismissal has been a clear and unambiguous example of abuse
of power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, like others, he said he had been initially supportive of
Coleman's innovations: ``I thought the college was headed for
disaster. Her determination, her vision, her energy, saved us from
imminent closure. She kept this institution alive. Liz sees herself
as an educational visionary. But she cannot tolerate dissension or
dialogue.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's dismissal was ``the last straw,'' Merullo wrote in a
letter of resignation on March 4. ``In working so hard to rescue
Bennington and make it flourish, in putting in place your vision
for a different kind of higher education, you have, of late,
repeatedly crossed the line of basic human decency and are creating
a culture laced with quiet fear.''
</P>
<P>
   As controversy mounted, a philosophy professor, Carlin Romano,
was quoted in The Chronicle of Higher Education as calling Coleman
``a serial violator of academic freedom'' and predicting that he
would be fired.
</P>
<P>
   He was, almost immediately. But Coleman and other officials say
it was because he was chronically late with the evaluations
students get instead of grades and that he had made threats to a
dean.
</P>
<P>
   The college spokesman, David Rees, insisted that the process at
Bennington was actually a triumphant one. ``Separate incidents have
been bundled together,'' he said, ``to create the impression that
something dark and ominous is going on here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
