<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7545 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-955(2T     05-27 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-955(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER GIULIANI: NEW STRATEGIES FOR THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Senate race has been transformed from a
narrow battle over a tiny number of undecided voters into a broad
and complex contest, with voting blocs and geographic regions that
had seemed fixed in place suddenly churned into play by Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's departure, Republican and Democratic strategists
say.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republican candidate, and Hillary
Rodham Clinton, the Democrat, said that since the political
calculus of the race has now been scrambled, they have been forced
to change tactics and abandon long-held assumptions _ that Clinton
would be an unusually strong candidate upstate, for example, or
that Giuliani would encroach on Democratic voting blocs.
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason that when Clinton made her first campaign
appearance after Lazio completed his announcement tour last week,
she did it in Westchester County, just north of New York City,
before an audience of elderly voters. The suburbs now seem at least
slightly more hospitable to Clinton with Giuliani out of the race,
and the elderly _ always among the most dutiful voters come
Election Day _ have been identified by Clinton's advisers as more
open to her appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Lazio, once he concludes his acceptance speech at the
Republican convention in Buffalo on Tuesday, plans to make a
theatrical departure in a bus caravan, which will roll through the
small towns and farmlands of upstate New York for two full days. It
will be the second time that the new candidate has turned up in a
part of the state where Giuliani had rarely been seen.
</P>
<P>
   And plans call for Lazio to make a concerted appeal to moderate
and even to conservative voters, who some upstate Republicans
feared had been alienated by Giuliani's manner and the public
unraveling of his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the calculations evident in the candidates'
schedules show how much this has reverted to a traditional race for
Senate, albeit one including a first lady. Both sides are relying
on historical models in trying to assemble winning coalitions,
based on appeals to different parts of the state and different
voting groups.
</P>
<P>
   But after months in which Clinton and Giuliani courted a state
in which most voters seemed firmly set in their positions, both
campaigns have concluded that Clinton and Lazio are now facing a
vastly more complex and fluid political picture.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to both candidates agreed, to a striking extent, on the
ways the political deck had been reshuffled. Not surprisingly, they
disagreed on which of the two candidates would benefit from it, and
both claimed the advantage. The advisers said that any polls taken
so early measuring the support of Lazio were almost certainly
unreliable, given the tumult caused by Giuliani's leaving the race,
and the short time Lazio has been on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   The clearest shift is in the changing assessments by Republicans
and Democrats of which regions favor which candidates.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani was in the race, upstate New York had seemed to be
unusually strong ground for Clinton, a matter of some concern for
Republican leaders, because upstate has always provided the
electoral base for Republicans, a counter to the advantage that
Democrats have in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Her appeal upstate was the result of Clinton's near-constant
visits upstate, as well as the problems inherent in running a New
York City mayor for office in a part of the state that has always
viewed the city with deep suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Several upstate Republicans said last week that Giuliani's
chances would have been further eroded by the revelations about his
marriage, and that before he quit, they had grown more pessimistic
about how he would do there against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is now planning what aides said would be a summer-long
charge to recapture that part of the state, and upstate Republicans
have cheered the end of the turmoil that had clouded the Republican
Party and are pleased that their candidate is a Long Island
congressman rather than a New York City mayor. ``There is almost a
sigh of relief,'' said state Sen. Thomas Libous, a Republican from
Binghamton and a senior adviser to Lazio. ``No question: upstate is
back in play.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of Clinton's advisers acknowledged that Lazio could be
much more attractive to upstate voters than the mayor, and that he
was already showing a level of interest in the contest that
Giuliani never had. Still, Clinton's campaign manager, Bill de
Blasio, said he was not worried. ``Hillary has spent so much time
upstate that Lazio will not find it easy to cut into her support
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may now find that opportunities lost upstate might be
opportunities gained in the suburbs. The counties around New York
City had been extremely supportive of Giuliani's candidacy _ a
testimony to his nightly dominance of television news and to the
credit that suburban voters gave him for the improved fortunes of a
city where so many of them go for work and pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Now the race has, however improbably, turned into a contest
between two suburban candidates, one from Suffolk County on Long
Island who is barely known outside his district, and the other a
first lady who lives, at least sometimes, in Westchester. Clinton
spent two days campaigning in the suburbs last week, and she plans
to return to Westchester on Monday for an event marking Memorial
Day.
</P>
<P>
   As a final matter of geography, Lazio is unlikely to have the
level of support that Giuliani would have drawn in New York City.
He will probably spend a minimal amount of time there, in deference
to the emerging political reality of this state and because he will
not want to do anything to remind Clinton's voters to turn out.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The roles of nearly all the major New York voting blocs _
blacks, women, Jews, and gays in particular _ have shifted almost
as suddenly, though not as clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously, advisers to both candidates have concluded that
Clinton cannot count on the large turnout among black voters that
seemed likely with Giuliani at the top of the ticket. Republicans
argued that Clinton would have to spend more time in New York City
to ensure that Democratic voters turn out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the race was against the mayor, there was a guaranteed
base of voters that would vote against him,'' said Zenia Mucha, the
senior adviser to Gov. George Pataki. ``That is no longer the case.
Mrs. Clinton will now have to spend an enormous amount of time and
energy making a case for herself with the voters that were against
the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clinton may now have an opening to voters who have
tended to be Democratic but with whom Giuliani was competitive _ in
particular, Jewish voters, the elderly, gay voters and women. For
one thing, Lazio is a more traditional Republican than the moderate
mayor, and for another, Clinton's advisers hope to use Lazio's
voting record in Congress against him with those groups.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, Clinton noted Lazio's opposition to gun
control and to public financing of abortions for the poor, both
issues that could help the first lady's problematic standing with
female voters.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that in the weeks ahead she would point to cuts in
Medicare supported by congressional Republicans in an attempt to
challenge Lazio's position with the elderly, and to strengthen her
support among gay voters, Clinton would also note, they said, that
Lazio had not been a co-sponsor of federal gay rights legislation
or the hate crimes bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest single difference is that you now have somebody
with a voting record,'' one of Clinton's advisers said. ``Three
weeks ago we were trying to make the case that the Republican mayor
was going to vote with a Republican majority. But it was a
hypothetical argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, both sides believe that Jewish voters, whose support
for Giuliani had been a constant source of concern for Clinton, may
have shifted to at least undecided ground. ``Let's face it _ that
was a tough nut to crack,'' an adviser to Clinton said. ``I think
now it's a much more open situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not be so easy. Giuliani's support among many Jewish
voters was a product of the perception that he was strong on
Israeli security, and of Clinton's perceived sympathy toward the
creation of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's advisers said that he had a long history in favor of
voting for Israeli security measures, and that they would make a
point of highlighting this record. ``Rick has a very strong
pro-Israel record, and we think that contrasts favorably with Mrs.
Clinton,'' said Mike Murphy, Lazio's senior adviser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
