<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, May 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The merging of two branches of the jet stream over the northeast
quarter of the nation will lead to a variety of weather conditions.
In New England, clouds and sprinkles will linger over northern
sections as chilly breezes circulate around low pressure in Nova
Scotia. Across central and parts of southern New England, sunshine
and seasonable temperatures will be the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Along the axis where the two jet streams meet, a veil of clouds
will extend from western New York to Long Island, N.Y. Embedded in
the southern jet stream is a potent disturbance that will cause
heavy rain from sections of Ohio to Virginia, and strong to severe
thunderstorms in the southern Appalachians and eastern Gulf states.
</P>
<P>
   A slight shift in the anticipated position of these merging jet
streams could either make New York brighter and mild or turn Boston
dull and damp.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SPREADING HEAT
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the temperature topped 101 degrees at Columbia,
S.C., for a daily record. Myrtle Beach and Augusta also set record
maximums in the 90s. While some of the heat in the Southeast was
generated in Texas and blown into the region on sultry breezes,
part of the hot spell was locally grown. The area from northern
Florida to central South Carolina has been excessively dry,
allowing much of the sun's energy to be transferred from the heated
ground to the air. Drought and heat followed each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
