<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-RIDGE-CONSERVATIVES-1     05-27 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIDGE-CONSERVATIVES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDGE DERIDES CRITICS ON RELIGIOUS RIGHT, BUT LIKES BEING ON BUSH
SHORT LIST
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to delete redundant Vietnam.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. _ Of all the things he is being called lately by
his critics, ``liberal'' and ``dove'' make Gov. Tom Ridge laugh out
loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet the only combat ever seen by the guy who wrote that
has been in front of a Nintendo machine,'' said Ridge, his
credentials as a Bronze Star combat veteran of Vietnam unsullied by
the slings and arrows now pelting him from within his own
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam-fighting experience of the husky, 55-year-old
Pennsylvania governor comes in handy these days. He is being
targeted by the social conservative right for being a Roman
Catholic who unapologetically favors a woman's right to choose
abortion, yet remains prominently featured on a list of potential
running mates of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the putative
Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor says there is no litmus test, and I believe
him,'' Ridge said, referring to the simmering abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   But social and religious conservatives see things differently,
and have issued stern warnings to Bush of dire consequences in
November if he picks someone like Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The base in the Republican Party is pro-life,'' James C.
Dobson, the conservative religious leader, said on Wednesday. ``You
can't win without that base.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge, his abortion rights stand firmly defying party platform
dogma, remains the most mentioned prospective running mate. He set
a Republican record for this heavily Democratic state with a
780,000-vote victory margin in his 1998 re-election. A Bush-Ridge
ticket might well deliver this critical battleground, the
fifth-largest state in electoral votes, to the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In two elections, Ridge has shown considerable crossover
attraction among Democratic voters. He has the power to garner up
to 30 percent of them, according to polls _ a factor that Bush must
weigh as he charts a centrist strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans also note that Bush had to be more sensitive
to the nation's large Catholic vote after his controversial speech
in the South Carolina primary at Bob Jones University, a campus
that critics denounce as anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   And while Ridge's support of abortion rights might signal a
harsh party split for some Republicans, others said his candidacy
as vice president would draw more women to the Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this wonderful speculation,'' remarked Ridge, his smile
broad but fatalistic as he noted that the decision on a running
mate was entirely Bush's to make after a long process involving ``a
lot of other people,'' in the Texas governor's words.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if? What if?'' asked Ridge, happily teasing himself as
much as his boosters and critics. He seems to be enjoying the
freedom of having no say in the matter as he looks forward to being
the state host at the Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But as the vice-presidential question is debated, conservative
critics in National Review and other publications, nettled by his
support of abortion rights, are busily vetting Ridge's 12-year
record in Congress to argue that, even beyond the abortion issue,
he is not an authentic conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protectionist,'' another charge made against Ridge, brings
more open laughter here in the executive chamber of the governor,
who noted that he was a card-carrying member of the hod-carriers
union when he was a college student who worked in construction
during the summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for Nafta, in Congress,'' Ridge said, bemused at what
he was reading lately from conservative polemicists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, this gets comical,'' he continued. He repeatedly used
the word ``conservative'' to characterize himself in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Only the November election, he said, with all the variables
brought to the voters by the candidates and their campaigns, might
settle the question of whether the Republican Party is ready for an
abortion rights candidate on the ticket beside the anti-abortion
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the decibel level may be going down a little bit on
this issue,'' said Ridge, whose political career in Pennsylvania
has not measurably suffered from his support of abortion rights,
even after his being obliquely criticized by his bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think we're done with the very important struggle
we're having within the party as to how to deal with it,'' he
continued. ``Certainly, my friend Governor Bush disagrees with me,
and a majority of the delegates at the convention probably disagree
with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're not going to change the platform. But it's
interesting to note there are some people in the party who, instead
of defeating Al Gore, would suggest that if the No. 2, whether me
or somebody else, doesn't share their belief on abortion, they
might abandon the party.''
</P>
<P>
   One quarter where Ridge is bolstered in his insistence that he
is a true-blue conservative is across the Statehouse, within the
Democratic minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Ridge is a perfect fit for George Bush,'' said state Sen.
Christine Tartaglione, speaking in her role as the state Democratic
chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``His actions speak louder than his words,'' Tartaglione said,
contending that Ridge, in the state's recent tax cuts of more than
$1 billion, favored big business interests at the expense of needy
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all wait for Tom Ridge's leadership,'' she said scornfully.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's supporters quickly cite a raft of new social
welfare and education laws to argue that he is the very model of
the ``compassionate conservative'' that Bush has proclaimed as the
cornerstone of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And Ridge has just the sort of paradoxical touches in his resume
that politicians dream of.
</P>
<P>
   His parents were postwar strivers; his father, a Navy veteran,
worked two jobs to finance his children's parochial school tuition.
Up from public housing, the family bought a modest house in Erie,
that is still home to the governor's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My DNA is a little confused,'' Ridge said lightly in noting
that his father was a fervid blue-collar Democrat while his mother
was a no less fervid Republican ward worker. The family dinner
table was a forum that respected politics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Harvard after winning a needs-based
scholarship and, while studying at Dickinson Law School in
Pennsylvania was drafted into the Army and served in the infantry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dwell on Vietnam; I draw on it,'' said Ridge who, with
a similar margin of removal, recalls the feverish anti-war protests
at Harvard as a fascinating backdrop that did not draw him away
from his studies.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As the attacks by social conservatives heighten, the governor
does not hesitate to defend his view on abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult personal decision that has enormous
emotional, psychological, intensely physical and oftentimes
religious dimensions to it,'' he said. ``This is a tough decision
for people to make. One of the things I talk about is trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to whether I would place ultimate responsibility
in that very difficult personal decision, with so many dimensions
to it, in the hands of government _ I mean, some of the people in
my party would criminalize it! _ or leave it up to the individual,
leave it up to the woman.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the intramural sniping, the old combat sergeant admits
he enjoys the extra political notice and power that seems to come
with the vice-presidential speculation, however fruitless it may
prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the what-if factor,'' Ridge said, describing a state of
``irrational exuberance'' that he is experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a heck of a ride,'' the governor added. ``I've already
got a great job, and I'm going to help my old friend George Bush
get elected president. And you know? I think he can carry
Pennsylvania without me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1408EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GAS-PRICES-ART-820&AMP;AD     05-27 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-ART-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY MOTORISTS FACE SOARING PRICES AT PUMP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mass., Conn., Calif., Ill., Wis., Mo.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ By now, most of Eddie Slack's customers are accustomed
to paying $30 or more to fill their gas tanks. ``The big sticker
shock was several months ago,'' said Slack, owner of the Delwood
Chevron service station in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   After falling a good bit following a decision by the
petroleum-exporting countries in March to increase oil production,
gasoline prices have soared to the highest levels of the year in
many parts of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers now filling up are paying record prices for the Memorial
Day weekend. And analysts say tight supplies, particularly in the
Midwest, could push prices higher as demand increases with the
beginning of the summer driving season and as parts of the country
struggle to meet a June 1 deadline for using a cleaner-burning
reformulated fuel as required by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The average national price for regular unleaded is $1.53 a
gallon, the same level reached in March and almost 40 cents higher
than last year, federal officials said. In New York City, drivers
are paying $1.64 a gallon, compared with $1.27 last year, according
to AAA, the automobile association.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusted for inflation, of course, gasoline is still cheap, even
with the sharp rise of the last year. The 30 cents a gallon that
Americans paid in the early 1960s translates to about $1.75 today,
according to Cambridge Energy Research Associates. And the $1.25 a
gallon that drivers paid in the early 1980s is equivalent to $2.50
today.
</P>
<P>
   In April, prices around the country fell almost a dime a gallon,
on average, after OPEC ministers voted in late March to increase
production. But the decline turned out to be short-lived, as
drivers everywhere learned this week when they gassed up for the
holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs so much that I don't even fill up the tank anymore,''
Tadd Balfour, a 25-year-old computer network engineer, said as he
added $10 worth of gas to the 20-gallon tank of his Montero sport
utility vehicle at Slack's station on Friday. Balfour, who commutes
more than 20 miles each day, says he has considered buying a
smaller car. ``If gas goes up another couple of points, I may have
to make a change,'' he said. ``But I'm closely watching what prices
do. Right now, it's out of control.''.
</P>
<P>
   Balfour and other customers at Slack's small but busy service
station on Interstate 35 near downtown Austin paid $1.41 a gallon
for regular gasoline last week, $1.52 for midgrade and $1.61 for
premium. That is less than in most other parts of the country, but
that did not stop customers from complaining about recent
increases. ``They were really hollering,'' Slack said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high prices, holiday driving is expected to eclipse
last year's rates. AAA said it expected more than 34 million
Americans to travel at least 100 miles from their homes over the
weekend, 3 percent more than last year and 31 percent more than
during the 1991 Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the blame for the recent price increase lies with the
low inventories of gasoline around the country, a factor that
played a big role in high prices earlier this year. But the latest
run-up has been accelerated by the scramble to introduce a new
reformulated fuel in most large metropolitan areas. Prices have
also moved higher because of worries that a legal dispute involving
the Unocal Corp.'s patents for certain reformulated gas is holding
back production at some refineries.
</P>
<P>
   The cleaner-burning fuel is being sold in the
Boston-to-Washington corridor, including much of New York, New
Jersey and Connecticut, as well as in much of California and in
Chicago, Milwaukee, Houston and Dallas. Worries over tight supplies
of the fuel have been particularly acute in the Midwest, where
prices are soaring. In Chicago, for example, drivers are paying an
average of $1.85 for regular unleaded, up 30 cents in the last
month and more than 60 cents over last year, according to AAA. Some
of the city's service stations have already raised prices above
$2.00 a gallon. Milwaukee drivers are paying $1.74 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers in Wisconsin have authorized the filing of a
lawsuit to block adoption of the new fuel rules there. And in St.
Louis, officials won a waiver from the Environmental Protection
Agency allowing use of the old gas until June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, the EPA denied requests from both Chicago and
Milwaukee for waivers there. The agency said there was enough of
the reformulated fuel to make waivers unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The reformulated fuel is harder to blend, and Midwest refiners
are unlikely to be able to increase production soon, said Philip K.
Verleger, a senior adviser to the Brattle Group, a consulting firm
in Cambridge, Mass. Absent an EPA waiver, gas prices in Chicago and
Milwaukee could go much higher, even well above $2 a gallon, before
the situation stabilizes, Verleger said. ``There's no real way out
of it for the next three or four weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On top of pressure to meet the new fuel requirements,
inventories are low even for regular gasoline, and that leaves the
nation exposed to price spikes, said Daniel Yergin, president of
Cambridge Energy Research Associates. Stocks are so low, he said,
that ``any change in supply will reverberate in the markets right
away _ there isn't much of a normal cushion.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about a shortage of reformulated fuel helped push
gasoline futures to $1.026 a gallon on Friday, their highest level
since the Persian Gulf War, before settling back a few cents in the
shortened pre-holiday trading session at the New York Mercantile
Exchange. Oil futures closed at $30 a barrel, only a few dollars
short of the high for the year and at the top end of a trading band
in which OPEC ministers want crude to remain. Should oil prices
stay at these levels, or rise, analysts say the cartel could act to
increase production once more.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices have more than doubled since early last year. OPEC
decided in March 1999 to cut back production, and cartel members
largely adhered to the new limits on output, which, combined with
stronger demand from Asia, caused prices to soar.
</P>
<P>
   At Slack's service station, Edward Wyndham, a 64-year-old
carpenter and part-time minister, remembers when gas stations gave
away glassware to attract customers. Now he says he and his friends
just seek the cheapest prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous, what they've done,'' Wyndham said as he
finished putting gas in his pickup truck. ``It's the poor people
who are suffering. I'm mad about it.''
</P>
<P>
