   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FOX _ VERACRUZ, Mexico _ A day after the second formal
presidential debate in Mexico, we analyze the event from the road
with opposition candidate Vicente Fox Quesada. Developing.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS _ PRISTINA, Kosovo _ It's coming up on one year
since a U.S.-led United Nations peacekeeping force went in to
liberate this war-torn province Serb military forces and
paramilitary thugs. There are 5,600 U.S. troops currently deployed
here. Their status has become so controversial, that a week ago,
the U.S. Senate nearly voted to cut off funds to the operation _
effectively forcing their withdrawal unless Congress authorized an
extension. But they can't worry about that here. They have their
hands full keeping the peace between ethnic Serbs and Kosovar
Albanians. We go on patrol with them to observe the daily problems
they face and how they interact with the local culture. (Coker, Cox
News Service). 40.
</P>
<P>
   With chrono box of past year's events attached to end of story.
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: The story is expected to contain quotes from individual
troops from Cox states and should make a nice Memorial Day package.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Fri., May 26.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-HOPE _ ABUJA, Nigeria _ Monday (May 29) marks the first
anniversary of Olusegun Obasanjo's inauguration as Nigeria's first
civilian leader since 1983. A man who counts among his friends Bill
Clinton and former President Jimmy Carter, Obasanjo is regarded
widely as an honest, dedicated leader. Yet, the problems
confronting him and Nigeria are both broad and deep, a dangerous
combination in a country whose people have high expectations and
little patience. (Roughton, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., May 24, in both (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NUCLEAR _ WASHINGTON _ An advance setting up President
Clinton's trip this week to Portugal, Germany and Russia that will
focus on nuclear nonproliferation and the test ban treaty. Topping
his agenda in Moscow are talks aimed at fundamentally restructuring
the future of strategic arms control between the world's largest
nuclear powers. Clinton hopes to amend a 30-year-old treaty and lay
the groundwork for a third SALT treaty, calling for increased deep
cuts in long range nuclear weapons in this country and in Russia.
He's pushed aside Republican threats to kill any deals he might
make on the hope that Al Gore might inherit his office? _ and
perhaps even a more treaty-friendly Senate. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., May 24, in both (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: President Clinton's trip is expected to begin Monday, May
29. White House correspondent Bob Deans will be traveling with him
and filing spot.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Venezuelan elections are scheduled to be held.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GUN-SHOWS _ WASHINGTON _ Ten minutes vs. three days. The length
of background checks at gun shows is a central point of contention
in the congressional battle on guns. Gun show operators say a
three-day wait will put them out of business. Gun control advocates
and President Clinton say an instant check would be worthless
because it would not weed out criminals. We ask both sides whether
there is room for compromise as gun legislation remains stuck in
Congress. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GUNSHOW-LIST _ List of states with the most gun shows. Texas is
number one.
</P>
<P>
   VENTURE _ WASHINGTON _ Since the early 1960s, venture capital
firms have been backing babies that have grown up into massive
corporations, such as Microsoft Corp. and Intel Corp. Today, many
of those now-grown companies are turning around and using their own
profits to fund in-house venture capital subsidiaries, hoping to
make big profits while gaining insights into the new technologies
being developed by entrepreneurs. (Geewax, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED TUESDAY in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-MUSEUMS _ BALTIMORE _ Children's museums are booming across
the United States. Brighter, busier and more interactive than ever,
they have doubled in number in the last 15 years, and 60 more are
due to open by 2003. Two reasons for the explosive growth: Working
parents like the idea of combining education and play during their
limited ``quality time'' with their children, and teachers like to
expose their students to ``hands-on'' learning activities.
(Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-FLOOD _ WASHINGTON _ How museums around the country rallied
to the aid of the children's museum in Rocky Mount, N.C.,
devastated by last years floods. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-LIST _ Museums, highlights and contact information for each
Cox state.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-BEST _ Prize-winning museums across the nation.
</P>
