<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SHOOTER0528-COX     05-27 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTER0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good boy goes bad
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Nobody expected violence from Nate Brazill,
the 7th grader who smiled a lot and made good grades, played the
tuba and stayed out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Lake Worth Middle School cafeteria at breakfast a few
weeks ago, schoolmates say, the 13-year-old Brazill talked about
getting his hands on a gun. And on Friday, after an
uncharacteristic brush with trouble, police say Brazill used it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me his grandfather had a gun and he knew where it was
at,'' said Marc Lawerns, a sixth-grader at Lake Worth Middle
School. ``He didn't say what he was going to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, in the final minutes of the last day of the
school year, police say, Brazill shot 35-year-old teacher Barry
Grunow, killing him with a single shot to the head.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill got As and Bs, seldom missed school and had no
disciplinary record, Palm Beach County school district spokesman
Nat Herrington said.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, Brazill was sent home from school early for
throwing water balloons.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers, students and family members say they can't believe
what happened two hours later when Brazill came back to campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in total disbelief. Every indication points to the fact
that Nate was a good student and a good boy,'' said Frank Bermudez,
Brazill's band director the past two years. He said he saw no hints
that the 13-year-old was capable of killing.
</P>
<P>
   Bermudez called Nate a ``team player'' who switched instruments
from trumpet to tuba at the beginning of the school year to fill a
gap in the band. Added Bermudez, the father of an 11-year-old: ``I
would have had him hang out with my son.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not Nate,'' said Elizabeth Koontz, the gym teacher
at Barton Elementary, where Brazill was a student until two years
ago. ``I would never have imagined this child to do something like
this . . . Out of all the kids that have passed through my field,
this is one that I would never have expected to be involved in
something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nate walked the halls with a smile on his face,'' said Marc
Ariot, 14, another student.''This is really messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Near Brazill's apartment in a one-story gray stucco building on
South H Street, neighbors said they would often hear Brazill
playing his trumpet or tuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed like a good boy. He did,''' said neighbor Zenaida
Maldonado.
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor, Pastor Corey Jackson of the New Birth Family
Worship Center, said Brazill and his mother had planned to come
hear him preach Friday night at a church in Boynton Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill's apartment is shared with his mother, stepfather and
2-year-old sister, neighbors said. Brazill's parents divorced and
his father lives in Daytona Beach. His mother, Polly, recently had
surgery for breast cancer, said her mother and Brazill's
grandmother, Everlina Josey.
</P>
<P>
   Josey, 75, came to the police station with Brazill's sister
after she saw reports of the shooting and arrest on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was the best boy in the world. We gave him
everything he wanted,'' Josey said. ``Everyone gave him the highest
praise.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazill took the gun he used to kill Grunow from a grandfather
in Boynton Beach about a week ago, Lake Worth Police spokeswoman
Lt. Rachel Houston said. She would not release the grandfather's
name.
</P>
<P>
   At Brazill's other grandfather's house, family members and
friends began arriving shortly after Brazill was named on
television as the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it,'' said Rena Brazill, an aunt, over the
sound of crying from inside the house.
</P>
<P>
   Family friend Marcy Hardemon, who said she has known Brazill
since he was a little boy at New Hope Baptist Church, also
expressed disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone called and said that was Nate, I said 'No, that
was someone else,' `` Hardemon said. ``The kind of guy he is, he
wouldn't even associate with people who would carry guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
