</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TURKEY-HUNTING0528-CO     05-27 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-HUNTING0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hunter's hear the call of the wild is heard
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Goobble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gobblegobblegobble,'' he continued, passionately, flogging a
fallen tree trunk with his hat to make a sound like the beating of
large wings.
</P>
<P>
   Still no reply. Far away, a crow cawed. Finally Doug Benefield
got to his feet, shaking his head in disgust. ``He's a wise old
bird,'' Benefield said. ``He's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Benefield is a master of the art of talking to turkeys, but this
time he was unable to persuade an old tom to venture across the
sights of his shotgun. It tended to prove that this suburban turkey
is just as wily as his country cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkeys can see 10 times better than we can,'' said Benefield,
a professional hunter and guide. ``They can hear better than we
can, too. If they could smell, you'd never be able to kill one.''
Mankind's only salvation, apparently, is that turkeys can't grow
opposable thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Turkeys are being hunted and killed only a handful of miles from
the shadow of the state Capitol. But
</P>
<P>
   it's no massacre. According to Benefield, only those toms who
throw caution to the wind in a fit of lust, jealousy, boastfulness
or mere stupidity meet their end that way. The others just fade
into the underbrush, clucking with amusement.
</P>
<P>
   On a weekday morning toward the end of the season, Benefield
took a reporter into the suburbs in search of a gobbler. The only
real difference in hunting turkeys there and those deeper in the
country is noise. It seems as though there's always a jetliner
overhead. ``I hate that,'' Benefield said.
</P>
<P>
   At first light the hollows were filled with a fog so dense that
Lon Chaney, hairy of brow and paw, might have slunk out of it at
any moment. This led to an explanation of the first rule of turkey
hunting: You Never Know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fog might be bad for us,'' Benefield said. ``But you never
know. I've known 'em to gobble in the fog.''
</P>
<P>
   A hunter neither tracks turkeys nor sits in a tree hoping one
will stumble along. He calls them up. He wanders around the woods
making noises like a hen turkey until a tom or a jake _ an immature
tom _ answers. Then the hunter hunkers down and tries to entice the
bird within gunshot.
</P>
<P>
   In a huge tract of forest whose owner had given Benefield
permission to hunt, Benefield drove slowly down dirt paths,
stopping on the hilltops to call. In addition to sounding like a
hen turkey, he can also imitate the barred owl. He has placed in
the top five in numerous turkey calling contests, but he is the
world champion barred owl caller. This is significant because toms
will often gobble at the sound of a barred owl.
</P>
<P>
   So will anyone standing next to him when he does it; at such
close proximity he sounds like the Owl that Ate Palmetto. But on
this chilly morning, suburban turkeys were indifferent to owls.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping the owl act, Benefield begins talking turkey. Imitating
the hen is called ``yelping,'' because a major component of their
vocal repertoire is exactly that. There are also demure clucks and
coos, loud, demanding ``kak-kak-kak'' calls, and a long, passionate
wail.
</P>
<P>
   He managed to whip the geese on a nearby lake into a frenzy of
honking, and from far, far away a tom gobbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like a turkey in a pen somewhere,'' he said, and moved
on.
</P>
<P>
   Between hen-yelping and owl-hooting from one vantage point after
another, Benefield described turkey hunting as a battle of wits
between man and bird. The hunter seeks that which will,
essentially, float the tom's boat, and as usual, it's sex, machismo
or gratuitous violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's really lovesick, he might just come running. But
usually he's more cautious than that. Lots of times, a tom won't
move at all when you call him. He'll gobble and strut and expect
the hen to come to him. If she doesn't, then that's it, because
he's not going to go to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other times, he'll come just so far and no further. It's like
he's drawn a line on the ground, and he might strut and demonstrate
along that line for hours, but he won't go any further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then sometimes a tom won't respond to yelps at all, but if you
gobble like another tom he'll come to investigate and maybe drive
him off. Gobbling and making a noise like a couple of toms
fighting, sometimes that'll bring another tom along real quick.
They love to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest sport there is,'' said Benefield, a tall,
wiry man of 30. ``You won't believe how loud a tom can sound when
he gobbles in the woods. It just sends a chill down my spine every
time. It's a wonder I haven't had a heart attack out here, I get so
excited.''
</P>
<P>
   But the excitement mustn't show. Once a turkey is located and
the calling begins, the hunter most remain as still as possible.
The tom is likely to scan the killing ground before the hunter sees
him, and the slightest movement may betray the trap. Sometimes a
hunter will set out a few decoys before he begins calling. There
are even decoys to be set up to represent a jake copulating with a
hen _ ``guaranteed to drive a tom wild with anger,'' according to
one catalog. That, Benefield believes, is going a bit too far.
</P>
<P>
   The fog lifted well after sunup, and for the 20th time,
Benefield got out of his big Ford truck to call _ this time in a
hollow. He has many ways of calling. There is the tube with a
diaphragm, a kind of simple accordion. There is a piece of clear
plastic set in metal, over which he scrapes a fancy stick of
hardwood to make the appropriate screeches and yelps. But mostly he
uses, in his mouth, a small bladder with three reeds attached. By
various combinations of blowing over it and tonguing it, he can
produce all the sounds of a lovelorn hen.
</P>
<P>
   He utters only a few yelps before there comes, from up the hill
somewhere, a mighty response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gobblegobblegobblegobble'' _ a commanding, masculine overture,
beginning with a harsh, metallic clash as though two copper pans
were banged together. Benefield ducked as though the turkey had
shot at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ruined!'' he hissed. ``He'll see the truck!'' In hopes
of avoiding ruin, Benefield pulled a camouflage mask over his face
and camouflage gloves over his hands and began creeping up the hill
at an angle to the sound of the turkey. Halfway up, he yelped
again, and received a quick answer.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he reached a spot which seemed to be behind the turkey,
away from the truck, and settled down to business. He sat down,
back to a tree, shotgun at the ready on his knees.
</P>
<P>
   He called, tentatively. Not too aggressive to begin with. Some
toms don't like pushy hens.
</P>
<P>
   The tom answered. The exchange went back and forth a dozen
times, with the tom's gobble growing louder. Benefield began pawing
at the dried leaves on the forest floor as he yelped and squawked.
</P>
<P>
   The turkey gobbled twice more, sounding as though he was holding
his position, and his final gobble was more faint than the one
before. Desperate, Benefield switched genders.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing his neck exactly like a tom, he began to gobble. He even
imitated the snort and whirring sound of a strutting tom. No use.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have a hen with him,'' Benefield said, ``and she lured
him away. Hens are really jealous.''
</P>
<P>
   Or it may just have been too much trouble. ``It's getting toward
the end of the season. The more established, dominant toms are
tired. They're not so interested in new hens.'' You Never Know.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, he was gone, reminiscent of a great old stomp
that Sonny Terry and Willie McGhee used to do, about a fellow who
realized he had overstayed his sentence on the county farm and
decamped forthwith.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, looka yonder, what I see . . .
</P>
<P>
   The woods at that point were open, and the old tom might have
gotten close enough to peer over a log and catch sight of
Benefield, even though everything about him _ even his shotgun _
was covered in camo.
</P>
<P>
   Ole red-eye cap'n,
</P>
<P>
   He's a-comin' after me . . .
</P>
<P>
   No use going after that old tom. A week later, Benefield went
back to that hill and called again. This time he got a glimpse of
The One that Got Away. ``Biggest turkey I ever saw,'' he reported.
``Head the size of a softball. So big he could hardly run.''
</P>
<P>
   But I'm lo-oo-ng gone,
</P>
<P>
   Long gone, long gone!
</P>
<P>
   Like a turkey through the corn.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
