<HEADER>
A7569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-CUTTING0528-COX     05-27 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CUTTING0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Secret Cutting'' discloses reality of painful disorder
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Dawn Cottrell doesn't have any friends.
Classmates tease her constantly. Her musician boyfriend only wants
her for sex. She has an overbearing mother and a passive father.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Dawn isn't happy. But the only way the teen loner
knows how to deal with her gloomy existence is by harming herself.
She stabs herself with tools. Slices her wrists with glass. Burns
her arm with a cigarette lighter. Her body looks like a grotesque
human pin cushion. Dawn may not control her life, but, she reasons,
she can be in charge of her own pain.
</P>
<P>
   The logic may be twisted, but self-injury is a problem that
affects over two million Americans, including one in every two
hundred teens. It's a disorder in which people injure themselves to
secure relief from their emotional pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secret Cutting,'' a sensitive, thought-raising film, tackles
this thorny issue head-on. Disorders such as Dawn's (Kimberlee
Peterson) are often easily dismissed. After all, anyone who
constantly harms herself must be crazy, right? In Dawn's case,
she's crying out for help.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn's mom (Sean Young) doesn't help matters much. After her
daughter injures herself again, her first concern is the amount of
stress Dawn is putting the family through. Meanwhile, dad (Robert
Wisden) is no help. He buries himself in his work or just simply
ignores the warning signs. And Dawn's angry brother shouts things
like, ``The next time you slice yourself, I hope you die!''
</P>
<P>
   With seemingly no one to turn to, Dawn is finally able to
confide in a caring therapist (Rhea Perlman), who seems to
understand Dawn's inner torment.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to dismiss ``Secret Cutting'' as yet another
half-baked, victim-of-the-week TV movie. Indeed, the film barely
strays from the standard TV movie formula. Nevertheless, ``Secret
Cutting'' is a film parents should watch with their kids. Too many
parents fail to communicate with their kids or connect with them on
any level. That's at the root of Dawn's problem. All she really
needs is someone to listen to her. Kids should feel like they can
talk to their parents about anything. No wonder so many young
people are behind school shootings and violent outbursts. Often, so
much rage is pent up inside. Eventually, that anger has to be
released.
</P>
<P>
   As the emotionally disturbed Dawn, Peterson is eerily effective.
Her ghost-white skin, joyless eyes and painful expressions make
Dawn someone you pity and sympathize with. Young, who has had some
emotional problems of her own (actor James Woods once filed a
harassment suit against her) is also in fine form as Dawn's
self-absorbed mom.
</P>
<P>
   The subject matter certainly isn't pretty. And, at times, when
Dawn is stabbing herself, she looks downright possessed. But if
``Secret Cutting ``makes you a better friend _ and parent _ to your
kid, it's definitely worth your time. Remember, your child could be
screaming out for help and you don't even know it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
