<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO0528-COX     05-27 2162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trial evidence may shed light on events at Waco
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Like John F. Kennedy's last moments in the
convertible and the shattered shell of the Oklahoma City federal
building, the image has been seared into the national psyche: fire
engulfing the Branch Davidian compound with more than 80 men, women
and children inside.
</P>
<P>
   Before the flames were extinguished at the Mount Carmel compound
near Waco, ending the deadliest law enforcement action in U.S.
history, the questions began: How and why did this happen?
Attorneys Mike Caddell and Mike Bradford want to answer the
questions and dispel the conspiracy theories that have smoldered
since the April 19, 1993 FBI assault. From opposite sides of the
Davidians' wrongful death lawsuit against the federal government,
the lawyers want the truth revealed when the lawsuit goes to trial
June 19 in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The case is much more than a wrongful death lawsuit for Caddell,
a Houston lawyer representing surviving Davidians and families of
Davidians who died, and Bradford, a U.S. attorney from Beaumont
defending the government. It's an opportunity to help heal a
national wound.
</P>
<P>
   Both want to win and both have different interpretations of what
happened at Mount Carmel. But both say it's time for facts to be
aired and debated.
</P>
<P>
   The trial before U.S. District Judge Walter Smith _ who will
rule on the case instead of a jury _ will bring the events of Mount
Carmel to life again, as Davidians who survived the flames and
federal agents who took part in the confrontation tell their
stories.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 28, 1993, 76 agents from the federal Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms raided the Davidians' compound, seeking to
arrest the Davidians' leader and self-described prophet, David
Koresh, and search the compound for illegal guns. Gunshots were
exchanged, killing four ATF agents and five Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   That began a 51-day standoff that ended on April 19 when FBI
agents ordered the Davidians to surrender and assaulted the
compound with armored vehicles and tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   As the armored vehicles began demolishing the structure, fires
broke out and quickly spread throughout Mount Carmel, where Koresh
preached end-of-the world predictions. Each side blames the other
for starting the fires.
</P>
<P>
   Koresh and 73 of his followers _ including 22 children _ died
inside from gunshots wounds or the fire. Both sides in the lawsuit
say some of the Davidians' wounds appeared self-inflicted. Nine of
the people inside survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in many respects, (the trial) will have a cathartic
effect for not only the participants but for a lot of the American
public,'' Caddell said. ``The truth is, most people feel like they
don't know what really happened, even today.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress held hearings on the incidents, Caddell said
the plaintiffs have ``found critical document after critical
document that was not revealed to Congress, that was not disclosed.
We now have a much clearer picture of the story. To me, the case is
about abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said plaintiffs also have found some evidence that
supports the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have investigated something and we have concluded that
there was no irresponsible action on the part of the government, we
say so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford, a former state district judge, said he hopes the trial
will vindicate the federal agents and restore trust in the federal
agencies involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important case, and one of the reasons I agreed to
become a part of it is because I think it's important for the truth
to come out, and for the public to have confidence in the
government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Richardson, a researcher who has worked with the FBI to
prevent future incidents like Waco, said the Davidians' lawsuit has
brought new scrutiny to evidence that has sat in government offices
for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the trial and the judge making the pre-trial rulings
that he has, we'd know a lot less than we know,'' said Richardson,
a professor of sociology and judicial studies at the University of
Nevada at Reno. ``So the legal process is working.''
</P>
<P>
   LAWSUIT TAKES AIM AT GOVERNMENT
</P>
<P>
   The Davidians' lawsuit claims federal agents shot
indiscriminately at the Davidians during the initial raid and fired
into the compound on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 100 plaintiffs claim the FBI ``created a death
trap'' at Mount Carmel by demolishing the building earlier than
planned, using devices that could have started the fire and failing
to have firefighters present.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who presided over the 1994 criminal trial of eleven
Davidians _ eight were convicted of manslaughter or lesser charges
_ first must decide whether the government is responsible for the
Davidians' deaths. If Smith finds the government liable, he then
will consider the plaintiffs' demand for monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
   Smith could award whatever compensation he considered
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case was never about trying to collect a huge amount of
money,'' Caddell said. ``This case was about forcing the government
to accept its share of the responsibility for the deaths of the
people who died at Mount Carmel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford and Justice Department lawyer Marie Hagen will argue
the government's case. Bradford said he's confident the evidence
will put the responsibility on Koresh and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, law enforcement didn't handle everything perfectly,
but we think the evidence is clear that the cause of this tragedy
was the Davidians themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial has generated a mountain of evidence _ and allegations
by Caddell that the government has concealed, lost, or destroyed
key information.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Smith ordered all federal agencies to turn over any
Davidian-related evidence. The government initially fought the
order, then began shipping hundreds of boxes of documents,
videotapes, audio recordings, photographs, and Mount Carmel debris
to the Waco federal courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Caddell asked the judge to force the government to
produce ``missing'' evidence or hold the government's lawyers in
contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Smith denied the request. He ruled that the FBI may have
mishandled or mislabeled some evidence, but ``there is nothing to
indicate that this was the result of anything more than mere
negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell will argue that negligence permeated every aspect of the
government's handling of its encounter with the Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   Each side has accused the other of pulling the trigger first
during the initial raid. Caddell said he isn't conceding that the
Davidians shot first, but will focus on how the agents fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``ATF agents were firing at the building even when they couldn't
identify a specific target, and consequently, we believe that
people who were not firing a weapon were killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also in question is whether FBI agents shot at people inside
Mount Carmel during the April 19 assault.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen Davidians died from gunshot wounds at close range,
according to a 1996 congressional investigation. It concluded that
the federal agencies botched the operation but laid the ultimate
blame on Koresh.
</P>
<P>
   Koresh died of a bullet wound to his head. He was found lying
next to his close friend, Steve Schneider, who apparently shot
himself in the mouth with a rifle according to an autopsy report.
</P>
<P>
   The government insists the agents did not fire at the Davidians
on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell argues that the FBI agents and leaders, tired and
frustrated after weeks of negotiations with a religious group whose
doctrine they didn't understand, sent a couple of agents in with
the armored vehicles to try to kill Koresh and other leaders _
under the theory that other Davidians were being held hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they were sent in to kill all the Davidians, I
think it was a misguided, unfortunate decision by people who were
frustrated and angry and became impatient,'' Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO SPAWNS FURTHER QUESTIONS
</P>
<P>
   A key piece of evidence from the April 19 assault is the
infrared surveillance video filmed from an FBI aircraft. The video
shows bright flashes that the plaintiffs say are proof of
government gunfire that kept the Davidians from escaping the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The government contends that the flashes are sunlight reflecting
off the broken glass and other debris.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Vector Data Systems, a British subsidiary of a U.S.
defense firm, conducted a simulation at Fort Hood of conditions on
the day of the raid at Mount Carmel, using equipment similar to
what the FBI had used. Caddell had urged the simulation and former
Sen. John Danforth, the special counsel appointed by Attorney
General Janet Reno to investigate the events, agreed, suggesting
Vector for the job.
</P>
<P>
   The company concluded that flashes on the FBI infrared
videotapes were sunlight reflected off debris, not flashes
indicative of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   The report, Bradford said, ``was really favorable to the
government in all respects.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell, who recently interviewed the Vector analysts in sworn
depositions, said at least one of the three people who signed the
company's report admitted he wasn't qualified to interpret the
infrared tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are going to be shocked when they read the
deposition testimony,'' he said. ``They don't even agree with each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he did not consider the simulation conclusive
evidence and will listen to experts from both sides before ruling
whether government agents fired at the Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DID THE FIRE START?
</P>
<P>
   The government was listening intently to the Davidians'
conversations inside Mount Carmel, using bugging devices smuggled
into the compound. What they heard on April 19, 1993 also is
disputed.
</P>
<P>
   As the armored vehicles began their tear gas assault on the
compound, government agents monitored the conversations inside. The
government claims the voices were too garbled to know what was
being said at the time, but that later enhancement showed the
Davidians talked about ``spreading fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said the conversations, combined with the infrared
video that shows fire breaking out ``almost simultaneously in three
parts of the compound,'' suggest that the Davidians set the fires.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs say that the audio tapes show the government knew
of the potential for fire and did nothing. There were no
firefighters at the scene, and local firefighters didn't arrive
until 30 minutes after the fires started.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no plan at all to fight a fire,'' Caddell said.
``(The FBI) had even been offered, free of charge. . . an armored
firefighting vehicle, and they thumbed their noses at it. And I
think that's criminal. That's criminal negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the government agents involved face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said he's prepared to defend the FBI's decision to not
have firefighters at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision was made not to expose the firefighters to the
danger of being shot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``WE DO NEED TO KNOW WHAT HAPPENED AT WACO.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the discovery of a tear gas canister in an evidence
room intensified the debate over who started the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney William Johnston wanted to defuse
charges that the government was covering up what really happened at
Mount Carmel. So he allowed Michael McNulty _ the researcher whose
work anchored the Academy Award-nominated documentary ``Waco: The
Rules of Engagement'' _ to view evidence held by the Texas
Department of Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   McNulty spotted a 40 mm cartridge later determined to be the
remains of a military round used to fire tear gas _ a round capable
of starting a fire.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery punched a hole in six years of government denials
that federal forces used explosive or flammable devices during the
assault. And it increased doubt about the government's honesty,
feeding conspiracy theories and spurring Reno to appoint Danforth,
of Missouri, as special counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the evidence that the government started the
fire is at least as good as the evidence that the Davidians started
the fire,'' Caddell said. ``The myth that's been created, of
course, is that the Davidians wanted to commit suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who killed themselves apparently did so after fire began,
he said. Faced with the flames, Caddell said, the Davidians
thought, ``Here's my choice, burn to death or put a bullet in my
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, the University of Nevada professor, said the trial
may not answer once and for all how the fire started or whether the
FBI shot at the Davidians. But he said he hopes that by airing the
evidence _ from both the Davidians' and the governments'
perspectives _ the trial can give Americans enough information to
make their own judgments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to know what happened at Waco,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
