<HEADER>
A7571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-520&AMP;A     05-27 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S OPPOSITION CANDIDATE REBOUNDS
</HEADLINE>
  By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Vicente Fox Quesada, the leading opposition
presidential candidate, gave a vigorous but level-headed
performance Friday night in a televised debate with two rivals that
helped him recover from embarrassing mistakes in his campaign last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who dissected the 90-minute face-off _ and telephone
polling _ agreed that Fox won the encounter by keeping his cool,
playing down attacks on his opponents and stressing proposals to
bring a wide range of Mexicans into his programs for change.
</P>
<P>
   A leftist opposition contender, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano,
made points by continually assailing his rivals, although his main
target was Francisco Labastida Ochoa of the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The post-mortem consensus was that Labastida's bland showing,
and the fire he took from both rivals, put him in third place for
the debate.
</P>
<P>
   All three candidates had acknowledged that the debate, the
second and last televised meeting between presidential contenders,
was pivotal to their prospects in the July 2 balloting. Opinion
polls showed Fox ahead in the race briefly earlier this month, but
he has recently fallen back into a dead heat with Labastida.
Cardenas is a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   Because of electoral reforms since the last presidential vote in
1994, the field is more level for opponents to compete with the
PRI, which has held presidential power for seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have made for the most dynamic race Mexicans have
ever seen as polls shift from week to week in response to the
campaigns. The candidates agreed to a free-wheeling format that
allowed for unusually spontaneous exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   In a national telephone poll conducted Friday night by the daily
newspaper Reforma, 47 percent of those contacted said Fox was the
winner, 19 percent named Labastida and 18 percent Cardenas.
Responding to a separate question that asked who was the loser, 43
percent named Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida sought to appear presidential by avoiding personal
attacks, ignoring his opponents' jabs and sticking with an upbeat
roster of his proposals to improve education and fight crime. But
his rhetoric was often vague, making him sound like a bureaucrat
instead of a man keen to prove himself against Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the voice of the system,'' said Enrique Krauze, a
political commentator on the Televisa network. ``His language was
too institutional and antiquated.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida did not stress that he would change the PRI to
eliminate the corruption that has alienated many voters, but
neither was he forceful in defending his party's accomplishments in
government.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was fighting for his political life. He needed to repair
damage he inflicted on himself with peevish behavior in
negotiations on live television where he tried to force the other
two contenders into an on-the-spot debate Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Fox started out by apologizing to viewers for the stubbornness
he revealed earlier, but he said it was the product of firm
character. ``Do you think a weak and gray person could stand up to
the PRI and its allies?'' he asked.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He trumped his opponents with a bit of theater when Cardenas
hammered at him about the support of his party, the right-of-center
National Action Party, for an unpopular $80 billion bailout of the
Mexican banks.
</P>
<P>
   Several political parties in the Congress are holding secret
codes needed to open a computer file that contains the names of
Mexicans who benefited from the bailout. Although the opposition
parties believe that the files will show extensive corruption in
the bailout, they have not agreed on opening them.
</P>
<P>
   With a flourish designed to show that he would not protect
corrupt bankers, Fox handed the secret codes belonging to his party
``for safekeeping'' to the moderator of the debate, Ricardo Rocha,
an independent journalist. Fox said he would open the bailout files
if he became president.
</P>
<P>
   When he did not get his way over the date of the debate, Fox
suggested petulantly he would not participate in it at all. After
emergency meetings with leaders of his party, he agreed to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, after siding with Labastida against Fox over when to
hold the debate, went out of his way to show that he is no friend
of the governing party candidate. He worked hard to link Labastida
to Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the disgraced former president who is
now in forced exile in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas sought to portray himself as a consistent crusader for
democracy. ``I'm still fighting the fight and I will always be just
as you have always seen me, as a man of principle,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
