<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IVORYCOAST-MAPOUKA-56     05-27 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORYCOAST-MAPOUKA-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE HAS AFRICANS SHAKING BEHINDS AND HEADS 
</HEADLINE>
   By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ The night was getting wild, the air tense
with expectation, as the crowd at a military academy waited for the
show's top act, three female Ivoirian dancers known as ``Les
Tueuses,'' or The Killers. Until last December, Les Tueuses, the
queens of a suggestive dance craze called the mapouka, had been
banned from television, judged too vulgar by the government, which
was subsequently toppled in a Christmas Eve coup.
</P>
<P>
   Their reputation rehabilitated under military rule, Les Tueuses
finally took the stage recently, quickly shedding their diaphanous
white robes in favor of blue sequined bikini tops and long skirts
with, of course, never-ending slits.
</P>
<P>
   As uniformed soldiers stretched to keep the crowd of hundreds
under control, Les Tueuses plunged into the audience, targeting a
cadet here, another there, leaving the young men, and women
spectators, dazed under a blur of gyration and wiggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I adore mapouka, but I especially like Les Tueuses,'' said
Eliane Meledje, a 25-year-old seamstress, who had traveled several
hours from her neighborhood of Yopougon to attend the show at the
academy outside Abidjan this Saturday night. ``With them, you feel
liberated.''
</P>
<P>
   The army is still in charge in this West African nation. The
military ruler, Gen. Robert Guei, has yet to announce elections or
say whether he will run, to the dismay of international donors who
are staying away.
</P>
<P>
   But as the political transition drags on in what was once the
most stable country in West Africa, an unexpected entry in the
winners' column has been mapouka, a dance that had been treated in
official corners as something like an infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
   Banned from Ivoirian television _ chased away by officials in
neighboring countries such as Togo, Niger, Burkina Faso and Benin _
mapouka has spread nevertheless along the West African coast, from
Dakar to Kinshasa, in the last couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   The dance _ which focuses on, but is not limited to, the
surprisingly difficult act of wiggling one's buttocks without
moving one's hips _ also became an endless source of discussions
and newspaper ruminations on culture, sex, women and men,
especially in the Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   It was perhaps a measure of the fallen government's
disconnection with its 16 million citizens that it tried to ban
mapouka, even as the dance grew so popular that many young women
desperately tried to gain weight _ the better to perform a dance
that works best with an ample backside. After the military took
power, it seemed that the new government's first major policy shift
was directed at mapouka.
</P>
<P>
   The dance popped up on television. Les Tueuses led a performance
for soldiers at the national stadium, and their photos appeared on
the front pages of newspapers, including the government-controlled
ones. Then, on the day before their recent Saturday show at the
military academy, Les Tueuses put on a private show for Guei
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president loves mapouka,'' said one of the dancers, known
as Victorine the Viper, before the show in the stadium. ``During
our show yesterday, we saw him move his head, his feet. But we have
to admit that we, Les Tueuses, have three kinds of shows: one for
TV, one for our regular show, and one for officials. In front of
the president, we couldn't show him our buttocks and shake them
under his eyes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mapouka became popular in the nightclubs of Abidjan before
catching on abroad. Congo has traditionally been the big exporter
of music and dance in Africa, so the mapouka was something of a
first for the Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The dance is believed to be the descendant of a far tamer,
traditional dance in the country's coastal regions. By the time it
had reached Abidjan, though, the dance was performed mostly by
young women who bent and shook in ways that men could never
duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Abidjan's fairly easy-going cultural climate, Ivoirian
national television yanked video clips of popular performers,
saying that the mapouka did not follow the ``rules of good
behavior.'' Some criticized mapouka dancers for supposedly debasing
the country's cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have turned it into a depraved dance to the point that
the Ivory Coast became notorious, known in the region because of
it,'' said Jacques Powply, a cultural critic at Le Jour, a
newspaper based here. ``To me, it's lewd pleasures sought by men
who want to corrupt our original dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Others pointed out that suggestive dancing was nothing new to
the region. But the mapouka had upset officials, they said, because
the dance left out men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem with mapouka,'' said Valen Guede, a
musicologist and director of the Ivoirian Office of Authors'
Rights, ``lies in the fact that this dance can be danced only by
women, and only by a plump woman with a generous behind. All of
sudden, men are pushed to the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the dance caught on. As young women sought to outperform
one another, a large posterior became de rigueur. Contrary to the
beauty standards of the West, fleshiness is regarded as attractive
in both women and men in Africa, a sign of wealth and health on a
poor continent. But mapouka made plumpness fashionable even among
Westernized young women who had toyed with slimness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women started saying that fleshy was beautiful, and that one
had to be at least chubby,'' said Konate Yacouba, an author and
member of the National Institute of the Arts. ``Some who had been
dieting made an about-face and even started taking vitamin pills to
fatten up.''
</P>
<P>
   With the military's relaxed, if not enthusiastic, attitude
toward the mapouka, success looms large for Les Tueuses _ at least
until the next dance craze. The trio has recently gone on foreign
tours, including to New York and Montreal, said their manager, John
Chahin Sombo.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage just before their recent performance, the dancers
defended the mapouka against criticism of lewdness and female
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, our fans are made up in great part of women,'' said
a dancer who goes by the name Julie the Supple. ``Women become as
delirious as men. The mapouka is a phenomenon for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   One 16-year-old girl who came to the show, Amie Gbane, said she
was a big fan of Victorine the Viper.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a wicked look and dances really well,'' Gbane said.
``I'd love to dance like them.''
</P>
<P>
   But a 43-year-old nurse, who gave only her last name, Kone, said
she had come only to keep an eye on her two sons in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why the cadets invited them, but they must
have their own reason,'' said Kone. ``Look at how delirious they're
becoming! I don't like it when the dancers leave the stage and come
provoke the men in their seats. It embarrasses me greatly, and it's
the reason why I preferred asking Mr. Kone, my husband, to stay at
home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
