<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SHOOT-MAIN0528-COX     05-27 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-MAIN0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teen held in shooting of teacher
 &HT;    By Stephanie Desmon and Antigone Barton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ A Lake Worth Middle School seventh-grader
shot and killed his popular English teacher during the last period
of the last day of school, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Honor roll student Nathaniel Brazill, 13, who had been sent home
earlier Friday for his part in a water balloon fight, returned to
campus with a .25 caliber handgun in his pocket around 3:30 p.m.
Brazill shot Barry Grunow, 35, once in the face after the teacher
refused to let him say good-bye to two girls in his classroom, Room
301, said school district spokesman Nat Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   Several students and a teacher watched as Grunow fell to the
floor. His class had been watching a movie based on the book
``Killing Mr. Griffin,'' a tale of kids who plot to kill their
English teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh shit,'' Brazill said after firing the shot, fellow student
Ryan Otero told police.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Brazill waved the gun around, put it to the head of
teacher John James and ran from the building through an emergency
exit, students said. A school security camera recorded it all.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Brazill flagged down a police officer a
quarter-mile from the school and handed over the gun. He was in
police custody Friday night, charged with first-degree murder and
aggravated assault with a firearm, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a big pop,'' said 14-year-old Marc Ariot who passed by
just as the shot was fired. ``Everybody came running out of class.
They were shouting, 'He shot Mr. Grunow.' And instantly people
started crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked inside and I saw him laying there in a pool of blood
. . . I knew there was nothing I could do for him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a teacher has been killed inside a Palm
Beach County school.
</P>
<P>
   When word of the shooting spread _ some parents saw it crawl
across the television screen as they watched ``The Rosie O'Donnell
Show,'' others got frantic calls from their children _ parents
flocked to the school, crowding toward the street in front. They
cried. They used their cell phones. They tried to piece together
what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Students were locked down inside. Soon after the shooting,
Principal Sharon Walker came over the intercom and told students
and teachers to duck, to get away from the windows and to lock the
doors.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Lake Worth Police Chief William Smith shouted through a
microphone: ``Your children are safe. . . . No child in the school
is in any danger right now. No child has been injured. A teacher
has been injured by a gunshot.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene looked like pictures from Columbine High School in
Colorado, where last year two students went on a rampage and killed
12 classmates and a teacher before killing themselves. Since then,
schools across the country and in Palm Beach County have been on
heightened alert, extra wary of talk of guns and bombs and violence
in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the worst nightmare that could ever happen in
a public school,'' interim Superintendent Ben Marlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what, my son is not coming back to this
school,'' said parent Susan Wells. ``No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the gray walls of Grunow's classroom were empty
except for cut out letters that read, ``Welcome to Mr. Grunow's
Class.'' Grunow's cluttered desk offered clues to his life: A worn
brown briefcase, a golden apple paperweight, a half bag of Jelly
Belly's candy, a carnation. Still on the 39 student desks:
notebooks, hair brushes, purses, pens and old homework, a thumbed
copy of ``The Klutz Strikes Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Brazill had stolen the tiny gun, unloaded but with
bullets sitting alongside it, from a dresser drawer at his
grandfather's home sometime last week.
</P>
<P>
   So far, police don't know why Brazill brought the gun to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no information to support there was any plan or any
prior thought to this,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill had been sent home from school around 1:30 p.m. for his
throwing water balloons. Grunow had nothing to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill then walked the nearly 25 blocks from school to the home
of Everlena Josey, one of his grandmothers. He arrived hot and,
Josey thought, angry, around 2 p.m. or 2:30 p.m. He asked her for
the key to his apartment a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if anything seemed wrong with Brazill, Alfred Josui, an
uncle, said: ``He was the same old Nate. Just that he wasn't
smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazill went to his place and apparently took the gun he had
stolen a week earlier. He grabbed his green bicycle and started
back for school. No one noticed him as he came back on campus, said
Schools Police Chief Jim Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill wanted to see two girls in Grunow's classroom so he
knocked on the door. It was the last day of school, after all, and
he wanted to say goodbye, students said. Grunow answered and said
he had to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The two exchanged words. Brazill told police Grunow shoved him
and told him to return to class. Brazill took out the gun, firing
once. There were three more bullets inside, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he aimed the gun at teacher James and said, ``Don't bother
me, Mr. James.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazill surrendered quietly, putting his hands in the air a few
minutes later when a police officer spotted him on 17th Avenue
North. He told the officer, ``I shot somebody,'' according to a
police report.
</P>
<P>
   A father of two young children, a 5-year-old son and an infant
daughter, Grunow and his wife, Pam, had known each other since they
were 20 years old. Grunow loved to play basketball (he was an
All-Conference player at Jupiter High) and even coached the
after-school team. He was always seeking out those who needed extra
help, colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   Grunow started teaching at Lake Worth Middle in 1995,
transferring there from another middle school in suburban Boca
Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the bad kids, he'd find the good in them,'' said Ashley
Watson, a 16-year-old former student. ``He could do that. He saw
something in me. He knew I was looking for something and he
encouraged me to get into drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlin went to the teacher's home and met with Pam Grunow for
about 30 minutes Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's devastated,'' he said. ``Like she said, the question is
'Why? Why?' We don't have an answer for her.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cruz, a 15-year-old in eighth grade at Lake Worth Middle,
said Grunow had been riding Brazill pretty hard in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been saying for a while he don't like the teacher
(Grunow),'' said Cruz, who didn't attend classes Friday but stopped
by to pick up his previously confiscated cell phone. ``He's always
bugging him: Tuck in your shirt. What about your grades? You know.
He's been saying he's going to shoot someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz said he didn't take Brazill seriously because he didn't
think he'd do it. ``He's a goofball.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said teacher and student seemed to have a pretty good
relationship. Brazill's grades were A's and B's and he rarely
missed a day. He played the tuba in the band and planned next year
to be a peer mediator for kids in trouble. ``He told the
investigators that he liked the teacher,'' Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look that way to Loren Looney, 13, who was in the
classroom when Brazill came to the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get it out of my mind . . . Mr. Grunow said, 'Don't
point that thing at me,''' she said. ``And he shot him. I feel so
bad, I loved Mr. Grunow so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Gandolfo was also in Grunow's class when he saw Brazill
fire. ``I was 10 feet from the gun,'' the seventh-grader said.
``Everyone was screaming, crying, hysterical. One girl was on the
floor. She couldn't move she was so scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what Mr. Grunow could have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazill lives with his mother in Lake Worth and his father lives
in Daytona Beach. The father, also named Nathaniel Brazill, said he
had seen his son two weeks ago on a visit to Palm Beach County and
he seemed fine. He described his son as a quiet, respectful,
bright, articulate, church-going computer nerd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tragedy,'' the father said. ``I am so sorry for the
family of this teacher, so very sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The father plans to drive to Lake Worth today. ``It's going to
be a long weekend. Let's face it _ the boy could be facing the
chair for this kind of crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Grief counselors will be at school today for any students or
teachers who need to talk. Smith and Marlin may appear Monday on
ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Frank Bermudez, Brazill's music teacher at Lake Worth
Middle: ``I don't know who to pray harder for: Nate's family or Mr.
Grunow's
</P>
<P>
   family.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
