<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SOFT-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SOFT MONEY EXPLOSION
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, May 28:
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, at the MCI Sports Center in Washington, the
Democratic Party raised an astonishing $26.5 million at a dinner
headlined by President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore and
attended by about 12,000 loyal Democrats, some paying a
half-million dollars for the privilege. This staggering sum
surpassed what until then had been the record, the $21.3 million
raised less than a month before by the Republicans and George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion cemented Clinton's legacy as the most persuasive
and productive fund-raiser in American political history. Joe
Lockhart, his press secretary, suggested that his boss might end up
raising a cool billion before he is through. But it also dramatized
something less deserving of awe, namely the complete domination of
the campaign environment by soft money.
</P>
<P>
   At one time or another, Clinton and Gore have decried soft
money. Even so, the soft money race proceeds at a torrid clip,
without shame or remorse in either political party. As of last
week, the two parties had raised at least $200 million in soft
money, a record for this point in the election cycle, and they are
well on their way to doubling the $260 million in soft money raised
in 1996. Meanwhile, individual contributions are reaching nosebleed
altitudes when some dinner guests fork over $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money has been making a mockery of the post-Watergate
campaign finance laws ever since the parties began exploiting a
loophole that permitted unlimited contributions to the political
parties rather than individual candidates. But the new numbers are
so outlandish that they numb the mind and threaten to dull the
capacity for outrage. Yet this is the very same money that has
purchased not only overnight stays in the Lincoln bedroom, but
access to the congressional offices where legislation affecting
millions of people is written. The main difference now is that
there is more of it.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the post-Watergate system has come about for
several reasons. One is Janet Reno's political timidity and the
failure of her Justice Department to investigate the fund-raising
abuses of 1996 _ the illegal foreign money, the Lincoln bedroom
money and all the rest of it. Another is the unwillingness of the
Republican leadership in the Senate, notably Trent Lott, to allow a
fair up-or-down vote on the broad ban on soft money sponsored by
Sens. John McCain and Russell Feingold. But why should he? A system
that allows Lott and Republican big shots in the House like Tom
DeLay to shake down contributors in exchange for influence rewards
them every bit as much as it rewards the administration.
</P>
<P>
   A third reason is the spinelessness of the Federal Election
Commission, the government's main enforcement agency. The
commission has been as ineffectual as Reno in investigating abuses
and imposing restraints on the parties. But Lott and others, with
Bill Clinton's acquiescence, are determined to make it weaker
still. Last week, the Senate confirmed a Republican named Bradley
Smith for a seat on the commission despite Smith's sworn opposition
to the very campaign finance laws he is supposed to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   His approval was part of a deal in which the Republicans agreed
to unblock 16 of Clinton's judicial nominations. So just when the
fund-raising system is spinning wildly out of control, the country
is treated to a bipartisan sellout of the agency that is obliged
under the law to regulate it.
</P>
<P>
   The polls say that the public wants reform, and in recent months
dozens of corporations have decided to boycott what they see as
little more than a shakedown operation. But for the most part the
political leadership seems tone deaf. Bush would preserve the soft
money loophole. At the Democratic gala, Gore said that the next
dinner four years from now would not cost nearly as much because as
president he would bring ``meaningful'' change. But neither he nor
Clinton seemed the least bit embarrassed about dipping into the
trough one more time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1439EDT &QL; 
