<HEADER>
A7582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.J.-COLUMN-CHARMER-N     05-27 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.J.-COLUMN-CHARMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: A CHARMER FINALLY HAMSTRUNG IN A ROGUES BIATHLON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Fla.)   By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back when life was good, Robert E. Brennan had racehorses,
waterfront homes, helicopters, a plane and the tanned good looks
and hint of mystery that make for star quality. Financing it all
was his nationwide penny stock firm, First Jersey Securities, which
he promoted with televised commercials from his helicopter,
imploring investors to ``Come grow with us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, he always seemed headed somewhere exciting _ a
possible run for political office, the dedication of another
building his generosity made possible, a visit with an important
politician.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday he seemed headed for jail.
</P>
<P>
   An artist of the shady deal and a champion charmer, Brennan, 56,
was momentarily out of moves. In civil actions, a federal judge
ruled in 1995 that Brennan's operation was a ``massive and
continuing fraud,'' and last year a New Jersey judge called him ``a
big crook.'' He owes $120 million in restitution to state and
federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he surrendered his prized golf course in Monmouth
County to avoid jail on contempt charges. Creditors are also
seeking the palatial house in Juno Beach, Fla., where he lives and
the multimillion-dollar off-shore trusts they say he controls in
Gibraltar and Nevis.
</P>
<P>
   His eyes a bit bloodshot, the once-voluble Brennan was subdued
outside the courtroom in Manhattan, saying only: ``This is a
difficult time. I hope you'll respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Brennan may be downcast now, but for years he led the
crowded field of New Jersey's Rogues Biathlon _ winning respect
while outrunning investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you summed it up in a word, it might be audacity,'' said
James M. Smith, once chief of the New Jersey Bureau of Securities.
``The in-your-face way of operating, the open challenge to
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan created First Jersey in 1974 out of an investment firm
that had been suspended by New Jersey officials for securities
violations. It went nationwide even as authorities investigated
Brennan for fraudulently inflating the price of cheap stocks, often
in lackluster companies in which he had an interest. The stocks
were sold by more than 1,000 salesmen making cold calls and reading
from sales scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Government investigations rarely went smoothly. In 1980, an
entire filing cabinet of documents in a case against First Jersey
vanished from a Securities and Exchange Commission office in New
York. A federal judge, John E. Sprizzo, removed himself from the
case after learning that Brennan had named a racehorse Sprizzo. The
two-legged Sprizzo barred Brennan from ever again naming a horse
after a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan saw opportunity everywhere. When Forbes magazine ran an
article critical of him, he ripped off the cover, which featured
his picture, and sent it to clients, never mentioning the words
inside.
</P>
<P>
   If his money was ill-gotten, at least he was charitable.
Buildings at Seton Hall University, the Jersey Shore Medical
Center, and St. Benedict's Prep School in Newark bear the Brennan
name. ``He is a hero to our students, to their parents and to the
people of the city of Newark,'' the Rev. Edwin D. Leahy, St.
Benedict's headmaster, testified at Brennan's 1994 federal civil
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful people were drawn to him and his money. Richard J.
Hughes, the late governor of New Jersey, and John Degnan, a former
state attorney general, were on one of his corporate boards. W.
Hunt Dumont, the former U.S. attorney in Newark and now a state
judge, was First Jersey's general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have charm up the gazoo,'' said Edward Koch, the
former mayor of New York, who attended parties at Brennan's home
and had him to Gracie Mansion. ``He had it. He would make you feel
comfortable. If he could send a car or his helicopter to bring you
to his home in South Jersey, he would do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for his business, all you knew was he never went to jail,''
Koch said. ``You had the feeling, here was this brave guy standing
up to government. I guess they finally got him and rightfully so, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever ``getting'' Brennan means. Although bankrupt and
adamant that he cannot pay the government, he ran up $2,000 in golf
fees and nearly $3,000 in liquor store bills in two months last
year, and $248,000 in private jet fees for an overseas trip last
summer, government lawyers say. Just after filing for bankruptcy in
1995, they say, he went to a Las Vegas casino looking to cash in
$500,000 in chips he neglected to report in the bankruptcy case.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's court agreement takes away the aptly named Due
Process golf course, formerly his horse farm, but allows him to use
his office and apartment there until the course is sold in
bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   He left court crushed. But there were reports Friday that back
at the golf course, he was flying high again _ in a helicopter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1447EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
