<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-RUN-REYNOLDS0528-COX     05-27 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-REYNOLDS0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reynolds running out of time
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before a recent morning workout, Butch Reynolds
ponders what has lured him to the track at Life University. Why
bother with the aggravating 45-minute trek from his Spartan
apartment in Stone Mountain? Why, at 35, put the body through the
torture that is the 400 meters? Why solicit contributions for his
training fund?
</P>
<P>
   A guy his age should be through with chasing the dream. Others
in his shoes are living large in the 'burbs, using their name to
secure a cushy job, if not simply living off their winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds has a historian's sense of where he has been _ of
battles won and lost _ but what stirs him from the past more than
anything is Michael Johnson, hero of the 1996 Atlanta Olympics and
the sport's current leading man. The same character who last summer
covered 400 meters in 43.18 seconds, trampling a world record
Reynolds clocked 11 years earlier on the night of his life in
Zurich, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a love for running, and I still think I can
really give him a race,'' Reynolds said. ``We know who the favorite
is, of course. But I don't see him as invincible.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds fancies himself a threat to Johnson later this summer
at the Sydney Olympics, although his spot on the U.S. team is far
from a sure thing. That's why he headed south from Ohio almost two
years ago, to ready himself for one last go at Olympic gold.
</P>
<P>
   And to regain his world record, implausible as it might seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``August 17, 1988, at 8:40 in the evening, I knew that that was
my day,'' said Reynolds, reflecting. ``I was the man, Harry `Butch'
Reynolds. . . . Oh man, that was a quarter-of-a-million-dollar day
_ $100,000 bonus from the meet promoter, shoe bonuses, everything.
I did all that, then in 1990 I went to running for $200 and $300 (a
race). It was never about the money, but obviously money pays the
bills and makes the house payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back at my bank account, I say, `Man, what
happened?' But that's what happens when you pay legal fees and you
live to a certain standard, and you're not making money for three
years (during a suspension).''
</P>
<P>
   If ever a man had reason to be ticked, to swear that he had been
cheated by the running gods, he is Reynolds. A month after his
blistering 43.29 record, he settled for a silver medal in the Seoul
Olympics behind 19-year-old upstart Steve Lewis, only the
third-fastest American at the trials. An Ohio State graduate,
Reynolds did return to Columbus with a gold after anchoring the
1,600-meter relay in a time that equaled the world record.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two years later, at 26 and in his prime, Reynolds was
busted by the International Track Federation for alleged use of the
steroid nandrolone. After a series of legal fights, it eventually
required a last-minute order from U.S. Supreme Court Justice John
Paul Stevens to clear Reynolds to run in the 1992 Olympic Trials in
New Orleans, where he finished fifth, making him an alternate.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Reynolds successfully fought the drug charges
and cleared his name. His lawyers argued that the urine samples
producing the positive test result had not been kept safe from
tampering, suggesting even that the samples tested belonged to a
female German athlete.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. courts later ruled in his favor, awarding a lottery-like
sum of $27 million as compensation for the false accusation.
Reynolds has not seen a dime, however, because U.S. courts have no
jurisdiction over the Monaco-based International Amateur Athletic
Federation. ``I'd have been cool with half of it,'' he said with a
laugh. ``I'd take a cool million, even.''
</P>
<P>
   The chances aren't good. ``I haven't come across an attorney yet
that said I'm going to get that money,'' Reynolds said, shrugging.
``I'm fought out when it comes to that. I can't fight no more. That
would make me sick, because I fought so long to clear my name.''
</P>
<P>
   The redemption he so desperately sought at the Atlanta Olympics
dissolved into pain when he crumpled to the red-rubberized track
with a hamstring injury during the 400-meter semifinals. The man
considered Johnson's only real threat for the gold was done for the
Games. Another gold medal on the relay was gone, too.
</P>
<P>
   But the new-and-improved Harry ``Butch'' Reynolds is back for
another run, and what matters most is that he has found peace of
mind. So what if the odds are badly stacked against him. Or if
Olympic history tells us that the average age of the past four
400-meter champions is 25, and the oldest of the bunch _ Johnson,
28 in Atlanta _ appears not to have lost a step as he readies for
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't always just trying to beat Michael. I was trying to
beat the world,'' Reynolds said. ``I was fighting the world
governing body. I was racing everybody _ athletes, federations and
their leaders. I haven't just raced the competition since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has been fortunate enough that a lot things have been
given to him. The only person he's really beaten for four or fives
years (in the 400) was Butch Reynolds, when I was out there. I've
been taking second to him. So who knows what I could have achieved
without all the little anguish.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you run, you want to run free. I ran with lot of
redemption on my mind, a lot of bitterness. I'm tired of running
like that. I want to come this time and run because I want to
run.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Reynolds functions on prayer and a shoestring
budget. Gone are the corporate sponsors and the entourage of
massage therapists and coaches. Reynolds covers his rent and
grocery bills with a modest paycheck from Olympic sponsor Home
Depot, where he works part-time in the inside-gardening department.
(``Welcome to Home Depot, can I help you? Want to buy a lawn mower?
Want to buy an edger?''). Fitness instructor and health specialist
Anita McGhee, chiropractor Michael Hatrak, coach Chad Black and his
support staff don't receive a paycheck. Fitness International
allows him free use of its Stone Mountain facility.
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Akron, where he often has pitched in to help the
community, several businessmen have established a fund that is
accepting donations to help cover his training expenses of more
than $25,000 leading up to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds qualified for the trials with a 45.1 clocking early
last season, but he rarely has ventured into competition since.
Instead, he has spent most of his time on the Life University track
working out with Olympic hopefuls Kevin Braunskill, Kevin
Jefferson, Milton Campbell and Torrence Zellner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butch is stronger than he's ever been,'' said Black, the
group's coach. ``Physically, he should be ready to go. We're
working on his strength and power _ trying to peak him for the
Olympic Trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether his dream has a prayer will be determined after he opens
his season next month in Europe, followed by the Olympic Trials in
July. ``My job is to make the (Olympic) team,'' Reynolds said.
``Then, I have another two months to beat Michael in Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, if the longshot were to come home, Reynolds finally might
gain redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
