<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CRIME-NYT     05-27 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CRIMES, NEW YORKERS GO ABOUT THEIR BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 By RANDY KENNEDY and ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In recent months, even a statistician could be
forgiven for feeling as if the bad old New York crime days weren't
so far away after all: Seven Wendy's employees herded into a
walk-in refrigerator in Queens and gunned down mercilessly, shot in
the head. Nine livery-cab drivers killed in four months. Mother
robbed in a subway by a gunman holding a pistol to a toddler's
head. Woman pushed into an oncoming train. Woman attacked with a
brick on Midtown street.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s and early 1990s, it was exactly these kinds of
violent crimes that made the city seem like a dark, cartoonish
Gotham _ a town of mayhem completely beyond the control of the
police. The hallmarks of those days have not faded from memory _
the random attacks, the bystanders caught in crossfire, the gunmen
taking money from victims and killing them anyway, gratuitously,
almost for sport.
</P>
<P>
   So one might expect that the recent headlines _ especially when
combined with a surge in the murder rate, the first jump in a major
crime category in eight years _ would be dredging up some old
feelings. Feelings, maybe, that the reliable downward march of
crime, like the reliable upward march of the stock market, cannot
last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Feelings like the ones voiced by Mohammed T. Abboud, a clerk at
a Harlem bodega, who remembers the jittery days when he kept a ice
pick in the cash register. ``There is nothing inside but money
now,'' he said. ``But you never know. There may come a time to put
it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in dozens of interviews across the city, it turned out to
be difficult to catch many people _ especially affluent people _ in
the act of worrying about the return of crime. As New Yorkers do,
most start out conversations by saying reflexively that, of course,
``you have to keep your antennas up,'' as one Bronx resident put
it. But after a few minutes, it becomes apparent that they are much
more preoccupied with a long list of more prosaic issues that seem
to affect their lives more directly than gnawing fears of crime:
their children's education, their sky-high rents, street-side
parking, even getting a seat on the subway.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises some questions: Why does it seem that high-profile
crimes do not resonate in the city the way they used to? Wasn't
there a time when five people slain in a fast-food restaurant would
cause people to think twice before venturing from home? A time when
nine related killings, five of them in one month, would have been
seen as something of a crime wave?
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and police officials certainly worry
about New Yorkers seeing it that way. When several hundred officers
were assigned last month to protect independent taxi drivers, one
official explained that the police were under pressure from City
Hall to safeguard the perception, not just the reality, that crime
is down.
</P>
<P>
   But if the views of Sandra Frierson, 55, a painter and sculptor,
are in any way reflective of the mood of New York, City Hall does
not have much to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Frierson lives in Brooklyn, and has rented apartments in every
borough except for Staten Island. She remembers the days when she
was so unnerved by the city's sense of imminent danger that she
often had her husband walk her to the store.
</P>
<P>
   Although she said that the killings in Flushing, Queens, were
``despicable'' and proved ``how sick we've all become,'' she went
on to make this admission: ``As bad as I feel for the people who
were killed, I never think something like that could happen to me
these days. It's like it's outside the realm of my world.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Repetto, president of the Citizens Crime Commission, a
police watchdog group, said he thought those feelings were
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think New Yorkers have certainly become more concerned about
crime over the last few weeks as these high-profile crimes have
been happening,'' Repetto said. ``I don't think that they are
necessarily more fearful about crime because it hasn't touched them
like it once did, unless you're a livery-cab driver or part of
another group that's been affected.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems striking is that this localized sense of fear has
apparently not percolated through the city at large.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, experts say, is simply a matter of context.
Crime remains at 30-year lows in New York, and despite the rise in
homicides, violent crime overall was down 7.5 percent during the
first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just that the volume of crime is much lower, they
say. It is also that the kinds of violent crime that were peaking a
decade ago, mostly associated with the crack trade, seemed more
random and thus more threatening. Both periods were marked by high
numbers of livery-cab shootings, but it was other kinds of
shootings back then _ drive-bys, gunfights on street corners and in
playgrounds _ that created the real fear and amplified the effects
of livery shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was more randomness,'' said Jeffrey Fagan, director of
the Center for Violence Research and Prevention at Columbia
University. ``Two kids bump into each other in the subway station
or the street and just shoot each other, and that's a crime that
could affect anyone. Or at least there was a subjectively plausible
possibility that it might affect any citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, while there were about 13 percent more killings in
the city from January through March, the police say that most of
those homicides occurred indoors and involved people who knew one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that the lack of widespread anxiety is a kind
of flip side of the ``broken windows'' theory popularized by James
Q. Wilson, a professor emeritus at the University of California in
Los Angeles, and George Kellingof Rutgers University in a 1982
article in The Atlantic Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   The theory, a big influence on the style of policing that
evolved under Giuliani, holds in part that crime and low-level
civic disorder are closely linked. A fear of crime can sometimes
actually just be anxiety caused by a ``sense that the street is
disorderly, a source of distasteful, worrisome encounters,'' as the
article stated it.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps now, with the police still vigorously pursuing
quality-of-life crimes and low-level criminals, a perception of
greater orderliness has contributed to a more unassailable feeling
of general security and manageability, a feeling that could
withstand even a sizable jump in the crime rate before it eroded.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in some neighborhoods, the crime rate _ or, at least
the fear of crime _ never really eroded at all.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Lawrence spoke of those feelings while washing his
10-year-old Buick sedan on the streets of East New York, Brooklyn.
Lawrence, 47, worked as a cable television installer until 10
months ago when he lost his left eye in a scuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Although he acknowledged that crime had dropped in his
neighborhood, he insisted that there were still problems.
</P>
<P>
   So what about the recent crimes in the headlines then? Did they
augur a return to the chaos of the past?
</P>
<P>
   ``Return to what?'' Lawrence asked. ``We ain't never left
nothing behind to return to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1515EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
