<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7589 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-EYE-SURGERY0528-COX     05-27 1895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYE-SURGERY0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seeing is believing for many top athletes who have opted for
laser eye surgery
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At times, the hole looks bigger to Tiger Woods. Laura
Davies no longer squints while asking her caddy, ``Where did that
shot go?'' and actually recognizes who she's waving to in the
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Joyner and Jeff Bagwell don't swing blindly at blurs
anymore. Danny Kanell now can see, and read, a defensive back's
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Buchanan? He's positively eagle-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing like a bird,'' the Atlanta Falcons' cornerback said.
``I can see an ant walking along and what food he's carrying to his
hideout.'' That's a far cry from the not-so-distant Dark Ages, when
football was still a contacts sport for Buchanan. When one of his
contact lenses would slip or pop out and he would squint into the
backfield at the receiver he had to cover and wonder, ``Is that 88
or 89?''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's ol' Two Eyes himself. It's been nearly 11
months since his procedure, but Greg Maddux still finds himself
wide-eyed at the wonder of it all. The wonder of LASIK, the laser
eye surgery that has given Maddux, Woods, Buchanan and a multitude
of other professional athletes a most precious gift. A sight for
poor eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still something I think about almost every day,'' Maddux
said. ``I'm still noticing things, playing little eyesight games
with myself. Reading a license plate. Reading a billboard. Watching
TV.'' Maddux's eyesight is doing even better since getting lasered
in July. Hoping for Mad Dog 20/20 vision, Maddux wound up with
20/15. So did Joyner and Kanell. Buchanan improved to 20/10. They
are just a few of hundreds of athletes _ and several million
Americans _ who have undergone LASIK, an acronym for laser-assisted
in situ keratomileusis and an increasingly popular procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting more and more common among athletes,'' said Dr.
Alan Kozarsky, the Atlanta eye specialist who performed LASIK on
Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   For some, improved eyesight has directly improved performance.
For others, it is the convenience of no longer having to use
contacts; it, too, often yields better results on the playing
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I'm normal, the slopes are bigger, objects are
bigger,'' Woods said. ``The hole is bigger, the ball is bigger,
clubs are bigger.'' He was a long-time contacts wearer who suffered
badly from irritation during allergy season, had LASIK in October
and won his next six events. The world's No. 1 golfer now does
promotional work for TLC Laser Eye Centers, which did his surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rubbage,'' was Davies' description of her eyesight. In
February, the English golfer had LASIK on a Thursday afternoon,
awoke the next morning, saw ``everything I couldn't see before''
and shot 67 in the first round of the LPGA Los Angeles Women's
Championship. Davies led the whole tournament and won.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Adkins, the ex-Georgia Tech star, had a contact lens
fold up in his eye 10 minutes before the 400-meter hurdles final in
the 1996 U.S. Olympic Trials. ``So I ran with good vision in one
eye and bad in the other,'' said Adkins, who finished second in the
trials but won the gold in Atlanta. A week after LASIK surgery in
January 1997, Adkins won in the Millrose Games in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it because I was blind,'' said Joyner, the first baseman
who had LASIK in November 1998 while with San Diego. His old
eyesight was ``20/3,000,'' Joyner said jokingly. ``Any improvement
toward 20/20 was an improvement. I went in for a tuneup and they
got me perfect.'' With contacts, Joyner said, ``The wind and
blinking and something getting in your eye affected maybe 50
at-bats. I'd have to take a pitch because of blurring from
blinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell reacted differently. When one of the Houston Astros
slugger's contacts moved and caused his eye to blink or twitch
while at bat, he instinctively swung at the pitch. He, too, felt he
lost 50 at-bats a season before having LASIK in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent athlete who has had LASIK is Hale Irwin, who
earlier this month won the Senior PGA Tour Nationwide Championship
at the Golf Club of Georgia, three months after the procedure.
Another golfer, Jesper Parnevik, had LASIK in April and won the
Byron Nelson Classic two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Other golfers who had it are reigning U.S. Women's Open champ
Juli Inkster, Se Ri Pak, Tom Kite, Fred Funk, Steve Elkington and
Bob Tway. Among other athletes are basketball players Patrick Ewing
and Matt Geiger; football's Troy Aikman, Gus Frerotte and Rodney
Peete; and a number of baseball players, including Bernie Williams
and Jose Cruz Jr. MADDUX, THE PERFECT CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Maddux, the four-time NL Cy Young Award winner
who never wore glasses, or contacts, until coming to Atlanta in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about LASIK from a golfing buddy who had the
surgery, Maddux researched it and wanted to have the procedure in
spring training of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe for a second that it was going to make me any
better, or worse, a pitcher,'' Maddux said. ``I did it for selfish
reasons.'' He hoped to ``see the signs from the catcher clearly,''
but he also wanted to dispose of his contacts for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really needed to rub your eyes (when lenses irritated),
and you knew you couldn't,'' Maddux said. When he left a game, he
would remove his contacts first, even before taking off his spikes
and then going to ice his pitching arm.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had told Maddux to wait until after the season to
have LASIK. ``Then, I was pitching bad,'' he said, smiling. ``I had
a very bad May.'' He was 0-3 in six starts and was hit hard in five
of them. ``I got a little shove, a little push that if I wanted, to
go ahead and do it now.'' A little shove from whom? ``The Braves,''
Maddux said, still grinning.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had 20/40 vision in his left eye, 20/200 in his right. On
the advice of Braves orthopedist Dr. Joe Chandler, he went to be
examined by Kozarsky on July 4. It was hoped that the surgery could
be performed promptly and Maddux would have the All-Star break to
recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't pick a better candidate than Greg,'' said
Kozarsky, who has performed LASIK for six years and has had the
procedure himself. ``He's right in the range you can easily correct
with LASIK, just two or three diopters _ units _ of
nearsightedness, with some astigmatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox saw Kozarsky that day, too. Older
people _ Cox turned 59 last Sunday _ with bad vision often are poor
LASIK candidates, but Cox said he was approved. ``I chickened
out,'' said the manager, who still wants to have the surgery. No
athlete's career has been damaged, or ended, by complications
caused by LASIK. So far. ``It's a remote possibility,'' Kozarsky
said. He says that LASIK is ``extremely safe,'' but he doesn't
advocate using athletes to do paid endorsements for LASIK.
</P>
<P>
   For most athletes _ indeed, for most any patients _ there still
are varying degrees of trepidation. ``I was a little concerned,''
said Buchanan, who underwent the procedure in March 1999.
``Whenever you're messing with your eyes and facing the possibility
of going blind with a mistake, and with my income, what I'm making
now, it was a risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan forged ahead. Where once the football moved on him in
flight _ ``Everything used to shake a lot. I couldn't focus.'' _ he
now can see the stripes on the ball as it approaches. He made one
interception last year ``that was so quick, I couldn't believe
it,'' he said. ``I jumped in front of the tight end and boom! the
ball was right there for me. Before, I'd have dropped it, or batted
it away. If I drop a ball now, it's because I got bad hands, not
because of my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kanell, the Falcons' backup quarterback, LASIK meant no
longer staring at the sideline with a contact dislodged.
``Sometimes, I couldn't even get the (hand) signals from a coach on
the sideline,'' said Kanell, who researched LASIK on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   When Maddux had the procedure performed, on July 9, teammate
John Smoltz drove him to the Emory Vision Correction Center.
Kozarsky took eye measurements and then put numbing eyedrops in
Maddux's eyes before using the laser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing he didn't tell me was it was going to smell,''
Maddux said. ``When the laser started, I said, `Is that my eye
burning?' He said, `Yeah.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At first, it was ``hard to see,'' Maddux said. ``I couldn't
focus.'' Smoltz drove him home. Maddux turned on the TV to the
Braves-Red Sox game. ``I could tell Bruce (Chen) was pitching,'' he
said. He watched an inning or two, then fell asleep. When he awoke
in the seventh inning, he said, ``I could read everything on the
TV. I said, `Oh, cool, it's working.' ''
</P>
<P>
   During a followup visit to Kozarsky the next morning, Maddux,
who intentionally walked into a wall, asked, ``Alan, when can I
pitch again? Bobby says I can pitch tomorrow, if I want.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux wanted to, even if he and Kozarsky had agreed that he
would take the All-Star break off and pitch the Thursday after.
``There was no medical background for this, if Greg Maddux could
pitch within 48 hours,'' Kozarsky said. ``We're used to letting
people play golf, but pitching major league baseball? There's no
way that's been done in the history of the world. I figured, well,
he's a smart guy. What the hell?''
</P>
<P>
   So Cox juggled the rotation and Maddux went out Sunday, worked
eight innings and allowed Boston one run on six hits. It was the
first of nine victories in his next 10 decisions, and he finished
with a 19-9 record after a 4-3 start.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even now, Maddux doesn't think LASIK has directly affected
his performance. ``It doesn't have any effect on how I throw a
baseball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who had 20/400 vision before LASIK surgery in February,
is 20/15 now. ``My far vision out there (on the course) is
excellent,'' said Irwin, whose astigmatism is gone in one eye and
nearly gone in the other. ``I thought if LASIK brought things into
a little better kilter, it'd help my golf game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I haven't seen any difference in my golf. It hasn't made
my golf better,'' Irwin said. He marvels at the laser technology
but wonders, ``Would I do it again? I don't know. I don't miss
contacts at all. But I'm nearly 55. I think I'd learn to live with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST GIFT
</P>
<P>
   One superstar who has resisted the LASIK urge: Mark McGwire,
whose eyesight is about 20/600 without the special contacts that
let him see 20/10. McGwire might have LASIK after retiring, but not
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a successful professional athlete who's doing well
wearing contact lenses with no problems at all, an eye doctor
shouldn't go out of their way to convince him to have eye
surgery,'' Kozarsky said. ``When you consider the risk-benefit
situation, if you can hit 70 home runs with your contacts, you
don't mess with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of other athletes, however, have turned to LASIK.
Nearly all are pleased. More will follow and see the light of the
laser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you'll appreciate as much as any car you drive,
any home you own, any round of golf you'll ever shoot,'' Maddux
said. ``It's something you appreciate whenever you're awake. It's
the best thing I ever bought myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
