</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOUR-BUSES-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.J.)  
 A TROUBLED TRAIL, BEHIND THE SUCCESS OF TOUR BUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS and JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It seemed an almost comic gamble, bringing red
double-decker buses from Britain and setting them loose on New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the man behind the idea, Harry Grant, a New Jersey
developer, in bankruptcy proceedings, but New York in 1991 was
saddled with a staggering crime rate and a sour economy. Times
Square, where the buses were to pick up passengers, was a haven for
vagrants and sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   Grant's leap across the Hudson River turned serendipitous. Crime
rates fell. The economic downturn reversed itself. Times Square was
transformed from grit to gaudy commercialism. As more tourists came
to the city, the company, New York Apple Tours, prospered, growing
from two used buses to an operation with $10 million in annual
income.
</P>
<P>
   But as tourists flocked to the used British buses, so did city,
state and federal regulators. The company amassed hundreds of
thousands of dollars in fines for falsifying records and
sidestepping inspectors, and drew the ire of neighborhood groups
and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how intense the scrutiny, though, the company
survived, even thrived, until last Monday, when a bus operated by a
driver who police said did not have a proper license turned onto a
crosswalk at West 45th Street and fatally struck Randolph Walker,
71.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, Apple Tours was in the fight of its life in an
administrative hearing at the City Department of Consumer Affairs,
facing a city effort to immediately suspend its license. Susan
Kassapian, a department lawyer, contended that the company had shed
even the veneer of decency and accumulated a list of civil and
criminal violations that was remarkable for its scope and scale.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials have strenuously objected to the hearing,
calling it a naked violation of due process. ``What they're doing
to us here is completely unacceptable,'' said Hayim Grant, company
president and Harry Grant's son.
</P>
<P>
   But hearing the city's case, critics were left to wonder how a
company of that description could have survived for so many years
in the law-and-order climate established by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a company flagrantly violate the law on this
scale,'' said John Kaehny, executive director of Transportation
Alternatives, a watchdog group. ``How much evidence do they need?''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and business associates offer a two-word answer as one
possible explanation for the bus company's resilience: Hurricane
Harry, the nickname given to the company's patriarch and organizing
force.
</P>
<P>
   They say Apple Tours is a company made in Grant's image, and
that Hurricane Harry is a man undeterred by adversity, even
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who immigrated to the United States from Israel with his
wife and three children in 1975, penetrated New Jersey's
construction industry and was a quick success, so quick that after
building houses in Bergen County, he began proposing projects of an
enormous scale.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Grant said he would build the tallest building in the
world, a 121-story office tower in Newark, N.J. He never did. He
proposed digging a tunnel from Bergen County to the Bronx. It never
happened. He said he would open the Newark Renaissance Mall. All
that remains of that venture is an uncompleted shell.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, a bank started foreclosure proceedings on two of
Grant's properties, saying his companies had defaulted on loans in
excess of $17.5 million. The federal Environmental Protection
Agency was pursuing another of his companies for 119 violations of
the Clean Air Act stemming from the illegal demolition of
asbestos-laden buildings in Hoboken, N.J. The case eventually
resulted in a $60,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, under pressure from banks and regulators, Grant
filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection for at least four of the
companies under his control. But he insisted he was not done. In
bankruptcy court, he promised he would recover within three years.
</P>
<P>
   His resurrection came through Apple Tours.
</P>
<P>
   Walter F. Timpone, one of his lawyers, said the idea for the
company came to Grant when he saw double-deckers on a trip to
London.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1991, New York Apple Tours was incorporated. Grant
built the company in his vision of salting the city with stops,
giving riders the chance to hop off one bus and, whenever they
wished, board another.
</P>
<P>
   ``This opened it up to tourists and let people see places around
their city at their leisure,'' Timpone said. ``It was, and is,
fantastically successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and business associates say that if Harry Grant was
stung by his long run of setbacks in New Jersey, he did not show
it. He was driven, they say, and resourceful. No job was beneath
him. He turned wrenches in the motor yard. At times he flew to
London and returned with luggage crammed with spare parts.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Gelber, who was with the company in 1993 and is now manager
of tour services for a rival, Gray Line, recalled Grant's work
ethic. ``Harry would do everything,'' he said. ``He'd be up to his
elbows in grease.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Grant's leadership, the business flourished, growing from
a fleet of two double-deckers to 63 today, according to state
records and the company's office. Mike Alvich, vice president of
marketing and development, said that as the company grew, it
provided a public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've helped the city in a number of ways,'' he said.
``Tourism is a big part of the New York City economy, and we think
that we've contributed to the growth of that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But as the company grew, it attracted doubters, then enemies,
who said its problems were pervasive, affecting all aspects of the
business, from environmental compliance and public safety to
record-keeping and customer service. Gelber, for instance, said
that from its earliest days, Apple Tours regularly sent out buses
staffed by unqualified guides. ``Even for part of the high season,
I was the only one there who had a license,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Tours also angered residents and community leaders, many
of whom said it illegally took empty buses down residential
streets, made curb-side stops in unauthorized places, idled buses
under apartment houses, irritated residents with diesel smoke and
routinely double-parked, clogging byways already inundated with
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, residents from West 22nd Street protested after
discovering that the company was using a rented parking area as a
repair yard without proper permits. Under pressure from the city,
the company moved its repair operations to Long Island City,
Queens. Tom Kirkland, who lives on West 22nd, said that neighbors
concluded that Grant and Apple Tours deliberately played outside
the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't do anything by the book,'' he said. ``The idea was
to do it his way.''
</P>
<P>
   In August 1995, the Department of Consumer Affairs accused the
company of switching licenses on 43 occasions, apparently in an
effort to use buses that had not passed state safety inspections or
might not be insured. The entire fleet was temporarily taken off
the streets. A settlement agreement required that the company pay a
$100,000 fine and, among other things, remove Harry Grant as an
officer in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and lawyers say that although Harry Grant may have
severed his formal ties with the company, he has remained a
presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very much involved,'' said Frank Lucianna, one of Grant's
lawyers and friends. ``He's the guiding light.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Grant, who lives in Alpine, N.J., did not return three
phone calls last week. And in an interview Friday, Hayim Grant
declined to comment on his father's role in the company, except to
say that the company had grown more responsible since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our record is very good,'' he said. ``The company has really
developed into a mature, professionally run, deep-management
company. It's not a fly-by-night operator.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever that role, Harry Grant's troubles, and the company's,
did not stop after his removal as vice president. During the late
1990s, new problems mounted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, an inspection team audited the company's compliance
with a state law that mandates driver fitness and training and
found more than 200 discrepancies, according to testimony on
Thursday from Thomas Fullington, an assistant director of the State
Department of Motor Vehicles. Apple Tours was fined $6,500,
Fullington said.
</P>
<P>
   Fullington also said the department was investigating Apple
Tours again. According to his testimony, its initial review found
similar problems, including an absence of documentation for driver
training and medical exams.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1998, Harry Grant was indicted on charges of
first-degree sexual abuse, accused of attacking a female employee
at the company's bus yard in Queens. He pleaded guilty to
third-degree assault and was sentenced to counseling and one year
of probation, a law enforcement official said.
</P>
<P>
   And in December of that year, a group of employees filed a
class-action lawsuit against the company, claiming it had failed to
pay overtime to as many as 700 workers from 1992 to 1998. The suit
is in settlement negotiations, said Adam T. Klein, a lawyer for the
employees.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, inspectors from the State Department of
Transportation began noting that the company's fleet had safety
problems. In a series of inspections in 1998 and 1999, Apple Tours
buses failed 42.5 percent of the time, according to state data. The
state sets an inspection failure goal of less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The state's data also show that the company's most frequent
violations were in the most serious category, including deficient
brake systems, steering or suspension components and emergency
exits. Subsequent inspections have found that the company's
inspection failure rate is improving, to 24.5 percent, but that is
still 2.5 times the state's compliance goal.
</P>
<P>
   Hayim Grant said the failures did not affect safety or the
accident last Monday. ``There's no bus that's on the road operated
by us that has not passed New York State Department of
Transportation standards,'' he said. ``Our safety record is
excellent. This is the first serious injury that we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   But Judy Shotwell, vice president of the Midtown North Precinct
Council, a neighborhood organization that works with the Police
Department, said that for a long time, she and others also thought
that it would take a pedestrian fatality to force the city into the
current fight. ``We all knew it,'' she said. ``It was going to take
a catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was a federal case that set in motion the city's
efforts to close the company. Last week's fatality merely
accelerated the action.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Apple Tours pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court in
New Jersey to falsifying documents submitted to three federal
agencies _ the Customs Service, the Department of Transportation
and the Environmental Protection Agency _ to avoid meeting federal
safety and environmental standards on 70 buses it imported from
1991 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   By admitting to a sustained deception, city officials said,
Apple Tours gave the Department of Consumer Affairs the evidence it
needed to try to revoke the company's licenses. ``They were
convicted of a crime of essentially dishonesty,'' Giuliani said,
adding that the evidence allowed ``the extraordinary step of trying
to remove their license for reasons that would usually be
considered beyond the Department of Consumer Affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   With the death last week, the city filed an emergency motion
asking Administrative Law Judge Judith Gould to suspend the
company's license immediately, pending the outcome of the case. And
as Gould was beginning her hearings, the company faced another
action.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the board of NYC &AMP; Co., the city's tourism agency,
voted unanimously to terminate the membership of New York Apple
Tours. Cristyne Lategano-Nicholas, the agency's president, said the
board had acted with knowledge of the pattern of problems, but had
based its vote primarily on letters from disgruntled tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complaints against this company exceed those against any
of our other members,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With the licensing fight still undecided, Hayim Grant remained
resolute as the hearing ended on Friday. The tourists were pouring
into the city for Memorial Day weekend. And though Hayim Grant said
the police were cracking down on their buses, the company that
Hurricane Harry founded was still in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking to hurt this city,'' Hayim Grant said. ``We
love this city. We show it to thousands of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
