A7599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.Y.-CABBIE-JOURNAL-N     05-27 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-CABBIE-JOURNAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASPIRIN, CHAI AND SYMPATHY AT CABBY CENTRAL
</HEADLINE>
  By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mosharaf Sarder was bleeding money as he stepped out
of the bathroom and looked around for his fish sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should charge you one dollar for every minute,'' he said to
Maqsood Ahmad, who was standing behind the counter of Lahore Deli.
Ahmad pulled the sandwich out of a microwave and shoved it toward
Sarder.
</P>
<P>
   The cabby from Bangladesh ripped into his dinner. Every minute
spent in the deli was a minute he could have been getting a fare.
For him, time was measured in the shifting display of red digits on
his meter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are out there in Brooklyn, in Queens, in the Bronx,''
he said. It was Saturday night, usually a good time for picking up
riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you do tonight?'' asked a cabby who was sipping chai
on a vinyl bar stool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started at 8 o'clock,'' Sarder said. ``One fare Queens, one
fare Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're comparing what's in their pockets,'' Ahmad, the
deli owner, said to a visitor who was watching the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad has listened in on hundreds of conversations like this.
The cabbies have been stopping in since 1995, when he opened the
24-hour deli. They come for the samosas and the dhal, the basmati
rice and the cool lhassi drinks. The meat is halal, and nothing
costs more than $3. Not even the hundreds of cassettes of Hindi and
Urdu pop music stacked against a wall, or the videotapes of dance
numbers from those epic-length, Bombay-produced movies called
Bollywood musicals.
</P>
<P>
   Above the door hangs a hand-painted wooden sign with the deli's
name scrawled in red Roman letters and flowing Urdu script. At any
time of day, a couple of yellow cabs wait outside on Crosby Street
in the SoHo neighborhood of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between lofts and boutiques, the tiny shop stands
across from the Gaseteria at Houston and Broadway, where cabbies
hand off their cars during shift changes. Culinary connoisseurs
would never mistake its cuisine for that of the Savoy or Balthazar,
both down the block. But this is a place that the drivers can call
their own, a four-stool joint where a Bollywood video always plays
and packets of aspirin are sold at the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have headaches,'' Ahmad said. ``They use a lot of
painkillers.''
</P>
<P>
   He also sells rolls of meter paper, batteries for cell phones
and pagers, and paper towels for wiping windshields _ one-stop
shopping for cabbies. Some drivers post signs looking for day- or
night-shift partners. Others buy lentils to cook at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to keep them happy,'' the deli owner said. ``Give them
a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad knows that smiles are rare in the taxi business. He worked
as a cabby on and off for three years before opening the deli.
Driving was tough, but it was better money than the odd jobs he
held after moving to New York in 1990 from Lahore, Pakistan:
security guard, textile factory worker, newsstand salesman. Then in
1995, his wife joined him in New York and told him that if he
opened a deli, she would do the cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``She makes home-style food,'' Ahmad said. ``Not like restaurant
food.''
</P>
<P>
   More home cooking is on the way. Ahmad's parents are moving to
the United States before the end of this month, and his mother
insists on helping out.
</P>
<P>
   For Ahmad, running the deli beats driving a cab. In the taxi
business, for every 10 good customers, there was one bad one, he
said. Like the man who once told him to run a stop sign because he
was in a rush. Ahmad did so, only to get slammed by another car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the good drivers survive,'' he said. ``There's a lot of
tension because they have to pay their lease, and a lot of stress
from their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   A driver who had just walked out of the bathroom, his hands
dripping water, heard Ahmad telling this to a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they are outside the cab, they are polite,'' the driver,
Zafar Ali, said. ``When they get in, they think they are the
boss.''
</P>
<P>
   That was on top of the other headaches, he said. No parking
spaces on the street. Fifty-five dollar fines for double parking.
No public bathrooms. Ali pointed over his shoulder, where there was
a line six deep just to get into the deli bathroom. It had been
like that all night.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the recent spate of cabdriver murders. Ten men
had already been killed this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about 10 to 15 percent of the drivers have quit their
jobs because of the dangerous situation in this city,'' Ahmad said
as he threw chick peas into a blender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say it is 25 percent,'' said an Indian driver known as
Clinton. ``A lot of my friends have gone to limousines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, maybe 25 percent,'' Ahmad said. ``That sounds right.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton nodded. He shoveled another spoonful of rice and dhal
into his mouth. No one here knows his real name. Everyone calls him
Clinton because he once had a girlfriend named Monica.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly catchy Bollywood tune called ``Kuch Kuch Hota
Hai'' began playing on the television. It had been the most popular
song last summer on the Indian subcontinent, heard from Karachi to
Katmandu. Sarder finished the last bite of his fish sandwich and
stared at the beautiful dancing actors, his thoughts seemingly lost
amid the heat and dust of another land.
</P>
<P>
   Then he hopped off the stool and walked out into the
rain-slicked streets of a night that was already half over, a
packet of aspirin in his hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
