<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-ADBOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: SOME TIMELY HELP FROM FRIENDS OF FLORIO 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This 30-second commercial, titled ``Wall Street,'' was released
by the Camden County Democratic Committee, which has endorsed
former Gov. Jim Florio in his bid for the Democratic Senate
nomination in New Jersey against Jon Corzine. It is a classic
``soft money'' ad, in that it does not explicitly advocate voting
for or against anyone. The commercial began running on Wednesday on
television stations in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER
</P>
<P>
   Murphy Putnam Media.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN
</P>
<P>
   New York's financial district _ introduced with the caption
``Greed is good'' _ is made to look as sinister and intimidating as
possible. Photographed looking up from street level, through a blue
filter, the New York Stock Exchange and other imposing Wall Street
buildings roll by. An unflattering photo of a squinting Corzine
takes up one corner of the frame, as printed warnings sidle across
the screen: ``$250 Million Penalty for Raiding Pension Funds.''
``Supports Republican Plan to Privatize Social Security.'' ``Good
for Goldman Sachs, Bad for Seniors.'' The commercial ends with the
admonition to ``Tell Jon Corzine to Leave Our Retirement Funds
Alone,'' along with the phone number of Corzine's campaign
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT
</P>
<P>
   Narrator: ``Wall Street. A place where some say greed is good. A
place Jon Corzine feels right at home. When he was chairman of
Goldman Sachs, the firm paid a $250 million penalty for raiding
employee pension funds. Now, Jon Corzine supports the Republican
plan to privatize Social Security. Good for Goldman Sachs. Bad for
seniors. Raiding pensions and privatizing Social Security. Tell Jon
Corzine to leave our retirement funds alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY
</P>
<P>
   As Florio has done less artfully in his own ads, this commercial
flatly misrepresents Corzine's position on Social Security. In
fact, it brazenly cites as a source a Business Week article that
actually makes clear Corzine's opposition to individual investment
accounts, the heart of the Republican plan. Goldman Sachs did pay
$253 million in 1995 to settle charges that it had conspired with
Robert Maxwell, the British publishing magnate, to defraud
pensioners of hundreds of millions of dollars. It is debatable
whether a settlement of a lawsuit, under which Goldman did not
admit wrongdoing, amounts to a ``penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD
</P>
<P>
   Florio's campaign, which began running $900,000 worth of
commercials on Wednesday, is now essentially out of money, and the
former governor's friends in Camden County, his political base,
have done him a tremendous favor by buying $500,000 in television
time to run this commercial. Conveniently, because it does not
explicitly urge voters to back Florio or reject Corzine, the ad can
be paid for with soft money, which has much larger individual
contribution limits. The ad is arguably more effective than any of
Corzine's attack ads and is as polished as his positive ones. It
manages to paint Corzine as a pension robber out to cheat the
elderly, and a New Yorker running for office in New Jersey _ all in
an economical half-minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
