<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BERNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARD L. BERNDS, 94, DIRECTOR OF SHORT FILMS FOR THREE STOOGES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edward L. Bernds, one of Hollywood's first sound effects
producers and a director of comedy shorts starring the Three
Stooges, died on May 20 at his home in Van Nuys, Calif. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Bernds began his career as a radio operator in Chicago. He went
to Hollywood in 1928 as a sound mixer for some of the first talking
pictures and worked with such directors as Frank Capra, Leo McCarey
and Howard Hawks. By the late 1930s he was at Columbia Pictures,
writing scripts for the Three Stooges. He soon began directing as
well as writing their films, working steadily with them from 1945
through the mid-60s on ``Monkey Businessmen,'' ``Fright Night,''
``Out West,'' ``The Three Stooges in Orbit'' and other films.
</P>
<P>
   During that time he also directed shorts featuring Hugh Herbert,
Sterling Holloway, Billie Burke and other actors.
</P>
<P>
   He directed his first feature film, ``Blondie's Secret,'' in
1948 and went on to direct four other films in the popular series,
which starred Penny Singleton and Arthur Lake as Blondie and
Dagwood Bumstead. Bernds moved to the Allied Artists studio in the
1950s to direct several films in the Bowery Boys series.
</P>
<P>
   His other directorial credits include ``Quantrill's Raiders,''
``Queen of Outer Space'' and ``Valley of the Dragons.'' He also
directed episodes of several television series, including ``Colt
.45.'' He retired in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a son, Edward Jr., of Van Nuys, Calif., two
grandchildren and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
