<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LOPEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARY LOPEZ, 80, CONSUMER ADVOCATE  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Gardner Lopez, a former director of consumer education and
research for the New York state Consumer Protection Board, died on
May 16 in Pembroke Pines, Fla., where she lived. She was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1964 to 1984, with time out in 1974 and 1975 for service
with the Consumer Protection Board, Lopez was with the New York
state Division of Human Rights, primarily as director of its Queens
bureau. In the late 1980s she was regional manager in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   She was born and raised in Nashville, Tenn., and earned degrees
from Tennessee State University and other institutions. She was a
teacher early in her career.
</P>
<P>
   Her survivors include her husband, Dr. George Lopez; two
daughters, Sharon Rhoden and Adrienne Lopez; a brother, Kossie
Gardner Jr., and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
