u a BC-NY-WENDYS-SLAYINGS-NY     05-27 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WENDYS-SLAYINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY SUSPECT'S PISTOL WAS USED IN WENDY'S CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Story is Page One in city editions; will be updated with
arraignments.) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police ballistics tests confirmed Saturday that a
handgun found in the possession of one of two suspects now in
custody was used to kill five Wendy's restaurant workers and wound
two others who had been bound, gagged and shot execution-style in a
gruesome robbery-massacre in Queens last week.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the ballistics tests added another piece of
evidence to the case against the suspects, John B. Taylor, 36, and
Craig Godineaux, 30, who were arrested on Friday less than 48 hours
after the shootings at the fast-food outlet on Main Street in
Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   The gun, a .380-caliber semiautomatic, was found in a belt pack
on Taylor when he was arrested at his sister-in-law's home in
Brentwood, on Long Island. A senior law enforcement official said
it appeared that only one gun was used to shoot all the victims in
a walk-in basement refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   While the two suspects, in videotaped statements to
investigators, accused each other of being the gunman, the senior
law enforcement official noted that accomplices in a murder are, in
most cases, equally guilty in the eyes of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Taylor has worked at, and robbed, a series of
fast-food restaurants in recent years, including the Wendy's where
last week's massacre took place, while Godineaux, they said, has
served three prison terms for robbery and drug offenses in the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   The two were to be arraigned in Queens late Saturday on charges
of armed robbery and first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   If the suspects are convicted of those charges, they would
potentially face the death penalty or life in prison, prosecutors
said. The Queens district attorney, Richard A. Brown, has 120 days
to decide whether to seek the death penalty. The decision would be
based on factors like the nature of the crime, the defendants'
criminal records, their state of mind at the time and the wishes of
the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, in their videotaped statements to investigators,
gave almost identical accounts, except for accusing the other of
being the gunman, one senior law enforcement official said. Still,
the suspects implicated themselves as they described planning the
robbery in advance and giving step-by-step details on how the
robbery and shootings were carried out, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, in his statement, told investigators that Godineaux had
been adamant about shooting the victims. ``No witnesses! No
witnesses!'' he quoted Godineaux as saying, according to the
official.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators, while emphasizing that they did not know who
fired the shots, were leaning toward Taylor as the more likely
shooter. It was his gun, and it was found in his possession, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Godineaux, in his statement, suggested that, besides robbery,
Taylor had another motive, the official said. Taylor had worked at
the Wendy's in Flushing last fall, but had been dismissed by the
manager, Jean Dumel Auguste, for stealing receipts, police said.
Auguste was one of the five slain workers.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the statements described how Godineaux bound
most of the victims with duct tape, how plastic bags were placed
over their heads, apparently to catch the blood as each was shot,
and how, when it was all over, the two men walked out and took a
bus to an apartment, where they split $2,400 in cash taken from the
Wendy's basement office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are saying, `I got nothing,' or `I only got a little,'''
the senior law enforcement official said. ``Both are attempting to
minimize their part in the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ballistics tests and the videotaped
statements the suspects made to investigators, the senior law
enforcement official said that a key item of evidence would be a
videotape taken from a surveillance camera in the Wendy's dining
area on the night of the killings. It was found at the house where
Taylor was taken into custody.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape does not show the carnage in the basement, but
both suspects appeared on it in the dining area, proving they were
there, the official said. ``I understand they are both visible in
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An unspecified amount of cash _ believed to be taken from
Wendy's _ also was found in the Brentwood house, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's palm print also found on a box in the basement where
the shootings took place, the official said. He added that
investigators hoped to recover more finger and palm prints from the
duct tape used to bind and gag the victims, and from plastic bags
that had been placed over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the tape and the plastic bags were to be tested for
moisture, like sweat, that might be linked through DNA testing to
the suspects, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   One witness, a woman waiting at a bus stop, identified Taylor as
one of two men who emerged from Wendy's about the time of the
shootings, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, 22, who was shot through the cheeks and left for dead,
managed to free himself from his bonds and call 911 on a phone to a
fax machine. The police said he did not identify either suspect
from photos.
</P>
<P>
   The other survivor of the massacre, Jaquione Johnson, 18, who
had a bullet wound to the head, remained in critical condition
Saturday at the New York Hospital Medical Center of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Funerals were being planned by the families of the dead _ Anita
C. Smith, 22, of South Jamaica; Ramon Nazario, 44, of Flushing;
Jeremy Mele, 18, of Neptune, N.J.; Ali Ibadat, 40, of Ridgewood,
Queens; and Auguste, 27, the night manager, who lived in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials attributed the swift arrests and the
strength of the case against the defendants to a combination of
circumstances _ a tip, a bit of luck, and legwork by more than 100
detectives on the job around the clock.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The investigators said the two entered the restaurant last
Wednesday shortly before the 11 p.m. closing time _ not at closing
time, as previously reported _ and sat in the dining area for a
time. At least one ordered food. Taylor then asked for Auguste, and
was directed to the basement office. He went down while Godineaux
waited in the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after closing time, Auguste, using an intercom, called
the six members of his staff to the basement. They went down,
followed by Godineaux, and were confronted by Taylor, who had a
gun. Godineaux then bound most of the victims, who were herded into
the refrigerator, made to lie on the floor and methodically shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
