u a BC-BROWN-GRADUATION-NYT     05-27 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-GRADUATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMMENCEMENT FOR A CLASSMATE BELOVED BY MANY
</HEADLINE>
 
 (With GRAD) By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Instead of caps and gowns, the graduates wore
basketball and soccer jerseys. Instead of ``Pomp and
Circumstance,'' the crowd swayed to ``Stand by Me.'' And instead of
conferring 1,000 degrees, Brown University presented only one on
Thursday, to Casey Shearer, a beloved member of the senior class
who died less than a week before he was to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Shearer, 21, suffered a sudden shutdown of his heart, brought on
by an undetected viral infection, after a basketball game with
friends on May 19, his family said. He never regained consciousness
and died four days later.
</P>
<P>
   His classmates, determined that Shearer should still graduate
with fanfare, organized this commencement four days before their
own, which is Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There were as many laughs as tears at the gathering, as friends
and family praised Shearer's quick smile, poked fun at his penchant
for giving everyone a nickname (his was ``Case,'' or ``Case Dog''),
and maligned his mediocre jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his magna cum laude degree in economics, Shearer was
remembered foremost as a sports lover who covered games for Brown
Student Radio and wrote a sports column for ``The College Hill
Independent,'' a weekly college newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Derek N. Shearer, a longtime friend and economic
adviser to President Clinton, said he was amazed by the 80 friends
who kept vigil at the hospital while his son was in a coma. He said
the service typified all the things his son loved about Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chose Brown because it was his sense that this was the most
friendly and diverse mix of kids,'' said Shearer, a fellow at the
Woodrow Wilson International Scholars Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Shearer's network of friends stretched from Providence to
southern California, where he grew up, to Finland, where he
attended high school while his father was ambassador. Through his
father, he made friends in the White House, as evidenced by
Clinton's attendance at the service.
</P>
<P>
   The president, his arm around the first lady, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, recounted how Shearer had tried to tutor him in rap music
before an appearance on ``The Arsenio Hall Show'' in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But politics was not in his game plan. Nearing graduation, he
had already mailed out tapes of his broadcasts of Brown games, in
hopes of landing a broadcasting job.
</P>
<P>
   Politics did not seem to matter much to his friends, either, who
remembered him more for his ability to memorize the statistics of
every Brown athlete and his inability to eat his usual morning bowl
of Cheerios without dribbling milk down his chin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of you who belong with Casey to the Class of 2000 will
know that he marches by your side on Monday,'' said Sheila E.
Blumstein, the interim president of Brown. ``You will hear his
laugh and see his smile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
