<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL SECTION: SOUTH LEBANON &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISRAELI `DOGS' EXIT LEBANON WITH TAILS BETWEEN THEIR LEGS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISRAEL'S-VIETNAM-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARJAYOUN, SOUTH LEBANON _ The bearded Hezbollah guerrilla puts
down his load of stolen Israeli grenades and turns to admire the
view. ``See how they go?'' the guerrilla asks, waving towards the
fleeing Israeli soldiers who have occupied southern Lebanon for 22
years. ``They leave everything and go like dogs.'' Despite the
denials of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, his army certainly
seemed this week to leave Lebanon with its tail between its legs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 150-word optional trim; 1,025 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTH LEBANON EXODUS: FINALLY ONE ISRAELI PROMISE KEPT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EXODUS-BARAK-ECONOMIST-900&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Ehud Barak's election promise to end Israel's
22-year occupation of a slice of southern Lebanon was brave as well
as popular. Israel's dark military adventure into Lebanon was never
its proudest hour. This week's dramatic events, which turned an
orderly withdrawal into a disorderly rout, should not detract from
the wisdom of the decision to get out. Still, the chaos adds
markedly to the tribulations of Barak as he battles to make peace
with his Arab neighbors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
