<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS AWAIT THEIR NEXT OPPONENT
</HEADLINE>
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now that they have overcome a seemingly
insurmountable obstacle by rallying from two games down in the
semifinals, an achievement unmatched by any team in the history of
the Stanley Cup since expansion in 1967, the Devils are taking aim
at hockey's ultimate prize.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils seem to have everything in place going into the
Stanley Cup finals. They have a coach who has his finger on the
pulse of his team, a goaltender who has raised his play to the
highest level at the right time, a captain who has been the
dominant player in the first three rounds of the playoffs and a
first-line threesome that has been no match for anyone thus far.
</P>
<P>
   All these ingredients converged to help the Devils rally from a
three-games-to-one deficit and eliminate the Flyers in the Eastern
Conference finals on Friday night in Philadelphia with a 2-1
triumph. This seventh and deciding game of a physical series also
may have marked the end of Eric Lindros' career.
</P>
<P>
   By eliminating the Flyers, the Devils have reached the Stanley
Cup finals for the second time. In 1995, with Jacques Lemaire at
the helm and Larry Robinson as his assistant, the Devils swept the
favored Detroit Red Wings in a memorable series.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike 1995, when they opened the finals on the road, this time
the Devils will play host to the first two Cup games, starting
Tuesday night. And this time, Robinson, who replaced Robbie Ftorek
with eight games left in the regular season, is behind the bench as
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were awaiting the outcome of the seventh and deciding
game of the Western Conference finals in Dallas between the
defending champion Stars and the Colorado Avalanche to determine
their opponent in the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Savoring their comeback against the Flyers, the Devils had no
interest in talking about next week's opponent. They politely said
that it didn't matter whether they faced the Stars or the Avalanche
because, in the words of Bobby Holik, ``either team is a great
team.'' The Devils were given the day off on Saturday and will
practice on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Western Conference teams have captured the Stanley Cup every
year since the Devils won it in 1995. As they were against the
Wings then, the Devils must again be considered the underdogs
because the elite teams in the Western Conference have been
superior in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Against Western Conference teams that made the playoffs, the
Devils posted a regular-season winning record only against the Los
Angeles Kings (1-0). Detroit swept the Kings in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Devils have Robinson, who has become their X-factor.
Robinson's tirade after the Devils fell behind by 3-1 in the series
with the Flyers was so perfectly timed that it drew the admiration
of his players as well as outsiders. The Devils gave Robinson the
bulk of the credit for their comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it from the heart,'' was the phrase almost a dozen
players used about Robinson's fusillade after the third consecutive
loss put the team on the verge of elimination. Robinson's reaction
to his inspirational ploy was almost a shrug. ``Sometimes it works
and sometimes it doesn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, this time it worked to perfection because it
obviously touched a chord in the hearts of the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   They responded. Scott Stevens' dominance of the opposition's top
players in each of the three rounds, starting with Florida's Pavel
Bure and Toronto's Mats Sundin, culminated with his crunching check
on Lindros that took the heart out of the Flyers Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur's brilliant saves in a second period dominated by
the Flyers on Friday night gave the Devils the chance they needed
going into the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty gave us a chance to win in the third period,'' said
Patrik Elias, who scored the winning goal with 2 minutes 32 seconds
left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Elias also scored the first goal, and both scores came on passes
from Jason Arnott, who has combined with Elias and Petr Sykora to
form the team's top line. The threesome combined for eight goals in
the series, four by Elias and two each by Arnott and Sykora, and
was a constant threat to the Flyers. Philadelphia simply failed to
come up with a solution for the combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone had to come through for us and Patty was the one,''
Sykora said of Elias' winning goal. ``It's unbelievable how
satisfying it is to come back like that and go to the finals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
