<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FLYERS-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BELIEVE, AT LAST: FLYERS SADDENED BY LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ There was a sense of disbelief in both dressing
rooms at First Union Center late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   For the stunned Philadelphia Flyers, it stemmed from their
inability to close out an Eastern Conference semifinal series that
they had once led, three games to one. For the elated Devils, it
was because they had somehow come back to win the series in seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say that we completely believed we could,''
said defenseman Ken Daneyko, the only player to appear in all 125
of the Devils' postseason contests.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott, who assisted on both of Patrik Elias' goals in the
series-deciding 2-1 victory, was more succinct when asked if he
honestly thought the Devils could come back after losing Games 3
and 4 at home. ``No,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils did it the hard way. Three of their four victories,
including two of the last three, came away from home. No team had
ever erased a 3-1 series deficit this late in the playoffs, but the
Devils did so with a nail-biting Game 7 victory on Elias' second
goal of the night, only 2 minutes 32 seconds away from sudden
death.
</P>
<P>
   That Elias provided all of the Devils' offense was fitting. He
led New Jersey in goals, points and game-winning goals during the
regular season. That came after he sat out the first month in a
contract dispute with the team president, Lou Lamoriello.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a weird feeling,'' Elias said. ``But it's a great
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other dressing room, the mood was predictably subdued.
``It stinks,'' said Brian Boucher, the rookie goaltender who had
powered the Flyers in the playoffs. ``Up three games, we had three
cracks at it.''
</P>
<P>
   But all three times, Philadelphia came up short. And the Devils
will begin the Stanley Cup finals at home on Tuesday against the
winner of the Dallas-Colorado series. The Devils won the cup in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   In a series that was tied through six games, two periods, 17
minutes and 28 seconds, the most enduring image was the Flyers'
Eric Lindros slumped on the ice 7:50 into Game 7, with what turned
out to be another concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros' head crashed against the ice in his second game since
returning from post-concussion syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sickening to see something like that,'' said Lindros'
teammate John LeClair, one of two skaters who helped carry Lindros
off the ice. Lindros walked out of the building Friday night under
his own power, accompanied by his father, Carl. Today, the Flyers
confirmed their hulking 27-year-old center had sustained a
concussion, his third this season and fifth in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Stevens, who was responsible for the clean but vicious hit
at the Devils' blue line that knocked Lindros out, felt about the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely thinking about his career,'' said Stevens,
who at 36 has imposed his physical stamp on each of the Devils'
three playoff series this spring. ``I don't want to be anybody who
ends someone's career. I went into the dressing room all by myself
and I was upset. It takes a bit away from this win.''
</P>
<P>
   While his teammates headed home to ponder what could have been,
Lindros spent the evening at Pennsylvania Hospital. ``You don't
want to lose Eric Lindros,'' Flyers coach Craig Ramsay said. ``And
we don't want to see this young man get hurt again.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Lindros does return next season, Friday's game was
probably his last for the Flyers, given his family's bitter
relationship with general manager Bob Clarke. But that did not stop
the Flyers from bringing Lindros back for the end of the series
with the Devils. He returned for Wednesday's Game 6, after one
practice; he had been medically cleared to play.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Ramsay approached his mentor, Roger Neilson,
about joining him on the bench for Friday's game. Ramsay replaced
Neilson as Philadelphia's head coach this season, while Neilson has
battled cancer. The succession process was strained. And like the
continuing Lindros saga, it was a distraction to the team. In the
end, Ramsay and Neilson decided against having Neilson return
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   During the second intermission, Devils coach Larry Robinson,
upset with his team's performance during the period, replayed the
tirade he had delivered to the team after Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in and gave us an earful again,'' Randy McKay said.
``Maybe not quite as much, but he was pretty loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Robinson said, it worked. ``After Larry gave us that
little rant, it seemed to light a spark under us,'' Daneyko said.
</P>
<P>
   That made Lamoriello look like a hockey genius. He replaced
Robbie Ftorek with Robinson with eight games left in the regular
season, while the Devils were in the midst of losing the points
title _ and the ensuing home-ice advantage in the playoffs. ``In my
mind, I didn't think we were going anywhere,'' Lamoriello said.
</P>
<P>
   And now, for only the second time in the franchise's history in
New Jersey, the Devils are going to play for the Stanley Cup. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
