<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-BLUEFISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: BLUEFISH SEASON ON MARTHA'S VINEYARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ The day was dark and dank, a stiff near gale
from the south hurling good-sized combers against the outer beach
of Martha's Vineyard Island, when, with Nelson Sigelman and me on
board, Cooper Gilkes nosed his four-wheel-drive vehicle out onto
the strand and headed west toward Wasque Rip on Chappaquiddick.
</P>
<P>
   Coop had already been there several times this spring, but it
was the first visit of the season for Nelson and me. We were after
the northward-migrating bluefish that year after year in recent
times have arrived at Wasque Rip off Chappaquiddick shortly before
mid-May. This year, the first bluefish was caught from shore at
that location on May 1, and by May 11 bluefishing at Wasque Rip was
well under way.
</P>
<P>
   Scanning the water as we drove, we were about halfway to Wasque
when we thought we saw a different wave pattern on the water,
perhaps indicating feeding bluefish even though no gulls or terns
were about.
</P>
<P>
   We stopped and began casting metal jigs: Hopkins, Kastmasters,
Krokodiles and others of that genre. Within 10 minutes, Coop had a
couple of hits and Nelson and I were each fast to a fish that
subsequently pulled free. Nothing more occurred after that flurry,
so we kept on to the west to where we could see more than a dozen
vehicles parked on the beach. When we got closer, Coop said, ``I
don't see any bent rods.''
</P>
<P>
   It was true. About half the anglers were casting and the others
were sipping coffee or working on gear or sitting on tailgates and
gamming.
</P>
<P>
   We stopped about 100 yards short of them and resumed fishing.
Ten minutes later, bent rods were the rule rather than the
exception, and all hands were catching fish ranging from five to
eight pounds.
</P>
<P>
   At first, most of the fish were taken on the aforementioned
metal, but some casters switched to popping plugs, which also
worked. Many anglers prefer to go after bluefish with poppers, the
surf fisher's equivalent of the flyrodder's floating fly, because
it's exciting to see the wind-blown spray from a smashing strike.
</P>
<P>
   At one point some of the blues were right against the beach, and
that reminded me to shorten my casts. There's little point in
hooking a fish 90 yards offshore when you can accomplish the same
thing with a 30-yard toss. This has particular merit when a strong
tide _ for which Wasque Rip is famous _ is running, greatly
reducing the time needed to bring your quarry to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   A classic bluefish blitz was soon under way, rods bent, fish
flopping on the sand, an occasional angler frantically striving to
remove a deeply embedded hook from a fish without getting part of a
finger bitten off, all the while glancing over his shoulder at the
action. A bluefish minuet developed: anglers fast to fish moving
downtide with them, a maneuver that requires the casters in their
path to reel in and get out of the way. With a big rod and heavy
line, you can usually stand your ground and bring the fish to you,
but it's a different ball game with light tackle, particularly if
the blue was hooked at the end of a long cast.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Janet Messineo, a Vineyard taxidermist and a
talented angler who was catching bluefish at a furious rate, asked
if I would help her put an elastic bandage on her wrist to
alleviate her tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   On another occasion, such is the camaraderie among surf casters,
Don Mohr, a longtime regular at Wasque, took pity on me as I was
trying to extract a popping plug's treble hook from the upper jaw
of a bluefish and offered me his pliers. I asked him how he was
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My replacement parts seem to be wearing out,'' he said
cheerfully and limped away to resume casting. Don, a former semipro
football and baseball player, has had a series of operations that
include two hip and two knee replacements, but that doesn't keep
him from his beloved Wasque.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Sigelman, who is a reporter for the weekly Vineyard
Times, couldn't focus solely on fishing. He needed photographs of
the event, which were hard to get because spray kept dashing over
his camera, but he did beach a couple of blues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to catching that evening's supper, I wanted half a
dozen or more fish to put in my smoker, a once-sacrosanct ritual
for me with the first bluefish of the season. Coop took the
pressure off me by saying I could have his fish.
</P>
<P>
   Coop, who runs a tackle shop in Edgartown, is also a well-known
fishing guide. He was taking a busman's holiday with Nelson and me
and hinting that he might return to Wasque that evening. Keeper
striped bass _ in Massachusetts the minimum length this year is 30
inches _ are already being caught at Wasque and the area east of
it, East Beach.
</P>
<P>
   We were fishing the latter part of the falling tide at midday on
our bluefish caper, but Coop said that he had been doing well with
stripers on the rising tide, particularly at night.
</P>
<P>
   Back home by midafternoon, I began fileting my fish and
discovered that the stomachs of most were empty. Those that had
been feeding recently had been dining on squid, sea robins and
something that appeared to be from the herring family. I was
delighted to find that the bluefish were still stiff and firm.
Bluefish deteriorate rapidly after capture.
</P>
<P>
   I was still busy at my task when Ruth, my companion, returned
from a trip to the supermarket, squealed with delight and confessed
that she had purchased a pound of hamburger just in case I had
failed in my quest, a purchase that, if nothing else, reveals
something about my angling prowess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
