<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-5     05-27 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION RALLY IN BELGRADE DRAWS RELATIVELY LOW TURNOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Some 10,000 people showed up Saturday for
an anti-government rally, a relatively low turnout reflecting
popular disappointment with the leaders of the political opposition
here.
</P>
<P>
   They heard Vuk Draskovic, the head of the main opposition party,
the Serbian Renewal Movement, describe a city and a country
``paralyzed by fear, despair and a feeling of helplessness'' in the
face of the power of President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But Draskovic, in a wandering speech, seemed unable to
articulate a clear strategy to alleviate that paralysis, other than
a united push for early democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
   Zoran Djindjic, head of the Democracy Party, the main element of
the Alliance for Change coalition, preached unity, patience and
collective self-defense. ``We can't checkmate Milosevic in one
move,'' he said. ``We have to pressure him, surround him and drain
out his political life drop by drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic ``is most afraid of 3 million people who will come to
the polling station and say, `We don't want you,''' Djindjic said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous rallies, this one heard only three opposition
leaders speak _ not all 16 _ and there were more speakers from
other parts of Serbian society, including academics, women's
activists and the spreading student movement, Otpor, or Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, said Zarko Korac, a political leader in the alliance,
is to present a wider social front of solidarity against the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition right now is not capable of making a very
consistent, clear program,'' Korac said. ``It's not just that the
big parties are not up to the situation, but what you need is a
wider front to confront the dictatorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Ognjen Pribicevic, a Draskovic adviser, said: ``We are doing
what we can at the moment. And we are more united than you think,
especially the big parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the opposition would concentrate more on meetings
and retail politics in the countryside, where feelings run higher
than in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But an Otpor speaker named Nemanja, from Krusevac, criticized
the politicians for disunity and squabbling. ``For seven days, dear
leaders,'' he said, ``you were wasting time on useless meetings.''
He said Otpor had drawn up a plan for hunger strikes, then tried to
give it to Draskovic, who kept his hands to his side. Djindjic
finally took it.
</P>
<P>
   With declining numbers _ a rally in mid-April drew more than
100,000 people, but one on May 15 drew only about 25,000 _ this
rally is likely to be the last of its kind for now.
</P>
<P>
   It followed a dispiriting 10 days for the political opposition
here.
</P>
<P>
   On May 17, the Serbian government seized control of the Belgrade
television station Studio B, controlled by Draskovic's party. But
fearing a wider crackdown on all opposition-run cities and
independent media, Draskovic urged other opposition leaders not to
attempt outright confrontation with the government, bringing
accusations that he was capitulating without a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Otpor in particular has been urging a program of civil
disobedience, but at the same time, nightly rallies here for Studio
B have shrunk to fewer than 500 people. To blunt Otpor, the
government closed universities a week early, allowing students to
enter only for final exams.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a rally of 3,000 people in the southern city of Nis Friday
night, Goran Svilanovic, head of the Civic Alliance, said his
opposition colleagues were not rising to the new challenge by the
government. ``If we do not resist now, they will come into our
houses, burn them and chase us away,'' Svilanovic said, referring
to Serbian tactics against Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has wide support in Serbia as the only
alternative to Milosevic, but polls indicate that the support can
be shaky and is not growing. A poll just done for the National
Democratic Institute shows the Alliance for Change in early May _
before the seizure of Studio B _ recovering some of the support it
had lost earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the alliance plus Draskovic's party get about 46 percent
of the vote, with the ruling coalition getting about 30 with 18
percent still undecided and 7 percent saying they will not vote,
with a margin of error of 2.9 percent. The problem with all polls
here is that they underestimate support for the Radical Party of
Vojislav Seselj, part of the ruling coalition, whose voters are
more suspicious of pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of undecided indicates deep uncertainty about the
credibility of the opposition, since 63 percent of those polled say
they are unfavorable toward Milosevic and some 70 percent say
``it's time for someone new.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, 38 percent say Milosevic ``may not be perfect, but he's
better than the opposition,'' and he remains the only single leader
whose ratings are larger than the ``don't knows.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 percent of those polled say opposition leaders
spend so much time ``fighting among themselves that they don't
accomplish as much as they should.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, in yet another court case by an official against the
independent media, the newspaper Danas and its editor were fined
570,000 dinars (about $14,300 at the unofficial rate of exchange)
for printing a letter from a law school professor to his dean
accusing Seselj of plagiarizing Lenin. It was the seventh such case
Danas has lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
