<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT IN SPOTLIGHT ON A DAY TO HONOR PETTY
</HEADLINE>
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ The specter of Adam Petty will be evident on
Sunday when Dale Earnhardt Jr. tries to expand on a distinguished
rookie season and Robby Gordon goes for an usual racing double in
the Nascar Winston Cup series' longest race of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A flag honoring Petty _ the 19-year-old driver killed in a wreck
on May 12 _ will fly over Victory Lane at Lowe's Motor Speedway,
site of the Coca-Cola 600.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Petty, Adam's father and head of Petty Enterprises, will
not be there. He is taking off until next weekend's race in Dover,
Del., to mourn his son's death.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr., the only driver to win more than one Winston Cup
race this season, understands the potential peril that comes with
every race.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to Adam puts everything in perspective,'' the
25-year-old Earnhardt said. ``You never know when you're going to
be here or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt has certainly been driving as if there were no
tomorrow. He has two victories and recently became the first rookie
to win the series' all-star race, The Winston, and has been taking
a lot of the spotlight away from his legendary father, Dale Sr.
</P>
<P>
   After Earnhardt Jr. won in Richmond, Va., his father gave him
congratulatory hugs, but then the seven-time series champion
whispered to his son that he was leaving and to find his own ride
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's happy and proud when his son and his car win,''
Earnhardt Jr. said. ``But at the same time, if his son and his car
win, he doesn't, and that's got to be a little tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. collected $516,410 for his victory in The Winston,
not bad for a guy who was working in the service department of his
father's auto dealership several years ago. He bought a 25-foot
boat and pickup truck with recent winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the real gravy may lie ahead. Earnhardt Jr. is blossoming
into a crowd favorite. He received the warmest applause of the
night on Wednesday when he qualified for the Coca-Cola 600 pole
with a lap of 186.034 miles an hour, breaking the track qualifying
record established in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' he said of the crowd's reaction. ``I just
hope I don't get tired of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gordon wants to attempt a racing double accomplished
by just two men: driving in the Indianapolis 500 and the Coca-Cola
600 on the same day. John Andretti (1994) and Tony Stewart (1999)
are the only to do so. The Indy 500 starts at noon today, the
Coca-Cola 600 at 6:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon plans to leave Indy by helicopter from the track infield,
head to the airport for the flight to Charlotte, then take a
helicopter to Lowe's. A nurse will be on the plane to make sure he
is not dehydrated.
</P>
<P>
   If Gordon cannot make it to Concord, Bryan Reffner will be
standing by to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who went without food for much of the day in performing
his double, said Gordon should make it barring rain or a victory in
the Indy race. A victory would likely require him to stay for a
celebration and news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll probably fare better physically than I did last
year,'' Stewart said. ``I think nutrition-wise he'll know what to
do to keep his energy up during the day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
