<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-DEFENSE-0528-COX     05-27 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DEFENSE-0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE COMES CLOSE TO PLAYING POLITICS WHILE TOUTING WHITE HOUSE
NATIONAL MISSILE DEFENSE STRATEGY
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (w) Washington and (p) Politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ Vice President Al Gore skirted dangerously
close to partisan politics Saturday in an address to graduating
West Point cadets that included indirect criticism of Texas Gov.
George Bush's recent nuclear defense proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in an interview with Cox News Service that followed the
roughly 15-minute address, emphatically denied that his remarks
were aimed at Bush. He also insisted that he scrupulously adhered
to the tradition of avoiding partisan politics at the U.S. Military
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I defy you to find anything political in them,'' he said of
his graduation remarks, his first at the historic campus. He said
his comments reflected nuclear disarmament positions ``I have held
for 15 years,'' beginning with his career in Congress in which he
became an acknowledged expert on nuclear arms reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Feurth, Gore's longtime national security adviser, told
reporters that Gore's comments were timed to precede President
Clinton's upcoming trip to Russia, not in response to last week's
policy proposals by Bush. Clinton's trip is expected to center on
talks with Russian President Vladimir Putin about further arms
reductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is mainly triggered by the fact that the president is about
to leave for Moscow in a matter of a few days to engage in exactly
this set of issues,'' Feurth said in a hastily arranged session
with reporters. ``The speech is not political, the speech is
policy-based. The ideas that the vice president presented have been
in his record for a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no protest from West Point officials. Lt. Gen. Daniel
Christman, the academy's superintendent, said the vice president's
speech was ``an apt description of the environment'' in which West
Point's graduating class of 943 cadets will find themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to defending the administration's nuclear defense
policies, Gore also reaffirmed his commitment to upgrading defense
readiness and improving the life of military men and women through
increased pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also proposed strategies in which the United States aligns
itself with those nations moving toward freedom and ``still
pressing for reform,'' while at the same time modernizing its own
weaponry and strategies for a ``Global Age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have ... to transform today's armed forces into tomorrow's
information-age force, one that fully invokes America's strategic
advantages, talent and technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not mention Bush in his address. Yet many of the vice
president's comments alluded to stands staked out by Bush last week
and echoed comments the vice president had made about Bush's
proposals on Air Force II Friday night en route to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any effort to go back in time to the Star Wars proposal ...
is, in the opinion of most experts that have talked about it,
wildly optimistic,'' he said on his way to New York. ``I'm
persuaded by their arguments.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, surrounding himself with GOP foreign policy luminaries
last week, called for building a national missile defense system
while simultaneously beginning unilateral cuts in the U.S. nuclear
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``An approach that combines serious unilateral reductions with
an attempt to build a massive defense system will create
instability, and thus undermine our security,'' Gore said in his
address Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuclear unilateralism will hinder, rather than help, arms
control,'' he said. ``Reductions have to be carried out in a way
that reduces the risk of confrontation. If you're not careful, you
could have a reduction of missiles and a more dangerous world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore outlined the Clinton administration's efforts toward
creating a national missile defense system that would protect all
50 states from a limited attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe, however, that it is essential to do this in a way
that does not destroy the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty,'' Gore
said. ``The ABM Treaty is the cornerstone of strategic stability in
our relationship with Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts have suggested that Bush's missile defense
proposal, which he envisions being extended to European, Asian and
Middle Eastern allies, would violate the 1972 ABM Treaty with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush himself has said he is willing to scrap the pact to
make room for the development of technology that could protect the
country against missile strikes from a growing number of nuclear
threats.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in unveiling his proposal at the National Press Club last
Tuesday, suggested that the nuclear policies of the Clinton
administration ``still resides in that already distant past'' of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, before handing out diplomas to the graduating cadets,
noted that ``the classic security agenda is still with us,'' and
that ``we still face competition among nations that can lead to
war.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the upcoming meeting between Clinton and Putin is ``an
historic meeting.'' And, in an apparent reference to the tradition
of muting political differences over national security issues while
the president is traveling abroad, he added, ``The president should
leave with the full support of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   West Point is one of the most prestigious forums for discussions
of national defense issues, and the only politicians invited to
speak at graduation ceremonies are the president, vice president
and Speaker of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Inviting politicians to speak at West Point grew into a
controversy in 1996 when the service academy withdrew an invitation
to then-Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole after he became a candidate
for president.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Dole has complained about West Point's
invitation to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, in responding to Gore's speech, did not
repeat Dole's criticisms, but rather alluded to the friction
between the Pentagon and the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the Texas governor would work
to ``renew the bond of trust between the president and the
military.''
</P>
<P>
   The last vice president to deliver remarks at West Point was the
father of the Texas governor, George Bush, in 1984 and again in
1988. In 1988, the elder Bush was a candidate for president when he
spoke at West Point.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's E-mail address is: scotts(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.usma.edu
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
