u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-NY     05-27 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT GIVES THE LAKERS QUALITY LEADERSHIP JUST WHEN THEY NEED IT
MOST
</HEADLINE>
  By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ He launched the ball toward the Rose Garden
rafters with as much relief as joy. In those desperate, final 29.9
seconds of Game 3 on Friday night, Kobe Bryant had amazingly swung
the Western Conference finals in his team's favor and defined his
young career.
</P>
<P>
   His was a single-handed sequence that transcended the box score.
Although seemingly impossible for the All-Star guard, Bryant played
beyond his 21 years in the Lakers' 93-91 victory. These were not
the raw, unpredictable playground instincts that have highlighted
and hindered Bryant during his four seasons in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   These were championship moments delivered when his team
absolutely needed a leader. First, Bryant set up the game-winning
basket, driving toward the middle to draw defenders his way, then
flipping a pass to Ron Harper for a 18-foot jump shot that the
Portland Trail Blazers never had a chance to contest.
</P>
<P>
   On the Trail Blazers' next possession, as Rasheed Wallace took a
pass and positioned himself near the free throw line, Bryant
slapped the ball away, creating a wild 20-second scramble that
ended with Portland center Arvydas Sabonis lumbering down the lane.
The 7-foot-3-inch Sabonis was met by the 6-7 Bryant, and with one
swat, Bryant put the Lakers ahead, 2-1, in this best-of-seven
series.
</P>
<P>
   An assist. A steal. A block. Fittingly, Bryant grabbed the last
rebound, too, and was immediately met with a high-five from
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time since we've been together that we've
had to lead a team together in playoffs,'' Bryant said of O'Neal.
``We're up to the challenge. We're not going to let the team down;
we're not going to let the fans down. We're going to give it our
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant assumed command of the Lakers with 25 points on 11-of-18
shooting, seven rebounds and seven assists to squelch whispers that
the Portland Trail Blazers were making him look like an ordinary
player. In the first two games of this series, Bryant averaged only
12.5 points and was doing little to lift the burden on O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided to score,'' Bryant said. ``They can send one
guy, two guys, three guys, it doesn't matter. You have to pick your
spots. It's not something you can do for the full 48 minutes. But
you have to make them pay at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant kept the Lakers from being blown out in the first half
Friday night. He scored 14 of his team's 22 points in the first
quarter and had 18 at halftime on eight of 13 shooting while O'Neal
was still trying to figure out how even to get a shot off against
Portland's defense.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal took only one shot in the first quarter and didn't score.
At halftime, he had only eight points and obviously needed help
breaking loose from Sabonis and help from Scottie Pippen and
Rasheed Wallace, who again roamed freely on defense, buzzing along
the perimeter, then dropping down to harass O'Neal in a game of
human bumper cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe had a fantastic game,'' O'Neal said. ``Everybody was
ragging on him, saying he was nine shots a game. He was more
aggressive tonight, and his shots were falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, the NBA defensive player of the year, also kept Pippen
under wraps, holding the Trail Blazers' leader to 12 points on five
of 13 shooting. Bryant was assigned to guard Pippen for Game 3
instead of Glen Rice, who was nursing a sore knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come out and set the tone,'' Bryant said. ``I
wanted to send a message not only to us as a ballclub, that we can
win here. But also to Portland, that the team you are facing now
isn't the team you faced'' in Game 2, which the Trail Blazers won,
106-77.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' statement included a 20-6 run in the third quarter
to complete a rally from a 14-point deficit in the second quarter.
Bryant ended the Trail Blazers' comeback attempt with his play
against Sabonis. Replays clearly showed that Bryant blocked the
ball and did not foul Sabonis. In hindsight, Sabonis should
probably have taken the 15-foot jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't have been able to take it,'' said O'Neal, who had
come out to try and put a hand in Sabonis' face. ``I was on the
fly, and I was high.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen said that Bryant had hit Sabonis. ``We didn't get the
call,'' Pippen said. ``The officials just aren't going to call it
in that situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
