<HEADER>
A7673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-N.Y.-RENT-RULES-400&AMP;A     05-27 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-RENT-RULES-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REWRITING RENT REGULATIONS CREATES NEW BATTLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a new battlefront between tenants and
landlords. It is 200 pages of dense legalese quietly created by New
York state officials to rewrite the rent regulations that cover 2.4
million residents, most of them in New York City, and that document
has caused a furor.
</P>
<P>
   The state Division of Housing and Community Renewal says that it
is simply updating the rules to conform to laws, court decisions
and regulatory directives.
</P>
<P>
   But tenant groups accuse the state of making changes that favor
landlords and undermine key protections for renters; changes for
which, they say, there is no statutory authority. They say the
changes will enable owners to raise rents improperly and to evict
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   But the housing agency's general counsel, Marcia P. Hirsch,
denies those claims. The updating is required by law, she said, and
the proposal clarifies numerous issues, including some that are
being contested in court.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state has not yet formally adopted the revised
regulations, tenant leaders say they are preparing to challenge
them in court. ``There's no question that we're going to be suing
to stop this,'' said Michael McKee, associate director of the New
York State Tenants and Neighbors Coalition, which represents 17,000
individuals and 144 affiliated groups.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp debate characterized public hearings on the issue Thursday
in Manhattan, White Plains and Manhasset. Most of the
rent-regulated apartments are in New York City, but about 70,000
are in Nassau, Westchester and Rockland counties.
</P>
<P>
   Landlords gave qualified supported to the proposal, but called
for more changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For both owners and tenants, this codification is an extremely
valuable and useful process'' because it consolidates all the rules
in one place, said Joseph Strasburg, president of the city's
largest landlord group, the Rent Stabilization Association, which
represents 25,000 owners and managers. ``The bottom line is that
there is nothing new here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Strasburg urged several changes, including removing the time
limit on when an owner can challenge whether the tenant whose name
appears on a lease is really living in an apartment, and allowing
owners to charge more than one month's rent as a security deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Tenant advocates adamantly opposed the changes in the revision,
and accused the state of pushing the changes through without
sufficient public review.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McKee linked the state agency's changes to an effort three years
ago by state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno to eliminate rent
stabilization. Gov. George Pataki eventually forged a compromise
between Bruno and tenant groups that was perceived as a defeat for
Republicans. But McKee called the latest move an attempt ``to
achieve pro-landlord changes that George Elmer Pataki could not win
from the state Legislature in 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   The opponents of the changes said that under the proposal,
owners could use illegally high rents charged in the past as the
basis for computing current rents, ignoring the correct amounts
filed with the state. Landlords could also prohibit tenants from
charging roommates more than their ``proportionate share'' of rent,
a term that was not defined. And tenants would be barred from
seeking lower rent for certain reduced services, like staffing
levels, that go back more than four years.
</P>
<P>
   The tenants' advocates said that the hearings were not well
publicized, that the proposal was not advertised and that copies of
the draft were not available at the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I comment on your proposed code when I don't have a
copy?'' asked Pat McGovern, a tenant from Manhattan. ``I asked for
a copy at the desk, and they said they would mail me one.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the proposal's length, speakers were limited to five
minutes each and were barred from proposing further changes,
although that rule was ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a landlord's wish list,'' said David Robinson, a
lawyer for Legal Services for New York City, a nonprofit advocacy
group. ``I looked through 125 pages and found one page of
protection for tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Stanley E. Michels said: ``This is a travesty.
You are trying to destroy what's left of rent control and rent
stabilization.''
</P>
<P>
   One surprise speaker at the Manhattan session was the head of
the union that represents the housing agency's 475 employees in New
York City, Ralph F. Carbone, president of Local 1359 of District
Council 37. Carbone said that he was impartial in disputes between
between landlords and tenants, but that he felt compelled to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that the proposals were slanted significantly toward
owners,'' he said, ``going beyond what I believe the current state
law and judicial precedents are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WV-RESORT-REAL-690(2T     05-27 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WV-RESORT-REAL-690(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENBRIER PLANS TO ADD RESORT HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By LYN RIDDLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE SULPHUR SPRINGS, W.Va. _ The Greenbrier hotel, the
luxurious resort in this Appalachian Mountain valley town, and
Dolan, Pollak &AMP; Schram, a Georgia developer, are planning a
community of vacation houses on the hotel grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan, Pollak, which built a similar development near Savannah,
Ga., at a plantation once owned by Henry Ford, expects to begin
selling the first of 500 lots at the Greenbrier in July. Prices
will range from $250,000 for cottage-sized lots of 60 feet by 100
feet to $1 million for three to five acres at the base of the
mountains that surround the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The focus will be a sporting-club atmosphere, with golf, tennis,
riding and other activities, and the developers will handle grass
cutting and yard maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Ted J. Kleisner, who has been the president of the Greenbrier
since 1987, said the resort had embarked on a real estate venture,
Greenbrier Village, in the 1980s but discontinued it because
company officials were not confident they could successfully
develop the property. Thirty-eight cottages were built beside a
golf course, and 14 houses were constructed on larger lots nearby.
A 15th is now under construction.
</P>
<P>
   One limitation on the earlier sales effort was that a
significant piece of property _ a hillside tract surrounding the
hotel _ could not be touched until 1995, when the federal
government ended its lease on a once-secret underground bunker,
designed to house Congress in the event of nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   The 112,000-square-foot bunker had two meeting halls, one for
the House and one for the Senate; communications centers; a safe
room with copies of documents that would be necessary to keep the
government running; a hospital; 18 dormitories with 30 metal bunk
beds in each; and enough food to last for a month or more.
</P>
<P>
   A wing of the hotel was built over the bunker to conceal it, and
it remained secret until 1992, when newspaper articles about it
appeared. It is now open for tours.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland Hill will be the site of the first cottages to be built
as part of the sporting club. The property now has 10 tennis courts
on it, the only use the federal government would allow.
</P>
<P>
   Kleisner said that after the government lease ended, the company
decided to take another look at development. ``But we had to do it
right,'' he said, explaining that most developers wanted to build
tightly spaced houses along the resort's three golf courses,
creating ``fairway canyons.''
</P>
<P>
   The resort, which is owned by CSX Corp., spreads over 6,500
acres, from the top of Kate's Mountain northwest across the valley
to the top of Greenbrier Mountain. ``This land has been maintained
in an almost pristine fashion, and it is unacceptable to do
anything less'' than to be a good steward of the land, Kleisner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kleisner had originally met two of the principals in the
development firm, Peter Pollak and Chip Dolan, when he was looking
for a vacation home several years ago. The third partner in Dolan,
Pollak is Steve Schram, a former investment banker who once ran the
Boston Celtics basketball team and other businesses it owns.
</P>
<P>
   Kleisner looked at Bray's Island Plantation, a former estate
turned vacation-home community near Beaufort, S.C., that Dolan and
Pollak were marketing. He chose a home in Savannah instead but
remembered the two salesmen, who moved on to develop the Ford
Plantation, 1,800 acres near Savannah on the Ogeechee River, which
has sold $60 million in building lots in the last 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   The partners are relying on the reputation of the Greenbrier as
a grand hotel with fastidious service and on its long history to
help market the real estate. AAA gives the resort five diamonds,
its top rating, and it has been designated a National Historic
Landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenbrier has about 90,000 guests a year, about half of
whom have been there before. Conventions make up about 50 percent
of its business, and in the last year it has been host to the
Business Council, the Grocery Manufacturers of America and the
Chemical Manufacturers of America.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   People have been coming to what is now White Sulphur Springs and
to the valley along Howard's Creek since 1778, when a woman now
known only as Mrs. Anderson is said to have found that the sulphur
spring cured her rheumatism.
</P>
<P>
   The spring house, built decades later when the property became a
full-fledged resort, still stands, but people wanting to take the
sulphur water, with its smell of rotten eggs, now dip from a
free-running spigot, not a hole in the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The resort served as the summer White House for Martin Van Buren
in 1838. Dwight D. Eisenhower was the last sitting president to
stay at the hotel, and his visit has been the subject of much
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower came in 1956 to meet with the president of Mexico,
arriving by train and making no stops along the 250-mile route
between Washington and White Sulphur Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert S. Conte, the Greenbrier's staff historian, said that
many people believe this was a test run to see if it might have
been possible to move Congress to White Sulphur Springs if nuclear
war broke out. About the time of the Eisenhower visit, or perhaps
before, the federal government and Chesapeake &AMP; Ohio Railway, the
forerunner of CSX, began negotiations on building the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   It was completed just before the Cuban missile crisis in 1962,
and that was the only time in its history that the bunker was on
high alert, said Paul E. Bugas, its on-site manager from 1971 to
1995. He still manages the bunker, but for the Greenbrier, which
operates it as a tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Some 14,000 guests each year pay $25 to see where their
legislators would have lived if the Cold War had ever turned hot.
The president and the judicial branch would have been evacuated to
another bunker, this one at Mount Weather near Berryville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The bunker cost the government $10 million. It also spent $4
million on what is now called the West Virginia Wing, an 86-room
hotel addition that sits atop the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Bugas, who is known as Fritz, said a six-word phrase _ ``The
lease agreement is being activated'' _ would have set his staff to
work. The bunker was supposed to be ready to run within a four-hour
time limit. Information on how the legislators would have been
transported is still classified, but the Greenbrier airport, 10
miles away, has a 7,000-foot runway, long enough to land a military
transport.
</P>
<P>
   This history is what Dolan, Pollak is counting on to help it
sell 100 lots a year, or about $300 million over five years, Pollak
said. A fourth golf course, a lodge and stables are to be built for
the sole use of the homeowners, Pollak said, but they will also be
able to use the Greenbrier's existing golf courses, tennis courts,
stables, indoor and outdoor pools, spa and Land Rover driving
course.
</P>
<P>
   The architectural plans for the homes' exteriors must be
approved by the developers, who, unlike many resort developers, do
not plan to turn over the operation to the homeowners once the
project is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The homes will be spread out over the property, and the goal is
to make them as unobtrusive as possible, Pollak said. Kleisner, the
Greenbrier's president, said the target market would be wealthy
families who enjoy the outdoors but also want to preserve the land.
</P>
<P>
   The partners hope to expand the sporting club idea to other
historic sites but say their standards will limit the choices.
``We've turned down opportunities,'' Schram said. ``Some things
won't work, and some things won't fit. It has to be a very special
place, one of historic significance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
