<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SPIDER-PHOBIA-NYT &LR;      05-27 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIDER-PHOBIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DOCTOR IS IN, AND SO IS THE TARANTULA 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Raise your hand if you want to get really close to a
big hairy tarantula, five giant cockroaches or a rat with a 10-inch
tail. Take one step forward if bugs and vermin give you sweaty
palms, weak knees and shortness of breath.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harvey Baker, a professor of psychology at Queens College,
who himself suffers from a mild cockroach anxiety, is struggling to
find enough highly phobic subjects willing to stare down the stars
of their worst nightmares in the name of science.
</P>
<P>
   If he could just get 100 volunteers, Baker said, he could
determine whether his rather unusual treatment for the intense fear
of rodents and insects _ which draws on self-esteem building,
psychotherapy and the principle of acupuncture _ holds up as a
genuine cure. But since he began seeking subjects in February, he
has come up with just six people.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be difficult to find New Yorkers who are afraid of
the urban critters that Baker keeps in glass boxes in his
laboratory on the college's campus in Flushing. This is a city that
has so many rats that exterminating them commands an annual budget
of $13.5 million, and where the price of living in a
rent-stabilized apartment is often rooming with a cockroach _ or
10.
</P>
<P>
   But Baker seeks the truly phobic for his experiment, which he
believes is the first of its kind in the United States. He needs
the people who can't move for hours after they see a spider on
their window sill or have to flee their apartment for weeks when a
rat crawls from behind the refrigerator. He has posted fliers all
over the campus urging students to sign up for the study and noting
that the treatment might help.
</P>
<P>
   But Baker is fully in touch with the feelings behind the low
turnout, and he said he was willing to wait for subjects. At the
rate he has been going lately _ one volunteer every other week _ he
will need an extra 188 weeks of research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people with specific phobias do not seek treatment,'' he
said. ``Instead, they rearrange their lives to avoid the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing helps, so they live with it,'' he added, speaking the
other day in the cluttered laboratory he shares with five
Madagascar hissing cockroaches, also known as water bugs, and a
Chilean rose-haired tarantula named Matilda. (The rat, Albert, is a
hooded rat, a ``friendlier'' species than the typical city rat. It
is kept at another spot in the science building and taken to the
lab for experiments, Baker said.)
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who has researched and taught in the Queens College
psychology department since 1974, said 6.1 percent of Americans _
almost 17 million people _ had a potentially debilitating phobia
about small animals, including rats, snakes, spiders and
cockroaches.
</P>
<P>
   With some encouragement from a friend who attends Queens
College, Baker's sixth subject, Joe Orsi, decided to tackle his
spider phobia and volunteered for a 90-minute session the other day
with Baker and the tarantula.
</P>
<P>
   Orsi, 24, who lives in Queens, works for a restaurant supply
company in Manhattan. He often sees dead spiders in his company's
basement, he said. It makes him panic.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's assistant, Michelle Guttman, a graduate student,
interviewed Orsi about his phobia for 15 minutes. Then she slowly
guided him into another room, where the tarantula was waiting. She
scored his level of fear during the approach.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Orsi opened the door to the other room, the
heart-rate monitor clipped to his ear lobe showed that his pulse
was racing. By the time he laid his eyes on Matilda, his pulse had
shot up 20 beats per minute. He could not take the final step of
what is known as the ``feared-animal approach task,'' in which he
was asked to touch the part of the glass cage closest to the
tarantula.
</P>
<P>
   Orsi returned to his seat to fill out a spider phobia
questionnaire about his experience and checked ``yes'' to all nine
symptoms of the phobia, from ``lump in throat,'' to ``hands feel
cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a 45-minute treatment, known as the Emotional Freedom
Technique. Baker said he learned about it at a conference a year
ago and decided to apply it to the rat, spider and cockroach
phobias.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the silly business,'' Baker said as he began the
treatment. Then he asked Orsi to tap various parts of his body
while saying, ``fear of spiders,'' to hum, count aloud and say
things like ``I forgive myself for anything I might have done to
cause my fear of spiders.'' The tapping, drawn from acupuncture, is
aimed at pressure points that, when struck, are supposed to release
negative energy from the body, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Orsi seemed to have a lot of negative energy toward Matilda.
</P>
<P>
   When the session was over, Orsi went through a second interview,
and again approached the tarantula. This time, his pulse was 15
beats slower than when he first looked at the spider, and he took
the final step, touching the glass near the tarantula, and
lingering for a moment to look at the spider.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of Baker's six subjects have undergone the full
treatment, because some are randomly placed in a control group, but
all three have shown signs of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Baker acknowledged that it might be years before he could
draw any conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's something to it,'' he said. ``For the first 80
years they used aspirin, no one knew why it worked. Something can
work without our knowing why.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
