u i BC-ISRAEL-U.N.-NYT &LR;      05-27 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL MAY LOSE OUTSIDER STATUS AT U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After decades of exclusion from all regional groups in the
United Nations, Israel has been accepted on a temporary basis by
the Western Europeans, ending its virtual disenfranchisement in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's ambassador to the United Nations called the long-sought
invitation, issued on Friday, a turning point in his country's
relations with the organization, where a voting bloc of Arab and
Third World nations has perennially attacked and isolated the
Israelis in the General Assembly and other bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Only two nations, Israel and Estonia, have never belonged to one
of the regional groups, formed 40 years ago to decide on candidates
for many council and committee positions at the United Nations and
its agencies and programs around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Estonia chose not to join the Eastern European group, holding
out for membership in the Western European caucus, which also
includes Australia, New Zealand, Canada and sometimes the United
States. But Israel has been barred by Arab and other opposition
from the Asian group, which covers all nations from the eastern
shores of the Mediterranean to the Pacific. Membership in the Asian
group is still Israel's goal, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been lobbying hard over the last year to
get Israel into the Western Europe group. The decision was bumped
from one level to another in the 15-member European Union for
months, before the Netherlands, which now holds the rotating
chairmanship of the group at the United Nations, pressed for
closure.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, U.S. diplomats said, the Dutch ambassador to the
United Nations, Peter van Walsum, circulated a letter to the
group's members saying that if there were no objections raised by
Friday, Israel would be invited to join the group, under certain
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   One is that temporary membership will be extended initially for
only four years, after which Israel's relationship with the group
would be reviewed. Israel would also have to forgo seeking elected
positions for two years.U.S. officials say intense competition for
contested posts was a major factor in keeping Israel out of the
Western European group.
</P>
<P>
   Other positions in the U.N. system will be closed to Israel for
longer periods because of past agreements. Israel must formally
accept the limited invitation.
</P>
<P>
   There are five regional groups at the United Nations _ Western
Europe, Eastern Europe, Asia, Africa and the Western Hemisphere,
which covers Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
