<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FOX-0528-COX     05-27 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIS CONFIDENCE (RE-)BOLSTERED, TOP MEXICAN PRESIDENTIAL
CHALLENGER RETAKES THE OFFENSIVE
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERACRUZ, Mexico _ He's back.
</P>
<P>
   With characteristic brash confidence, Mexican presidential
challenger Vicente Fox Quesada emerged Saturday from the previous
night's three-way debate glowing with triumph and claiming that he
was once again on the road to an historic victory.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans are preparing for the most competitive presidential
election ever in this country, whose presidency has been controlled
by one political party for more than seven decades. The tall, rangy
57-year-old top opposition challenger is coming off of a week
embarrassing negative publicity that threatened to set his campaign
back.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts and some quick independent polls indicated he may
have recovered much of his momentum during the Friday debate. After
being accused in much of the media of acting childish and stubborn
during televised negotiations over a debate with his rivals, Fox on
Friday admitted to being bull-headed.
</P>
<P>
   But he converted his blunder into something positive by telling
Mexicans that ``firm character'' is what Mexico needs to change a
country with an entrenched political monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   With five weeks to go before the July 2 election, Fox was met on
the streets here Saturday morning by throngs of supporters who were
cursing Mexico's ruling party and waving foam rubber hands with
Fox's V-for-victory sign. One supporter passed Fox a leaflet
through his bus window that said: ``If Fox is stubborn, I'm even
more so.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, candidate of Mexico's conservative National Action Party,
or PAN, has been criticized by some rivals for being arrogant. The
rancher and former Coca-Cola executive is unapologetic about his
behavior, which he says has been key to pushing him into a
neck-in-neck race against Francisco Labastida Ochoa, candidate of
Mexico's ruling Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``A candidate who goes out on the street and acts like a loser
might as well stay at home,'' a relaxed, grinning Fox said in an
interview with the Cox News Service as he flew here Saturday
morning on his private jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I transmit this conviction to the Mexican people every day,
and they return it to me,'' Fox said. ``This is what produces
'Foxmania.'''
</P>
<P>
   This oil-rich region on the Gulf Coast has long been considered
a PRI stronghold. Fox will need to make inroads in enemy territory
like this to achieve a victory he says is just a few percentage
points away. Veracruz has the third greatest number of voters of
any state in Mexico and Fox claims he is now dead even here with
Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see he's a man who has the guts to do what he says
he'll do,'' said Nyla Desgrennes, 18, a high school student who
will vote for the first time. ``All the students at school are with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox was also met by enthused crowds of working-class victims who
have lost hundreds of thousands of dollars in a national bank
scandal that rocked Veracruz and other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to see (Mexican President Ernesto) Zedillo to
complain and all they did was send police out to block us,'' said
housewife Yolanda Arrevalo. ``We think Fox will listen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   All three candidates in Friday night's debate _ Fox, Labastida
and leftist candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano_ claimed
victory after the event. They sparred over Byzantine economic
policies and proposals. But both Fox and Cardenas lashed out at
Labastida, heaping blame in blunt language on the PRI for running a
country riddled with corruption and where half the population lives
in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Mexico City newspaper Reforma published an instant
telephone survey of 1,611 people nationwide that found that Fox was
considered the winner of the debate by 47 percent of those who
witnessed it. Only 37 percent of those polled had seen the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper pointed out that those surveyed were select urban
residents with an above-average education and enough income to own
a phone. But urban voters _ which comprise 60 percent of Mexico's
voters _ are the core of Fox's support and he appeared bolstered by
the findings.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   With five weeks to go before the election, Fox says he must
especially cut into votes that might go to Cardenas, a former PRI
politician who bolted to start his own leftist Democratic
Revolution Party, or PRD, 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Cardenas, who lacks the charismatic speaking style
of Fox, performed better than ever before in Friday's debate. But
even though Fox praised Cardenas at one point during the debate for
his ferocious attacks on Labastida, on Saturday he expressed no
affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's jealous,'' Fox said of Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I need the votes of the PRD, but I don't need
Cardenas.''
</P>
<P>
   For months _ even though the two men haven't spoken at length
for more than a year _ Fox has been publicly urging Cardenas to
join his campaign. He says polls are indicating that only Fox has a
chance of beating the PRI and he is promising to build a
pluralistic government.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago it seemed that Cardenas would become Mexico's
first opposition president. He won the race for Mexico City mayor
and enjoyed a reputation for being a fighter for more democracy and
justice for the poor. In 1988, Cardenas ran unsuccessfully for
president in an election that many Mexicans believe was stolen by
the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas is also the son of Mexico's most beloved president,
Lazaro Cardenas, a PRI politician who nationalized Mexico's oil
industry and earned affection for helping peasants with credit,
public works and land grants.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas ``can't accept the death of his father's PRI,'' Fox
said, referring to the PRI's decision to reduce subsidies to the
poor in recent years and adopt less nationalistic economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also said Cardenas had an ``obsession for power'' that
stemmed from his desire to follow in his father's footsteps and
become president.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also suggested that Cardenas has made a trade off with the
PRI. His theory is that Cardenas won't object to fraud in the
presidential election as long as the PRI doesn't try to prevent the
PRD's candidate for Mexico City mayor from winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``His heart still beats for the PRI,'' Fox said of Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, however, many analysts seemed to think that
Cardenas' trashing of the PRI was so strong it debunked Fox's claim
that Cardenas was in cahoots with the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Fox said his goal is to win the presidency with at least 51
percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he said, ``we should have a solid 46 percentage
points. I lack five. Those five are hard to take away from the PRI
because those are hard-core voters. I don't have any choice but to
fight for the undecided.''
</P>
<P>
   Sketching out calculations on a newspaper, Fox said he believes
about 15 percent of voters are undecided. Fox claims that when all
significant polls are considered, he leads Labastida 42.5 percent
to 39.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks that remain, he'll need to get to more poor voters
and PRD sympathizers in urban and rural areas. Fox acknowledges he
lags behind Labastida in rural provinces, where 30 percent of
voters live and the PRI get-out-the-vote machine is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's campaign has targeted the poorest, and what he believes
are the most corrupt voting districts in the country to send in
campaign workers and prevent voter fraud or vote buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dismantling the PRI machine,'' he said, referring to
the ruling party's alleged history of doling out gifts of money,
food or other supplies to lure the poorest voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense of the vote in the country is going to be very
important,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Acting sure of victory, Fox is already challenging President
Zedillo to make sure Mexico avoids a crisis if he becomes the first
non-PRI president since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will invite Zedillo to see that the transition will be
peaceful,'' Fox said. ``Zedillo, on July 3, becomes the key person
in this transition. He has to avoid any reaction by the hard-core
PRI supporters. He has to maintain order and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
