<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-STATUS0528-COX     05-27 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-STATUS0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witnesses gave only weak support to case against NFL star
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The three-day holiday weekend came in the nick of time
for Fulton County prosecutors, who are reeling from a turbulent
week of testimony in their murder case against NFL star Ray Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution has been marred by flip-flopping witnesses,
confused witnesses, one who says he was racially slurred by
investigators and another who's a professional liar.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement as the trial began last week, Fulton
County District Attorney Paul Howard made several promises to the
jury _ and on several he's fallen short: The two witnesses who
originally said they saw Lewis strike a victim changed their
stories. And one of them _ the driver of the rented limo in which
Lewis and co-defendants Reginald Oakley and Joseph Sweeting left
the crime scene _ didn't testify, as expected, that he heard Oakley
and Sweeting admit to the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the big question is, can the state salvage its case?''
said Alan Baverman, an Atlanta defense attorney who is providing
commentary on the case for ESPN. ``It's a bizarre trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Baverman might be understating it. On Friday, the prosecution's
case against Lewis featured a convicted con artist, Chester
Anderson, who said he has gone by seven names and lives to scheme
``to get something for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb County District Attorney J. Tom Morgan, who like many in
the legal community has been closely watching the case, said
Anderson is a bad witness because he's a ``new-found witness and
that's always suspect'' and because ``jurors don't like snitches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the worst kind of record; fraud and deception (charges)
go straight to his credibility,'' said Morgan. ``But Paul Howard
can only take witnesses as he finds them.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said that, as a prosecutor, ``you lead off with your best
witnesses.'' If so, Howard's team has a tough week ahead. ``There's
been four days of testimony and (Howard) has not planted guilt
beyond a reasonable doubt,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Harvey, an Atlanta defense attorney who has commented on
the case for WXIA, said Howard needs to ``consider this week a
wash'' and try to regain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go back and try to get centered,'' he said. ``They should
go back and bring in the medical examiner. That should have a
sobering effect on the jury. It tells them what we're doing here
concerns the loss of life of two young men. That might have a
chilling effect on the havoc the defense has wreaked.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors have repeatedly shown photos of the
blood-stained Buckhead crime scene where Jacinth Baker, 21, and
Richard Lollar, 24, were stabbed to death after a night of
post-Super Bowl partying.
</P>
<P>
   And the prosecutors have been able to introduce evidence that
Oakely, and a lesser extent, Sweeting, attacked the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said he will try to finish his case by the end of the
week. He will probably call to the witness stand limo
passengerJessica Robertson, police investigators and some of the
victims' family members. Also, prosecutors are considering an
immunity deal in exchange for the testimony of another limo
passenger, Carlos Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the killings, Stafford and Robertson allegedly
helped dispose of a bag of items in a dumpster, a witness in the
trial has testified. Prosecutors are expected to contend that the
two threw away the suit Lewis wore the night of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   If they cut a deal with Stafford, prosecutors would finally get
testimony from a male limo passenger. But during jury selection,
Lewis defense attorney Don Samuel said he would be dumbfounded if
the state gave Stafford immunity because the defense teams contend
he was a participant in the deadly melee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the state gives him a deal, I'll exit the courthouse
through that window,'' said Samuel, pointing to the window outside
the fourth-floor courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   All of the attorneys interviewed said Howard should have
augmented his case by charging Lewis with lesser crimes like making
false statements to police, hampering an investigation and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   But Keisha Bottoms, who has both defended and prosecuted cases,
said that window is closed. ``They can't do it now, it's too
late,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
