u s BC-BKN-SPAIN-NYT &LR;      05-27 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYER GOING TO SPAIN TO TRY TO CARVE ROUTE TO NBA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darren Phillip has a goal: two years after his graduation from
Fairfield University in Connecticut this spring, the 6-foot-7-inch
power forward wants to be playing in the NBA. And like the
intelligent, persistent and resourceful fellow he is, Darren
Phillip has a plan to put firm foundations under his lofty
ambition. In fact, he has mapped out the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, two days before receiving his degree in
communications on commencement day at Fairfield, Phillip signed a
two-year contract with Malaga in the Spanish basketball league.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to play in the NBA sometime in the next two
years,'' said Phillip, the NCAA Division I leader in rebounding
last season with 14 a game. ``If I don't hook on with a team, this
opportunity gives me something to fall back on.''
</P>
<P>
   The chance to sharpen his skills overseas was too good for
Phillip to pass up, especially when weighed against the possibility
of starting his professional career as a bench warmer at home.
Phillip said he turned down more lucrative offers from teams in
Italy and Greece because he felt Malaga, an upper-echelon team in
the Spanish league, gave him the best opportunity to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will get to play a lot of minutes, which will give me a lot
of experience,'' said Phillip, who hopes to establish a more
consistent 15-foot jump shot in the more offense-orientated style
of play in Europe. ``I played at power forward in college, but I'll
probably wind up at small forward at the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   At Fairfield, appearing in 27 games this past season, Phillip
was named to the All-Metro Athletic Athletic Conference second
team. In addition to his strong work on the boards, Phillip
averaged 16 points, shooting 56 percent from the field. He led the
nation with 24 double-doubles, including 19 straight to end the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Fairfield finished the season with a 13-14 overall record, but
was 11-7 in the MAAC, good for third place. The Stags could not
match the success they attained during Phillip's freshman season,
when Fairfield qualified for the NCAA tournament, losing to North
Carolina in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year we lost in the semis of the MAAC tournament to a
great Iona team,'' Phillip said. ``We played well, but we came up
short. These things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those things happened when Phillip was being recruited
out of South Shore High School in the Canarsie section of Brooklyn.
As a senior, he averaged 22.5 points and 14.2 rebounds, but the
more elite college basketball schools overlooked him. Fairfield did
not. Phillip credits Stags coach Tim O'Toole with his development
over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an extension of my parents,'' Phillip said of O'Toole.
``He taught us about basketball and life experiences and how to be
classy on and off the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Phillip moves on, from Canarsie and Connecticut, to Spain.
He will report with the rest of the Malaga players on Sept. 11. The
organization will provide him with the necessities: a residence, a
car, and per diem expenses. But he will be without the Brooklyn
support system that has sustained him through his four years at
Fairfield. His parents, Frederick and Margurite, and his brothers,
Ryan and Douglas, often made the one-hour trip to Fairfield to
watch him play. Now, they will be an ocean away. Phillip has
accepted that distance as a necessary part of his career plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at Fairfield, I would be away from home for nine
months, so I am used to living by myself and being on my own,''
Phillip said. ``I'm trying to take things one step at a time, so
I'm not looking far into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillip points out that he has played in front of international
audiences before. In July 1998, he was a member of a MAAC all-star
team that toured Japan, playing the Japanese national team in a
series of exhibition games across the country. And, he added, he
was born in London; his family moved to the United States when he
was 3 years old. He still has several aunts, uncles and cousins
there and has visited them on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip also intends to get in touch with former NBA and NCAA
players currently playing in Spain, including Harper Williams, who
played at UMass-Amherst from 1989-1993 and Ken Cavanaugh, who
played at Manhattan from 1995-99.
</P>
<P>
   It is all part of the plan. As Phillip said, he hopes to be back
home in two years. ``But if the only way I could get into the NBA
was to stay in Europe for six years,'' he said, ``then that's what
I'll do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
