<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETER'S IN THE LINEUP AS YANKEES BEAT UP ON RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Yankees desperately needed Derek Jeter
back in their lineup, to restore potency in their offensive attack
and confidence for their minds. But before returning to shortstop
Saturday, Jeter rejected the notion that the Yankees were built
around him. They are the type of team, he said, that wins with
contributions from all corners of their roster.
</P>
<P>
   And they defeated the Boston Red Sox, 8-3, with a collective
effort. It was pot luck for 55,671 at Yankee Stadium: Jason
Grimsley, an emergency starter in place of Orlando Hernandez,
pitched in five solid innings, Mike Stanton added three innings.
Four different Yankees hit home runs, and in his first action since
May 11, Jeter had three hits and a stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   With the teams tied once more at the top of the American League
East with identical records of 27 victories and 18 losses, the
Yankees' Roger Clemens will pitch against Pedro Martinez Sunday
night in the final game of the series. Toronto beat Martinez last
Tuesday; the Red Sox right-hander has not lost back-to-back starts
since September 1998, when he lost three straight games, twice to
the Yankees in that streak.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was supposed to pitch this game for the Yankees, but
he felt spasms high in his back and had to stop, taking his hat off
and slumping against a bench in the bullpen disconsolately.
Grimsley hurriedly prepared to pitch in his place, before shutting
out the Red Sox in the first and second innings.
</P>
<P>
   In his relief role, Grimsley is accustomed to pitching about two
innings at a time, and he got into trouble in the third inning.
John Valentin pulled a home run down the left-field line leading
off _ the prominent response and presence of Red Sox fans was
striking in Yankee Stadium _ and Jason Varitek slapped a single to
left. Jeff Frye pulled a grounder down the third-base line, past
the base, the ball caroming off the front of the stands and into
short left field; on Frye's double, the Red Sox had second and
third and one out.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley lost his grip on a fastball and released the ball
perhaps 15 feet wide of the catcher Jorge Posada, allowing one run
to score, and Trot Nixon turned and bunted perfectly up the first
base line, his squeeze play surprising the Yankees and enabling
Frye to cross the plate. Grimsley hit Brian Daubach with a fastball
and walked Nomar Garciaparra, and with the Yankees trailing by 3-0,
it seemed as if they were unraveling in this series. Brian Rose
retired the first two batters in the bottom of the third _ before
Boston's strong adherence to an old-school baseball practice
probably helped to jump-start the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Rose drilled Ledee in the right leg with a pitch, and as Ledee
jogged to first, he probably wondered if this had been in
retaliation for Grimsley having knocked down Daubach in the first
inning and hitting him in the third.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Yankees came alive: Jeter singled, and Paul O'Neill
smashed a line drive through the middle to score Ledee. If, in
fact, Rose did plunk Ledee on purpose, then he violated another
traditional baseball credo _ do not wake the dead, do not give them
any reason to think they can come back.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did pick their way back into the game, one home run
at a time. Shane Spencer smacked a ball just inside the left field
foul pole in the fourth, his eighth home run. Ledee launched a shot
deep into the right field stands in the fifth, his third home run
of the season, tying the game at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   John Wasdin relieved for the Red Sox in the bottom of the sixth
inning, and the Yankees attacked. Posada bashed a lead-off homer,
giving the Yankees a 4-3 lead; Posada has 10 this season, after
hitting 12 all of last season. There were two out when Clay
Bellinger singled and stole a base, the third of the game for the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee drew a walk. Jeter _ who earlier in the game had snapped
an 0-for-14 streak that began before he was placed on the disabled
list _ dropped a single into right field, and Bellinger crossed the
plate. The left-hander Tim Young was summoned to pitch to O'Neill,
who was handled well last year by Boston's left-handed relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. O'Neill swung, made loud contact and ran toward
first, something he does when he hits the ball very well. It landed
in the lower deck in right field, his sixth homer of the season
counting for three runs. The Yankees had an 8-3 lead and were in
control of this game, and when O'Neill jogged to play his position
in the top of the seventh, fans in the bleachers _ quite dry on a
day of mixed clouds and sunshine _ stood and cheered him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
