<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-MIHM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIHM TOPS NBA'S LIST OF SLIM DRAFT PICKINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who follow the NBA Draft claim this year's class is the
weakest in years, but don't tell that to New Jersey Nets owner
Lewis Katz.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who won last week's NBA Draft Lottery, appear poised
to select Texas center Chris Mihm on June 28, when the NBA will
conduct its draft in Minneapolis. Katz hopes the 7-foot, 250-pound
Mihm can help the Nets reverse their disappointing 31-51 record
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly a big man is a priority, an inside presence,'' Katz
said. ``We must have lost 30 or 40 games in the last two minutes
due to the lack of second shots, or getting defensive rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz knows the No. 1 pick could have a domino effect within his
organization. The Nets had a plethora of injuries to key players,
including former All-Star center Jayson Williams, and also must
hire a head coach and vice president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen what happened in the past,'' Katz said. ``\RTim\S
Duncan came out, and suddenly there was a new team in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orlando changed quickly when they had the first \Rand got
Shaquille O'Neal and Penny Hardaway\S. This could be a real boost
in the arm to get us where we need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vancouver Grizzlies are expected to select Cincinnati power
forward Kenyon Martin with the second pick. Martin played high
school basketball at Dallas Bryan Adams.
</P>
<P>
   With the third pick, the Los Angeles Clippers probably will take
Louisiana State forward Stromile Swift, who can start after Maurice
Taylor leaves via free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very satisfied with our position at No. 3, because we
know that we'll get a very good player,'' said Elgin Baylor, the
Clippers' vice president of basketball operations. ``We'll get a
player \Rwho\S will come in and make a good contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have the 12th pick in the draft, and they will be
searching for someone who has a passion for rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get bigger, that's for sure,'' said Mavericks
general manager Don Nelson. ``We need to rebound better; we have to
solve those issues. Size and rebounding.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Dirk Nowitzki's former German teammates _ 6-11 forward
Olumide Oyedeji _ has already worked out for the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Oyedeji hails from Nigeria, and is another find by Amadou Gallo
Fall, who coordinates the Mavericks' international scouting
assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Other players the Mavericks are looking at include Michigan
State swingman Morris Peterson, Syracuse power forward Etan Thomas
and UCLA center Jerome Moiso, who enters the draft after his
sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, since no one is all that thrilled about paying guaranteed
money to a first-round pick in this year's draft, the Mavericks are
not against trading down for a lower pick or moving out of the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go down the board and it looks like there's a great
reason to keep it, we'll keep it,'' Mavericks owner Mark Cuban
said. ``If someone makes us a better offer, we'll trade it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a way that we can trade up because there's somebody
we want, that's the kind of thing that Nellie and I will sit and go
through _ and all of the coaches _ and make decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Front-office decisions are especially key during a weak draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This draft, I don't think they have a dominant player that's
coming out that's just going to turn the franchise around,'' Baylor
said. ``But I think they have players that can be productive and
who can come in here and help your team.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
