<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-HUNTING _ ATLANTA _ ``Gobble,'' he said. Silence. Far
away, a crow cawed. ``Gobblegobblegobble,'' he continued,
passionately, flogging a fallen tree trunk with his hat to make a
sound like the beating of large wings. Still no reply. Finally Doug
Benefield got to his feet, shaking his head in disgust. ``He's a
wise old bird,'' Benefield said. ``He's gone.'' Benefield is a
master of the art of talking to turkeys, but this time he was
unable to persuade an old tom to venture across the sights of his
shotgun. It tended to prove that the suburban South Fulton County
turkey is just as wily as his country cousin. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in (l) Lifestyle and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   GROUNDSKEEPER _ Steve Hopkins remembers when families used to
bring peonies for Memorial Day _ big droopy bunches of them _ in
Ball jars and old coffee cans wrapped in aluminum foil for their
loved ones. Today, they're more likely to bring artificial flowers,
silk mostly, although the occasional plastic bouquet still takes
bloom. ``Memorial Day is still the biggest day around here,'' said
Hopkins, 49, grounds superintendent at David's Cemetery. WITH
PHOTOS. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TV-CUTTING _ Review of ``Secret Cutting' May30 on USA Network.
Dawn Cottrell doesn't have any friends. Classmates tease her
constantly. Her musician boyfriend only wants her for sex. She has
an overbearing mother and a passive father. No wonder Dawn isn't
happy. But the only way the teen loner knows how to deal with her
gloomy existence is by harming herself. She stabs herself with
tools. Slices her wrists with glass. Burns her arm with a cigarette
lighter. Her body looks like a grotesque human pin cushion. Dawn
may not control her life, but, she reasons, she can be in charge of
her own pain. (Thompson, Dayton Daily News) MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
