<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 05/27/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 27, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-3 -- The
Indiana Pacers Reggie Miller may have been flying high in this
matchup against the New York Knicks Allan Houston, but it was the
Knicks who gained some momentum as they defeated the Pacers 98-95
on Saturday in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference finals. Latrell
Sprewell and Houston combined for 60 points to lead the Knicks, who
played without injured center Patrick Ewing and also overcame the
loss of forward Marcus Camby to a knee injury. Game 4 is Monday.
(Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 27, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-2 -- The
New York Knicks Latrell Sprewell pumps up his teammates as they
battled and defeated the Indiana Pacers 98-95 on Saturday in Game 3
of the Eastern Conference finals. Sprewell broke out of a
series-long slump and scored 32 points and Houston won his matchup
with Reggie Miller and scored 28 as the Knicks cut the Pacers' lead
to 2-1 in the best-of-seven series. Game 4 is Monday. (Barton
Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 27, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-1 -- The
New York Knicks Allan Houston follows through on a dunk against the
Indiana Pacers as New York defeated the Indiana 98-95 at Madison
Square Garden on Saturday to pull within 2-1 in the National
Basketball Association's Eastern Conference finals. Latrell
Sprewell and Allan Houston combined for 60 points to lead the
Knicks, who played without injured center Patrick Ewing and also
overcame the loss of forward Marcus Camby to a knee injury. (Barton
Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HARRISBURG, Pa. -- May 27, 2000 -- RIDGE-CONSERVATIVES
-- Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, remains the most mentioned
prospective running mate for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. Ridge, a
popular Republican leaving the Statehouse after signing a recent $1
billion tax cut, set a Republican record for the heavily Democratic
state of Pennsylvania with a 780,000-vote victory margin in his
1998 re-election. A Bush-Ridge ticket might well deliver this
critical battleground, the fifth-largest state in electoral votes,
to the Republicans. (Laura Pedrick/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) KIGALI, Rwanda -- May 27, 2000 -- WOMEN-PEACE -- Rwanda,
torn apart by genocide six years ago, has seen the emergence of
some strong women's organizations committed to rebuilding a
semblance of normality for their families. Mary Balikungeri, is the
coordinator of a peace group, Rwanda Women's Network. Balikungeri
recently toured the United States with 15 women from all over
Africa, and had the opportunity to meet American women living in
poverty and distress. ``You come to realize,'' says Balikungeri,
``we need each other. All of us, regardless of where we were from,
saw that everywhere women are the victims.'' (Barbara W.
Crossette/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) EMBALAM, India -- May 27, 2000 -- INDIA-ONLINE-2 --
Information from computers in the village of Kizur, where people
live in thatched mud huts, helped save the life of a milk cow named
Jayalakshmi. The cow's owner Subrayan Panjaili, who cannot read or
write, was aided by a local elder's 23-year-old, college-educated
daughter, who used the village computer to call a list of
veterinarians in the area. The computer was obtained through the
Madras-based M.S. Swaminathan Research Foundation, a nonprofit
organization that uses science and technology to tackle poverty.
(Celia W. Dugger/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BENNINGTON, Vt. -- May 27, 2000 -- BENNINGTON-DISPUTE-2
-- Bennington College president Dr. Elizabeth Coleman has been
labeled a dictatorial figure who crushes any criticism at the
college. Coleman says she is raising academic standards. ``What
people knew about Bennington was that it's the most expensive
college,'' says Coleman. But, she says, that was ``the only thing''
they knew. The past academic year has been marked by the dismissal
of four faculty members seen by their supporters as critics of the
administration and by Coleman as having fallen short in their
professional qualifications and responsibilities. (Keith Meyers/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BENNINGTON, Vt. -- May 27, 2000 -- BENNINGTON-DISPUTE-1
-- Bennington College, a tiny, quirky, hilltop jewel box of liberal
artsiness, is hardly a stranger to controversy. The past academic
year has been marked by the dismissal of four faculty members seen
by their supporters as critics of the administration. On the other
hand, Dr. Elizabeth Coleman, the tough-minded president who came to
Bennington after serving as dean of the undergraduate division at
the New School University in New York City, says those who were
dismissed had fallen short in their professional qualifications and
responsibilities. Students on the main campus. (Keith Meyers/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) EMBALAM, India -- May 27, 2000 -- INDIA-ONLINE -- At a
time of growing unease about the global gap between technology
knows and know-nots, India is fast becoming a laboratory for small
experiments. In the fishing village of Veerampattinam, children
play with with a computer, which some call a ``magic box.'' There
are serious questions about whether countries like India, weighed
down by high rates of illiteracy and illness, should spend heavily
on what most would consider a luxury. Still, others say a
well-placed computer, like a communal well or an irrigation pump,
may become another tool for development. (Celia W. Dugger/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CHESTERTOWN, Md. -- May 27, 2000 -- SPECIAL-GRADUATES --
Christine Lincoln's journey to Washington College, a small liberal
arts institution in Chestertown, Md., was as circuitous as it was
perilous. Lincoln, 34, with her son, Takii, at Washington College,
fought a long battle with drug addiction and depression, only to be
reborn in college as a short story writer. Now a graduate, Lincoln
says ``the possibilities for my life are endless.'' This fall,
Lincoln intends to begin her own adventure, moving to South Africa,
where she will study African literature. (Marty Katz/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MIAMI BEACH, Fla. -- May 27, 2000 -- MIAMI-BEAUTY-3 --
Only a fraction of the beautiful people from South Beach, the
southernmost tip of the city of Miami Beach, actually make a living
from their looks, fashion shoots, cosmetics advertisements and
runway jobs, say experts in the fashion industry. Yet, many live
the life. Chris Alex, 23, a model who also works a sales clerk at
the Todd Oldham store on Miami Beach, helps Michelle Stern, 24, of
New York, during her shopping spree on South Beach. (Andrew
Itkoff/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MIAMI BEACH, Fla. -- May 27, 2000 -- MIAMI-BEAUTY-2 --
Only a fraction of the beautiful people from South Beach, the
southernmost tip of the city of Miami Beach, actually make a living
from their looks, fashion shoots, cosmetics advertisements and
runway jobs, say experts in the fashion industry. Yet, many live
the life. Carolina Zadro, 25, an aspiring model from Miami Beach,
works part time handing out fliers for a local art gallery on
Lincoln Road in South Beach. (Andrew Itkoff/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MIAMI BEACH, Fla. -- May 27, 2000 -- MIAMI-BEAUTY-1 --
The southernmost tip of the city of Miami Beach, South Beach is
home to several of the country's top-tier modeling agencies.South
Beach is utterly absorbed by beauty, peopled with fashion models
and dreamers and others who just like moving about a place where
bartenders pose like Grecian statues, cafe hostesses are achingly
lovely, and waiters and waitresses sway blank-faced between tables
as if on an invisible catwalk. (Andrew Itkoff/The New York Times)
