<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7706 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LEBANON-BORDER-BOS &LR;      05-27 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-BORDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANON FACES PERIOD OF UNCERTAINTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ As UN cartographers examined Lebanon's southern border
Saturday with maps and tape measures to determine whether Israel's
withdrawal complied with UN resolutions, one thing was certain: the
political and strategic landscape here has fundamentally changed
along with the physical.
</P>
<P>
   The chaotic pullback of Israeli troops after 22 years of
occupation silenced the last active war front in a half-century of
Arab-Israeli conflict. It could help define Lebanon's future and
create paths toward a regional peace agreement. But those paths are
narrow, and run along a precipice of potential conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first chance we have to unify Lebanon and truly move
forward with the rebuilding of this country, and it is the last
chance before we could blow everything up and lose it all,'' said
Gebran Tueni, editor of Beirut's An Nahar newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible change in the strategic topography is that
Israel's withdrawal and the collapse of its proxy militia leaves
Syria deeply isolated.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, with 30,000 troops stationed in Lebanon, effectively
controls the country. It has long supported Lebanon's Shiite Muslim
guerrillas in their war against Israel as a way to exert pressure
for the return of the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from
Syria in the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has warned Syria that if it inspires any trouble along
the valleys and rocky hillsides of this new, raw border, Syrian
troops will be targeted for retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   A cache of heavy weapons confiscated from abandoned Israeli
military bases has been divided up by Hezbollah, the Shiite
fighters, and by a variety of less disciplined militias of
Lebanon's civil war, which began in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Some weapons also presumably ended up in Palestinian refugee
camps in Lebanon, where 400,000 Palestinians have remained since
they fled or were forced from their land in 1948, when war broke
out after Israel became an independent state.
</P>
<P>
   This new firepower, in a country that has never had a shortage
of weapons, raises a specter of conflict possibly created by a
fringe militia or splinter group, and possibly inspired by Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian frustration would seem likely to increase in this new
scenario. The Syrians are essentially hemmed in by Israel's move,
and it is likely that for Israel, the issue of the Golan Heights
will shift to a back burner.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of Washington, Ehud Barak spent much of his first
five months as Israel's prime minister trying to woo Syria's
president, Hafez Assad, to the negotiating table. Barak said at the
time that he wanted to withdraw troops from Lebanon as part of a
regional peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But a summit meeting between President Clinton and Assad in late
March in Geneva did not restart the deadlocked Israeli-Syrian
talks. And Barak's sudden withdrawal, six weeks ahead of his stated
deadline, has left many Middle East experts saying that Assad had
miscalculated by not settling.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrians arrived in Lebanon in 1976, a year after the civil
war began there. Their presence is not only military, but political
as well, and many in Lebanon have grown to resent the Syrian
meddling.
</P>
<P>
   Farid Khazen, a professor of political science at American
University in Beirut, said that the 1990 Taif agreements, which
ended the civil war, called for Syria to withdraw its troops to
positions closer to the Syrian border, in Lebanon's Bekaa Valley.
Syria has not done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of Lebanese would like to have good
relations with Syria, but there is an impatience that is setting
in. Many contest the army in Syria, and that feeling will increase
now,'' Khazen said.
</P>
<P>
   Few politicians and academics have dared to raise their voice
against Syria's presence; to do so had been seen as favoring
Israel. Such criticism in many cases brought threatsfrom the
Damascus regime's vast intelligence network.
</P>
<P>
   In Beirut, university students chanting ``Lebanon first! Syrian
Army out!'' have been brutally repressed, and some organizers have
been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Tueni, the An Nahar editor, who has spoken out against Syrian
dominance in Lebanon, said the ``next few days are critical'' to
the future of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   If the UN cartographers confirm that Israel has completely
withdrawn, Lebanese troops will deploy, they have said. Tueni says
the reason the Lebanese army has not yet deployed, leaving the
border crackling with tension between those seen as loyal to the
occupying forces and those who supported the resistance, is that
Syria wants to sustain a ``controlled chaos'' to keep Israel off
guard and insecure along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian-influenced politicians and Hezbollah leaders have raised
the issue of a rocky no-man's-land known as Shebaa Farms, which
they say is Lebanese soil that Israel is continuing to occupy.
</P>
<P>
   The UN has ruled that the area is part of Syria, and left many
observerers viewing the dispute as a pretext for Syria to create
instability in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Tueni says it is essential for the Lebanese government to play
this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lebanese army has to go in there as soon as possible,''
Tueni said. ``If they do not, then Christians will leave the south
and feel abandoned by their government. This will mean a
demographic rupture in a country that has a very fragile balance of
Christians and Muslims and Druze. We have seen that kind of rupture
cause disaster here before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
