<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7710 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRISH-UNIONISTS-BOS &LR;      05-27 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-UNIONISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER-SHARING TO RETURN TO NORTHERN IRELAND
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ A bitterly divided Ulster Unionist Party voted
Saturday to restore a power-sharing government with Sinn Fein, the
IRA's political representatives, giving the Northern Ireland peace
process a major boost and Protestant leader David Trimble a narrow
vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   According to one prominent unionist, the vote was ``a victory
for common sense,'' and represented a decision to test the Irish
Republican Army's word, following an IRA pledge to let
international inspectors check its hidden arms dumps.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton seemed to capture the sense of
relief, saying, ``The wind is back in the sails of peace in
Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Peter Mandelson, the British secretary of state
for Northern Ireland, signed papers that will restore home rule on
Tuesday. The power-sharing Cabinet could meet as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northern Ireland  &UR; today &LR;  has a second chance to get it
right,'' said Mandelson, who suspended the local government in
February after 72 days, when unionists threatened to walk out
because the IRA had refused to begin disarming or to say its war
was over.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, the Ulster Unionist leader, seemed relieved when he
emerged from a closed-door meeting of his ruling party council at
the Waterfront Hall, a concert hall with an elaborate glass facade
that would have been folly in the Northern Ireland of old.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Trimble met with the press to declare a victory of
459 votes to 403, or 53.2 percent to 46.8 percent, he referred to
the tower cranes and other signs of prosperity around him as
evidence that it was imperative for his party to accept the IRA
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belfast is booming,'' Trimble said. As he spoke, behind him a
tour boat crammed with passengers tooled by on the Lagan River,
something that would have been unthinkable a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The business community voiced strong support of the compromise,
despite misgivings among many Protestant unionists who want to
maintain the union with Britain and who deeply distrust the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   While downplaying the split in his party, Trimble said the
power-sharing government would face collapse again unless the IRA
took further steps to disarm voluntarily sometime in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have stretched ourselves, remarkably in the
circumstances,'' Trimble said. ``But it is also obvious there is a
limit to how far we can stretch ourselves. We are operating in
reliance of promises made by the republican movement.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those promises, made by the IRA in a statement on May 6
that broke a stalemate, is that the IRA will eventually put its
weapons ``beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the IRA offered a confidence-building measure
in its promise to let the former Finnish president, Martti
Ahtisaari, and the African National Congress negotiator, Cyril
Ramaphosa, inspect some of its arms dumps. Most of those are in the
Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let there be absolutely no doubt that I and my colleagues will
hold the republicans to the promises they have made,'' Trimble
said. ``If there's any foot-dragging, if there's any delay, there
will be difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote Saturday was essentially a referendum on Trimble's
leadership. Had he lost it, his position as leader of the biggest
party in Northern Ireland would have been untenable, and the peace
process would have been thrown into another crisis.
</P>
<P>
   A palace coup led by Trimble's would-be successor, Jeffrey
Donaldson, narrowly failed. But those opposed to the Good Friday
Agreement of 1998, which mandates power sharing, equity between
Catholic nationalists and Protestant unionists, and reform of the
overwhelmingly Protestant police force, took solace from Saturday's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's comfort margin has narrowed considerably. Last
November, he received 58 percent of his party council's backing
when he proposed going into government with Sinn Fein before the
IRA began disarming. That support slipped by a percentage point in
March when he was challenged as party leader. It slipped a further
four points Saturday. The vote was close enough to require a
recount.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson and other hard-liners had insisted that the party
should not go back into government with Sinn Fein until the IRA
began disarming, and accused Trimble of being unprincipled.
Trimble's backers called him pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McGimpsey, a Trimble confidant and the soon-to-be
restored minister for culture, said Trimble's speech to delegates
had turned the tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``David spoke from his head, not his heart,'' said McGimpsey,
who speaks better Irish than many of the Sinn Fein officials who
consider respect for the ancient language proof of respect for
them. ``The heart says you can't trust these guys,'' he said,
referring to the IRA, ``but the head tells you you have to test
them at their word. That's what David asked us to do. Common sense
prevailed  &UR; today &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Another key to Saturday's vote was the decision of Trimble's
deputy, John Taylor, to back him. Taylor said he was going to vote
no until Mandelson assured him that Britain would retain the name
of the Royal Ulster Constabulary and would continue flying the
Union Jack over government buildings. Many unionists say that
eliminating such symbols of Britishness in Northern Ireland shows
disrespect for their identity.
</P>
<P>
   While Sinn Fein officials applauded Trimble's ability to get a
majority of his party to back him, they were furious when Trimble
suggested that Irish republicans ``aren't house-trained yet'' as
democrats. Republicans say such language, comparing them to
animals, proves that unionists are still not treating them as
equals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inclusivity, equality and mutual respect is the way forward,''
said Martin McGuinness, who was once the IRA's chief of staff, and
who next week will resume his job as the education minister in the
restored home rule government.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ian Paisley, the hard-line unionist leader, denounced
the vote as another example of Trimble's treachery.
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, the leader of the moderate nationalist Social
Democratic and Labor Party, who shared the Nobel Peace Prize with
Trimble in 1998, urged people to look beyond the narrow victory and
focus on returning local government to Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once,'' Hume pleaded, ``let's look at the positive.''
</P>
<P>
   As he left the Waterfront Hall, Alex McWilliams, one of those
who voted no, vowed that opponents of the Good Friday Agreement
would continue fighting until they toppled Trimble and the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning,'' said McWilliams, 45, from West
Belfast. ``We can't accept such treachery.''
</P>
<P>
   As McWilliams drove his car from the parking garage, workers at
the Waterfront Hall were preparing for Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's
performance of Verdi's ``Aida,'' whose main themes are divided
loyalties and treachery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7711 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKW-WNBA-PREVIEW-TEX     05-27 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN ANYBODY SURPASS COMETS, ON AND OFF THE COURT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Houston Comets are not the WNBA's version of Microsoft, but
they're close, though.
</P>
<P>
   In three seasons, the Comets have won 78 percent of their games.
They are the top draw in the WNBA. They have two-time league MVP
Cynthia Cooper. They have former 1996 Olympic darling Sheryl
Swoopes. They have three-time coach of the year Van Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   The baby-faced WNBA is not about to divide and conquer its Bill
Gates. Remember, the league has cashed in on the Comets' dominance,
generating name recognition and making celebrities out of
relatively obscure players such as Cooper and Tina Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   As the WNBA begins its fourth season tomorrow with a rematch of
last season's WNBA Finals when Houston plays New York at 2 p.m. (
KXAS/Channel 5). The Comets are trying to become the second
professional basketball team since the Boston Celtics to win four
consecutive titles.
</P>
<P>
   However, some say a new champion would be best for the league,
its players and the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I think it would be great to have a different
champion,'' Washington Mystics coach Nancy Darsch. ``Either way,
it's going to be full of exposure. People are dying to see if
Houston can do it again. It's going to be worth talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Through three seasons, the WNBA's topic of conversation has been
the Comets. For good reason. They have led the league in victories
all three seasons. They have three of the best players in the
league, and one of its most marketable in Swoopes. And they draw
large crowds _ through the first three seasons they are averaging
around 10,000 per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``How in the world could that be bad?'' Chancellor said. ``You
go to Miami and people are wearing Comets jerseys everywhere. We
have been on a team that every fan in America can identify with.
... It has been a team that you either love or hate.''
</P>
<P>
   For an infant league, the Comets' success has been a gift not
even NBA czar David Stern could have planned. They were an
attraction _ a happening _ without a cheesy in-your-face marketing
gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of positives to having a team that has been so
celebrated,'' WNBA president Val Ackerman said. ``I don't think the
NBA suffered for having the \RChicago\S Bulls win the title as many
times as they did. I don't think the NFL ever suffered by having
the Dallas Cowboys win so many games or the \RSan Francisco\S 49ers
winning the Super Bowl multiple times and so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   No, they didn't. Those leagues were established in their
respective cities and the United States. The WNBA is faced with the
challenge of spreading the wealth without damaging its most prized
possession.
</P>
<P>
   Adding teams is one way to do it, and the WNBA added four
increasing the league total to 16. Adding more playoff games is
another way, and this season eight teams will reach the postseason.
The top four teams in both the East and West make the playoffs in
best-of-three series.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, if the WNBA wants to prevent one team from
dominating the league like Tennessee and Connecticut in college
basketball, teams must beat Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are the teams that can play with them and compete with
them, can they beat them?'' Miami Sol coach Ron Rothstein said.
``Those are totally different questions. They set the bar and
somehow we need to get to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some teams are close. Los Angeles, with center Lisa Leslie and
forward DeLisha Milton, and Sacramento, with reigning MVP Yolanda
Griffith, are given the best chance at dethroning Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's bad when you have some dominance people can
recognize,'' Rothstein said. ``It's the age-old question, do you
want parity or someone that dominates? You can make a case on both
sides. Maybe it raises our level as players and coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't have any choice.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
