<SLUG> BC-CAR-COKE-ADVANCE0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Raining on his parade?
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Robby Gordon's chances for the history books may
be washed away today.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who is a regular in the Winston Cup Series, is trying to
become the third person to ever compete in the Indianapolis 500 and
Coca-Cola 600 on the same day, following in the footsteps of John
Andretti (1994) and Tony Stewart ('99).
</P>
<P>
   However, The Weather Channel is predicting a 60 percent chance
of rain at the 500, which starts at 11 a.m. today. The forecast for
the 6:15 p.m. race at Lowe's Motor Speedway is not much better,
with a 50 percent of showers.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Gordon's bid to do the same double-duty in 1997 was
ruined when the 500 was postponed until Monday because of inclement
weather.
</P>
<P>
   If the start of the Indy 500 is delayed today _ endangering
Gordon's participation in the 600 _ which race would he choose?
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I'm starting fourth in the Indianapolis 500 and at No. 42
(out of 43 cars) in the 600. Which one would you choose?'' a
grinning Gordon said. ``We have to be competitive in at least one
of the races.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon almost won at Indianapolis last year, leading the
historic open-wheel event before running out of gas with one lap
left. Gordon's return to Winston Cup this season has been a
struggle, with the No. 13 Ford at 36th in the circuit's point
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Doing the double-duty is more than just a publicity stunt,
Gordon claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big challenge for me,'' Gordon said. ``At Indy
qualifying (last week), that was my first time back in (an
open-wheel) car in seven months and I did so well. So why not
compete at Indy if you can compete at the level of winning?
</P>
<P>
   ``Winston Cup is definitely my future, but we're still learning
there. I don't think it makes a huge difference if we ran in the
600 or not. Now if we were in the top of points, we'd have to
reevaluate the situation. But right now, we are way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Stewart accomplish the feat last year, the toughest
part of the double-duty appears to be the physical abuse on a
driver's body. Stewart collapsed after the 600 and was treated for
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with some of the doctors that worked with Tony last
year,'' Gordon said. ``Tony didn't take his IV after Indy because
he said he was feeling so good. So he didn't get all of his fluids
and vitamins replenished. And then, the only thing he ate all day
was a Power Bar. You can't live all day off a Power Bar.''
</P>
<P>
   After running the past two years in open-wheel racing, Gordon is
always fighting for respect in the NASCAR garage area. He said
qualifying so high at Indy is not as easy as he made it look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe if Dale Earnhardt Jr. (wins the pole) here,
he'd be 33rd at Indianapolis,'' Gordon said. ``I'd love a couple
more of these NASCAR guys to go down there and play with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
