<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-INDY-BIZ0528-COX     05-27 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-BIZ0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auto racing promising investment for corporate sponsors
 &HT;    By Jim Dillon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON _ As Sarah Fisher races 200 mph around the Indianapolis
Motor Speedway during today's Indianapolis 500, another rookie to
this fabled auto race will be watching intently and wishing her
well.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo Francis is director of marketing for Mead Carbonless
Paper, a product division of Dayton-based Mead Corp. She is
investing thousands of Mead marketing dollars and an equally large
amount of faith this racing season in the 19-year-old driver from
Commercial Point, Ohio, just south of Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Mead Carbonless is an associate sponsor of Fisher this year. The
undisclosed amount Mead is paying Walker Racing, the owner of
Fisher's car, buys the paper company prominent space on the sleek
blue-and-white car and Fisher's matching helmet and uniform. It
also buys Mead access to Fisher, the car and the Walker Racing
team.
</P>
<P>
   But big expectations come with the sponsorship, perhaps more so
for Francis than Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The onus is on myself and my department to make sure we're
realizing the most benefit for our money,'' Francis said last week
during a break in her hectic pre-race schedule. ``This really is a
test year. If we can prove that this is a venue that is worthwhile
for Mead Carbonless, then we will continue (to support Fisher as an
Indy Racing League driver.)''
</P>
<P>
   Mead is one of hundreds of major corporations trying to cash in
on America's fascination with motor sports.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400,000 people are expected to attend this year's
Indianapolis 500. Millions more will be watching on television and
listening on radio.
</P>
<P>
   Some 550 miles to the southeast in Charlotte, N.C., thousands
more will watch another Mead-sponsored driver, Rusty Wallace,
compete in the 41st Coca-Cola 600 NASCAR race.
</P>
<P>
   As the audience for motor sports grows, so does the amount
corporations spend to get their logos in front of all those
eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   Auto racing will earn $1.35 billion in sponsorship revenue from
North American companies this year, up 10 percent from 1999,
according to IEG Inc., a Chicago company that tracks sponsor
spending. In fact, corporate spending on auto racing will easily
surpass spending on golf, its nearest competitor, and dwarf
corporate spending on all professional sports teams, Olympic teams
and competitions, and tennis this year, IEG said.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL, which is sanctioning the Indianapolis 500 and eight
other races around the country this year, will take in an estimated
$143 million this year, up 18 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   CART, the other major open-wheel racing sanctioning body in the
United States, will receive an estimated $492 million in corporate
sponsorship money this year, up 8.6 percent from 1999, IEG said.
Meanwhile, NASCAR, the sanctioning body of America's most popular
form of auto racing, will take in an estimated $558 million, up 9.1
percent from 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auto racing is the No. 1 spectator sport in America now,''
Francis said. ``And to the extent the leagues can identify who
makes up their audiences, it makes it very attractive for potential
sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, research shows that race fans are remarkably loyal
to the companies that sponsor their favorite race teams and
drivers, Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's just too soon to say whether Mead's major investment
in Fisher _ it's somewhere below $1 million _ will pay off the way
Francis hopes it will.
</P>
<P>
   Francis and other Mead officials certainly have confidence in
Fisher. The company has a major mill in Chillicothe, not far from
where Fisher grew up, and supported her winning racing efforts as
she progressed from go-karts to midgets and sprint cars to Indy
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a local girl who has some ties to the community and the
mill,'' Francis said. ``I felt strongly it was the right thing to
do and that we could get a lot out of it this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Mead probably would not have ventured into IRL racing with
another driver, Francis added.
</P>
<P>
   Francis said one of her primary objectives in sponsoring Fisher
is to generate business-to-business sales to other sponsors of the
IRL. ``The business-to-business opportunity has not proven itself
yet, but it's early,'' Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   It's unusual for a paper company to be an IRL sponsor because
the payoff is not as obvious as it would be for, say, an oil
company or automaker. ``But I don't think it's impossible to make
that work,'' Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   Another objective is to entertain customers at IRL races. Last
weekend, for example, several Mead customers and employees watched
from trackside as Fisher and 32 other drivers qualified for today's
big race. Francis watched the tension-filled event from home and
focused hard on Fisher's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the whole thing,'' Francis said. ``I absolutely
watched her position, what her speed was, what the other drivers
were doing. And I was wondering what my customers were thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher qualified at 220.237 mph and will start today's race on
the inside of Row 7. She is youngest driver and one of two women in
the race. The other woman is 53-year-old Janet Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 25 Mead customers and employees will be at the
track to watch the race and root for Fisher. Few, however, will be
watching Fisher more intently than Francis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thrill. She's a very bright girl with a lot of talent
who is going to go far,'' Francis said. ``I'm just pleased we can
help her out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
