<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7726 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SHOOTING-MAIN0528-COX     05-27 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-MAIN0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS AN UPDATED VERSION OF SHOOT-MAIN
 &HT;    Alleged teen shooter faces first degree murder charges
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Manacles and leg-chains clinking softly,
13-year-old Nathaniel Brazill showed no more emotion than a
sleepwalker as he faced Judge Jorge LaBarga Saturday morning at the
Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office on Gun Club Road.
</P>
<P>
   The courtoom was as dull and nondescript as the classroom at
Lake Worth Middle School where Brazill allegedly shot and killed
his teacher, Barry Grunow, about 19 hours earlier. The wispy
accused youth, whom classmates described as a practical joker, was
clad in khaki prison garb. He blinked calmly, silently during the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   He could be charged with first-degree murder. If convicted, he
could spend the rest of his life in prison. He is too young to face
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first day of school vacation, after the last day of
school. Yet scores of Lake Worth Middle School students flocked
back to their campus Saturday morning, to wonder over the murder of
a popular teacher, by a well-liked student. There were 51 incidents
of criminal behavior reported at the school in 1999, well above the
Palm Beach County average of 32 incidents per middle school,
county-wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``THANK YOU FOR SAVING MY LIFE MR. GRUNOW,'' read one tribute
put up on the schoolyard fence. A woman scraped with her fingers in
the dirt, to plant a bouquet of flowers at the edge of the
property.
</P>
<P>
   All of them talked among themselves, reliving the events of a
dry, hot Friday afternoon. When most students and teachers were
looking forward to summer and its lazy delights, Nathaniel Brazill
allegedly walked up to his teacher, Barry Grunow, and shot him once
with a tiny Raven pistol he took from the dresser drawer of a man
police described as a family friend last week. Grunow fell down,
coughing up blood from the gunshot. He died in minutes, as his
students watched in horror.
</P>
<P>
   By a melancholy coincidence, Grunow died 18 years to the day
after his father, Frederick E. Grunow of Monroe, Michigan, died of
cancer in Lake Park at the age of 55. The elder Grunow was a cable
splicer for Southern Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Interim Schools Superintendent Ben Marlin, at times angry, at
times near tears, on Saturday afternoon lay some of the blame on
the government's failure to take handguns out of the hands of young
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm saying is you lock them (guns) up,'' said Marlin, who
grew up hunting and handling guns in rural Pennsylvania. ``Handguns
are made to hurt people. There probably aren't a whole lot of other
things you do with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that gun had been locked up, we wouldn't be having this
conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning police allowed reporters to view the murder
scene. It was an ordinary, humdrum classroom with 39 desks, a bag
of Jelly-Bellies candy on the teacher's desk, a golden apple
paperweight, a carnation flower, a worn brown briefcase never to be
used by its owner again, and a poster that said ``WELCOME TO MR.
GRUNOW'S CLASSROOM.'' On the desks lay notebooks, hair brushes,
pens, old homework and a thumbed copy of ``The Klutz Strikes
Again.''
</P>
<P>
   At Grunow's modest home in Lake Worth, friends and relatives
came in twos and threes Saturday afternoon, attempting to console
his widow, Pam. Each arrival signaled the outbreak of a small storm
of fresh weeping. Sheriff's deputies controlled traffic on the
street, screening each new visitor carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Grunow was an avid gardener and native plant enthusiast. His
butterfly garden was flourishing in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of mad, sad people here this afternoon,'' said
a friend of the family who asked not to be identified. Grunow's
five-year-old son played innocently with friends. The slain
teacher's nine-month-old daughter, Lee-Ann, was cradled from arm to
arm, peaceful and content, unaware that she is now suddenly
fatherless.
</P>
<P>
   With Grunow's shooting, Palm Beach County unwillingly became
another talking-point in the nationwide debate over gun control.
The old end-of-term schoolyard rhyme, ``No more pencils, no more
books, no more teacher's crabby looks,'' took on a grim, humorless,
right-next-door reality. Grunow was shot in the face. Security
videocameras captured the impact of the slug as it crashed home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Brazill, you will be held in custody,'' Judge LaBarga told
the zombie-silent young defendant, as he ordered him sent back to
the secured, dorm-like Palm Beach Regional Juvenile Detention
Center on 45th Street where he spent Friday night. LaBarga also
told him to have no contact _ directly or indirectly _ with the
witnesses in this case.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to a grand jury to decide whether Brazill, a
promising student with an A-B report card, faces first-degree
murder charges. His case will be brought within the next three
weeks. Only then will it be determined whether he will be charged
as an adult, said state attorney's office spokesman Mike Edmondson.
</P>
<P>
   The youth will be back in court on June 6 at 9 a.m. Brazill's
mother stood up for him in court but would not comment as she left
the hearing, tears streaming down her cheeks, supported by a throng
of family members.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Rodgers, an assistant public defender, told a crowd of a
dozen reporters outside the Sheriff's Office on Gun Club Road that
he hopes Brazill will only be charged as a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's only 13 years old,'' Rodgers said.''He has no prior
criminal record and he's a good student. Facts are still coming
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmondson said investigators are considering whether to file
charges against the family friend whose gun police said was used in
the shooting. Police refused to name the man. Leaving a gun where a
child can get access to it can be a felony.
</P>
<P>
   As television cameras and satellite dishes converged here, and
as President Clinton telephoned Lake Worth Police Chief William
Smith to express his concern, the rest of Palm Beach County and the
wider world was still coming to grips with the murder. Amid the
expressions of grief and outrage there was also a certain air of
weariness and resignation, almost as if school violence were
becoming routine, as if the shot that killed Grunow were more echo
than bang.
</P>
<P>
   By noon Saturday most major networks were no longer mentioning
the Grunow murder as their lead news item. Gasoline prices and the
onset of the big Memorial Day weekend were edging the young teacher
off the national radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   But Lake Worth Middle School students had fresh, poignant
memories, both of the alleged murderer and his victim. They were
both well-liked, and appeared to have been on friendly terms with
each other. Indeed there is some evidence the youngster was looking
for another teacher, when he happened to run into Grunow.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Bradley, 13, said she had been warned about what was
about to happen to Grunow but she didn't realize it. After Brazill
had been sent home, he told one of her friends that he was ``going
to come back with a gun to get Mr. (Michael) Locke (the science
teacher) for suspending him,'' Bradley said. Locke had reported
Brazill to the principal earlier in the day for throwing water
balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went in one ear and out the other,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
