<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7732 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-INDY-ARCHDEACON05     05-27 1894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-ARCHDEACON0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dayton's Salt Walther: Racer in free fall
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEBANON, Ohio _ A corrections officer led him through the
corridors of the Warren County Jail to a small room that had
nothing but a table and a few chairs, told him to take a seat and
then turned and left, making sure the door locked behind him.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Salt Walther didn't know what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need a few minutes to get myself together,'' he said
with a quiet edginess. ``I'm a little worked up right now. I don't
care how strong you are, you sit in here and it messes you up.''
</P>
<P>
   He wore blue canvas deck shoes and a faded green jumpsuit with
short sleeves. He looked thinner and a lot older than he did in
those days of his 1970s stardom when he roared around race tracks
and life with a pedal-to-the-metal attitude. It made him _
according to a recent Dayton Dayton News poll _ one of this city's
100 most influential sports legends of the past century.
</P>
<P>
   It also nearly killed him.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat there with his arms uncovered, you could see the scars
and scaled skin that remain from his fiery 1973 crash at the
Indianapolis 500. To this day, it's considered the worst Brickyard
carnage that anyone has survived.
</P>
<P>
   His mangled right hand was still bent at odd angles and the left
_ where the fingers were burned down to nubs and mended paw-like by
some 30 operations _ was no longer hidden by the trademark black
leather glove he's always worn.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, he usually managed to take that old disaster and
dress it to the nines with nice threads, a few diamonds, some
outrageous talk and a big smile. All that is gone now.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the smile sometimes resurfaces, but it looks out of
kilter now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost parts of two teeth playing basketball here at the jail,''
he said. ``For the time being, I fixed 'em myself. Put 'em back in
with Super Glue.''
</P>
<P>
   He flashed a discolored smile that soon faded. While his teeth
are cemented in place, his knows his life is in free fall. It's
been that way for too much of the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old Walther has been in jail for more than two
months now. He's serving a six-month sentence after being convicted
of child endangering for returning his 5-year-old daughter to the
home of her mother, Cindy Heitman, who claimed Walther was under
the influence of drugs at the time. That charge and the claim by a
probation officer that Walther recently tested positive for
cocaine, has him awaiting a June hearing to see if he has violated
the terms of probation from a 1998 drug case in which he was
convicted of smuggling three prescription painkillers into jail in
the fingers of his black glove.
</P>
<P>
   If Walther is found to have violated parole, he could go to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm scared a little bit, but mostly, I'm disgusted the
way things have been distorted here,'' he said. ``Am I afraid of
going to prison? No. Do I want to go? My God, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of God, Walther carried a small book _ God's Words of
Life _ given to him by his current girlfriend, Jeannie Blevins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking for jailhouse religion,'' he explained, ``but
there are some things to think about in this book.''
</P>
<P>
   He also held a packet of photographs of his daughter and he used
his workable hand to spread them out on the table. As he did, his
eyes began to brim with tears: ``Look at her, she's beautiful. . .
. I love her more than anything in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing he had was an Internet printout someone had given
him in the morning Alcoholics Anonymous meeting he'd just attended
in the jail. It was a rundown of the seven times he ran the Indy
500 _ from his 1972 debut to the crash in 1973, his ninth-place
finish in 1976 and his final race three years later. There was also
mention of his two aborted comeback attempts in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon as I get back to my cell,'' he mumbled, ``I know they'll
take this Indy stuff away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is _ paperwork or not _ he couldn't be much farther
away from the fabled race than he is right now. As the 33 drivers
in the 84th running of the 500 are introduced to a cheering crowd
of some 400,000 people today at Indianapolis Motor Speedway,
Walther will sit in his jail cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miserable way to live,'' he said. ``There's so much
tension in here. Some guys have been on suicide watch.''
</P>
<P>
   As for watching the race, he shrugged. There are two televisions
in the facility, but he doesn't know what will be tuned in. ``And
you can't hear either of them,'' he said. You just get the picture
with closed captions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might think that is apropos for him.
</P>
<P>
   David ``Salt'' Walther, they said, was the guy who never
listened anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The son of George Walther _ the wealthy Dayton foundry executive
who died two years ago _ Salt lived a life of privilege and, many
say, perceived entitlement. He was the wild child of the Walther
clan and his early days were filled with parties, pretty girls, big
talk and bigger action _ most notably, high-stakes racing. He ran
unlimited hydroplanes and some stock-car events, but the thing that
struck the chord with his dad was his pilgrimage to Indy.
</P>
<P>
   George Walther was a car owner at Indy from 1955 to 1980. During
the years, Elmer George, the father of IMS president Tony George,
drove for him, as did Dick Simon, Ralph Liguori, George Snider,
Phil Krueger, Rocky Moran and Larry Dixon. His best known
partnership, though, was with his son.
</P>
<P>
   After equipment failure ended Salt's 1972 debut with no fanfare,
he returned in 1973 for a race that would forever change his life .
. . for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had the race begun when Salt found his McLaren
Offenhauser launched skyward, spewing 80 gallons of methanol fuel
as it sailed upside down into a fence along the main straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   The battered car turned into a runaway Roman candle, bursting
into flames and spinning wildly in the first turn. The wild melee
that followed claimed 11 cars _ and everyone thought _ one life.
</P>
<P>
   Walther _ his legs protruding from the mangled car's
undercarriage _ was trapped upside down in the flames for 6
minutes. Much of the car melted and Walther _ badly burned about 60
percent of his body and suffering broken ribs, knees and elbows _
was given a 5 percent chance to live. Twice, he was given last
rites.
</P>
<P>
   For years, it's been whispered by some at Indy that Walther's
car was tapped from behind by A. J. Foyt. When asked about it now,
Walther shrugged: ``I've never admitted it publicly to anyone. But
I think we all know where the tap came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was Foyt, he started to nod, then thought better of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foyt bad-mouthed me in his book,'' he finally said, ``but
still, to me, A.J. was the greatest. That incident, that was just
part of racing.''
</P>
<P>
   His words sounded hollow. Heitman said she has known Walther for
seven years and while they are bitterly split now _ she asked the
judge to give him the maximum sentence in the child endangering
case _ she admitted one thing:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go through something as horrific as Salt did, who
knows what it does to you. It took a toll on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Walther endured terrible pain, suffered various organ failures
and had his body reject one skin graft after another. He said he
has had 109 operations since the wreck and to this day, his melted
left hand bleeds when barely touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the worst of it,'' he said. ``The worst thing was
the morphine that followed. When I was in the hospital, they
drilled two holes in my chest and mainlined morphine to me for
almost six months. I got addicted and in the long run, the drugs
did a better job of killing me than Indy did.''
</P>
<P>
   From morphine, Walther developed an affinity to cocaine, pain
killers, even heroin. And with the drug use came more and more
outlandish stunts. During the years, his troubles included
everything from passing bad checks, side-swiping a line of exotic
automobiles outside of a California party, obtaining illegal
prescription drugs and child support problems to stealing a golf
cart from IMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem was that Salt was his dad's favorite
child,'' Heitman said. ``His dad got him out of every jam he was in
and Salt never took responsibility. Even with all the drug rehab
programs he was in, he got to know what to say and how to play the
game. Every time he tried to clean himself up, it'd only last three
or four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``With him, when he's OK, the highs are the greatest highs in
the world. But the lows are the worst. I was naive to what he was
into.''
</P>
<P>
   Walther has said he met Heitman while they both were in drug
rehab and he claimed to have done drugs with her lots of times.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Saturday if that was true, she paused, then said: ``I'm
not going to get in arguments with him. He wants to discredit me in
the worst way.''
</P>
<P>
   Walther claims much of his problem with Heitman is sour grapes
on her part. He said because he has a new girlfriend and is happy,
she wants to get back at him. Blevins, Walther's new companion, has
three grown children and grandchildren of her own. She talked the
other day of ``the spiritual side'' she saw in Walther. She praised
his relationship with his daughter and said she knows nothing of
any drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Heitman disagreed: ``She's probably still into giving him one
more chance . . . like everybody has. As for me, I've given up
hope. And it has to do with our daughter. She had been taught that
her dad was this knight in shining armor. That she was his little
princess. Then he comes back into her life and he messes up. And it
depresses her. She can't understand `Why can't Daddy be good?'''
</P>
<P>
   Walther said he was not using drugs when he returned his
daughter to Heitman. He said he is clean and sober now. The
positive drug test the parole officer cited ``was not handled
properly,'' Walther said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Bill Knapp is representing Walther in the probation
violation hearing and may handle an appeal on the child endangering
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Salt has a good case,'' he said. ``The thing is, he's
like Ron Peters (of Pete Rose gambling fame), another client I
represented. They get reputations and then they're on the bubble
all the time. It's like they're wearing a scarlet letter. People
figure the worst even when it not the case. Salt has shown some
real positives. He's talked to young kids about the evils of drugs
and alcohol and he wants to pursue that as soon as he gets out of
jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Walther said the young person he's most interested in is his
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I've made so many mistakes. I've done a lot of stupid
things, but one thing I would not do is hurt my little girl. I was
not endangering her. She is everything to me _ everything.''
</P>
<P>
   As he studied the pictures, his face _ which still shows faint
burn marks from the 1973 crash _ started to tighten and crinkle and
all of a sudden he was sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   From outside the room, the guard signaled it was time to go.
Walther gathered up his things and before heading out the door, he
held out a bent hand and tried, but failed, to hold onto his smile.
His teeth be cemented in, but his life was still in free fall.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the guard led him back to his cell.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
