<HEADER>
A7733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0528-COX     05-27 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore pushed to define agenda
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service Gov. George W. Bush was praised this
<TEXT>
week for laying out a broad issues agenda that has driven the
campaign debate and thrown Democratic rival Al Gore's campaign on
the defensive. Political analysts have criticized Vice President
Gore for doing little to define his candidacy during the past two
months.
<P>
   On Thursday night, Gore met with Democratic leaders from around
the country to reassure them about his campaign. The meeting seemed
inconceivable to many, who months ago were questioning Bush's
intellec and preparedness for the White House. ``Bush is setting
the agenda right now,'' said Democratic pollster Fred Yang. ``He's
making us react to him.''
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY ADVOCATE CRITICIZING BUSH AND GOP PARTY
</P>
<P>
   James Dobson, president of the family advocacy group, Focus on
the Family, this week criticized the Republican Party and its
likely presidential nominee Bush for sacrificing dedication to its
core principles in an effort to be all things to all people. Dobson
said Bush and the GOP are trying to appeal both to religious
conservatives and to the moderate wing of the party. ``Some people
believe the only way to win the White House is to build a big tent,
but if you stand for everything you stand for nothing,'' Dobson
said. ``(Bush) sounds a whole lot more conservative when he is
talking to conservatives and a whole lot more moderate when he is
talking to moderates.'' Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said ``Bush
is uniting all wings of the party in reaching out to independents
and Democrats who support his compassionate conservative agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   `WARM-UP' DEBATES A POSSIBILITY
</P>
<P>
   Bush is kicking around the possibility of doing a couple of
early debates with Al Gore, perhaps as soon as late summer,
according to the New York Daily News. Some close close aides
believe one or two summer debates make sense, the Daily News said.
The rationale: Early debates would demonstrate that Bush isn't
afraid to duke it out and would lower the stakes for the three fall
debates. ``The more he does, the better he gets,'' one Bush aide
was quoted as saying. ``And it reduces the pressure on him for
October.''
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN BACKS WORK-PERMIT PROGRAM
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, the presumptive presidential candidate for the
Reform Party said he supports in theory a work-permit program that
would give some kind of temporary legal status to migrant workers
who now cross the border illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not an idea I would throw out on principle,'' he said
recently during a speech at the Arizona convention of the Reform
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan reiterated his support to severe limits to legal
immigration, an end to illegal immigration, an end to campaign soft
money and an end to U.S. participation in free trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
