<DOCNO> NYT20000527.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7734 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     05-27 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CAN LAKERS GET BETTER NEXT SEASON?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While many Laker fans are busy converting Game 7
tickets into parade confetti, the truly fussy believers are casting
a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   An answer for Rasheed Wallace, Portland's lanky ``four'' man is
required, they say. As stunt doubles for Lakers' personnel king
Jerry West, these well-intentioned citizens continue exploring
options that could yield a superstar power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Please feel free to exhale.
</P>
<P>
   The answers for Wallace are Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
Oh, the war effort also receives a considerable boost when
defensive pressure is applied to the entry pass needed to provide
Wallace -- the Blazers' top threat for exorcism -- with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   In O'Neal and Bryant, the Lakers claim the league's premier
center and shooting guard. Don't be greedy, be thrilled. And
remember, the budget (in grim conspiracy with reality) will not
permit West to add Tim Duncan, Gary Payton and Grant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Those who fancy themselves astute followers of the Laker
``predicament'' believe the solution is free agent forward Glen
Rice. Don't re-sign him, they howl, and use the leftover loot as
bait for some available free-agent monster.
</P>
<P>
   Nice try. Even without Rice's current $7 million contract on the
books, the Lakers already are committed to a payroll of about $49
million for next season. That's $13 million more than the expected
salary cap for 2001 and just $6 million shy of the anticipated toll
both between generous teams and the dreaded luxury tax.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury tax penalty will be a million scoots for each million
spent in excess of that $55 million. West and sidekick Mitch
Kupchak may refuse to go on the record with a response to the
question of what day it is, but they love to be quoted on the
absolute impossibility of owner Jerry Buss paying such a tax.
</P>
<P>
   Armchair GMs have another trump card: sign-and-trade Rice. And
what will the Lakers get in return? Well, the name of former Phil
Jackson whipping boy Toni Kukoc (who finished the season in Philly)
continues to be published, although Kukoc also is a free agent. The
NBA says signing and swapping one free agent for another is
forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Signing and trading Rice for someone still under contract is
made more challenging by the high-profit agenda of his agent, David
Falk. To equal the salary they're shipping away in Rice, the Lakers
might have to acquire the salaries of a player or players another
team doesn't want.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone else on the Laker roster is locked into
trade-prohibitive, multi-year contracts.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so how DOES West improve the roster?
</P>
<P>
   His first resource is the 29th pick in the June 28 NBA Draft.
We'll wait for your chuckling to subside. Done? Before you swallow
your tongue, it should be noted that while this year's draft is a
bit light on obvious greatness, it does offer many skilled but
ridiculously inexperienced prospects.
</P>
<P>
   West, who has taken a few mighty, late first-round cuts and
missed, did connect with Elden Campbell (No. 27), Vlade Divac (26)
and A.C. Green (23). Let's not forget Nick Van Exel, whose
pre-draft misery tour made him available in Round 2 at 37.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is the deployment of an ``exception,'' a
lowball, salary-cap safety valve that could nearly triple the
bottom line for a developing player who's been making the league
minimum. An example of such a rascal is the inexplicably athletic
Washington Wizards free agent Jahidi White, who - at 6-foot-9, 290
pounds -- could use Wallace as a scarf.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, White probably will choose to work for one of the
many teams preparing to offer him far more than a Laker exception.
</P>
<P>
   West attempted to unleash a $2.25 million exception to snare
Charles Oakley last summer, but the Raptors power forward stayed
put, choosing a bigger paycheck and a vacation window that includes
May and early June.
</P>
<P>
   The last variables for Laker improvement are expanded roles for
rookies Devean George and point guard John Celestand. They satisfy
West's addiction to quickness and have the defensive potential to
be nastier than a turnpike men's room.
</P>
<P>
   And while cursing the leaner moments of today's Game 4, please
realize your underwear is older than O'Neal and Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Ship a Hoya to Clippers
</P>
<P>
   For a franchise that has turned surrender into a cottage
industry, it makes sense to hire a coach who wears a white towel on
his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Such a coach is ex-Georgetown University prime minister John
Thompson, whose candidacy was announced by the Clips last week.
Thompson, a childhood chum of Elgin Baylor, was interviewed
Tuesday, but is rumored to be a leading contender to become GM of
the New Jersey Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson wouldn't move West without market compensation,
something Baylor still has to convince his owner (ol'
What'shisname) to spit up.
</P>
<P>
   So while ignoring Thompson's failure to strike gold with the
1988 U.S. Olympic team and Georgetown's slide over the last decade
(he'd need an offensive coordinator in the NBA), let's explore why
Baylor would be interested in hiring the guy:
</P>
<P>
   Training camp would be a bit more severe than the virtual weanie
roast conducted by Chris Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson would demand a commitment to defense - a screaming
deficiency -- from his players.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson satisfies a presumed requirement for a high-profile''
coach, his profile seemingly higher than the collective philosophy
of Cheech &AMP; Chong.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson could provide a persuasive nature to free-agent
bidding; his relationships with former G'town heroes now starring
in the NBA earning immediate respect (in theory) from other
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Clipper Tyrone Nesby probably wouldn't be allowed to use the
word ``baby'' as a sentence-capper when addressing Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's looming presence might discourage Lamar Odom from
crying about the officiating; if it doesn't, Thompson still has
that towel.
</P>
<P>
   According to legend, the team owner hates the notion of paying
long money to short people. Alleged former candidate Mike Fratello
is shorter than the Clippers' attention span; Thompson is 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   With thumbs-up workouts for the Lakers and Clippers last week,
UCLA freshman Jason Kapono has generated considerable first-round
chatter. The ex-Artesia High forward is expected to dump his
collegiate eligibility this week by formally signing with agent Arn
Tellem. According to sources, Kapono was planning to be a Westwood
goner anyway, possibly exploring options in Europe if the NBA
didn't become an immediate reality. ... Schea Cotton (St. John
Bosco, Long Beach City College, Alabama) will join Fresno high
school hotshot DeShawn Stevenson for a dress rehearsal in front of
the Clippers on Tuesday. ... Widespread rumors that LSU sophomore
Stromile Swift is terrified of being chosen by the Clippers at No.
3 have been diluted by tentative (and reciprocal) plans for the
springy forward to visit the Clips after the Chicago pre-draft camp
(June 6-12). ... The latest Gary Payton trade rumor is an old one:
GP to Minnesota for Terrell Brandon and other expendable T-Wolves
who can make up any difference in salary. Eagerness by Sonics coach
Paul Westphal to remove an enormous distraction in Payton (who
happens to be the league's best player at his position) brings an
element of truth to the deal. But Brandon's agent, Bill Duffy (the
college roommate of T'wolves GM Kevin McHale), said talk of such a
trade is a bit cold right now. ... The trade winds keep blowin'
Dikembe Mutombo's name across internet pages, but his $14.5 million
salary (in the last year of his current deal), makes any deal
dicey. The Hawks, hungry for cap space next summer, may want to
acquire short contracts and a high draft pick in return. ... A
source close to Detroit free agent Grant Hill says constant gossip
about the superstar forward's move to Orlando is right on the
money. ... The given name of Portland's second-year guard is Gawen
Deangelo Wells. You can call him ``Bonzi.'' But if you're Chick
Hearn, you can call him ``Banzai.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
