<HEADLINE>
WNBA CAPSULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
 subheds:SCOUTING THE WESTERN CONFERENCE  agatea:Predicted order of
finish with last season's records:
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Houston Comets, 26-6, won WNBA title
</P>
<P>
   The league's best team still has the Big Three of Sheryl
Swoopes, Tina Thompson and Cynthia Cooper. Even without a
dominating point guard or consistent center, the Comets are the
favorite to win the title, again.
</P>
<P>
   2. Sacramento Monarchs, 19-13, reached playoffs
</P>
<P>
   With a backcourt of Ticha Penicheiro and Ruthie Bolton-Holifield
plus WNBA Player of the Year/Defensive Player of the Year Yolanda
Griffith, the Monarchs might have the best chance to knock off
Houston. They just need to stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   3. Los Angeles Sparks, 20-12, reached Western Conference Finals
</P>
<P>
   Center Lisa Leslie showed last season she can lead a team and
forward DeLisha Milton is a nice complement. But Los Angeles must
have some backcourt stability to win to challenge Houston or
Sacramento in a playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   4. Phoenix Mercury, 15-17
</P>
<P>
   Coach Cheryl Miller has a mini Big Three in Michele Timms,
Jennifer Gillom and Tonya Edwards, but this team is erratic and
isn't deep enough to challenge the top three teams in the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   5. Utah Starzz, 15-17
</P>
<P>
   Guard Jennifer Azzi has a broken shooting hand and is lost for
most of the season. This means frontcourt players Margo Dydek and
Natalie Williams will have to do most of the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   6. Minnesota Lynx, 15-17
</P>
<P>
   Coach Brian Agler remade much of his roster, but still has guard
Katie Smith and three solid rookies in Grace Daley, Betty Lennox
and Maylana Martin.
</P>
<P>
   7. Seattle Storm, expansion team
</P>
<P>
   When former Houston point guard Sonja Henning is one of your
best players, you're in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   8. Portland Fire, expansion team
</P>
<P>
   After former Sam Houston High School standout Lynn Pride and
guard Sophia Witherspoon, there isn't much here. ALL-WESTERN
CONFERENCE TEAM G: Ticha Penicheiro, Sacramento G: Cynthia Cooper,
Houston F: Tina Thompson, Houston C: Lisa Leslie, Los Angeles F:
Yolanda Griffith, Sacramento Best Rookie: Lynn Pride, Portland Best
Scorer: Cynthia Cooper, Houston Underrated: Natalie Williams, Utah
Overrated: Katie Smith, Minnesota Best Shooter: Jennifer Azzi, Utah
Best Coach: Van Chancellor, Houston Coach on the Hot Seat: Cheryl
Miller, Phoenix  &LR; subheds:SCOUTING THE EASTERN CONFERENCE
 &LR; agatea:Predicted order of finish with last season's records:
</P>
<P>
   1. Washington Mystics, 12-20
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Houston, the best talent is in D.C. Chamique
Holdsclaw, Nikki McCray, Vicky Bullett and rookie Tausha Mills are
as good as any foursome. If they don't reach the playoffs, coach
Nancy Darsch will be sending out resumes.
</P>
<P>
   2. New York Liberty, 18-14, reached WNBA Finals
</P>
<P>
   Guard Teresa Weatherspoon is still one of the best leaders in
the game and Crystal Robinson is one of the best shooters in
basketball. Rebecca Lobo suffered yet another knee injury and won't
return until midseason.
</P>
<P>
   3. Detroit Shock, 15-17, reached playoffs
</P>
<P>
   Guard Dominique Canty is not the leader nor shooter the recently
traded Jennifer Azzi was, but is a much more creative dribbler and
scorer. Wendy Palmer and Val Whiting are one of the better forward
tandems in the league.
</P>
<P>
   4. Charlotte Sting, 15-17, reached Eastern Conference Finals
</P>
<P>
   As Dawn Staley goes, so go the Sting. Problem is, she is often
injured. Andrea Stinson and Rhonda Mapp are solid, but Charlotte
needs Staley to go anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   5. Orlando Miracle, 15-17
</P>
<P>
   How coach Carolyn Peck got 15 victories out of an expansion team
is a mystery. Guard Nykesha Sales should be an All-Star for years
to come, but forward Carla McGhee must begin scoring underneath.
</P>
<P>
   6. Cleveland Rockers, 7-25
</P>
<P>
   Suffered a drop in its second season, largely because the league
improved and they didn't. Cleveland's has little frontcourt scoring
to help Michelle Edwards. Top draft pick, center Ann Wauters from
Belgium, is years away from being a force.
</P>
<P>
   7. Indiana Fever, expansion team
</P>
<P>
   Gordana Grubin is one of the league's best shooters, but
home-state favorite Stephanie McCarty isn't the answer for this
team's future. Maybe coach Anne Donovan can play.
</P>
<P>
   8. Miami Sol, expansion team
</P>
<P>
   The team has a great logo, but their best player, Australian
Sandy Brondello, is skipping the season to play in the Olympics.
Tim Hardaway could play; he's got nothing else to do. ALL-EASTERN
CONFERENCE TEAM G: Dawn Staley, Charlotte G: Teresa Weatherspoon,
New York F: Chamique Holdsclaw, Washington C: Nikki McCray,
Washington F: Vicky Bullett, Washington Best Rookie: Edwina Brown,
Detroit Best Scorer: Chamique Holdsclaw, Washington Underrated:
Vickie Johnson, New York Overrated: Rebecca Lobo, New York Best
Shooter: Crystal Robinson, New York Best Coach: Carolyn Peck,
Orlando Coach on the Hot Seat: Nancy Darsch, Washington
</P>
