<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ELLIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Cowboys' Greg Ellis determined to return for season opener 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ More than five months after breaking his left
leg in two places while chasing Philadelphia Eagles quarterback
Donovan McNabb out of bounds Dec. 12 at Texas Stadium, Cowboys
defensive end Greg Ellis is finding that he must deal as much with
the psychological as the physical part of his rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Team doctors and trainers agree Ellis is ahead of schedule, and
Ellis considers it a ``realistic goal'' to be ready for the
Cowboys' regular-season opener Sept. 3 against ... yes,
Philadelphia at Texas Stadium. However, there are still moments,
usually once a week, that he wonders if he will ever play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, there are days when I feel like, man,
football is probably over,'' said Ellis, who required a titanium
rod and three surgical screws inserted in his leg to assist in the
healing process.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the screws were removed Feb. 10. The rod and one screw
will remain in his leg for as long as he plays in the NFL, Ellis
has decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never having been hurt like this before, I still find it hard
sometimes to visualize running \Rin a game\S, leaning hard, coming
off a corner the way we do, especially a defensive end,'' Ellis
said. ``I stop and imagine, `What if this is it?' That \Rquestion\S
comes into my mind about once every week _ real strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever that does happen, Ellis often receives a psychological
lift from Cowboys assistant trainer Britt Brown, who reminds the
Cowboys' 1998 first-round draft pick: ``We have plenty of time.
You're doing great. Just keep working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis was particularly encouraged by a recent phone conversation
with San Francisco 49ers defensive tackle Bryant Young, who had a
Pro Bowl season in 1999 after coming back from similar leg injuries
against the New York Giants on Nov. 30, 1998. Young, four years
older than Ellis, was in the 49ers' starting lineup for the Sept.
12 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just talking to him made me feel blessed,'' said Ellis, who
had never met or spoken with Young before phoning him on Thursday.
``He was forced to go through more than I've gone through, really.
He spent 17 days in the hospital, including one day in intensive
care because of an infection that he got in his leg. I didn't have
any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young also told Ellis that he will have ``bad days and
top-of-the-world days,'' and to forget the former and cherish the
latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the biggest thing he told me was that he's now
feeling pretty much his normal self,'' Ellis said. ``While I know
everybody is different, that's really encouraging to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis is an extremely hard worker. Coach Dave Campo points to
``Greg's character'' as a prime reason to believe that the
third-year veteran will be ready for the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``People probably don't think big, strong athletes can
appreciate something as small as being able to run or plant or
cut,'' Ellis said. ``But I'm doing those things now ... and they're
large to me.''
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks, Ellis has been running all out, although he was
held out of group and team drills again last week during a
voluntary quarterback school at Valley Ranch. Trainers and coaches
actually have had to hold Ellis back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg is hardheaded, that's with everything,'' said teammate
Ebenezer Ekuban, who has been a close friend of Ellis since their
college days together at North Carolina. ``If it takes four seconds
to get to the quarterback, Greg thinks he can be there in two
\Rseconds\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so determined. He works out five hours a day, five days a
week. That's just Greg. We need him back, not only for his football
ability but for his leadership as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis remembers his ``low point'' being when he couldn't push a
rubber tube with his leg during the first part of rehabilitation
after surgery. This is someone who normally squats 400 to 450
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, Ellis has watched the video tape of that fateful
third-and-three play in the first quarter on Dec. 12 when McNabb
scrambled around right end for 3 yards. In pursuit, Alonzo Spellman
and Ellis collided just as the Eagles quarterback ducked out of
bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alonzo and I both tried to get the quarterback ... and ended
up getting each other,'' said Ellis, whose wife, Tangie, saw the
videotape replay for the first time two weeks ago when she happened
to walk into a room where Greg was watching it.
</P>
<P>
   What haunts him about that play is that it appears so routine,
so harmless, so out of bounds as the play ended up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always going to have the question in your mind: `Why
did it have to happen?' '' Ellis has asked himself countless times.
``Everybody was going hard to the ball, then \RMcNabb\S ran out of
bounds. If I only had bailed out ... ''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't bail out.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Ellis never does. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
