u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BO     05-27 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES RIP RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Wasdin was still walking out to the visiting
bullpen when he heard a voice from on high. It was Yankee Stadium
PA announcer Bob Sheppard, who only sounds like God, proclaiming
that Jason Grimsley, and not Orlando Hernandez, would be starting
for the Yankees Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to El Duque?'' Wasdin was still wondering after
the game, an 8-3 Yankees win that turned more on what happened to
Wasdin and the Sox bullpen than it did on what befell the Yankees'
Cuban ace.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who pitched the clinching game of the ALCS against
the Red Sox last October and had not allowed a run by Boston in
Yankee Stadium in two regular-season starts, felt some tightness in
his upper back while warming up and was a late scratch.
</P>
<P>
   But no El Duque did not translate into a reprieve for the Red
Sox, as the Yankees relied on accidental starter Grimsley and two
other relievers, Mike Stanton and Mariano Rivera, plus four home
runs, to put away the Sox before another packed house (55,671) in
the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The win drew the Yankees, who rebounded from a 4-1 loss Friday
night and a 3-0 deficit after three innings Saturday, back into a
first-place tie with the Red Sox, adding even more flavor to what
already promises to be an overheated rubber match Sunday night,
when Pedro Martinez and Roger Clemens reprise last October's
much-hyped duel.
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin, meanwhile, was on the mound in the sixth Saturday when
the Yankees broke a 3-3 tie with five runs. Jorge Posada gave the
Bombers their first lead when he opened the inning with a home run
off Wasdin, who was taken aback less by the way-back than by what
the Yankees put together with two outs and nobody on.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Bellinger, the ninth hitter in the Yankee order, singled
and stole second, Ricky Ledee walked, and Derek Jeter singled home
Bellinger to make it 5-3. Jimy Williams dipped into his bullpen
again for lefthander Tim Young _ Rheal Cormier already had answered
an unusually early call when he replaced starter Brian Rose in the
fifth _ and Young was schooled by Paul O'Neill, who hit a three-run
home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, Jeter's hit was big,'' Wasdin said. ``That's what
kept the inning alive. First batter hits a home run, and it's
shoot, we're down by a run, but with two outs and two men on, a
two-out clutch hit by Jeter is huge _ it led to the (O'Neill) home
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter had three singles, stole a base, and scored ahead of
O'Neill's home run in his first game back from the disabled list.
He clearly had a better time of it than Nomar Garciaparra, who also
came off the DL and had a single and walk in four plate
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get Bellinger or Ledee, it's a different story, and Jeter
never gets a chance,'' Wasdin said. ``But he hit a good pitch _ a
curveball _ and he did what he could with it. It didn't seem like
he missed a step. I didn't see either shortstop miss a step.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was inclined to fault his management of the bullpen. He
had Tim Wakefield warming up in the third when Rose gave up a run
after hitting Ledee with two outs and nobody on and was spared
further damage by Jeff Frye's diving play on Tino Martinez's smash
with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   But with the game even in the sixth, Wakefield was sitting when
Wasdin was summoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever,'' said Wakefield, who eventually pitched a mopup
eighth, ``but I don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who left Jeter stranded on third in the fifth when
Cormier entered to retire O'Neill, Bernie Williams, and Tino
Martinez in succession, said he could have called on Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gone to Wakefield, but I went to Wasdin,'' he
said. ``He's got a good arm, he's been pitching pretty good. If
there was any mistake there, it's mine, not his. I put him out
there. Blame me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox scored all of their runs in the third off Grimsley. John
Valentin homered to open the inning, Frye's double put Darren Lewis
in position to score on a wild pitch, and Trot Nixon's perfectly
executed suicide squeeze scored Frye to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley hit the next batter, Brian Daubach, in the left knee
with his next pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he tried to hit me at all,'' Daubach said.
``Look at how I had to get out of the way on my first at-bat. It
looks bad after a squeeze, I guess, but those guys always pitch me
in. They probably hit me more than anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he wasn't trying to. Besides, he's got something like a
10th-degree black belt. I didn't even look at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley may indeed have been blameless, just as Rose may have
been when he hit Ledee in the exact same spot with two outs and
nobody on in the bottom of the third. It just didn't look that way
in either case. Ledee said that just before he went to the plate,
he borrowed a bat from Wilson Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was no way I was going to use it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been pitching inside all game long,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee came around to score, Shane Spencer hit a bases-empty home
run in the fourth, and Rose was gone after Ledee hit his first
pitch of the fifth for a home run and Jeter followed with another
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``First-pitch changeup, and I think he was looking for it,''
Rose said. ``We had a lead and I was trying to keep it. But then
you go up and give up a first-pitch home run, that doesn't set you
off too well.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley gave way to Stanton after the fifth. The lefthander
gave up six hits in three innings, but the Sox couldn't capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a battle of the bullpens,'' Wasdin said, ``and they won
today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 2140EDT &QL; 
