<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITING WAS ON THE WALL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hub hubris. Boston baseball fans _ and there are a
lot of them in the Apple this weekend _ were full of themselves.
Members of the Nation were getting cocky about the Red Sox' sudden
dominance of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's win made it four straight (regular season) Red
Sox victories in Yankee Stadium and a 9-4 record there over two
years. When Boston bolted to a 3-0 lead Saturday, there was a
serious prospect of another Bronx sweep. With Pedro Martinez going
Sunday night, there was a good chance of the Sox leaving the Apple
with a three-game lead over the staggering world champs.
</P>
<P>
   The planets were in line. The Yanks were suddenly vulnerable.
Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez (a late scratch because of shoulder
pain) was the latest New Yorker to go down and Boston talk-show
callers were touting Carl Everett over Bernie Williams, Derek Lowe
over Mariano Rivera, and Tom Menino over Rudy Giuliani. The Yanks
were free-falling, just like the guy who leaped out of the upper
deck Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Sox fans, it all unraveled on this field where
so many bad things have happened over the years. In the 913th New
York meeting between these signature franchises, the Yanks
re-emerged as Bronx Bombers, hitting four homers in three innings
en route to an 8-3 victory. All the good feeling and confidence
vanished faster than a John Wasdin gopher ball.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter, who returned from the shelf the same day as his
half-brother, Nomar Garciaparra, had a greater impact on his team,
cracking three hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been playing well,'' said the Yankees shortstop.
``But hopefully we can start playing well and now we can focus on
Pedro for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the New Yorkers are a band on the run. Certainly since the
end of last season the Red Sox are improved and the Yankees have
softened. The perceived vulnerability of the champs has been a
universal theme in seamhead circles this spring and Sox watchers
are certain that this will be the year.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch can't throw to first and has hinted he might
retire. Chili Davis retired and Darryl Strawberry is in drug rehab.
Roger Clemens and David Cone have struggled and now El Duque is
hurting. The Yanks missed Jeter (4-8) more than the Sox missed
Garciaparra (8-5).
</P>
<P>
   Yankees hurler Mike Stanton, who got the win Saturday, said the
champs were inspired by the return of their leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take somebody out, obviously it's going to hurt,''
said the lefthander. ``It's hard to go out there every day and
cover for someone the caliber of Derek for a long period of time.
He brings excitement. With him in the stadium, even the fans act
different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Derek back is a huge shot for us, no doubt,'' said
veteran outfielder Paul O'Neill. ``He does a lot of things for this
team. This was a good day for us. We lost El Duque at the start,
then fell behind, but we battled back.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a decidedly good day for the Pinstripers. The 2000 Red
Sox are emerging as media darlings and sleeper favorites to end the
Yankee dynasty. Remember that it was the 1975 Sox who dethroned the
invincible, three-time defending champion Oakland A's in a
three-game playoff sweep. Saturday's game was the Sox' first
network TV appearance of the season, and Sunday night will be the
second. It was beginning to look like the Sox had the Yankees on
the run.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeter's return made things normal for the New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really gave us a lift, no question,'' said manager Joe
Torre. ``We've been inconsistent without him. His coming back gave
us a little sense of security. He lights it up. He could have felt
a great deal of responsibility and pressure, but he just loves to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be mentioned that this might have been a day when the
Red Sox' unflagging insistence of frontier justice came back to
hurt them. In the third inning, Jeff Frye (running) and Trot Nixon
(bunting) executed one of the prettiest suicide squeezes you will
ever see. The run made it 3-0, but Yankee pitcher Jason Grimsley
seemed offended and hit Brian Daubach on the right knee with the
next pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rose was cruising in the bottom of the third with a 3-0
lead and there were two outs and nobody aboard when Rose
retaliated, hitting Ricky Ledee in the same spot. Ledee wound up
scoring when Jeter and O'Neill followed with singles. Rose never
got an out in the fifth and turned a 3-3 game over to the bullpen.
Perhaps payback is not always the best revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro goes Sunday night. Against Roger. Winner takes first place
into Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this is a big series because it's against Boston,''
said Jeter. ``But we keep things in perspective. It's only May.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't try telling Sox fans it's only May. Not if Pedro wins
Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
