<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE EXODUS CONTINUTES; WILL THEY EVER LEARN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY 
c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ UCLA coach Steve Lavin got a call a few days
ago from one of his former players, Baron Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got gray hair yet, coach?'' Davis cracked.
</P>
<P>
   If only it were a laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   The list of early-entry candidates for the NBA draft is out, and
no one took a harder hit than Lavin, who could lose three players.
Unless it's Florida's Billy Donovan, who's losing two and has seen
a top three program take a big dive.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, which still would have Davis had he stayed in school, is
losing Jerome Moiso, JaRon Rush, and possibly Jason Kapono. None
has spent more than two years at school. Florida is losing its best
player, Mike Miller, after only two years and Donnell Harvey, a
rebounding small forward, after only one.
</P>
<P>
   College basketball has its faults, but in the ongoing exodus of
players to the perceived land of riches, it is only partly to
blame. The NBA and its union talk a lot about the situation and do
nothing, except offer these kids 3-5 years of guaranteed money.
What are they supposed to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back to square one now,'' Donovan said. ``I wish they'd
do something like baseball, where if you step on a campus, you're
there for a certain number of years. It's better for us. It's
better for the NBA. You look at Jonathan Bender, Corey Maggette.
They can't even get into a game. And after the first five picks
this year, who is going to do anything?''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said he had Miller talk to Michael Jordan, Magic
Johnson, other coaches, and general managers (including Indiana's
Donnie Walsh, who has drafted high schoolers in each of the last
two years). They all said the same thing: Stay in school, kid.
</P>
<P>
   But when Miller asked where he was likely to be drafted, they
all said the same thing: five to eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's he supposed to say then?'' Donovan said. ``I don't
think he's ready for an 82-game schedule. He keeps telling me about
the players who are in the draft and that he's better than most of
them. I tell him, `Don't look at those names.' You should be
looking at Mitch Richmond, Jalen Rose, Scottie Pippen. Those are
the guys you have play against. You've got no shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin was not surprised that Moiso left early. He's an ``old''
sophomore and speaks three languages. He has played overseas. Rush
had his troubles with the NCAA. Kapono? Who knows? He can shoot.
But both Rush and Kapono may not even be first-rounders. Moiso, who
Lavin thinks has the best upside of anyone in the draft, is a
likely lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Lavin said. ``One day, you hope the pendulum
swings back and education and a degree become priorities again. But
you can't daydream. I was doing that the other day. I was thinking,
`We'd still have Baron for one more year and the other players.' We
have two good recruits coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't do that, even if it does start to cross your
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, there have been countless horror stories from
Europe. Marty Conlon and Dominique Wilkins are among many who went
across the pond and came back with their wallets thinner and their
faith shaken. Those kind of stories may soon be history if a new
organization has its way. The just-announced American International
Players Association now gives players outside the NBA a central
body to handle disputes. ``It's long overdue,'' said player agent
Tom McLaughlin, whose chief European client, David Rivers, is the
CEO of the new organization. Seven other European players are on
the AIPA board, including Wendell Alexis, a Euro veteran, and Steve
Bucknall, who plays in England. ``We all know about the problems
they have,'' McLaughlin said. ``I know what it's like. I played
over there for three years.'' There's still much work to be done to
get everything aboveboard. There is no standard player contract.
Individual teams can grease palms with ``carrying charges,'' as
Sidney Greenstreet would say. The AIPA wants to standardize the
process overseas, go global, and get every team on board. That may
be easier said than done, given the wide disparity of teams
overseas. Still, the AIPA already has had discussions with FIBA,
the sport's international governing body. McLaughlin says the
response of the players has been ``tremendous.'' Many ex-players
have told him they wish there had been a similar body when they
played in Europe. ``Playing in Europe can be a great experience,''
McLaughlin said. ``This can make it that way for everyone.'' . . .
You think the Knicks would like Latrell Sprewell to be a more
reliable go-to guy against Indiana? Over a stretch of seven games,
including the first two of the Eastern Conference finals, Sprewell
was 3 of 24 from the field in the fourth quarter . . . If you've
seen the movie ``Frequency,'' then you know that actor Jim Caviezel
is a deadbolt lock for the lead in ``The John Stockton Story.'' If
you could replicate a young Ron Howard to play Jeff Hornacek, then
you'd be on to something . . . Who wins more games next season:
Hawks rejector Tom Izzo or Hawks coach Lon Kruger? . . . Meanwhile,
ex-Laker Byron Scott is still on the lists of the Grizzlies and
Pacers, although Larry Bird favors Rick Carlisle to succeed him in
Indiana. Look for Carlisle also to be courted by the Grizzlies.
Vancouver's new player boss is Billy Knight, who came over from
Indiana. And new Vancouver ``consultant'' Chuck Daly (read: money
for nothing) had Carlisle on his staff during the years he coached
in New Jersey (1992-94) . . . If Lenny Wilkens is unable to land an
NBA job, it will be the first time since 1985-86 that he has not
been a head coach in the league . . . The Celtics had Michigan
State's Morris Peterson in for a workout Friday as they start to
evaluate the players who could be around at No. 11. One
complicating factor is that many of the top draftees are
represented by SFX, the conglomerate that bought out David Falk and
Arn Tellem (although they still represent and browbeat, er,
negotiate). And SFX doesn't want two of its players competing
against each other in workouts, so that makes it harder on teams.
SFX already has Peterson, Miller, Moiso, Quentin Richardson, Darius
Miles, DeShawn Stevenson, Etan Thomas, Jamal Magliore, and Hanno
Mottola . . . So would the Celtics be wise to take a serious run at
free agent Adonal Foyle? ``I'm not sure how he would fit in with
the way Rick (Pitino) likes to coach,'' said former Warriors coach
P.J. Carlesimo. ``He still doesn't really know how to play
basketball. He still plays a lot like a kid from another country,
sort of programmed. I may be in the minority, but I still like the
kid. He does have a big upside. He's smart. He's willing to learn.
He is an NBA rebounder and shot-blocker. He has most of the
intangibles. I think he can be a very effective 10-year player in
the league.'' If Foyle is looking to relocate, he could do a lot
worse than Boston, which has a large and active Colgate alumni
association, including former Patriots player Ray Ilg and
investment mogul John Wilkins . . . Here's what Jordan should have
done in the first place: kept Darrell Walker and lived with him,
and the inevitable losses, for the next couple years and then gone
out and got a big-time coach. By that time, the Wizards might be
worth watching, let alone coaching. It's still not too late for
Jordan to do the obvious. Walker wants the work, comes relatively
cheap, and the Wizards won't go anywhere regardless of who coaches
them next season . . . Old friend Kevin Gamble is back in the news.
The ex-Celtic has been hired to coach the Glenwood High School boys
team outside his home of Springfield, Ill. But there seems to be a
minor snafu. Gamble lacks a college degree and teaching experience,
and that has resulted in some opposition to the move. An official
in the school district was quoted as saying a teacher is better
qualified to be a coach. Gamble said he applied to be the coach;
that was the job description. The school board will act on the
matter next month. Gamble says he is one semester shy of a college
degree and hopes to complete it at the University of Illinois at
Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley said many things last week following yet another
painful playoff exit. Riley said he will be back in Miami and so
will the bulk of his team, though no one believes him. He also took
Jamal Mashburn off the hook for passing up the potential
game-winning shot in Game 7. Mashburn, who finished hideously in
Games 6 and 7, passed to Clarence Weatherspoon, who, of course,
missed. ``The one thing that blows my mind a little bit is the
criticism that Jamal is getting on the last shot,'' Riley said. The
coach said he is to blame for not diagramming the proper spacing
and for urging Mashburn to try to take it to the basket. Mashburn
never got the chance. He was double-teamed. ``The double-team came
quick,'' said Riley. ``Guys didn't get to their spots. And now Mash
is being taken to task. That's my fault. That's not his fault. He
was expected to drive the ball and create a helping situation. The
fact that he wouldn't shoot the ball is b.s. _ absolute b.s. And
people are going to take him to task. It's a bitter way for a young
man who has come all the way for us to have that. I'm the one who
drew the play. I'm the one that gave him the instruction. I'm the
one who told the guys to put the ball on the floor and maybe we
might get one of those tough fouls.'' Riley also said that he would
add to what he has to get the club over the proverbial hump. He
wants Tim Hardaway back, if Hardaway regains his health. Isaiah
Rider? ``That will be on the list,'' he said. And himself? ``I want
to go through it again and again and again and again and again and
again and again,'' said Riley. ``I'm going through it again. I have
no second thoughts about it. I'm going through it again. I'm coming
back and I'm coming back and I'm coming back and I'm coming back''
OK, but what will you be coaching? ``I know what it takes to win
and I know the kind of people that you have to have,'' Riley said.
``I do think we need to step up in some areas. But we have a great,
great, great core and you don't want to mess with that, because you
can go back, back to ground-zero quick. The next time this team is
stripped down and rebuilt, I won't be coaching it. So, if that says
anything, then you know where I'm coming from. That would be
someone else's job. But, we will continue to try to augment the
solid players that we have and go from there. I think that's how
you do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 2148EDT &QL; 
