<HEADLINE>
LABOR PEACE STILL IN ONE PIECE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The clock is ticking again on labor peace in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Although the present bargaining agreement has three years
remaining, the final year can be voided by either side, a decision
due by Dec. 1. A void would make the 2003 season an uncapped year;
teams could pay as much as they want to players.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first free agency agreement was reached in 1994, a
deadline has approached twice, and extensions have been hammered
out.
</P>
<P>
   Now owners and the NFL Players Association face another
seven-month deadline, and the posturing has already begun. During
last week's owners meetings in Baltimore, Pittsburgh Steelers owner
Dan Rooney said the game needed a harder salary cap that would
count all signing bonuses the same year they are paid.
</P>
<P>
   Under the present system, such bonuses are spread over the life
of each contract, an accounting maneuver that allows only a portion
of the bonus to count in any one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cash over cap creates problems for some teams,'' Rooney
said.
</P>
<P>
   NFLPA executive director Gene Upshaw pointed out that signing
bonuses are the only guaranteed money in most NFL contracts, and
sources within the union are adamant that players will never
renegotiate what they consider the cornerstones of their labor
agreement: 1. signing bonuses are to be spread over the life of the
contract; 2. free agency is conferred after four years; 3. players
have the right to renegotiate; 4. the labor agreement ends with the
final year uncapped if the contract is not extended.
</P>
<P>
   The union maintains that the threat of the uncapped year has
kept labor peace for seven years. It has spurred two extensions and
is likely to force a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way the union would allow those things to change
would be if we had an entirely different executive board and none
of the present staff was left,'' a union source said last week.
``Telling the players we wanted to negotiate away one of those
cornerstones would be the quickest way for all of us to be ridden
out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   The union contends the system has worked well for both sides.
Players receive 64 percent of designated gross revenues and have a
limited form of free agency. Although there are few guaranteed
contracts, there are guaranteed signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   On the owners' side, franchises are skyrocketing in value, and
more teams are in playoff contention late into the season because,
unlike baseball and basketball, nearly every team makes enough to
compete in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can argue that the contract can be improved on both
sides, but the owners can't argue that it's been bad for
professional football,'' said NFLPA assistant executive director
Doug Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney wants a tighter rein on teams that have worked around the
cap (some say violated it) such as Dallas and San Francisco, but
Allen has a different view.
</P>
<P>
   Who has lost under the present system?
</P>
<P>
   No one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Could Bruce Armstrong find a home in San Francisco? Probably
not, but Armstrong doesn't have a contract, and the 49ers just lost
starter Dave Fiore to another knee injury. Fiore started at left
tackle last year and is expected back by the start of the season,
but the 49ers don't have an experienced backup, and frankly, Fiore
couldn't carry Armstrong's knee braces on his best day. Salary cap
problems would probably preclude the 49ers from signing Armstrong,
but they will clear some space after June 1 by dumping Gabe Wilkins
. . . The Rams and Titans have been negotiating a deal to train
together for several days this summer, most likely at the Rams'
camp at Western Illinois University. They also play an exhibition
game Aug. 14 in Tennessee . . . Bengals running back Corey Dillon
is facing a Thursday deadline if he doesn't accept the team's
five-year, $18.3 million offer (which he believes is insufficient
because it does not average $5 million a year). He could be stuck
with a one-year tender offer of $1.371 million, and if he refuses
to sign that by June 15, the Bengals could slash the offer to 110
percent of last year's $503,250 salary. Club owner Mike Brown has
promised he will do just that, despite the fact that Dillon has
rushed for more than 1,100 yards each of the past three seasons.
Last year, Dillon averaged 4.6 yards a carry, best in the AFC. But
if you take out two games against the Browns and one against the
49ers, he averaged only 3.9 yards a carry, with one touchdown.
Still, the guy can run, and if the Bengals don't pay him fairly,
he'll be running elsewhere in 2001 . . . The NFL lost another solid
guy when assistant scouting director John Wooten retired from the
Baltimore Ravens last week after 36 years in the league. Wooten was
one of the league's best guards for 10 years with the Browns and
Redskins before moving into personnel . . . Three months ago, the
agent for defensive end Simeon Rice told the Arizona Cardinals his
client would sit out the season if he wasn't traded because the
club had made Rice its franchise player. Rice told a Phoenix radio
station last week he would play ``under the right circumstances.''
Which means drop the franchise tag and give him a huge raise. Rice
finished second in the league in sacks last year with 16 1/2. Not
so long ago, it appeared the Cardinals would have one of the
strongest front fours in football, but tackle Mark Smith is an
unsigned restricted free agent, former Pro Bowl tackle Eric Swann
will likely be released for salary cap reasons, and young end Andre
Wadsworth is coming off a slow-healing knee injury. That makes
Rice's bargaining position stronger. However, with the franchise
label, his only option is to sit out . . . The Atlanta Falcons
became the first team to sign all of their draft picks when they
brought seventh-rounder Mareno Philyaw into the fold. Atlanta,
which did not have a first-round pick, signed second-round choice
Travis Claridge to a four-year deal worth $3.224 million last week
. . . Things seem to be going from bad to worse for former Boston
College tight end Mark Chmura. He has been charged with
third-degree sexual assault, and preliminary hearings begin Tuesday
in Waukesha, Wis. Chmura will likely be cut by the Packers this
week. The team did not invite him to its recent passing camp, which
began a day after he was formally charged, and the Packers drafted
Miami tight end Bubba Franks less than a week after Chmura's
arrest. In a recent poll, Wisconsin residents said the incident
changed their thinking about voting for state funds to renovate
Lambeau Field.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Browns head coach Chris Palmer couldn't be happier every time he
sees linebacker Rahim Abdullah. Abdullah was considered too small
to hold up against some of the league's blocking tight ends, but he
added nearly 30 pounds and is tipping the scales at 255 . . . For
four years, Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet waged an off-field
war after Johnson called Chrebet the ``team mascot'' in a book.
Chrebet caught 84 passes in 1996 and gained 1,083 yards in 1998 but
had a subpar season last year, missing five games with a broken
foot. Asked what he thought of Johnson defecting to Tampa, Chrebet
said diplomatically, ``We'll live.'' He later acknowledged that
losing a two-time Pro Bowl receiver can't help, but when asked how
he felt about Johnson's departure, he said, ``I don't care either
way.'' Sure he doesn't . . . According to an NFLPA salary survey,
only one of the top 10 wage earners reached the Super Bowl last
season, Tennessee quarterback Steve McNair. McNair was paid
$6,075,200. No surprise here, but six of the top 10 were
quarterbacks, including Drew Bledsoe, whose $6,398,000 was second
only to Dallas's Troy Aikman, who earned $6,667,300 . . . Although
Baltimore's Art Modell is on his way out as a team owner, he's not
going quietly. Modell has joined Buffalo Bills owner Ralph Wilson
in calling for an outside consultant to interview team executives
on how the league should be run. This is partly a backlash by angry
owners who have not forgotten the huge pay and severance package
commissioner Paul Tagliabue and a few of his associates landed
without the owners' knowledge. ``I don't want to strip the
commissioner of any power, and I'm not trying to dilute his
importance,'' Modell said. ``I want to support him, but there have
been some complaints because people feel they don't know what's
going on.'' The rift is clear, as even the complaints of outcast
Oakland Raiders owner Al Davis, a longtime opponent of the
commissioner's office, are being taken seriously. Davis raised
questions about an incentive compensation plan for Tagliabue and
other league executives that some owners now claim they never knew
existed. Yet Tagliabue appears to have consolidated his power by
not replacing departed league president Neil Austrian . . .
Although the spring meetings are generally a mop-up session,
several important issues were discussed, and one of the biggest was
expanding the playoffs to 14 teams after the new Houston franchise
is added in 2002 and the league shifts to eight four-team
divisions. A straw poll taken the first day found 23 owners in
favor of expanding the playoffs. Supporters would need only one
more vote to pass such a measure. There would be seven teams from
each conference, four division winners and three wild-card teams.
Among those favoring the expansion was Patriots owner Robert Kraft
. . . Modell believes Ray Lewis will not be convicted of murder but
is guilty of something the Ravens will no longer tolerate. ``You
have to understand the psyche of the players,'' Modell said. ``Some
of them come from broken homes. They're drooled on by all the
athletic directors in America. Then they major in Ballroom
(Dancing) 101, and suddenly the pros throw $8 million at them. It's
a hard thing to cope with. I can tell you we're not going to
exonerate Ray Lewis from being around the wrong people. That will
change.'' Modell's point was driven home when a video surfaced
showing Lewis sitting with a co-defendant watching prostitutes have
sex in a club in Mexico. Lewis was introduced on the video by rap
star Luther Campbell. Although player conduct has been a major
topic for months, the league's reforms have had little impact. Both
the Ravens and the Panthers have player-conduct programs, and both
teams have a player (or ex-player, in the case of Rae Carruth) on
trial for murder . . . People around the league claim Lewis might
have avoided charges had he been cooperative with the Atlanta
police in the early stages of the investigation. Instead, he was
belligerent and unresponsive . . . New Houston owner Bob McNair got
lucky when he outlasted representatives from Los Angeles to win the
league's 32d franchise, but he didn't get lucky two years ago when
he sold a yearling colt named Fusaichi Pegasus for $4 million. The
colt won the Kentucky Derby recently and finished second in the
Preakness. McNair now says he'd pay $30 million to buy him back.
But all is not lost. McNair owns the colt's 2-year-old sister and
turned down $5 million for her a week after the Derby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
