<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; tdt-z
b x BYLINE &LR;      05-27 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BYLINE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Shira Springer
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Globe Staff
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it came to the performance of Red Sox reliev- er
John Wasdin, there was no posi- tive way to spin the simple facts.
Not even manager Jimy Williams could find a creative way around
stating the obvious. His evaluation was appropriately terse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasdin got hit,'' said Williams, whose brevity was matched
only by the length of time it took Wasdin to hand New York the lead
in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The righthander threw just one pitch before he surrendered what
would prove the winning run. With the count 1-and-0 on Jorge
Posada, Wasdin hung a changeup. Posada drove the pitch into the
right-field stands for a solo homer. From then on, the Yankees
slugged their way to an 8-3 victory, abusing the Bos- ton bullpen
as they went.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the pitch I wanted, but bad location,'' said Wasdin,
who L took the loss. ``Basically today was just location that got
me. I was try- ing to go out there and keep us in the ballgame at
least by one run. You get two quick outs after (the home run) and
then you give up a hit and then a walk and then all of a sudden
Derek Jeter comes up and hits a curveball through the hole. That
quick it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon in which the New York bullpen went above and
beyond the call of duty as Jason Grimsley started in place of the
in- jured Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernan-H dez, the Boston bullpen
rapidly un- raveled. The Sox pitchers failed to lead their team
through the often troublesome middle innings.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Wasdin hurled the final pitch of his abysmal outing,
he had allowed New York four runs on three hits and a walk. As he
depart- ed, a sigh of relief no doubt sounded throughout Red Sox
Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just today, it was not my turn to go out there and succeed,''
said Wasdin, who also struggled in his last outing against Toronto
when he gave up two runs in two innings of work. ``It's a game.
Next time I  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  go out and pitch, I'll go out
there with the same intensity that I did today and try to do the
best I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two outings haven't been exactly what I wanted, but
the majority of the month has been good and positive. I'm not going
to panic after the last two outings L that haven't been what I
wanted them to be. I'll have another outing in a day or so or maybe
tomorrow. You just never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin was relieved by Tim L Young, who was making his first
Yankee Stadium appearance, and knuckleballer Tim Wakefield L worked
the ninth. Young served up a slider to Paul O'Neill in the sixth
that ended up in the right-field L stands, the three-run shot
provid- ing the final margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' said Rheal Cor-HL mier, who was the bright spot
with a solid inning in relief of starter Brian Rose. ``We know that
some- times you're not going to do the job. It's just one of those
things where today is over and you've just got to forget about it.
Tomorrow is a new day. We have a chance to take the series with
Pedro (Mar-H tinez) going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing you have to do as a reliever is turn the page. L
There's nothing we can do. It's L tough because nobody wants to L
come in and fail. But everybody goes through it. It's part of base-
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The relievers got off to a seem- ingly auspicious start when
Cor-H mier completed the fifth. He quick- ly disposed of O'Neill,
Bernie Wil- liams, and Tino Martinez, keeping the game tied at 3.
</P>
<P>
   The gem of Cormier's outing came with center fielder Williams at
the plate and Jeter on third. L Cormier caught Williams, a right-
handed batter, off guard with a L fastball that tailed inside, and
Wil- liams struck out looking. When L Martinez flied to left to end
the in- ning, Cormier had done his part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a big pitch at the right time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the rest of the relievers were unable to follow L
Cormier's example.
</P>
<P>
