<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLAZERS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS SAY THEY'RE STILL CONFIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. - They licked their wounds, ignored ``death's
door,'' called themselves knuckleheads, said they were upset but
not shaken.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen lamented that he had not been more aggressive,
Rasheed Wallace said his sprained ankle was fine, Arvydas Sabonis
pledged a long series, Steve Smith still maintained they should
have won.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers may have been troubled by their 93-91 loss to
the Lakers here in Game 3 at the Rose Garden, but they were going
to do everything to show their confidence was unfettered, save
writing ``We Still Believe!'' across their little headbands.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers lost the home-court advantage Friday they had just
won back in Los Angeles, and now find themselves down 2-1 in their
best-of-seven Western Conference finals against the Lakers and
knowing full well should they lose today's Game 4, all the odds get
ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Only six teams in NBA history have ever come back from a 3-1
deficit to capture a playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson, that budding sports psychologist,
said after Friday's victory that the Blazers know they'll be at
``death's door'' should they lose Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Although Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy dusted off the ol'
``must-win'' scenario for today's game, Pippen once again claimed
not to buy into any of Jackson's mental ploys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to put any pressure on ourselves,'' Pippen
said. ``We're not going into this game thinking our backs are
against the wall. We just have to go out and play well. We've been
in every game, we just have to complete games.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland played well in the first half on Friday but could never
shake the Lakers. Still, when it became the Blazers' turn to
overcome the deficit, they were still surprised the Lakers didn't
panic down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was a little surprised,'' Pippen said. ``We felt like
we had them right where we wanted. If we just keep it close, those
are games we should pull out. But we were knuckleheads. We made
knucklehead mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy said one of the reasons the Blazers faltered in the
second half was that Wallace - who at times has looked unstoppable
- sprained his ankle and was in foul trouble, so he wasn't as
aggressive or quick in doubling Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy said the ankle was still swollen and sore Saturday, but
expected Wallace to be able to play today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all right,'' said Wallace, in about his only comment
about his ankle on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise as a team, the Blazers said they were not feeling any
pressure and promised Friday's tough loss had not scratched their
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel down,'' Dunleavy said. ``That's the response that
you want as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understand the situation they're in. In no way is our
confidence diminished. We totally understand we're capable of
winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
