u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-BOS     05-27 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME STAND FOR KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was the kind of day when the two key New York
scorers split 60 points. It was the kind of day when New York
turned the ball over only seven times. It was the kind of day when
a 6-foot-2-inch New York guard blocked the shot of a 7-4 Indiana
center. It was even the kind of day when Chris Dudley stepped up to
the line when it was very much a game and swished _ SWISHED! _ two
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   And just forget the final margin. Saturday's 98-95 score is a
massive fraud, the product of a messy final minute that culminated
in an Austin Croshere 3-pointer with 4.7 seconds to go. This was a
New York game from the midpoint of the third period. The Knicks led
by 13 (81-68) with 6:34 left, and they led by 12 (91-79) with 2:18
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Playing without Patrick Ewing (acute tendinitis in his right
foot) and getting a scant five forgettable minutes from Marcus
Camby before he went out with a sprained medial capsule in his
right knee (the MRI was negative, and he is listed as ``day to
day''), the Knicks called upon a pair of superior midsized
ath-a-letes to save their season. Losing this game would have meant
cetain series death, but Latrell Sprewell (32 points) and Allan
Houston (28) demonstrated, in the short run, anyway, that
basketball is still a game of quickness, movement, and, oh yes,
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   It was all very reminscent of last year's series, which the
Knicks managed to win even after losing Ewing in Game 2. Dispensing
with the formality of tossing the ball into the low post, New York
tortured the Pacers with the individual artistry of Messrs.
Sprewell and Houston, whose mixed bag of drives, feints, pull-ups,
step-backs, and about 17 other things embarrassed Larry Bird's
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't have the guys to match up with their quickness,
and it is a problem,'' acknowledged the Indiana coach.
</P>
<P>
   If the problem isn't solved to some degree by Monday afternoon,
Bird &AMP; Co. will be heading back to Indianapolis with this series
tied.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers went as far as they could with Rik Smits doing a
first-half Kareem Abdul-Jabbar imitation. The 7-4 guy with the
velvet touch scored 12 of his team's first 17, 17 of its first 24,
and 21 of its first 32, combining face-up inside-out jumpers with
low-post jump hooks and even a driving 3-point play sprung from a
high pick-and-roll. But he was quieted in the second half (2 of 5
after a 10-of-15 first half) to finish with 25 points. Reggie
Miller (19 points) bubbled up every now and then. But no one else
did anything on offense, and that includes Jalen Rose (26 points),
who nailed down the postseason Golden Trashcan Award with a bizarre
22-point fourth quarter that you really had to see to not believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, they were letting him score,'' dismissed Bird, and he was
right.
</P>
<P>
   An early Knick rumble put New York ahead by 9 points (22-13),
but the Pacers rode that out with minimal diffculty and took a
42-41 halftime lead into the locker room. ``We talked about being
24 minutes away from putting themselves in a good position to win
the series,'' Bird explained.
</P>
<P>
   As Bird likes to say, ``Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   New York came out of the locker room with the burning belly. At
47-45, Indiana, Dudley, whose previous 2000 playoff workload had
consisted of 10 minutes spaced out over three games, went to the
free throw line, his personal chamber of horrors. Not this time.
The affable Yalie nailed them both.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about omens. Before the period was over, Sprewell would
have 23 of his 32 and Houston would have 20 of his 28 and the
Knicks would be up, 71-64. The Pacers would not come closer than 5
again until Croshere's too-little-too-late bomb.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone doubted that it was destined to be a New York day,
consider the sight of 6-2 Charlie Ward flying at Smits and blocking
his shot cleanly from the side with 58.5 seconds left in the third
period and his team up, 69-62. ``I knew he could jump,'' said an
admiring Houston, ``but Charlie looked like he was jumping over a
car.''
</P>
<P>
   Had there been a car available, Bird might have run over a few
members of his team. ``We were turning the ball over (17 times, for
18 New York points) and there were too many guys not ready to
play,'' Bird said. ``Every time I put one of those guys back in to
redeem himself, he'd play worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, now. Did anyone think there was any possibility of a
sweep?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
