<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO NERVES ON EVE OF BIG DATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He has become the Main Event whenever he pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But when it is Pedro Martinez against the New York Yankees, it
takes on the aura of an uncommon celestial occurrence. People mark
their calendars so as not to miss a solar eclipse or a streaking
comet. They do the same when it's Pedro and the Pinstripers, and
even more so Sunday night, when the Yankee pitcher will be Roger
Clemens in Pedro-Rocket II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to me,'' Martinez said Saturday morning, sniffing at the
suggestion that this will be special. ``I'm not a very exciting
person. To me, it's just one more game.''
</P>
<P>
   No one should buy that for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Martinez pitched here, Sept. 10, 1999, he whiffed
more Yankees, 17, than any pitcher who had ever faced the Bombers.
He allowed just one hit, a second-inning home run by Chili Davis.
He set down the last 22 Yankees, the last five on strikes, and
finished the game by whiffing Chuck Knoblauch on a 96-mile-an-hour
fastball. By the end of the night, Yankee fans weaned on their
hatred of the Sox were on their feet, cheering for Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's gone,'' said Martinez, who claims never to have watched
the game on video. ``That's past. Everything I did is gone. What
counts is what I'm doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's past, but it burns a place in the memory of anyone who was
there. Jimy Williams was a coach with the Atlanta Braves when they
had their Cy Young trio of Greg Maddux, John Smoltz, and Tom
Glavine. As a player, he was in St. Louis when the Cardinals had
Hall of Famer Bob Gibson, and he batted against Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever seen a guy pitch a game like that
against a lineup like that,'' Williams said that September night.
``How many guys did he strike out? Seventeen? The kind of hitters
they have over there?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a guy pitch like that, one game, throughout
the whole game. Maybe you guys have, but I haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Pedro-Rocket I, in Game 3 of the ALCS, a 13-1
thrashing of the Yankees that ranks as their worst loss in the
postseason. Martinez pitched seven scoreless innings, allowing two
hits while whiffing a dozen. His two-game line score against the
Yankees: 16 IP, 0 R, 3 H, 29 K's.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, meanwhile, was driven from the mound two batters into
the third inning after a yield of five runs before a crowd gone mad
at the scent of blood. Yankees owner George Steinbrenner was so
distraught afterward that he came into the visitors' clubhouse at
Fenway Park and told his team, according to someone who was there:
``This can happen once, but it can't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That game was so blown out of proportion,'' Mike Stanley said
Saturday. ``The tale-of-the-tape picture, the heavyweight title,
clash of the titans hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were amused at all the hype, but we knew it was just a game
we had to win. We were already down two games in that series.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez insists this isn't personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger is just one more pitcher out there,'' he said. ``I have
to pitch a game against whoever. I don't care if it's Roger or
David Cone. Roger is a great pitcher, one of the best baseball has
ever had. But I've got to go out there and pitch. I've got to worry
about Bernie (Williams) and (Derek) Jeter, the guys hitting against
me. My teammates will take care of Roger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what. I wish it was Toronto. That's a game I
lost. I'd like the chance to take that back. I hate losing. Right
now, the teams I want are the teams that beat me before. See if I
can even up things.''
</P>
<P>
   If a dread of Martinez has been planted in the Yankees' heads,
said Stanley, they will not be alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it matters what team we're facing, they all have
a lot of respect for him,'' Stanley said. ``Robbie Alomar (of the
Indians) came down to first base the day before Pedro pitched and
said _ and I know this is a cliche _ `We'd better get as many as we
can today, because we're not going to get many against Pedro
tomorrow.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Harold Baines, who has been in baseball over 20 years, told me
he hasn't seen anybody better than this guy. A future Hall of
Famer, and he said Pedro is the best he's ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have had crowds of 54,000-plus in each of the first
two games of this series. Another full house is guaranteed Sunday
night. The game will be televised nationally by ESPN. It's the
rubber game of a three-game match between teams tied for first
place. And it's Pedro vs. Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a slight toward any of our other pitchers,''
Stanley said, ``but the energy you feel from the crowd when Pedro
pitches is unlike any other game. That in itself gets you pumped
up. I don't come to the ballpark more pumped up because Pedro's
pitching. But you feed off the energy of that crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Martinez said, he noticed the way he won over the Yankees
fans the last time he was here.
</P>
<P>
   ``That taught me one thing,'' he said. ``They understand
baseball. They appreciate a good performance. That's something I
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was like it was in Baltimore a couple of weeks ago. And
they understand baseball in Boston _ they probably know too much
about baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   They know what is happening at 8:05 Sunday night. They've got it
marked on their calendars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
