<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BULLPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BULLPEN TAGGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it came to the performance of Red Sox reliever
John Wasdin, there was no positive way to spin the simple facts.
Not even manager Jimy Williams could find a creative way around
stating the obvious. His evaluation was appropriately terse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasdin got hit,'' said Williams, whose brevity was matched
only by the length of time it took Wasdin to hand New York the lead
in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The righthander threw just one pitch before he surrendered what
would prove the winning run. With the count 1-and-0 on Jorge
Posada, Wasdin hung a changeup. Posada drove the pitch into the
right-field stands for a solo homer. From then on, the Yankees
slugged their way to an 8-3 victory Saturday, abusing the Boston
bullpen as they went.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the pitch I wanted, but bad location,'' said Wasdin,
who took the loss. ``Basically today was just location that got me.
I was trying to go out there and keep us in the ballgame at least
by one run. You get two quick outs after (the home run) and then
you give up a hit and then a walk and then all of a sudden Derek
Jeter comes up and hits a curveball through the hole. That quick it
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon in which the New York bullpen went above and
beyond the call of duty as Jason Grimsley started in place of the
injured Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, the Boston bullpen rapidly
unraveled. The Sox pitchers failed to lead their team through the
often troublesome middle innings.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Wasdin hurled the final pitch of his abysmal outing,
he had allowed New York four runs on three hits and a walk. As he
departed, a sigh of relief no doubt sounded throughout Red Sox
Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just today, it was not my turn to go out there and succeed,''
said Wasdin, who also struggled in his last outing against Toronto
when he gave up two runs in two innings of work. ``It's a game.
Next time I go out and pitch, I'll go out there with the same
intensity that I did today and try to do the best I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two outings haven't been exactly what I wanted, but
the majority of the month has been good and positive. I'm not going
to panic after the last two outings that haven't been what I wanted
them to be. I'll have another outing in a day or so or maybe
tomorrow. You just never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin was relieved by Tim Young, who was making his first
Yankee Stadium appearance, and knuckleballer Tim Wakefield worked
the ninth. Young served up a slider to Paul O'Neill in the sixth
that ended up in the right-field stands, the three-run shot
providing the final margin of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' said Rheal Cormier, who was the bright spot with
a solid inning in relief of starter Brian Rose. ``We know that
sometimes you're not going to do the job. It's just one of those
things where today is over and you've just got to forget about it.
Tomorrow is a new day. We have a chance to take the series with
Pedro (Martinez) going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing you have to do as a reliever is turn the page.
There's nothing we can do. It's tough because nobody wants to come
in and fail. But everybody goes through it. It's part of
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The relievers got off to a seemingly auspicious start when
Cormier completed the fifth. He quickly disposed of O'Neill, Bernie
Williams, and Tino Martinez, keeping the game tied at 3.
</P>
<P>
   The gem of Cormier's outing came with center fielder Williams at
the plate and Jeter on third. Cormier caught Williams, a
righthanded batter, off guard with a fastball that tailed inside,
and Williams struck out looking. When Martinez flied to left to end
the inning, Cormier had done his part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a big pitch at the right time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the rest of the relievers were unable to follow
Cormier's example.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
