<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTTIE'S TIME TO TAKE CHARGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. - After coaching him for nine years in Chicago,
Phil Jackson can read Scottie Pippen's body language the way an
actuary reads statistical tables. And Jackson sees Pippen
reasserting himself in a big way today when the Lakers and Portland
Trail Blazers tip off Game 4 of the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's 21 points led the Blazers to their victory in Game 2,
so Jackson countered by assigning Kobe Bryant to guard him. The
move worked, as Pippen managed just four points through the first
three quarters of Game 3 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But with Bryant in foul trouble, Pippen hit 3 of 4 shots in the
fourth quarter, for eight points in eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he ended that game makes me think that he's going to
want to start (today's) game the way that he ended (Friday's). He
came right at us,'' Jackson said. ``Of course, Kobe had five fouls
and he took the offense right to the front of our hoop basically. I
think that's what we're going to have to be prepared for, is that
Scottie said to himself, `I gotta take advantage of what I had and
create the aggressiveness for this team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Lakers have regained home-court advantage, Jackson
said the pressure is squarely back on the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to say that it's such a critical game for them,''
he said. ``It's critical for us too, because we want to establish a
momentum and continue with it. But for them to only have one game
left before you're eliminated says something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmering: Rick Fox was still a little heated over his
fourth-quarter scuffle with Pippen, touched off when Pippen zinged
the ball into Fox's back. Fox said Pippen had been showing
disrespect to the Lakers with his actions and words all night, and
it was time to send a message back: that the Lakers would not be
pushed around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's first and foremost,'' Fox said. ``Anytime you
find yourself in a war, in confrontation, you don't back down. You
stand up and defend yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bakery fresh: As usual, Shaquille O'Neal had a unique take on
the Lakers' fortunes, specifically their ability to come back after
the Blazers raced to a 10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that starts off hot always must go cold. You put a
croissant in a microwave and take it out, it's hot, aaaah,'' he
said, gesturing as if he'd burned his hand, ``but eventually it
will cool down. And I think they cooled down a lot. And we just
withstood all their pushes and we just kept playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
