<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MEMORIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS LOOKS SOLID AS A ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ Rain is the usual culprit when PGA Tour events
are shortened to 54 holes, but you can cite Tiger Woods's magical
talents for putting an early halt to this week's Memorial
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   He continued his assault on a softened Muirfield Village Golf
Club course Saturday with a 7-under-par 65 that featured an
outgoing 30 and a couple of second shots into par-5s that were
mistaken for NASA launches. Under a blanket of clouds that spit
light rain but not the downpours that had been predicted, Woods
finished at 17-under 199, which is six shots clear of Steve Lowery
(66), who thus draws a front-row seat to watch the world's greatest
player in Sunday's final round.
</P>
<P>
   It's an 18-hole trip that promises as thrilling a plot as an
episode of ``My Mother The Car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, guys, it's over,'' said a disenchanted Ernie Els, who
started the day in third place, just three behind Woods. But Els
and Harrison Frazar, who started just one behind Woods, looked like
a couple of guys out for a weekend round at the local muni when
compared with the third member of their group.
</P>
<P>
   Els (72_209) hit the trees once and found water twice to make
bogeys on three of four par-5s and lost seven shots in seven holes
to Woods. Frazar, meanwhile, made just one birdie and stumbled home
in 43 to shoot 78_213. No one would have blamed them had they asked
Woods if he wanted to play through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played with him in a long time,'' said Frazar, who
was on the express elevator from solo second to a tie for 23d,
``and now I know why.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome,'' said Els, who fell into a tie for seventh. ``I
mean, he missed a couple of putts, or he could have shot 61
easily.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Frazar is a winless lad still cutting his teeth on the PGA
Tour, but Els is the world's eighth-ranked player and a man quite
capable of hitting the finest golf shots on the face of this earth.
It's just that Woods seems to be from another golf world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say I could hit shots like that . . .,'' said Els,
who shook his head rather than complete the thought. He was
referring to Woods's second shot into the 563-yard par-5 seventh, a
3-iron from 230 yards _ off a downslope, no less. The ball came to
rest 18-20 feet from the pin, and when Woods curled in the putt for
eagle, he was 5 under on his round, 15 under for the tournament,
and had officially mailed exit notices to everyone else in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   When a 7-iron to the 182-yard eighth tracked the pin all the way
and left Woods a tap-in to get to 6 under on his round, thoughts of
59 must have entered his head.
</P>
<P>
   Woods shook his head. His only thought, he said, ``was to put
myself in position to make birdie (on the next hole).'' Which he
did, only the 10-footer from above the pin rolled over the left
edge, making him settle for a 30.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, there was no shortage of candidates stepping up
to replace Frazar and Els as so-called challengers to Woods. They
ranged from Lowery, whose only Tour victory came in 1994; to Justin
Leonard, who aced the eighth hole and was trying to enjoy his round
of 66_206 and not ponder being seven shots out of the lead; to
lefthander Mike Weir (68_207), who was 6 under through 13 holes
when he got a migraine that led to bogeys on 16 and 18 and a finish
of 9 under.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Steve Flesch, who arguably shot the most overlooked
64 in recent history (though it lifted him into a tie for fifth at
8 under), these players were all reminded of the seemingly
impossible task at hand: Woods has won 15 of 17 times he has owned
the 54-hole lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as players appreciate what he's doing,'' said Leonard, who
has been battling the worst slump of his six-year PGA Tour career.
``The amazement has gone away. You almost come to expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery almost went unnoticed, despite making his seventh birdie
of the day on the difficult 18th hole to pull into second. Woods
was still on the course, and not much of an audience awaited the
soft-spoken man from Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to get to the point where you feel like you're just
trying to stay out of the way of him,'' said Lowery, who has missed
six cuts in 15 starts and wouldn't seem to be much of a threat to
Woods, who added to his legend with his second shot into the par-5
11th.
</P>
<P>
   It was a 5-iron from about 215 yards and found air space
directly over the pin, coming to rest 18 feet away. His bid for
eagle lipped out, but he tapped in for birdie to go 7 under on his
round.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because he would birdie just one of the final seven
holes, perhaps because he would make just his second bogey of the
tournament at the 18th, or perhaps because he hasn't won any of the
last four events in which he's played, Woods refused to go along
with the sentiment expressed by Els and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's over,'' said Woods, who already has won
three of his nine PGA Tour starts this year and finished second in
three others.
</P>
<P>
   He stood alone in that thought, just as he stands alone when
golf talent is measured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
