<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' SHAW BENCHED BY NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. - Brian Shaw says he was just trying to
congratulate his teammates. The NBA says Shaw was moving toward a
fight in progress.
</P>
<P>
   There is a major difference in interpretations surrounding
Shaw's decision to leave the Lakers bench Friday night, just as
teammate Rick Fox and Portland's Scottie Pippen began a shoving
match.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the NBA's strict interpretation of the rules - which
prohibit leaving the bench during a fight - that led to the league
suspending Shaw from today's Game 4 of the Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which cannot be appealed, leaves the Lakers with
just 10 players available. And it left Shaw angry and confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the court because there was a timeout called. I
didn't run off the bench to what was going on with Rick and
Scottie,'' said Shaw, who was also fined $2,500. ``I was already on
the court. And then I did take a couple of steps over in that
direction to see what was going on ....
</P>
<P>
   ``The money isn't the thing. But getting suspended for a game in
the Western Conference finals and my reputation as a player in the
league .... I've never caused any trouble, never done anything. I
didn't go over there in an aggressive manner. And now I'm getting
penalized for being on the court already when there was a timeout
called. It doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA did not issue an explanation. But the decision was
consistent with the league's zero-tolerance policy on fighting, and
its desire to avoid the kind of bench-clearing brawls that make pro
baseball look like pro wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA rulebook states, ``During an altercation, all players
not participating in the game must remain in the vicinity of their
bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen and Fox scuffled briefly with 7:23 left in the game,
after Pippen threw the ball at Fox's back near the scorer's table.
Shaw first walked onto the court, then toward the fracas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked on the floor to congratulate our guys as they were
coming off the floor. And then that whole thing broke out with
them, so I walked... over toward where it was going on, and we were
standing there, talking, and that was it. So I didn't think I did
anything wrong,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   No other players were suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry (West) has voiced his dissatisfaction, and so have I,''
general manager Mitch Kupchak said of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak noted that players are allowed to walk on the court
during a timeout, ``but the issue here seems to be making a move
towards the altercation at the scorer's table .... We know Brian,
and we know he would never get involved in anything like that.
Maybe there was a curiosity factor or just an impulse to make a
step, but in the NBA's opinion it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw played only three minutes Friday, but he has been one of
the Lakers' best scorers off the bench and had averaged 21.5
minutes in the first two games of the series. His absence, combined
with an injury to rookie Devean George, leaves the Lakers without
another big guard to back up Kobe Bryant and Ron Harper. That will
mean more minutes for Derek Fisher, but at 6-foot-1, he could be
overmatched when the Blazers use a big-guard tandem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big loss for us,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``I'm
unhappy about it .... He's allowed to be on the floor because it's
a timeout .... The league has to be very cautious about what's gone
on in the past. And whether it's an overreaction or not, I don't
know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-27-00 2250EDT &QL; 
