<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, May 28. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
COYOTES-GRETZKY _ Just minutes after developer Steve Ellman
announced that hockey superstar Wayne Gretzky would join the new
Phoenix Coyotes ownership team, the phone started ringing with $1
million offers. Nearly a dozen investors, local and out of state,
called late Friday night and expressed interest in a possible
financial share in the franchise, Ellman told The Arizona Republic.
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``S'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ATHLETE-EXECUTIVE _ The superstar _ and super-rich _ athletes such
as Wayne Gretzky, Michael Jordan and John Elway, are switching to
the business side of sports, becoming part-owners and front-office
executives, or considering it. Story will move in the ``A'' and
``S'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FIRE _ Down in the flaming canyons near Los Alamos, a grimy New
Mexico firefighter joked with a hotshot from Arizona. ``Guess we'll
come to your side of the state line next week,'' he said. Except
that he wasn't really joking: It's the burning season in the
Southwest. Experts agree that no fewer than 100 cities in the state
are considered at risk for an ``urban/wild-land interface fire,''
the official name for a blaze at the edge of a forest whose beauty
has attracted human settlement. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HISPANIC-TV _ Young, female Spanish-speaking viewers are the
fastest-growing demographic group in the Valley, a population that
has catapulted Phoenix to the 10th-largest market in the United
States for Hispanic TV viewers. Story will move in the ``A'' and
``F'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN _ It's sounds like a long time to be in prison _ 20
years. Maybe it is, if you're the one behind bars. But to the
family of the victim, it flies by. Just ask the adult children of
Robert James Lugiewicz, whose father was murdered when they were
kids. By EJ MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K''
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODY-SEASON _ Who Wants to Be a Millionaire made history,
changing not only the course of the television season but the way
TV does business for the near future, if not beyond, for better,
worse and both. In a curious year for television, Regis Philbin
became a household and arguably saved network television from the
advancing clutches of cable. Story will move in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODY-COL _ I was thinking about how - and it kills me to say
this - Rush Limbaugh might not be such a terrible choice for the
Monday Night Football booth. Yes, he's a blowhard; yes, he's
infuriating; yes, his views are often so offensive that you want to
pull the car over and yank out the radio and hurl it into the
river. All of which is why Limbaugh would be, if not exactly a good
pick, at least an intriguing one. Story will move in the ``E''
category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
