<HEADLINE>
FINALS RATE RIGHT UP THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Admittedly, when the barbecue is rolled out of the
garage for Memorial Day weekend, the NHL is going to have a hard
time getting people to drop their beach towels and picnic baskets
to follow the road to the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL will be an easy mark for sports columnists to besmirch
and belittle because of low television ratings. Hockey has been the
weakling of the sports family for decades, and increasing ratings
is difficult. Too many choices. Too little time. Clicker, please.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who care about what goes on in the Original 28 _
and that's a sizable number here in the six-sheet region of New
England _ this playoff season has been the best since the Rangers
shrugged off 54 years of futility and won the Cup in 1994. That's
especially true in the Hub of Hockey because of the delightful
dalliance with the Colorado Avalanche of Ray Bourque, an aging icon
trying to keep his dream alive in the spring prom. Does it get any
better than both conference finals going to Game 7?
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, when the Blueshirts won, all the goodwill
disappeared only 90 days later when the NHL owners locked the
players out in hopes of retooling the collective bargaining
agreement. Four months later the games began again and the CBA was
retooled, all right, into a financial hand grenade that owners and
general managers continually jump on. We'll find out this summer
whether teams can stay in the lifeboat they jumped aboard last
summer and resist overpaying in the free agent market. If so, the
game may live to the next CBA summit in summer 2004.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I'm tired of watching baseball brawls _ hockey
got beyond that years ago _ and I can't keep up with the NFL's
growing list of deviants. We now have the final round to savor.
Bring me that 24-ounce iced tea, and don't dare touch that channel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Bruin Jim Nill, now assistant general manager with the Red
Wings, is a leading candidate to land the GM job in Calgary, still
vacant after the end-of-season firing of Al Coates. Nill is from
Hanna, Alberta, home of the most famous Flame of all, Lanny
McDonald. Who in Bruins Country could ever forget the headline,
``Bruins get Nill for McNab''? . . . Now that Wayne Gretzky has
invested his name and his millions in the Phoenix Coyotes, don't be
surprised if he lobbies longtime friend and super agent Mike
Barnett to come aboard as chief contract negotiator. Barnett would
have to sever ties with IMG, where he represents, among others,
Bruins center Joe Thornton . . . While mulling his future in the
wake of Glen Sather's resignation in Edmonton, ex-defenseman Kevin
Lowe alluded to the possibility of taking a GM job, but not
necessarily the one left open by Sather. Hmm, let's see, Lowe is
fluent in French and English. Now, what French-speaking NHL city
might be interested in someone like that? . . . As expected, the
Red Wings informed Larry Murphy that they won't pick up his $3
million option for next season. That doesn't mean he's finished in
Wheeltown. It just means he'll have to take 25 or 30 cents on the
dollar if he wants to come back. The Wings also will be saying
goodbye to veteran pivot Igor Larionov, who had a chance at
midseason to sign for two more years at about $2 million per _ a
deal the Wings pulled off the table when his game began to look
old. One rumored landing spot for Larionov: Florida, where he could
help set up countryman Pavel Bure. But that could be more fantasy
than fact, especially if the Panthers are successful in signing
Czech star Jiri Dopita, once a Boston draft pick . . . Jobs
everywhere, but no offers for either Mike Keenan or Ted Nolan. Who
says the same names keep going round and round? . . . The Senators
had no complaints with the performance Tom Barrasso turned in after
joining them at the March trade deadline, but his salary demands
sound too expensive for their liking. For the right price, the
Wings could be interested, especially if Scotty Bowman returns as
coach. Remember, Bowman was Pittsburgh's director of player
development and recruitment when Barrasso backed the Penguins to
Stanley Cups in '91 and '92. Bowman, in fact, was behind the
Penguins bench for the second Cup and was the GM in Buffalo when
the Sabres drafted Barrasso . . . It appears Alain Vigneault will
remain behind the Montreal bench, but ownership hasn't issued a
vote of confidence for GM Rejean Houle. If Houle keeps the gig, he
may add Guy Carbonneau _ still playing for the Stars _ as his
assistant next season. Carbonneau said during the Avalanche-Stars
series that he wants to make the move to the front office . . .
Ever notice how few goalies _ Grant Fuhr being one exception _
catch with their right hands? According to Kelly Hrudey,
ex-backstop for the Islanders and Kings, there is no mystery to it.
It's simply the law of averages, the fact that most people are
righthanded. ``It's not like they're discouraged in youth hockey or
something,'' said Hrudey, who quit hockey as a youngster and had to
be coaxed back as a teenager, starting again for Inland Cement, a
Class D squad in Edmonton. ``You'd think there would be more _ kind
of like the pro golf tour, where you don't see many guys hitting
from the left.'' . . . The rumor mill has Jacques Lemaire surfacing
as the first head coach of the Minnesota Wild, possibly with ex-Hab
Mario Tremblay as an assistant. Wild GM Doug Risebrough and
Tremblay were linemates in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The order of the draft won't be known until next week, but the
Atlanta Thrashers likely will pick first or second. Wouldn't it be
interesting if the Bruins, currently holding the No. 7 pick,
offered Anson Carter and the seventh pick for the Thrashers' No. 1
or 2? Carter no doubt will be difficult to sign here in the Hub,
and he would have a chance to become an instant favorite in
Atlanta. The Thrashers need bona fide players even more than the
Bruins do. The Bruins could use the pick to draft Boston University
goalie Rick DiPietro, who is considered a top-five talent . . .
While the Flames are turning inside-out to boost their season
tickets to 14,000, let it be noted that the Canucks have seen their
season-ticket base slip to 7,500, from a high of about 12,000 five
years ago. The Canucks have to find their stride soon and get back
into playoff contention, or GM Brian Burke's warnings that the
franchise could be forced to move might turn into reality.
Meanwhile, 23 Flames have purchased a pair of season tickets each
for 2000-01, lifting the current total to about 10,500 . . . Ex-BU
forward John Cullen, who recently left his Tampa coaching job for a
career in the car business in Atlanta, will have two reasons to
stay home this fall. The Cullens are expecting twins in October . .
. WBZ Radio has yet to name a replacement for Bob Neumeier, who
packed in his play-by-play mike at the end of the season. Let it be
duly noted once more that it was Neumie, back in his Hartford days,
who discovered the Whalers' fight song, ``Brass Bonanza,'' while
flipping through a stack of LPs one night (kids, ask your parents
about phonograph needles) . . . Word out of Long Island is that
Mike Milbury sat down recently with Sanjay Kumar, one of the
Islanders' new co-owners, and he was given assurances he'll remain
as GM. And don't be surprised if Milbury makes a serious run at
unrestricted free agent Don Sweeney when the July 1 shopping spree
arrives. In his Boston days, Milbury was a huge Sweeney booster,
and the Islanders could use the veteran's guile and pluck . . .
Hockey Heartthrob Dept.: Blesk, a Prague gossip magazine, reports
that Jaromir Jagr is hot and heavy with 19-year-old Andrea
Veresova, better known as Miss Slovakia . . . Alexei Yashin and the
Senators went to arbitration last week, the Senators adamant the
star Russian still owes a year's worth of work at $3.6 million.
Yashin wants to be declared a free agent. ``If he is declared a
free agent,'' said ex-NHL coach Harry Neale, now one of the game's
top color commentators, ``then shouldn't owners win the same right
to tell a player in the last year of his deal, `Look, we know
you've got a deal, but we don't want you, and we're not paying
you'?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michel Bergeron and Harry Sinden will be linked in the history
books as the only GMs to trade Bourque. Bergeron was the boss in
Trois Rivieres almost a quarter-century ago when he swapped the
future Hall of Fame defenseman for a chance to win the Memorial Cup
(junior hockey's version of the Stanley Cup). ``It made sense
because we had a very talented team,'' said Bergeron, who dealt
Bourque for a scoring winger, Benoit Gosselin. ``But the first game
Gosselin played for us, he took a slash and broke his hand.''
Bergeron was on the Bourque beat last week, covering the
Avalanche-Stars series for French TV in Canada . . . Sather, who
could be offered more than $3 million and stock options in
Cablevision to become the Rangers boss, recalled recently that he
was a man of little clout in his playing days for the Blueshirts.
Emile Francis, then the Rangers head coach, once hurried Slats into
duty during a game, but the call wasn't to the ice. Instead,
Francis dispatched him to the dressing room with orders to sharpen
Jean Ratelle's skates. In those days, Sather ran offseason hockey
camps and was well-schooled in the art of sharpening blades. ``I
don't remember that,'' said Ratelle, who still scouts for the
Bruins. ``But it wouldn't surprise me if it happened, because in
those days, the Rangers had a guy who sharpened skates, and he
wasn't all that great at it.'' . . . Looking for a better edge,
Claude Lemieux convinced former Avalanche equipment manager Rob
McLean to come to New Jersey for the playoffs, exclusively to
sharpen skates. McLean and Lemieux were in Colorado before McLean
headed back to Ontario for a change of careers. Lemieux was dealt
back to the Devils _ for Brian Rolston, now with the Bruins . . .
Brian Bellows, who didn't catch on anywhere after Washington
released him following the 1998-99 season, is now a stockbroker
back home in Minnesota. He and Gord Kluzak, the top picks in the
1982 draft, both followed the yellow brick road to the finance
world after their hockey careers. Kluzak works in Boston for
Goldman Sachs . . . Ex-BU winger Tony Amonte was among those
Blackhawks most pleased to hear new Chicago coach Alpo Suhonen
extolling the virtues of the skate-and-shoot game. ``I'm smiling
about that,'' said Amonte, whose speed and shot could produce 100
points. If Suhonen's style can revive Alexei Zhamnov, that alone
would make his hiring worth it . . . One report out of New York had
Devils GM Lou Lamoriello pocketing no less than $30 million when
the team is finally sold and becomes part of the Yankees-Nets
package. That would mean Lamoriello holds roughly a 17 percent
equity position in the club . . . Look for the Columbus Blue
Jackets to sign Boston College forward Blake Bellefeuille to a
two-year free agent deal. Doug MacLean, the Blue Jackets GM,
scouted more than 20 BC games.
</P>
</TEXT>
