<HEADLINE>
AFTER THIS YEAR, JACK WON'T BE BACK FOR MUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ We are in the midst of a farewell tour, though
it's hard to fathom because he will, after all, be quite present.
As the joke goes: ``What's he going to do, retire to play golf?''
</P>
<P>
   For all intents and purposes, 2000 is it for Jack Nicklaus in
the life he has known for four decades. He will play all four
majors this year, plus the four with the over-50 crowd, and
sprinkle in a few PGA Tour events so he can tee it up alongside his
son, Gary. But come 2001, his appearances will be limited to some
Senior stops, most likely his beloved Memorial tournament, and
perhaps the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. It's time to slow down, said Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked hard at the damned game for 40 years and, frankly,
I'm tired of that,'' he said. ``Your body can't take it. I mean, I
get up every morning and I've got a new ding here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've put my wife through 40 years of tournament golf. I
don't think she needs to have any more of that.''
</P>
<P>
   It strikes at the heart of the game's magical appeal that we can
talk of a man's ``retirement'' when he is 60 years old. Golf is a
game for life, the reason Nicklaus has been able to share his
talents with three generations of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments are made in almost all sports as to who was the best,
but not in golf, thanks to Nicklaus. Perhaps Tiger Woods will get
the flames going in the next 10 years, but for now, the answer is
Nicklaus. Let people argue about No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Player knows everyone will point to the 18 major
championships as evidence of Nicklaus's superiority, but to do so,
he argues, is to overlook the foundation of his greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can be great when they win,'' said Player. ``But Jack
was the greatest loser ever.''
</P>
<P>
   There were heart-wrenching losses to Tom Watson at Turnberry
(1977) and Pebble Beach (1982), to Lee Trevino at Merion (1971) and
Muirfield (1972), to Arnold Palmer at Cherry Hill (1960), even to
Hal Sutton at Riviera (1983). All part of his 17 runner-up finishes
in major championships, though in each one Nicklaus's character and
dignity stood out.
</P>
<P>
   Player said you never saw Nicklaus act badly on the course, but
Nicklaus said that wasn't true. He threw a club once in front of
his father, the guiding force in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He introduced me to golf, but when he saw me throw the club,
he told me I better never do that again,'' said Nicklaus. ``And I
haven't.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was not only my father, he was my best friend. He tried
to teach me the right way to do things.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider them lessons learned well, because Nicklaus has been an
exemplary athlete in a world that has too few of them. Those still
pained by the fact that he came along and knocked the beloved
Palmer from his throne can find satisfaction in the knowledge that
Nicklaus is deserving of every accolade that comes his way.
</P>
<P>
   He has been great to the game, but more importantly, he knows
the game has been great to him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nicklaus, the PGA Tour rookie and 31-year-old son of a
living legend, smiled when asked if his father gives him advice.
``A little bit,'' he said. ``When he's around and I need some help,
I'll obviously ask for his advice.'' A sly grin came to his face as
if Gary were suggesting that it isn't always a case of Father Knows
Best. Is that what he was getting at? ``Sometimes we have different
ideas,'' he said. ``Even though he's the greatest player that's
ever played, he's wrong sometimes. At least in my mind. But he is
getting smarter as he gets older.'' Gary indicated that the most
recent father-son ``disagreement'' came last weekend. ``He thought
I should have been here (Dublin, Ohio, for the Memorial) on
Saturday and I wanted to go home Saturday. He wasn't real happy
with me. I wasn't real happy with him questioning what I wanted to
do. But we talked about it and that was the end of it.'' . . . Tom
Lehman had been the biggest name supporting the fledgling
Tournament Players Association but he has changed his mind. After a
meeting with the Players Advisory Committee, in which Lehman and
the TPA were soundly shut down in their request to employ an
independent adviser to look at PGA Tour financial records, it
became obvious there was no place for such a union. ``I basically
decided that any further effort by the TPA is harmful to our
Tour,'' said Lehman, ``and I think it should disappear. Basically I
have resigned my membership.'' Mark Brooks remains the only ``big
name'' fighting for the TPA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There may not be a more unheralded two-time PGA Tour winner than
Gabriel Hjerstedt, the Sweden native who moved with his family to
Australia when he was 11. He may not be as zany as Jesper Parnevik,
but he's not exactly conventional, either. For one thing, Hjerstedt
prefers footwear that resembles high-top sneakers. ``I had a groin
problem earlier in the year, so they have actually helped me
walk,'' he said. For another, he has no inclination to jet back and
forth to keep contact with the European Tour. The American PGA Tour
is home. ``I like it over here,'' said Hjerstedt. ``I don't think
I'm going to go over and try to play 10 events or whatever it is
(to maintain a European PGA Tour card). I mean, I've got to look
after my own interests.'' Hjerstedt became the first Swede to win
in the US when he captured the 1997 B.C. Open, and he triumphed
again at Tucson in 1999. He went from 157th on the money list in
1998 to 41st in 1999, and he's currently 115th with $158,748 . . .
So, Greg Norman, what have you been doing since you played that
grueling back-to-back stretch at Augusta and Hilton Head? ``I've
been around the world in eight days.'' With anyone else, you'd
laugh, but with Norman, this is his life. He started in New York,
then checked in on a course he is building in Shannon, Ireland.
(``I've been very, very fortunate to get that piece of property.'')
From there, it was off to Dubai, then to Sydney and Melbourne, then
Honolulu, then home to Florida. It was strictly business, said
Norman: ``I didn't take my clubs overseas.'' Norman will skip next
week's Kemper Open but play the Buick Classic at Westchester CC
``because I love that golf course. Kind of like a fitter's golf
course. You've got to shape your ball.'' He is not alone in his
love of Westchester, for this year's field has attracted Phil
Mickelson, Davis Love, and Ernie Els, players who think so much of
the course that they will play the week before the US Open . . .
Speaking of the next major, don't count John Daly among those
looking forward to Pebble Beach. He stared blankly when the
question went his way. ``Not the way I'm playing,'' he said after
his round of 78 Thursday. ``I have no confidence in my golf game
right now. It's really tough. The more I work, the worse I get. I'm
swinging great, but scoring awful. It's weird, just weird.'' . . .
From excitement to despair for Mary Lawrence, a member of the LPGA
teaching division. She was awarded a spot into this week's Corning
Classic because of two late withdrawals, but then was disqualified
when she arrived at the first tee seven minutes late. Had she been
there two minutes earlier, officials would have let her start.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sophie Gustafson, who broke through for her first LPGA Tour win
a few weeks ago, showed that her game translates well overseas,
too. She won the Ladies Italian Open last week. The two who
finished second _ Valerie Van Ryckeghem of Belgium and Silvia
Cavalleri _ certainly had interesting caddies. Manoel Williams, her
coach and boyfriend, carried for Van Ryckeghem, while Vittoria
Cavalleri lugged the bag for her daughter. You may remember
Cavalleri from her US Women's Amateur conquest at Brae Burn CC in
1997 . . . Ford Olinger, the professional from Warsaw, Ind., with
the degenerative hip condition, shot 90 in local qualifying for the
US Open. He failed in his court case against the USGA and was not
allowed to use a cart, but they compromised on a Swedish Rollator.
``Sort of like a grocery cart,'' said Olinger, who is now 0 for 3
in local qualifiers. Two years ago, after winning a court
injunction against the USGA, Olinger drove a cart and shot 83. Last
year, after being denied a permanent injunction, he walked and
scored 88. Since then, the 7th US Circuit Court in Chicago ruled in
favor of the USGA, that a cart would change the nature of
competition, so while he appeals, Olinger had to settle for just a
walker. ``I'm in the same shoes (as Casey Martin). What's the
difference?'' asked Olinger. Well, to be honest, the difference is
that Martin has shown he can play at the highest level. Olinger
hasn't. In 1998, while Olinger was riding and shooting 83 in an
Open qualifier, Martin drove and made it through local and
sectional qualifying, then won legions of admirers by finishing
tied for 23d at The Olympic Club. The other difference is Martin's
case was heard in front of the 9th US Circuit Court in San
Francisco, which ruled in his favor. Martin, by the way, shot 78
and did not advance in the local qualifier at Austin CC in Texas .
. . Craig Stadler's stays at the Memorial continue to be short and
unmemorable. Citing continued back woes, he withdrew before the
start of Round 1. That makes it three WDs in four years. He hasn't
played in a PGA Tour event since he lost in a playoff at the Shell
Houston Open a month ago . . . George Bush, the former president,
was ever-present at the Memorial, having been named the most recent
member of The Captains Club, an international group of golfing
dignitaries invited by Jack Nicklaus to advise on matters
concerning the operation of this tournament. Sean Connery is also a
member . . . The Memorial Golf Journalism honors this year went to
Dave Anderson of The New York Times, Nick Seitz of Golf Digest, and
Renton Laidlaw, the Scotsman whose golden voice is reason enough to
get out of bed Sunday mornings for European Tour broadcasts on The
Golf Channel . . . Bruce Fleisher's father, Herbert, died Tuesday
after a three-month battle with pancreatic cancer. He was 76.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
