<SLUG> BC-NYTSPRT, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT-WORLDCOM MERGER UNLEASHES EMPLOYEE STOCK OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE ONE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Kansas City, Mo. _ If executives at
Sprint Corp. and WorldCom fail to steer their proposed merger past
antitrust regulators, shareholders may want some answers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the first questions they may ask: Why, if the merger
failed, was the process still a financial bonanza for executives
and senior management?
</P>
<P>
   Sprint shareholders overwhelmingly approved the WorldCom deal
April 28, enticed by the prospect of $76 in WorldCom stock for
every Sprint share, which closed Friday at 56.
</P>
<P>
   What many shareholders may not have realized was that they also
approved a provision that accelerated the vesting of stock options
worth as much as $1.7 billion to Sprint executives and employees _
even if WorldCom never completes its purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you could have here is the worst of both worlds, a huge
wealth transfer to management and employees, with no benefit to
shareholders,'' said Nell Minow, editor of a corporate governance
Web site. ``Shareholders may be paying for something they never
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint declined to comment on the stock option provision.
</P>
<P>
   At the a special shareholders' meeting in April, Chief Executive
William T. Esrey told shareholders that regulatory hurdles were to
be expected in a deal of such magnitude, but that the companies
expected to win approval by fall.
</P>
<P>
   That may still happen. If it does not _ and regulatory prospects
for the deal have darkened in recent weeks _ shareholders may look
back on the vote with some skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   On Page 78 of the company's 400-page mailing to shareholders
about the merger is a fairly innocuous sounding disclosure. ``Most
of Sprint's stock option plans provide that options outstanding for
a year at the time of the Sprint special meeting will become fully
vested, if not previously vested, and exercisable upon adoption by
Sprint shareholders of the merger agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the shareholder vote triggered the immediate
vesting of employees' options on millions of shares of Sprint and
Sprint PCS, accelerating a benefit that otherwise would have taken
employees and executives years to accrue.
</P>
<P>
   It is not uncommon for options to vest when companies merge. The
rationale is to minimize management's motivation to protect its own
interests by blocking a merger that would benefit shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual _ though not unique _ in Sprint's case is that
the benefits accelerated with the shareholder vote, not with the
completion of the deal. And with a deal of this size and
complexity, companies do not normally hold shareholder votes before
the government's concerns are resolved, some compensation experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   Regulatory concerns have been public since the companies agreed
to merge and presumably were debated in detail by the companies and
regulators in their six-month investigation of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the shareholder vote, the European Commission
announced that it had ``serious concerns'' about the deal. Its
investigation concluded that the merged company would have a
dominant position in the markets for Internet connectivity and
global telecommunications services. The commission will hold a
meeting Tuesday in which the companies and the deal's critics will
make their case to the antitrust arm of the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, staffers at the U.S. Department of Justice also
forwarded a recommendation to block the deal on antitrust grounds
to the department's chief antitrust regulator, Joel Klein. WorldCom
and Sprint officials reportedly were scheduled to meet with Klein
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the acceleration of the employee options could be
troublesome in two ways.
</P>
<P>
   First, the value of existing shares may be watered down as
employees convert their options to new shares.
</P>
<P>
   Experts call such exposure an overhang. And while it's unlikely
that employees would all choose to exercise their options at once,
outstanding options were about 6 percent of the outstanding shares
at year end.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a dramatic number compared to some high-tech
companies, but it isn't such a good thing for the company,'' said
Charles Elson, a law professor at Stetson University College in St.
Petersburg, Fla., whose specialty is corporate governance.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Melloul, a securities analyst with Argus Research, said
that the ratio of options to outstanding shares was relatively
small and that the potential dilution was manageable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the deal will go through, even through it will face
some challenges,'' he said. ``When the deal goes through,
shareholders will get a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   A second concern is that the shareholder vote may have turned
the company's golden handcuffs into a golden handshake.
</P>
<P>
   Options are designed to keep talented employees from leaving by
allowing them to profit from their company's rising share price.
Employees receive grants giving them the right to buy a set number
of shares at a set price, anytime in, say, the next 10 years. Those
options are typically phased in, or vested, over a number of years,
and the employee is tied to the firm as they wait for all their
options to become exercisable.
</P>
<P>
   In Sprint's case employees have seen the potential payoff from
their accumulated options balloon in recent years as the price of
Sprint shot up.
</P>
<P>
   Option holders also got a bonus when Sprint issued shares of its
wireless company to shareholders. An employee with existing options
on 1,000 shares of Sprint received an additional option to purchase
500 shares of PCS.
MORE: Accelerated vesting ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
