<SLUG> BC-NYTSPRT-TAKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT-WORLDCOM MERGER UNLEASHES EMPLOYEE STOCK OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 2-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ Accelerated vesting of those options could
give thousands of Sprint employees new financial independence.
Coupled with a robust job market in the telecommunications
industry, many could cash in their chips and walk away.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you don't want to do is provide them with the same
walk-away money for a deal that doesn't go through,'' Minow said.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to put an exact number on the wealth created by
the accelerated vesting, or how many employees share it. The
company would not confirm any numbers, and there were some
limitations on the vesting.
</P>
<P>
   Based on 1999 year-end filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, however, the vote accelerated the vesting of as much as
$1.7 billion worth of options for employees and executives, adding
to $1.4 billion worth of options that were already exercisable.
</P>
<P>
   Most went to top managers. Esrey saw as much as $320 million
worth of benefits accelerated by the vote. Sprint President Ronald
LeMay's paper wealth jumped by as much as $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Kevin Brauer, former president of Sprint's national
integrated services division; Arthur Krause, chief financial
officer; and Andrew Sukawaty, president of Sprint PCS, saw the
value of their ``exercisable'' options leap by as much as $45
million.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the company's 77,000 employees shared in as much as
$1.2 billion, almost $16,000 apiece, although the options are
heavily skewed toward employees who are director level and above.
</P>
<P>
   Many senior employees at Sprint are now sitting on hundreds of
thousands, some even millions, of dollars in paper profits from
their options in a robust job market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates the opposite kind of incentive that you were trying
to create with a long vesting schedule for the options,'' Elson
said. ``What's the incentive to stick around now? You can take your
money and run.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint did institute a retention program for senior employees to
minimize any talent drain after the vote, offering additional
options for employees who agree to stick around until a specified
date, and putting existing options in trust.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey and LeMay also are subject to additional limitations for
directors of the company, preventing them from exercising some of
their options.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's situation bears some similarity to Northrop Grumman's,
when regulators chose to fight that company's proposed merger with
Lockheed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sprint, Northrop's stock options accelerated when
shareholders approved that merger, triggering $150 million to $160
million in stock awards and payments to company executives.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department subsequently challenged the deal on
antitrust grounds. And when the companies scuttled their deal,
Northrop's management was sued by shareholders who said management
knew the deal was in trouble, but went ahead with the shareholder
vote that accelerated their options.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the shareholders said they were still fighting the
case in state and federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management created a win-win situation for themselves,'' said
Randall Baron, the attorney who filed the shareholder case against
Northrop.
</P>
<P>
   Regulatory concerns over the Sprint-WorldCom deal have been far
more public than those in the Northrop-Lockheed case. And Sprint's
stock has not fallen precipitously since staff at the Justice
Department forwarded their recommendation to block the deal, as
Northrop's did.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Baron said the circumstances shared similarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If shareholders know that there are millions of dollars in
benefits that the company has to pay, even if the deal doesn't go
through, they may be less likely to vote in favor of the merger''
until it's assured of passing, he said. -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
