A7947 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-27 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARPER HAS WINNING VISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. - Poor, proud, pedestrian Ron Harper. It was hard
not to pity the Lakers' wily warrior as he limped along in the
first 12 games of these playoffs. While teammates Kobe Bryant and
Shaquille O'Neal were maturing before our very eyes, Harper
appeared to be merely aging.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year veteran had been giving Father Time the slip for
years, but it was beginning to look like his longtime nemesis had
wrapped himself around Harper and was harassing him so he couldn't
get a hand on Sacramento's Nick Anderson, Phoenix's Penny Hardaway
or Portland's Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Harper was starting to look horribly miscast in Los
Angeles, which is less a city than a sprawling spa where people go
to look and feel younger. Not since Larry Robinson coached the
Kings had we seen someone come to L.A. and put on so many years so
fast.
</P>
<P>
   We hardly recognized Harper when he hurried out of the Lakers'
practice facility, barely breathing a word to reporters, on the
days between Monday's Game 2 and Friday's Game 3 of the ongoing
Western Conference finals. We took his sudden silence as a
reflexive response to a game that had gone quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Silly us.
</P>
<P>
   We should have known Harper, like Robinson, had a lot of life
left in him. Both men looked rejuvenated Friday, with Robinson
guiding the New Jersey Devils into the Stanley Cup Finals and
Harper scoring the decisive basket in the Lakers' 93-91 win.
</P>
<P>
   Harper's 19-foot jump shot from the left corner with 29.9
seconds remaining was sweeter than Chick Hearn's syntax. Fittingly,
it came off a feed from Kobe Bryant, who would have been a lot less
inclined to pass in such a situation if he hadn't had Harper in his
ear all year, gently reminding him that teammates are what make the
triangle offense work.
</P>
<P>
   What's really remarkable is Harper didn't just call for the
ball, he called his shot.
</P>
<P>
   During one of the final timeouts, Harper set the scene for his
teammates, saying something to the effect of, ``Look. I've been
open all night, so if someone would be so kind as to pass me the
ball I'll make the shot. I promise.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked for all the pressure and then let go a shot that was as
true as his word.
</P>
<P>
   That's not easy, no matter how many NBA championship rings you
own. But at some point in a successful title run, it must be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ron's seen enough, he's in a sense a visionary,''
Laker forward Rick Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Experience would appear to be the mother of all foresight. In
the third quarter, Harper started chasing the ball, the better to
disrupt the Trail Blazers' rhythm on offense. With Harper using his
one good leg as a pogo stick, the Lakers outscored Portland 27-16
in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody told Harper that was the thing to do. He just knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an instinctive thing,'' he said before Saturday's
practice.
</P>
<P>
   That's Harper, compensating for his tired old limbs with a
perfectly preserved sixth sense.
</P>
<P>
   His gut instinct told him to put off retirement for another year
to help usher in the Phil Jackson era in L.A. And something told
him he was the guy to turn this best-of-seven series around.
</P>
<P>
   At the tense juncture of Game 3, Harper was able to stay really,
really tranquil. He took what he had learned all those years of
sharing a backcourt in Chicago with Michael Jordan and passed it on
to the Lakers in a way none of them soon will forget.
</P>
<P>
   Harper ``was probably the calmest one out there at that point,''
Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   His composure was contagious. A team that had come undone under
duress four days earlier pulled itself together for a gallant last
stand.
</P>
<P>
   With 1.9 seconds left, Bryant rose to block the shot of Arvydas
Sabonis, conceding eight inches to the Portland center but not one
damn thing more.
</P>
<P>
   They don't give out assists on game-saving blocked shots, which
is why the box scores will never tell the complete story of
Harper's value to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fills up the box score in different ways,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, he was back to filling up our notebooks as well.
His silence earlier in the week was intended to send a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to tell my teammates, enough of all this hype
stuff,'' Harper said. ``Let's not talk a good game, let's go out
and play one.''
</P>
<P>
   That's experience talking. Which is nevermore to be confused
with old age. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
