<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEMS PERSIST IN MONTREAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Montreal owner Jeffrey Loria has increased the
Expos' payroll to $33 million, the team has signed young players to
multi-year deals, has been active in the free-agent market and has
one of the game's top players in Vladimir Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday, the Expos were also a surprising 25-20 and in
second place in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   However, Montreal is still having problems because of problems
getting television and radio deals, opposition and a lack of
funding for a downtown ballpark and reported friction within the
new ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos are expected to lose money again this season, and
Loria is still fighting to get English- and French-speaking radio
and television deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are already in a situation where it's costing us several
hundred thousand dollars just to be on French radio,'' Loria said,
``while all of our competitors have a minimum of $8 million to $10
million in broadcast revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   But one thing Loria won't do is have another
franchise-debilitating fire sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely will not do that,'' said Loria, who added he
would do the opposite. If the Expos are in contention in August,
Loria said he would look to add a player or two.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling of himself: Phillies right-hander Curt Schilling isn't
scheduled to pitch this weekend against the Dodgers, but even if he
did he might not be recognizable. The guy who overpowered National
League hitters before arm surgery is having trouble these days.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts who've seen Schilling pitch this season say his velocity
is below 90 mph. He's 1-2 with a 5.58 ERA in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   Trade bait: Yankees scout Gene Michael was at the Dodgers'
brawling series in Chicago to evaluate a few Cubs players,
including left-handed hitting Henry Rodriguez. The Yankees want
Rodriguez to play left field, and the Cubs are entertaining the
idea. The deal would send Rodriguez to the Yankees for highly
regarded outfielder Ricky Ledee and minor-league pitchers Mike
Buddie and Jay Tessmer, who could help the woeful Cubs bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But Sammy Sosa said it's much too early to start thinking about
unloading players for prospects, even though the Cubs are 19-31 and
near the bottom of the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the time to make that move,'' Sosa said. ``We have to
stay together. What are they going to do, bring in some young kids?
Then nobody will go to the ballpark. Jeez, we're not even two
months into the season, but everybody thinks it's September.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop, thief!: Reds manager Jack McKeon wasn't happy with the way
the Dodgers won Monday. It came when Reds catcher Eddie Taubensee
was ruled to have missed home plate on a force play in the bottom
of the 14th inning. Several Dodgers remarked they thought
Taubensee's foot hit the plate, but McKeon seemed a little more
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (bleeping) game was stolen from us,'' McKeon said. ``We
might have lost it with the next hitter. But we certainly shouldn't
have lost that ballgame on that play. That's a perfect reason for
baseball to have instant replay.''
</P>
<P>
   He said what?: Giants catcher Bobby Estalella had no qualms
about what spurred a recent huge collision with Atlanta's Andres
Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned around and saw his face,'' Estalella said. ``He was
three feet away from me with eyes like the devil trying to hit me.
So I put the ball in his face as hard as I could. If he's going to
hit me, I'm going to try to hit him, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
