<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTCEMET-TWO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOUT COMPLETES PROJECT TO HONOR THOSE WHO DIED AT MENTAL
HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSAWATOMIE, Kan. _ Monday morning, as the sun rises and the
birds begin to sing, Eagle Scout Jeremy Woods will pay homage to
hundreds of people he never knew.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old will unfurl an American flag, run it up a pole
atop a hill overlooking this old railroad town of 4,500 and think
to himself of those who have come before.
</P>
<P>
   No flowery Memorial Day speeches. No brass band. Just a young
man standing in front of an unnamed memorial plot he helped
refurbish last year as part of his Eagle Scout project.
</P>
<P>
   In front of him, jutting from the Miami County earth some 30
miles south of Overland Park, will be nine symmetrical rows of
numbered concrete headstones.
</P>
<P>
   The 346 plots face west toward the Osawatomie State Hospital, a
134-year-old place that started out as the Kansas State Insane
Asylum, the first facility of its kind west of the Mississippi
River.
</P>
<P>
   In the strictest sense, it would be a mistake to identify this
spot along old Asylum Road as a cemetery, for only some of the
plots _ and nobody can say how many _ hold the remains of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what the concrete tablets represent are the hundreds of
people who are now buried in unmarked plots scattered about the
800-acre wooded facility overlooking the Marais des Cygnes River.
</P>
<P>
   Woods plans to be here to remember those who so many others
forgot _ by design.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would live their entire lives and be locked away (at
the state hospital) and die there, and nobody would see them. Then
they would be given an anonymous grave plot,'' said District Judge
Stephen D. Hill, who helped guide Woods' Eagle Scout effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``But through this project one young man has forced us to
recognize that these people have value, and they're not just
throwaways.''
</P>
<P>
   Osawatomie is a town that embraces its history. Files at the
town's historical society are thick with stories of abolitionist
John Brown, the Old Stone Church and the birth of the Republican
Party in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they make scant mention of the state hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ask city librarian Dorothy Ingram for records on the hospital
memorial site, and she'll tell you the same thing she's told so
many before _ sorry, but there's precious little information.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who have lived their entire lives in Miami County
do not even know the plot exists. Others know but are reluctant to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' mother, Lylise Evans, just wants her town to come to
grips with its past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like it brought to people's eyes that there was a cemetery
out there,'' she said. ``A lot of people don't even know it's
there. I don't think the community really wants to be known for the
hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who plans to attend Wichita State University in the fall
to study criminology, is motivated by a simple message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The names at the plots were just forgotten, and that's how I
see it,'' Woods said. ``If that was my brother or my sister or my
grandpa or my parents buried out there, I would not want them
forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital opened in 1866, a time when mental illness
stigmatized sufferers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than half of the patients at Osawatomie State Hospital
fell into the `forgotten' category,'' said Tom Lawson, now
superintendent of schools in Eureka. He received his doctorate in
education in 1994 after spending three years researching the
hospital's archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you were sentenced there you were lost, and your family
was scarred, and you were never mentioned again and never talked
about,'' Lawson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families literally would drop folks off here and then
disappear,'' said Norma Stephens, who worked at the hospital for
more than four decades. She started as secretary to the
superintendent in 1946 and retired as superintendent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often there would be no relatives who were willing or could
financially claim the bodies. Hospital staff would often make every
effort to locate relatives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would all get very close to those individuals who had been
there for so many years. It was just like losing a member of our
own families. We wanted them to have the burial they would have
had, had family been there to claim them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not always possible.
</P>
<P>
   At its most overcrowded, in World War II, Osawatomie State
Hospital had 1,693 patients with three doctors, two consulting
doctors and a superintendent. At its height, some 300 people died
at the hospital each year.
MORE What records ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
