<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTCEMT-SECOND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOUT COMPLETES PROJECT TO HONOR THOSE WHO DIED AT MENTAL
HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   Kansas City, Mo. _ ... each year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What records do exist show that from 1874 to 1928 the unclaimed
bodies of patients were buried in a different spot on the northwest
corner of the hospital grounds. Before 1874 the dead were buried
elsewhere on the grounds, but where is now a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1928 the headstones from the old cemetery were moved to the
current memorial site, but the bodies were left behind. In the
1960s the hospital constructed its new Adair buildings on the old
cemetery. The buildings were built on slab foundations so as not to
disturb the dead.
</P>
<P>
   So the plot one sees today east of the hospital mixes memorial
headstones from the earlier burial site with the actual graves of
those buried from 1928 to 1960. Hospital records that identify
those memorialized in the 346 plots are sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Some scant facts are known.
</P>
<P>
   Plot No. 1 represents a patient, name unknown, who was buried on
Feb. 2, 1928, according to archives.
</P>
<P>
   No. 157 is one of two to offer a name for the person buried
there. Beside the numbered headstone is a polished stone of granite
that reads: ``In memory of granny. Minnie M. Devine, born Jan. 4,
1875, died Oct. 23, 1933.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 230 is partly swallowed by a cedar tree.
</P>
<P>
   At plot No. 279, a stone indicates the grave belongs to ``Clyde
Nelson, born Dec. 27, 1880, died Nov. 30, 1941.'' Written by hand
in concrete that borders the stone: ``father.''
</P>
<P>
   The final stone, No. 346, represents someone who died April 6,
1960.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, attitudes toward mental illness have changed,
and Lawson says it would be wrong to judge the actions of the past
by the standards of today. Since 1960, only one patient's body has
gone unclaimed and is buried in the Osawatomie city cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Woods and a dozen fellow scouts from Troop 106 of
the Twin River District with the Heart of America Boy Scout Council
placed artificial flowers on the first and last grave markers of
each of the nine rows of stones. Late in the afternoon a Scout
color guard then presented the flag and recited the Pledge of
Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Last year troop members spent 175 hours resetting headstones,
removing lichen and putting up a sign and bench. A grounds crew
from the state hospital erected the flagpole.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the sign was erected, it was repainted by the
hospital crew, Woods said. The original wording, ``Osawatomie State
Hospital Cemetery,'' was changed to ``Historic Memorial Site.''
</P>
<P>
   A hospital administrator said the original sign was simply
confusing to visitors seeking information about the plots.
</P>
<P>
   Woods first found out about the change when a friend called to
say it appeared as if his sign had been vandalized. Later, while
attending a City Council meeting to receive a citation for his
Eagle Scout project, he learned his sign had been reworded by a
hospital worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not seeking any glory by fixing up this cemetery,'' said
Woods, a soft-spoken assistant Scout leader. ``I just want people
to know these people were still human and deserve some respect.
This is the right thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
