<HEADLINE>
SLEUTHS OF EVERY STRIP HELP SNIFF OUT COMPUTER VIRUS CREATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Kansas City, Mo. _ Suddenly, Roger
Thompson _ for three decades a mild-mannered computer whiz _ was a
bloodhound unleashed for the hunt.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When scoundrels somewhere in the Philippines set loose a
computer virus dubbed the ``love bug,'' infecting personal
computers everywhere by e-mail, Thompson reacted as a growing
number of high-techies do these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm chasing the perp,'' the Atlanta cybersleuth said.
</P>
<P>
   And off Thompson went, tapping his PC keyboard, searching the
love bug's coded pathways for electronic breadcrumbs that might
lead him to the perpetrator who wrote the virus. Thompson worked
alone at his home, but countless other detectives were out there in
cyberspace with him.
</P>
<P>
   They are not cops. They tell the cops where to look.
</P>
<P>
   Complex as it sounds, tracking the mad scientists behind deadly
computer viruses can be done rather swiftly, experts and law
enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a process repeating itself this weekend, as the FBI looks
into another virus that struck several corporate e-mail systems
Friday. This bug, ``killer resume,'' arrived pretending to be a job
candidate's resume.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said the latest threat would not likely spread far
during a holiday weekend, but the FBI warned users of the Microsoft
Outlook program not to open e-mail with the subject line ``Resume _
Janet Simons.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the love bug, which had wormed its way through
e-mail attachments seductively marked ``ILOVEYOU,'' authorities
working with cybersleuths in the private sector traced the virus to
a band of students at a Philippine college within a day.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bug had time to strike an estimated 45 million
computers in 20 countries, causing nearly $10 billion in damage.
Industry observers are calling ``the killa from Manila'' the most
widespread act of computer vandalism in history.
</P>
<P>
   The crime is an increasingly common one that, for now, human
ingenuity cannot stop. On the other hand, these mass invasions _
unlike all other criminal acts _ may leave evidence out there that
the public at large can sift through, given the proper know-how and
Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   Professionals such as Thompson, 47, knew where to look when the
love bug hit May 4.
</P>
<P>
   As technical director of malicious code research at ICSA.net, an
Internet security company that tests anti-virus software, Thompson
scanned eight pages of computer code affixed to the malignant
e-mail. Some clues jumped right off the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The code included: ``barok...i hate go to
school...spyder...AMACC...GRAMMERSoft Group...''
</P>
<P>
   Barok: The name of a password-stealing software program written
by a Filipino hacker last year.
</P>
<P>
   I hate go to school: A student with an adolescent gripe?
</P>
<P>
   Spyder: The apparent e-mail handle of the virus' author.
</P>
<P>
   AMACC: AMA Computer College in Manila.
</P>
<P>
   GRAMMERSoft: An underground group of AMA hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer virus hunters from all corners of the World Wide Web
passed their findings to the FBI's National Infrastructure
Protection Center, which was established in 1998 to fight
``cyberterrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in Kansas City, the regional office of the FBI fielded tips
from online Sherlocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of hours after the news reports, someone out there
gave us the source code,'' FBI regional spokesman Jeff Lanza said.
``By then headquarters already had it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do get unsolicited contacts from computer people who, like
most people, want to help solve crimes,'' Lanza said. ``We can't
complain about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1990s, virus writing was an obscure craft only the
most knowledgeable programmers could master. Computer systems were
less powerful, less interconnected, less easy to use and, thus,
more difficult for vandals to infect in epidemic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   The battleground changed when Microsoft introduced WordBasic and
VisualBasic, freeing PC users from many repetitive tasks and making
programming more accessible to everyone. In the meantime, the
widening Internet provided a hot medium by which viruses could
travel faster to more computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the computers used at Xerox Park, at government agencies
and nuclear power plants are essentially the same as the computer
in a 14-year-old's bedroom,'' said Carey Nachenberg, chief of
research for the Symantec AntiVirus Research Center in California.
</P>
<P>
   As such, many of today's virus launchers are young pranksters
driven by the urge just to do it, to show their pals _ if not the
world _ all they know. Self-styled groups even offer virus-building
kits on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``A typical 14-year-old could go online and create their own in
an hour or so,'' Nachenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that ``most viruses are pretty stupid,'' he
said, and will never spread and harm other computers.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said a virus writer who creates something original can
be an admirable foil. ``But the ones who make a variation of what's
already been done? Those guys are lame.''
MORE Even when ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
