<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7963 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-NYTVIRS-2NDTAKE-KAN &LR;      05-27 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTVIRS-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEUTHS OF EVERY STRIP HELP SNIFF OUT COMPUTER VIRUS CREATORS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   `` ... are lame.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo. _ Even when a virus does propagate _ as the
love bug did _ sloppy coding often will lead investigators directly
to the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most virus writers aren't particularly skilled at covering
their tracks,'' said David Chess, one of the top virus hunters at
IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some wish to take credit. In other cases, it's my guess they
don't take the time to think, `This could spread all over the world
and people might catch me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In a Boston suburb, James Atkinson faced a wall of 17 computer
monitors.
</P>
<P>
   On these screens, he said, you can watch a virus behave as it
spreads from computer to computer, leaving information at each
stop. The procedure is called ``sandboxing,'' analogous to the way
psychologists study children's behavior by watching them play in a
sandbox.
</P>
<P>
   ``You create a environment in which the virus can play,'' said
Atkinson. He works for the Granite Island Group, which deals in
``technical counterintelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atkinson's world there exists but a handful of ``big-game
hunters'' of computer viruses _ himself included, he said
sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding them are ``crowds of tribesmen running around
hunting water buffaloes with peashooters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The big-game hunters will not often volunteer their services to
investigate viruses and report them to the FBI, Atkinson said.
``It's their stock and trade,'' and for Atkinson, that means $250
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   When the love bug hit, a large corporation asked Atkinson to
sniff out the menace that had damaged its computers. Within six
hours he had traced the virus to five collaborators, aged 19 to 23,
affiliated with AMA College in the Philippines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Probing deeper, Atkinson even found a membership roll of the
college's mischief makers _ the GRAMMERSoft Group _ and sent e-mail
questionnaires to 50 students listed. From their responses,
Atkinson said, he learned the roles each suspect played in creating
the virus and how ``one of them snapped'' and zapped it to the
world.
</P>
<P>
   After Philippines police began arresting suspects, including
bank employee Reomel Ramones, Atkinson was the first to tell
Internet news site Wired.com that the police had the wrong guy. Two
days later, police released Ramones for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson said the brightest cybersleuths always will remain in
the private sector, where the income and stock options far surpass
what law enforcement pays.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and President Clinton have vowed to hire
more Internet-savvy investigators and to do whatever is needed to
keep the nation safe from keyboard-tapping terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Attorney General Janet Reno announced a Cybercitizen
Partnership between law enforcement and the technology community.
The campaign includes a personnel exchange program to share
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Virus experts said they welcomed the increased vigilance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal investigators definitely have turned to private
industry for assistance, and we've responded admirably to the
invitation,'' said Alan Komet of Computer Associates, a major
producer of anti-virus software. ``We work with (the FBI) on a
daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Symantec and IBM soon will introduce a ``digital immune system''
designed to watch for known viral intruders and any other
suspicious activity in a computer's system. Any file with odd
characteristics would be routed to the Symantec research center and
``a cure'' would be sent back to the affected network, Nachenberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   That will not keep virus writers from plugging away. Every new
computing feature becomes a potential target of the viruses of
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Already some 40,000 viruses lurk out there, most of which have
been concocted in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   They'll keep the cybersleuth posse busy for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it when I can track a perp down,'' Thompson said.
``And if not, I'll get them next time.'' -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
