<HEADLINE>
FOR A'S, IT'S A QUESTION OF ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. - Many preseason publications picked the
Oakland A's to win the AL West, but things haven't gone quite as
they hoped so far. They are in last place in the division, but it's
no time to panic.
</P>
<P>
   All four teams are right around the .500 mark and none of the
four are likely to run away with the division.
</P>
<P>
   A's general manager Billy Beane could do well by asking former
Angels GM Bill Bavasi what it's like to oversee a young team with
high expectations, but so far Beane is struggling with his team's
mediocre start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm focused on the fact that we're in last place and
no one in the organization is happy with that, period,'' Beane
said. ``I don't like the general malaise that has surrounded this
team, and I know that (manager) Art Howe feels the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's are fielding offers for outfielder Matt Stairs, a big
part of last year's success but someone who has been hurt and has
struggled at the plate (.206, 7 homers, 22 RBI). A trade of Stairs
would open up right field for Jeremy Giambi.
</P>
<P>
   Stairs normally is the A's cleanup hitter, but in a game last
week against the Devil Rays, Howe pinch hit for him. How many
managers pinch hit for their cleanup hitter?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not hitting,'' Howe explained. ``I don't know if he's
pressing, but he's not hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Bronx showdown: Pedro Martinez will start tonight for the Red
Sox against the Yankees and former Red Sox pitcher Roger Clemens at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the two perennial Cy Young award winners faced
each other was in last season's ALCS, a game won by Martinez and
the Red Sox. It was the Yankees' only postseason loss of the year.
</P>
<P>
   For Martinez to have the same result, he needs to bounce back
from his second loss of the year, when he gave up three runs and
seven hits and struck out ``only'' seven in a loss to the Blue Jays
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After that game, Martinez told reporters expectations of him
have grown too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am only a little man pitching out there and trying to do my
job,'' said Martinez, whose ERA rose from 0.90 to 1.19 and whose
record fell to 7-2. ``You are the guys who got me so big. You write
all that crap about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Freak injury: The Orioles have been considering moving Brady
Anderson out of center field because at age 36, he seemed to have
lost a step. But he recently explained that he's been feeling
numbness and weakness in his left foot all season.
</P>
<P>
   The reason?
</P>
<P>
   An ice pack applied to his knee during spring training
apparently deadened a nerve in the foot. The Orioles had considered
moving Delino DeShields to center field, but Jerry Hairston, who
would have taken DeShields' spot at second base, got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson just recently is reporting improvement in his foot.
</P>
<P>
   Juiced-ball theory: More evidence that the baseball is juiced -
Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn hit the speakers that hang high
above the field in the Metrodome twice in one game last week.
</P>
<P>
   The second one Vaughn hit would have ended up a foul ball in the
seats behind the third-base dugout, but instead caromed back toward
the field of play where Twins third baseman Ron Coomer made the
catch for the out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just laughed,'' Vaughn said. ``What can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Twins manager Tom Kelly told the St. Paul Pioneer Press that
it's happening too much this year to be coincidence: ``The balls
are hitting the speakers,'' Kelly said. ``The balls almost never
used to hit the speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Short hops: Rickey Henderson recently drew his 2,000th walk, and
now trails only Babe Ruth (2,062) and Ted Williams (2,019) on the
all-time list. ... he Blue Jays have called up former Angels
catcher/DH Todd Greene. ... Through Friday, Angels outfielder Darin
Erstad had 77 hits, a pace for 260 over the course of the season.
The all-time major league record is 257 set by George Sisler in
1920.
</P>
</TEXT>
