<SLUG> BC-NYTFISHER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKELY ECONOBOX FINDS A PLACE ON PERFORMANCE CAR PEDESTAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Troy, Mo. _ Not long ago Travis
McMillian was waiting for a stoplight here when a snazzy new Camaro
Z-28 pulled up beside him.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Z's driver glanced over at the aftermarket decals on
McMillian's car and offered a challenge by revving his engine.
</P>
<P>
   The light changed. McMillian and the Z-28 took off.
</P>
<P>
   McMillian blew the Camaro's doors off.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, McMillian did it in his 1996, two-door magenta Neon _
aptly named ``Venom.''
</P>
<P>
   A Neon? Yes, that strangely named and bulbous car with the funny
headlights whose introduction six years ago featured a goofy ad
campaign that said ``Hi.'' A grocery-getter for a new mom. The
econobox that car-rental companies foist on tourists looking for a
rock-bottom price. And a ``program car'' that dealers sell for well
under $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   While Kansas City drools in anticipation of the coming Kansas
speedway, while weekend TV is dominated by Chevys, Fords and
Pontiacs blazing around racetracks at 190 miles an hour, and while
media coverage builds to a crescendo over the Indianapolis 500,
something else is going on.
</P>
<P>
   People _ especially late baby boomers _ are rediscovering
performance cars, be they dragsters, hot rods, rally cars, racers
and all the other permutations of American car culture. And one of
the winners in that rediscovery has been the Dodge and Plymouth
Neon, small, economical, and cheap.
</P>
<P>
   While not exactly at the Harley-Davidson cult status, the mild
fanaticism among its enthusiasts now means that every summer
hundreds of Neon owners make a pilgrimage to the Chrysler (now
DaimlerChrysler) assembly plant at Belvidere, Ill., northwest of
Chicago, where the little cars are assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturn helps sponsor their customers coming down to their
plant in Tennessee,'' said Matt Wiggins, a Neon enthusiast in Ames,
Iowa. ``Ours is truly grass-roots. Ours has passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Come September, there'll be nearly a thousand people _ and their
Neons _ for an autocross event at Forbes Field at Topeka, Kan. Pick
any weekend, and somewhere there's a rally or race featuring Neons,
Saturns, Sentras, Proteges, Intergas and Civics.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a new phenomenon has now spread from the West Coast
_ ``import drag racing'' featuring front-wheel-drive cars with
modified engines.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, a bunch of Neons competed in an autocross in
parking lot C at Arrowhead Stadium in Kansas City to benefit the
Dream Factory charity, said Eric Linnhoff, a Neon owner.
</P>
<P>
   The nuttiness about Neons and other makes, said Doug Reed,
marketing manager for club racing at the Sports Car Club of America
in Denver, proves that the American love of performance cars never
really went away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a whole generation during the 1970s and 1980s when we
were building such terrible cars,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take people between about 30 and 43. As teen-agers they grew
up when the cars in the showrooms had all that government-mandated
junk that killed performance. Plus when you got the car home, a lot
of them literally fell apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said the performance cars _ the Plymouth Hemis, the precise
cornering MGBs and Triumphs and the Chevys with a list of options
resembling a criminal's rap sheet, seemed to be things of the past.
But then along came imaginative engineering, a new breed of car
executives who had been car crazy when they were youths, and the
blooming of NASCAR racing.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1995 Neon was introduced, McMillian said, people
noticed something. The plain little car was dirt cheap, had a
nimble suspension, 132 horsepower crying out to be modified for
more and a close-ratio five-speed transmission. And best of all,
the computer card didn't limit speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you wind out most cars and get to their top end,'' said
McMillian, ``the computer tells the engine to cut off the fuel.
Then they start bucking, 'cause they're starved for gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not the Neon. They left that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins said Chrysler did something quite clever. It aimed for a
niche in the small-car market _ the one called ``club racing,''
folks who like to spend an afternoon dodging cones on mall parking
lots or running laps or racing with one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all word of mouth,'' he said, adding that people were
amazed that the car was American-made and that the manufacturer was
Chrysler, which had produced its share of horrendous Detroit iron.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the enthusiasm made its way to the Internet. Although
Chrysler couldn't have known it, Wiggins said, the popularity of
the Neon parallels the growth of the World Wide Web, which now
contains roughly 3,000 Neon sites.
</P>
<P>
   One of those lists the ``Neon Commandments,'' the third of which
orders:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thou shalt remove thine stock exhaust and ensconce it in thy
shrine/garage. Thou shalt now smite thine enemies with thy custom
exhaust and wear ear plugs. And thou shalt limp past the law with
thy power and fury.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor could Chrysler have anticipated the past decade's boom in
NASCAR racing. McMillian thinks that among every 10 spectators, at
least one sees himself as Bobby Labonte or Darrell Waltrip in the
cockpit of a Monte Carlo, Taurus or Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what do those cars cost?'' he asked. ``Probably $140,000
each. And you've got to have more than one if you crash. Plus crew
and tires and all the extra stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there're the Corvettes and Vipers and Stealths, but
you're still talking big money. Heck, you can get a used Neon, put
$3,000 in it, and add some big tires. Then you've got something
really neat that you can drive to work or take out on the weekend,
spend $20 bucks on entry fees and have a time of your life. And it
gets good mileage, too.''
</P>
<P>
   David Williams, president of the St. Louis Neon club
www.drive.to/gwneon said he never intended to buy a Neon. Now he
has one and has talked two members of his family into buying their
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother has a Grand Prix,'' he said. ``I went down to one
of his events, and there were all these guys with Neons. You know,
we traded stories. We talked. That's a lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said that in the days when American cars were king, the
Sports Car Club of America catered to the English sports car set,
owners of Porches and Alfas, plus an occasional Lotus and Mercedes
gull-wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty snooty,'' he said. ``So we had to change. But
all the time we knew there was a hunger out there. We started
sponsoring events for cars like Neons and Sentras. We worked with
Chrysler and other manufacturers. There was prize money, not a lot,
but enough to make going to an event worth your while.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, Reed said, the club had 13,000 members. Today there are
55,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for McMillian, his Neon is in the shop for an engine rebuild.
When it's done the little car will have 240 horsepower. With
sticky, 10-inch tires, it'll be a screamer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
