<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-27 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7968 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-WOMEN'S-TRIATHLON     05-27 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMEN'S-TRIATHLON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Michigan woman rolls to victory in triathlon trials 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Everyone knew Sheila Taormina could swim. She
has an Olympic gold medal to prove it. But bike? She bought her
first bike only two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed that yesterday, though, she was born in the saddle.]
She and Barb Lindquist jumped out of the water after swimming
nine-tenths of a mile with a 48-second lead, and stretched that to
a 3-minute, 36-second advantage over a frustrated pack of 12 during
the 40-kilometer bike race. Taormina followed that by running a
solid 10K in 40:48 to win the women's U.S. Olympic team trials for
the triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   Taormina, a 31-year-old from Livonia, Mich., finished the
swim-bike-run event through the Las Colinas area in 2 hours, 5
minutes, 27 seconds on a warm, humid morning that eventually took
its toll on Lindquist.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of Lindquist's problems, Joanna Zeiger, a
30-year-old from Baltimore, ran the fastest 10K of the 20 finishers
of the 28 starters to push into second place and grab the other
Olympic berth.
</P>
<P>
   Zeiger conquered the hilly, three-loop 10K course in 38 minutes
to finish in 2:06:17 and join Taormina and Jennifer Gutierrez on
the U.S. team for the first Olympic triathlon competition, at the
2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia, in September. Gutierrez had
secured a berth last month in the Sydney World Cup and finished
fifth yesterday in 2:08:08.
</P>
<P>
   Lindquist, the world's fifth-ranked triathlete, was overtaken in
Sydney by Gutierrez after suffering a fall during the bike ride.
Lindquist had another heartbreaker yesterday when she dropped out
after struggling through the first loop of the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I passed her on the second lap on a steep hill, and it looked
like she was in trouble,'' Zeiger said. ``I didn't see her drop
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Taormina, who won an Olympic swimming gold medal in 1996 in the
800-meter freestyle relay, said she had noticed Lindquist breathing
harder than usual as they worked off each other on the bike ride,
posting the fastest times of 1:24:18 and 1:24:20, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But Lindquist wasn't the only one to struggle in the warm, humid
conditions as officials reported that ``at least five'' had been
connected to IVs after the race for dehydration, including Jill
Newman, who collapsed after crossing the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Taormina wasn't counting her victory until she
crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I dehydrated in a couple of races last year, I know it's
never over until it's over,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Taormina looked behind her on the run for the first time when
she glanced back after a turn heading down the stretch on O'Connor
Road to see if she needed to sprint to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to sprint,'' she said. Instead, she was able to
smile and wave to the crowd lining the street to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   After the swim and bike race, it appeared that she and Lindquist
would be able to do that for most of the run, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   With many strong cyclists in the field, no one expected a big
gap to develop between the leaders and second pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Taormina said when she reached the first
turnaround and saw no one near her and Lindquist, who left Lake
Carolyn almost together after swimming the nine-tenths of a mile in
18:54 and 18:56, respectively. Next out was Laura Reback at 19:42.
Reback finished fourth at 2:07:53, behind Siri Lindley's 2:07:35.
Lindley, who celebrated her 31st birthday Friday, was ninth out of
the water in 20:07. She'll serve as the team's alternate.
</P>
<P>
   The gap was frustrating to many of the cyclists, who said they
couldn't understand why some of the stronger riders weren't trying
to push the pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't gaining, we were losing ground,'' Zeiger said.
``You'd think in the trials, people would want to work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindley said there was some ``dialogue'' among the group, and
that ``it broke my heart that not everyone wanted to go out there
and race their hearts out on such a big day.''
</P>
<P>
   A few times, a smaller group would try breaking away, said
Gutierrez, but it never became an organized commitment of sharing
the drafting, rotating and pulling.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Zeiger jumped off her bike, facing a 3:36 deficit, she
said she wasn't going to hold anything back. She felt strong
because she had bolstered her running by qualifying for the Olympic
marathon trials in February. Although she finished far back (''I
never expected to qualify,'' she said), she said the training had
her ready for the triathlon trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the nature of these races. I know anything can happen,
and I felt I had the strength to pull it through,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Taormina knows a commitment she made to continue training in
1994 has paid off.
</P>
<P>
   After a ``depressing'' period that started in '93 when she
didn't know if she wanted to stay in swimming, get a job or combine
them, she finally chose training and earning money as a
motivational speaker. She moved into triathlons upon the urging of
Waterloo Triathlon race director Lew Kidder after he saw her in her
first effort at the three-sport event in '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought my first bike, and threw myself into really hard
riding,'' she said. However, she got ``dropped'' by her group
``every ride and wanted to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I built up my strength, and this is the first year I
haven't been dropped by the group,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from yesterday, it'll be a long time before she is
again.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
