<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOLINA TAKES CHARGE AS NO. 1 CATCHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Catcher Bengie Molina's second-inning single
Saturday night extended his career-high hitting streak to 10 games,
during which time he's hitting .550 (22 for 40).
</P>
<P>
   Even though manager Mike Scioscia said at the beginning of the
season Molina and Matt Walbeck would share the catching duties,
Molina has taken hold of the position, starting 36 games to
Walbeck's 13.
</P>
<P>
   What's most important to Scioscia for a catcher is defense and
how he handles the pitchers. Molina's thrown out 42 percent (11 of
26) would-be basestealers. He did get a passed ball in Saturday's
game, but it was the first by an Angels catcher this season. They
had been the only team in the majors without making one.
</P>
<P>
   So Molina's hitting has been an added bonus. After a slow start,
Molina is now hitting .344. He went 3 for 4 Saturday, including the
game-winning hit in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the season he was trying to get his feet
on the ground,'' Scioscia said. ``Now he's more patient and laying
off pitches he can't hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Molina said it's simply a matter of getting the opportunity to
play almost every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more to do with playing time,'' he said. ``You leave a
guy out there, they're going to do OK. Playing time is what it's
all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia was still miffed one day after Garret Anderson was
thrown out of Friday's game by umpire Tony Randazzo. Randazzo, a
rookie umpire, apparently thought Anderson was showing him up by
``tracking'' the ball -- or watching the ball all the way to the
catcher's mitt.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia noted that a number of hitters in the game do the same
thing, and that Randazzo over-reacted.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, umps seem to have quick tempers and often
initiate confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think umps always try to maintain a semblance of order
during the game,'' Scioscia said. ``When a player crosses the line,
an umpire's going to react. But it seems that the line becomes
easier and easier to cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Benji Gil, in a 0-for-17 slump, saw his batting
average dip to .195 after Saturday's game, and he's made a
team-high 11 errors in 41 games. With Justin Baughman waiting in
the wings at Triple-A Edmonton, Gil might be pressing, Scioscia
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him about it,'' Scioscia said. ``He needs to relax
and just let his skills take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jason Dickson (strained left hip) threw Saturday and
felt no soreness. He's eligible to come off the DL May 30 but will
have to make a rehab assignment before returning to the big league
club.
</P>
<P>
   DAILY BOX
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS AT KANSAS CITY
</P>
<P>
   Time: 11:05 a.m. at Kauffman Stadium
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KCAL-9; KMPC-1540, KIK-FM 94.3, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Brian Cooper (1-0, 6.00 ERA) will start for Anaheim
against Kansas City's Miguel Batista (2-2, 5.70). The Angels have
hit 44 home runs in May, tying the club record for homers in any
month (August, 1982).
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
