<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This collection of paperbacks is from the New &AMP; Noteworthy
column of The New York Times Book Review since the 1999 Holiday
Books issue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST AMERICAN SHORT STORIES OF THE CENTURY &LR;  Edited by John
Updike and Katrina Kenison. Houghton Mifflin, $18.95. A collection
of short fiction from the annual Best American Short Stories
series, which began in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLIZZARD OF ONE: Poems &LR;  By Mark Strand. Knopf, $15. Brave verse
about small epiphanies in a godless world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CARELESS LOVE: The Unmaking of Elvis Presley &LR;  By Peter
Guralnick. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $17.95. The King's dark years
and drug-steeped demise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLEAR SPRINGS: A Family Story &LR;  By Bobbie Ann Mason.
HarperPerennial, $14. The writer revisits her old Kentucky home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLERIDGE: Darker Reflections, 1804-1834 &LR;  By Richard Holmes.
Pantheon, $18. An animated account of the romantic poet's final
years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CORRUPTION OF AMERICAN POLITICS: What Went Wrong and Why &LR; 
By Elizabeth Drew. Overlook, $15.95. A fresh perspective on the
campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CRYPTONOMICON &LR;  By Neal Stephenson. HarperPerennial, $16.
Audacious fiction about code making and code breaking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FIRST WORLD WAR &LR;  By John Keegan. Vintage, $16. An eminent
military historian demystifies World War I.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THE RELIEF OF UNBEARABLE URGES &LR;  By Nathan Englander.
Vintage International, $12. Stories about the tension between old
and new worlds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HOURS &LR;  By Michael Cunningham. Picador USA, $13. Fiction
about the haunting power of memory and books.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INCUBUS &LR;  By Ann Arensberg. Ballantine, $14. A postmodern Gothic
novel about a spooky Maine town.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ITALIAN FEVER &LR;  By Valerie Martin. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
A fictional study of the complications of lovemaking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE &LR;  By Thomas L. Friedman. Anchor,
$15. A columnist examines the effects of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LORDS OF THE HORIZONS: A History of the Ottoman Empire &LR;  By
Jason Goodwin. John Macrae/Owl/Holt, $15. The rise and fall of a
former imperial power.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARILYN MONROE &LR;  By Barbara Leaming. Three Rivers, $15. A
humanizing biography of the archetypal dumb blonde.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORGAN: American Financier &LR;  By Jean Strouse. HarperPerennial,
$18. A debunking biography of the Gilded Age financier.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC FOR TORCHING &LR;  By A.M. Homes. HarperPerennial, $14. A
willfully depraved novel about a suburban couple.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ORCHID THIEF &LR;  By Susan Orlean. Ballantine, $14. The
monomania of orchid growers and collectors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PALACE &LR;  By Lisa St. Aubin de Teran. Ecco/HarperCollins,
$13. An exotic fairy tale set in 19th-century Venice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PRAYER FOR THE DYING &LR;  By Stewart O'Nan. Picador USA, $13.
Historical fiction about a town plagued by diphtheria.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REPORTING VIETNAM: American Journalism, 1959-1975 &LR;  Library of
America, $17.95. A selection of writing by Vietnam War
correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SINGLE &AMP; SINGLE &LR;  By John le Carre. Pocket Star, $7.99. A master
of Cold War spy fiction turns to global finance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STORIES OF J.F. POWERS &LR;  New York Review, $14.95. Fiction by
a writer with a devoted following, about priests and parishioners
in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; T.C. BOYLE STORIES: The Collected Stories of T. Coraghessan
Boyle &LR;  Penguin, $16.95. A crazy quilt of styles, voices and
shticks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TESSERACT &LR;  By Alex Garland. Riverhead, $13. A complex
mosaic of a novel set in the Philippines
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THROWIM WAY LEG: Tree-Kangaroos, Possums, and Penis Gourds _ On
the Track of Unknown Mammals in Wildest New Guinea &LR;  By Tim
Flannery. Grove, $14. Encounters with cannibals and shrieking
frogs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOMAN: An Intimate Geography &LR;  By Natalie Angier. Anchor, $15. A
rapturous tour of the female body.
</P>
